<HEADLINE>
TRACK TO INTRODUCE PRACTICE SESSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ It's expensive to book track time at
Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Many teams hook up with other teams for midweek test sessions.
That generally leaves low-budget teams on the outside looking
in.However, the speedway and Legends Cars of California might have
found a way for those drivers to get non-race-day track time. On
Tuesday, the track and the Upland-based racing car company will
sponsor the first of six practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's twofold,'' track general manager Bob DeFazio said. ``It's
cost-effective for those who can't afford to test here and it's a
chance for someone who thinks they might want to go racing to give
it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the series that race at Irwindale, the Legends class
might be the best for rookie drivers; nearly everything on the car
is spec and competition on the third-mile oval is close, with
rookies frequently near or in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legend cars give the average guy a chance to drive a real race
car in competition and stay on a reasonable budget,'' competition
director Chris Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   The practice session is from 5 p.m. to 9 p.m., but nonracers
will have an opportunity to drive in an introductory program that
includes multiple laps between 2 p.m. and 5 p.m. The cost for the
practice sessions, or introductory class, is $50. Pit passes are
$10.
</P>
<P>
   The other Legend Tuesdays are Sept. 5 and 26, Oct. 3 and 24 and
Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   __ Long season: Baseball has its dog days of summer and so do
speedways.
</P>
<P>
   Money, vacations and broken cars have an effect on car counts.
But Morgan says he's pleased with this year's fields. Saturday
night had 92 cars entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up 20 percent,'' Morgan said. ``Last year, we had 17 or
18 Super Late Models at this point and (on Saturday), we have 27.
If they weren't running Super Late Models at Cajon and Mesa Marin
(Speedways), we'd easily have more than 30 cars.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Acronym confusion: So, what is it, CMC or CMC?
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday, Canyon Country's Tommy Fry had won two
consecutive Super Late Model races at Irwindale for CMC. Car owner
Ed Doyle owns Chatsworth Machine Company and Competition Machining
Center, both separate businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created unnecessary confusion,'' Doyle admitted.
</P>
<P>
   So from now on, Doyle, who won the SLM title with Rod Johnson as
his driver, will be racing for Chatsworth Machine Company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
