<SLUG> BC-ROD--BULL </SLUG>
 RIDING-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bull riders pay tribute to Bodacious' past
<TEXT>
<P>
   By SCOTT KAISER
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Bull-riding competitions are pretty much worthless
without good bulls, and there was none better than Bodacious.
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Bodacious, who died May 16 of kidney failure, is
such that a tribute in his honor was part of Saturday's Justin Bull
Riding Championship at Compaq Center. The six men _ out of 135
career riders _ who lasted eight seconds on the 1,800-pound
crossbreed Charbray bull were in attendance for a video tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's most dangerous bull'' was not only notorious for
his assaults on bull riders but became a multimedia star as well.
Bodacious is the only bull to have an agent and his own line of
merchandise, and a feature video of his exploits became a
bestseller. He was inducted into the Pro Rodeo Hall of Fame last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the baddest bull there has ever been,'' said Tuff
Hedeman, president of Professional Bull Riders Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman is one of the six who earned points on Bodacious, but he
also needed reconstructive surgery after getting his face smashed
by the bull in 1995. Hedeman drew Bodacious again at an event later
that year and refused to ride him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heart would drop when you saw your name next to his,''
said Montana's Clint Branger, who scored a remarkable 92 on
Bodacious in 1995. ``He weighed close to 2,000 pounds but moved
like a linebacker in the NFL. He was so big and athletic, and to be
able to jump and drop and still have all that power with it, he was
just incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something for me to say that I rode that bull. I didn't
sleep for two nights after I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious, originally called J31, came to prominence in the
early 1990s as champion bull riders were routinely thrown to the
ground, many seriously injured. In addition to his distinctive
coloring that earned him the nickname ``Yellow Whale,'' Bodacious
made unique moves that never before had been seen and left riders
defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1994 Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo, Bodacious used his
patented head-snapping move that resulted in life-threatening
injuries to Terry Don West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end (of his career), he had a deal where he set you
up and smacked you,'' Branger said. ``He got smart and had a move
where he would rear up and throw the rider over the front and then
smack him with his head, and it would mutilate them. If they hadn't
retired him, he eventually would have killed somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bodacious injured Scott Breding in late 1995, owners Sammy
and Carolyn Andrews retired the bull ``in the interest of cowboy
safety.'' Since Bodacious' death, his legacy has been kept alive by
Buckers Inc. through its distribution of Bodacious' semen as part
of a move to breed better bucking stock.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious' tradition was held up in Saturday's opening round as
only 18 of 46 riders completed their rides. Justin McBride, who
turns 21 on Monday, stole the show by posting the night's best
score of 90 on Lisa's Pet and then earned an additional $30,000 by
riding Rampage for 8.7 seconds in the Mossy Oak Shootout. McBride
was the first man in a year to complete a ride on the bull
considered today's Bodacious.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rampage) is the baddest bull going (right now), but that's
the kind of challenge I crave,'' said McBride, who picked up
$15,000 earlier this season in another shootout. ``If you want to
try and be the best at what you're doing, you have to match
yourself against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The 46 competitors have a second ride today beginning at 2 p.m.,
and then the top 15 _ based on the average of the first two rounds
_ get another ride as they vie for a first-prize purse of $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was great, but it's over now,'' McBride said. ``I have
to get after them again (today).''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
