<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E.Y. IS NOT OK WITH JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Chicago Cubs are coming to Dodger Stadium for
the first time this season Monday, but it's best to hold off on any
plans for that lovefest between Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson and ex-Dodger Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers traded Young to the Cubs during the offseason along
with right-hander Ismael Valdes, recently reborn a Dodger. Don't
look for Young to don Dodger Blue again, though, not as long as
Johnson is around and Young keeps firing verbal shots.
</P>
<P>
   Young was at it again, this time down in San Diego, where the
Cubs played a three-game series against the Padres. Young told the
Chicago Sun- Times he and Johnson did not speak when the teams
first met this season in Wrigley, only exchanged glares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make a move to apologize,'' Young said. ``If
he wants to make amends or something like that, I have no problem
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson maintains he liked Young and had no problems with him,
but Young said too many times the manager's private comments
criticizing his defense at second and leadoff ability have come
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done it before with me last season in front of the
team,'' Young said. ``But what ticks me off about the latest
episode is that he was continually bad-mouthing me after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once the trade was done, there should have been no
more talk about it by him. So it was time for me to come out with
my side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said part of his problem with the Dodgers was the L.A.
media tended to side with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some were pro-Davey, so they had to write positive about
him,'' he said. ``Some would write the facts and those were the
guys who were pro- E.Y.''
</P>
<P>
   __ And now, leading off: Young is batting .300 for Chicago and
giving the Cubs the kind of leadoff hitter the Dodgers were so
desperate for this season that last week they traded for another
ex- Dodger, Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, who spent part of three seasons with the Dodgers after
coming up through their organization, on Friday made his first
start at Chavez Ravine as a Dodger since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you come to a new team, you have butterflies,''
Goodwin said. ``I can't tell you if I had any more because it was
coming back here. I didn't lose my lunch, so I guess it wasn't too
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a platoon, sort of: Alex Cora has essentially taken over
the starting shortstop job from Kevin Elster. Or at least he's
being given the chance at it.
</P>
<P>
   Cora has started the past four games at short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a platoon,'' Johnson said. ``Left-handers are
off for Cora right now. I'm trying to get him comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: F.P. Santangelo served the third day of his
five-game suspension for his involvement in the incident with fans
at Wrigley Field back in May. . . . Right-hander Kevin Brown's
sacrifice bunt Friday night was his 11th of the season, tying him
with Atlanta's Kevin Millwood for the second most in the majors. .
. . The Dodgers' annual Hollywood Stars game, which once boasted
A-list stars like Frank Sinatra, Kirk Douglas and Dean Martin,
featured a mostly B lineup Saturday that included Carlos Alazarqui,
that noted voice of the Taco Bell Dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
