woman his telephone number. Maybe it was at a bar and the light
wasn't good. Or maybe he was behind her in line at a coffee shop
and scribbled it on a napkin. Whatever happened, when she finally
got up the nerve to call him, she reached the wrong answering
machine. Mine. By E.J. MONTINI. Column will move in the ``K''
category.
</P>
<P>
   ROBB {ndash} COLUMN (Philadelphia) --Is it possible that George
W. Bush, allegedly an underachiever most of his adult life, will
become the most transforming president since Franklin Delano
Roosevelt? That's the ambition he set forth, in the images and
messages carefully projected during the meticulously choreographed
convention, and in his acceptance speech. By ROBERT ROBB. Column
will move on the ``K'' wire.
</P>
<P>
   WILLEY {ndash} COLUMN (Philadelphia) - For sheer
``pleasantness,'' last week's Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia was more enjoyable than others in recent memory. It
was very politically correct. It was also very politically dull. By
KEVEN ANN WILLEY. Column will move on the ``K'' wire.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA REPUBLIC {ndash} EDITORIAL (Philadelphia) -The last time
there was an open seat for the presidency was 1988. Michael Dukakis
emerged from the Democratic National Convention with a 17-point
lead, yet failed to wrest the office away from the Republican
standard-bearer that year, a vice president named, ironically
enough, George Bush. Twelve years later and it's an open seat
again. George W. Bush just emerged from the Republican National
Convention here with a lead, at least in some polls on Friday,
approaching 19 percentage points over the Democratic
standard-bearer, a vice president named Al Gore. Is that where the
analogy ends? ARIZONA REPUBLIC. Editorial will move on the ``K''
wire.
</P>
