<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID ATTACK PROVES POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution finally have assembled a team
that can match the Columbus Crew's athleticism and speed. But even
the Revolution's second-half improvement in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's game
was not enough as they played to a 1-1 tie with the Crew and remain
in ninth place, 1 point behind Dallas, in the race for the final
playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes of regulation, the Revolution forced their
opponents back and kept them off balance with their aggression and
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Crew scored the first goal, on an impressive free kick
by Robert Warzycha that goalkeeper Juergen Sommer had no chance to
stop in the 85th minute. A first-half header by the Crew's Brian
McBride was nullified on a questionable offside call.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution pressure paid off. They were denied a penalty
kick when Johnny Torres went down in the goal area in the 80th
minute, then tied the score when Wolde Harris finished a William
Sunsing cross in the 88th.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Sunsing and Torres, who replaced an effective
but tiring Jose Luis Morales, added dynamism to the Revolution's
attack.
</P>
<P>
   New England concluded the match with eight players age 24 or
younger. The Revolution played with the defensive-minded midfield
of Joe Franchino, John Harkes, and Carlos Parra, with Imad Baba and
Jamar Beasley on the wings. Sunsing replaced Baba in the 60th
minute and ignited the attack, nearly providing a dramatic clincher
when his 91st-minute drive from 35 yards bounced off the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's three-man defense _ Rusty Pierce, Mauricio
Wright, and Brian Dunseth _ displayed cohesion and an
uncompromising attitude. They were also fortunate that McBride's
first-half goal was disallowed and a Dunseth handball was ruled
outside the penalty area by referee Noel Kenny in the 56th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first goal was not offside and Noel probably knows he
didn't have a good game,'' Columbus coach Tom Fitzgerald said.
``But everyone is human.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo was less understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would say this,'' Clavijo said. ``But my
enjoyment for the game is going away. It's frustrating because it
was not Columbus that stopped us from getting another 2 points. It
is tough to fight against a pretty good team and fight against
other forces, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I talked about the referee it cost me $2,000.
But if you look at it, we could have had an extra 2 points against
Miami, too. It's very hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Torres appeared to have drawn a penalty in the final
minute of a 1-1 tie against Miami April 29. But the referee _ Kenny
_ denied the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two players together holding each other and both went
down,'' Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He apologized to me before this game for the last (non-call)
and I said, `Don't worry about it, but don't let it happen again,'
'' Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution expected to capitalize on playing seven of their
final nine games at home. But this was their first home point since
a 3-0 win over San Jose June 10. The Revolution, who visit the
MetroStars next week, have 33 points in 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   At least this was one of the few times the Revolution appeared
capable of imposing their game on Columbus. They have only two
3-point victories in 19 games, 8 points of a possible 57, and a
33-15 goal deficit against the Crew since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
