u s BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-06 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Alou deserves better treatment
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you went by looks alone, Moises Alou would be the
anti-Lima _ a slow, solemn drumbeat of a man compared to Jose
Lima's bouncy Latin beat.
</P>
<P>
   He is dour in a world of pizazz.
</P>
<P>
   But if you went by looks alone _ and haven't most Astros fans
and wannabe experts when it comes to Mo Baseball? _ Alou would be
in New York today. Or Boston. Or anywhere but here, where style
sometimes seems to matter more than production and the world seems
to revolve around slidesteps and retractable roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Lima started the year 1-13 but received rousing ovations. The
Astros dropped 10 games, 15 games, 20 games out of first place in a
season that once held so much promise, but the company line
continued to be, ``Isn't it just great to be playing outdoors?''
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, Mo was perceived as less.
</P>
<P>
   For all his long, loping strides in the outfield and flyballs
bouncing in front of him, Alou was looked at like some kind of
Derek Bell without the lime-green alligator loafers.
</P>
<P>
   For all his stone-faced stares, slow walks to the dugout and
noticeable absences from playoff games gone by, Mo was traded by
Monday morning executives more often than Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life when all you do is produce without flash. Such is
life when you wear your emotions in your heart, not your sleeve and
loyalty becomes a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to give the man a break. And his due.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had to become the scapegoat when this Astros season was
blown to smithereens, but how it became Alou might be the saddest
twist to a season so sad Enron Field should be draped in black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it hurt to hear all the things fans have said about
me,'' Alou said. ``People think I'm lazy or I don't care. I could
have easily left this team.''
</P>
<P>
   At least twice, Alou was offered the opportunity to accept a
trade to a contending team this year, guaranteeing himself a chance
to perhaps win another World Series ring to match the one he earned
with the Marlins. But both times when the trade was offered, Alou
showed something that beloved former Astros like Darryl Kile and
Mike Hampton did not.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the boos and catcalls only continued, confounding those who
know what ticks in Alou's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation last year in the playoffs (against Atlanta) when
he wasn't with the team really affected how people look at him,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``It was vastly overplayed. But
ever since, some people look at him and they might see something
that's not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just an air of royalty about him. He maintains a quiet
demeanor, sort of like an inner competitiveness. That can be a good
thing in baseball. That type of a personality can keep you in good
stead in this game for a long time. But it also can be
misinterpreted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Alou's explanation of his playoff absence last year can be
interpreted like some kind of aloofness, or cockiness: ``Being a
player of my caliber, to sit and watch knowing that if I was out
there I probably could have done better than the guys in the
outfield, I didn't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a blunt, biting explanation. But is it wrong? With a pair
of doubles in Saturday night's 10-9 loss to the Expos, Alou raised
his batting average to .353, with 17 home runs and 61 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of Richard Hidalgo, Jeff Bagwell or Scott
Elarton being the team Most Valuable Player this season, has anyone
mentioned Alou?
</P>
<P>
   It must be the staid demeanor. It must be the scary stare and
the seriousness of his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people that are afraid to come up to me and
ask me a question or say hello,'' Alou said. ``I'm not a Mr. Smiley
Guy. People feel like I'm angry, but I'm not. That's one thing I'd
like to change about myself. If I'm at a restaurant or out
somewhere, people avoid me. They don't approach me. I hear people
saying, `Hey, why don't you smile?'''
</P>
<P>
   But it's time to give the man a break. Some people show a lot of
flash and little production. Mo Baseball only keeps producing _ and
wanting to play in Houston, which, strangely, few have appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have easily gone somewhere else this year and I could
have gone (after) '98, also,'' Alou said. ``I don't always know
what the fans are thinking. In this game, there's not a lot of
loyalty. I told myself, `I can take this (trade) and go win right
now.' But my No. 1 concern is to be happy. I want to feel that
happiness and peace about where I am. Right now, I like the
players, the coaches, the bat boys, everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It's time for fans and would-be critics to quit trying to say
goodbye to Mo and start saying hello.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
