<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MILLETT-JUDAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDAH TKO'S MILLETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCASVILLE, Conn. _ Terronn Millett's championship reign went
into permanent recess Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Millett had once been the International Boxing Federation junior
welterweight champion but was declared champion in recess after he
broke his left hand in his first defense and was unavailable to
defend against No. 1 challenger Zab Judah last December.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the IBF allowed Judah to fight Jan Bergman for the
vacated title and then named him interim champion, with Millett
still in recess until he entered the ring Saturday &UR;  &LR; night with his
entourage carrying the belt he felt was still his because no one
had beaten it out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   He felt that way until 2:47 of the fourth round when the last of
his three trips to the canvas at the Uncasville Pavilion at the
Mohegan Sun Casino set off the sound of bells in his head that
signaled recess was over and now permanent for Millett.
</P>
<P>
   Two solid left hands sent Millett reeling sideways before he
finally fell to the floor. He got up quickly but just as quickly
went down again from another left from Judah, and this time he was
wobbling badly when he rose to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me with a nice shot,'' Millett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my hat off to him. He's quick and he's got a lot of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee Michael Ortega watched Millett closely for several
seconds before asking him to walk forward. When he did and his
equilibrium was clearly still off, Ortega wasted no time in
signaling that the fight was over.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome had been clear long before Ortega's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Judah (24-0, 18 KO's) opened fast and his speed advantage was
obvious from the outset, but just as he seemed to have Millett in
trouble, the 32-year-old former champion nailed him with a body
shot that sent Judah to the floor. Judah seemed stunned at this
occurrence and could think of only one response.
</P>
<P>
   He got up and went after Millett.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he nailed Millett with solid right hands that seemed to
stun the champion from recess almost into a lunch break, but they
did not put him into permanent recess until midway through the
second round, when a sudden Judah left caught Millett right on the
chin again and floored him.
</P>
<P>
   He was up quickly, but it was too quick for his own good as
Judah strafed him with several more bombs.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Millett had no real answer for Judah's hand speed, and
his eyes began to blink noticeably in the third round as Judah
started to pepper him with his right jab and a long left behind it.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Judah began to taunt Millett, moving his body
from side to side, shaking his shoulders and dangling his tongue
out at him as his mentor, Pernell Whitaker, so often had done to
his many victims.
</P>
<P>
   One round later, the taunting stopped and the tattooing began
anew, but this time it didn't last long before the bell tolled for
Millett.
</P>
<P>
   When it did, recess was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the king,'' Judah said. ``If anybody wants to be IBF
champion they have to beat Zab Judah. What I learned tonight is I'm
the real champion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the semi-main event, Juan Lazcano (24-2-1) won a split
decision from former World Boxing Council super featherweight
champion Jesse James Leija.
</P>
<P>
   Judge William Hutt had Leija (40-5-2, 16 KO's) winning, 96-94,
while Fred Ucci had the same score in the opposite direction.
Stephen Weisfield had Lazcano winning seven of the last eight
rounds in the 10-round bout for a 97-93 advantage that gave Lazcano
his close victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it all,'' Leija said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the underdog coming in. I can't do anything about the
judges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
