<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MISS CHANCES, FALL IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Milwaukee Brewers can't seem to figure out
their designated role in this weekend's little get together with
the Los Angeles Dodgers, but major-leaguers tend to have this
aversion to being labeled a pushover.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers need to get some momentum going, need some
comparatively easy wins, but the Brewers keep playing them tough
and messing up their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the Brewers played them tough enough for a 4-2
victory in 10 innings, when light-hitting catcher Henry Blanco hit
a two-run homer off Mike Fetters.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodger Stadium crowd of 42,580 saw the Dodgers fail to pick up
a game on both the Giants and Diamondbacks in the NL West. L.A.
remains 2 games behind division leader San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters (4-2) and Juan Acevedo (2-4) reversed roles from Friday
night's game, this time Acevedo picking up the win and Fetters the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson normally doesn't pitch Fetters on
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to the time of year, I don't consider anybody
unavailable,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters started the 10th getting two quick outs, before Jose
Hernandez looped a single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco, batting .222, then jumped on Fetters' first pitch for
his sixth home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Both starting pitchers _ the Dodgers' Chan Ho Park and the
Brewers' Jeff D'Amico _ were long gone by the time the game broke
into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, the 6-foot-7 right-hander who missed all of the 1998
season following shoulder surgery, was an odd puzzle for the
Dodgers throughout most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   A big man who doesn't try to overpower hitters, he kept the
Dodgers off-balance with slow curves and change-ups.
</P>
<P>
   When he did start Gary Sheffield with a fastball in the fourth
inning, however, he regretted it in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield originally came up with the Brewers _ the only team in
the majors he hadn't homered against.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield jumped on D'Amico's fastball and delivered it several
rows into the left-field pavilion. It was his 35th home run of the
season, giving him back the major-league lead.
</P>
<P>
   That tied the score at 1-1, the Brewers having taken the early
lead when former USC Trojan Geoff Jenkins homered off Chan Ho Park
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' 20th home run of the season was a line shot to right
that almost left the park before the sound of the hit could be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   After Sheffield tied the game up in the fourth, Jenkins put the
Brewers back on top with a second solo home run off Park in the
sixth, this time going to left. It was his first multihomer game of
the season, and the second of his career.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, the NL Pitcher of the Month in July when he went 5-0
with a 0.76 ERA in six starts, was making the 2-1 lead hold up
through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked him,'' Johnson said. ``He's never been real
consistent in the past, but he's locating now and that's why he's
been winning.''
</P>
<P>
   He located one a tad poorly against Shawn Green in the seventh.
Green powered his 19th home run of the season to center and the
game was again tied, this time at 2-2 on four solo home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Park left for a pinch hitter after six innings. He allowed the
two runs on six hits, walked three (one intentionally) and struck
out eight.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, who hasn't lost since June 5, also left without a
decision. He went eight innings, allowing his two runs on five
hits. He walked one and struck out a career high eight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
