<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE WON'T BE A FORCE THIS WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Did Jerry Toliver's chance at upending John
Force's Funny Car reign end Saturday when he failed to qualify for
today's Fram Autolite Nationals?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it, says nine-time NHRA champion Force, who could
take a sizable advantage in the points race if he is able to win
today's national event at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``One race doesn't mean anything,'' said Force, who could take
over the points lead by winning a first-round matchup against
veteran Tommy Johnson Jr. ``Does Toliver not qualifying help us?
Does it motivate us? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't do anything exciting here but qualify. Toliver
didn't qualify, so that makes us feel like we did something. But we
have to take our runs now and try to win a drag race.''
</P>
<P>
   Toliver doesn't seem to be too concerned either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't qualify,'' said Toliver, who could go no quicker
then 5.316 before being bumped out of the 16-car field by Dale
Creasy Jr. ``We still have nine events to go (after Sunday) and
have plenty of time left to make up any ground we lose (today).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early in the third quarter and we have to go into the
next race (in two weeks at Brainerd, Minn.) and continue on. We're
staying focused on the grand prize and we're not about to let one
race prevent us from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Force will give it a good try today. The Bell Gardens native is
not the No. 1 qualifier, but he's been the most consistent here,
qualifying second with a 5.005 and backing it up Saturday with a
pair of 5.02s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got a shot at winning this race,'' Force said.
``The car's been really consistent. But what we need to do is just
focus first round. Whit Bazemore was No. 1 qualifier at Seattle,
then smokes the tires first round. So we need to really focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazemore could challenge Force after his Friday pass of 4.955
held up, earning him his third consecutive pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great run (Friday),'' said Bazemore, who faces
Creasy in the first round. ``We have a tough competitor in Dale
Creasy Jr., and as we showed last week in Seattle, every round is a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Today should also be a challenge in Top Fuel, where Gary Scelzi
leads a host of drivers who made two solid passes over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This racetrack isn't going to hold much,'' said Scelzi, who
qualified No. 1 for the seventh time this season with a solid 4.634
at 310.98 mph. ``It's pretty iffy. I believe you're going to have
to run low (4.70s) to get to the end of this deal. It's going to be
a crew chief and driver's race.''
</P>
<P>
   Which could play into the hands of Doug Kalitta, who ran a 4.657
Saturday to place second in qualifying. La Habra native Bob
Vandergriff Jr. remained third with a 4.666. Vandergriff faces Gary
Clapshaw in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Amato nearly suffered the same fate at Toliver. But the
five-time Top Fuel champion, who was unqualified after three
rounds, made the 16-car field with a steady 4.753 pass in
Saturday's final session.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not very strong, but it got us in the show,'' said
Amato, who faces Tony Schumacher in today's first round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
