<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NEWDODG-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 ... WRITETHRU 
DODGERS LOSE IN 10th 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Milwaukee Brewers can't seem to figure out
their designated role in this weekend's little get-together with
the Los Aneles Dodgers, but major-leaguers tend to have this
aversion to being labeled a pushover.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers need to get some momentum going, need some
comparatively easy wins, but the Brewers keep playing them tough
and messing up their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the Brewers played them tough enough to come away
with a 4-2 victory in 10 innings, when light-hitting catcher Henry
Blanco hit a two-run homer off reliever Mike Fetters.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodger Stadium crowd of 42,580 saw the Dodgers miss an
opportunity to pick up ground on the Giants and Diamondbacks in the
NL West. They both lost, but the Dodgers remain 2 back of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Brewers, who entered the game 20-34 on the
road, 45-64 overall and 14 games back in the NL Central. And
wouldn't play the patsy.
</P>
<P>
   Not with Geoff Jenkins hitting a pair of solo home runs off Chan
Ho Park, who otherwise pitched a strong six innings. And certainly
not with baseball's unexpected pitching sensation, Jeff D'Amico,
holding the Dodgers to a pair of solo home runs from Gary Sheffield
(his major-league leading 35th) and Shawn Green (his 19th) in his
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a good, young team,'' Green said. ``They're
obviously building for next year when they get their new stadium.
They're just out playing, having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, at the Dodgers' expense Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters and Juan Acevedo reversed roles from Friday night's
game, this time Acevedo (2-4) picking up the late win and Fetters
(4-2) the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson normally doesn't pitch Fetters on
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to the time of year, I don't consider anybody
unavailable,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters started the 10th well enough, before Jose Hernandez
looped a single to right for his third hit.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco, who also threw out three would-be base stealers, took
his .222 batting average to the plate and jumped on Fetters' first
pitch for his sixth home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Park and D'Amico were long gone by the time the Dodgers entered
their 10th extra-inning game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico, the 6-foot-7 right-hander who missed all of the 1998
season following shoulder surgery, was an odd puzzle for the
Dodgers throughout the night. A big man who doesn't try to
overpower hitters, he kept the Dodgers off-balance with slow curves
and change-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize that's the best pitcher in the National
League over the last month,'' Eric Karros said. ``It's not about
how hard you throw, it's about mixing it up and keeping hitters
guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   When D'Amico did start Sheffield off with a fastball in the
fourth inning, however, he regretted it in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield originally came up with the Brewers _ the only team in
the majors of the 29 he had faced that he hadn't homered against.
Until Saturday, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield jumped on D'Amico's fastball and delivered it several
rows into the left-field pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins had given the Brewers a 1-0 lead in the first when he
homered to right off Park. After Sheffield tied it, Jenkins gave
Milwaukee the lead back with his second solo shot _ this one to
left in the sixth _ his 21st of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically out of the pennant race at this point, so
we're playing the spoiler role,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico made one more poor pitch, when Green tied the game with
his solo home run the seventh.
</P>
</TEXT>
