<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0807-COX     08-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beyond speeches and balloons
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Those who thought this year's Republican
convention would be the same ol', same ol' were proven wrong from
opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the demographic makeup of the delegates,
they rocked to African and Latino rhythms and listened to the
nephew of the candidate address them in two languages _ the English
of his father and the Spanish of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   They might not have liked everything they heard, but this
convention had a different tone to it. The event that signaled the
change in tone was the impassioned speech Colin Powell delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during the Gulf
War, dropped a rhetorical bomb on the delegates by telling them
some things they probably didn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must understand, my friends, the cynicism that exists in
the black community. The kind of cynicism that is created when, for
example, some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly and
loudly condemn affirmative action that helped a few thousand black
kids get an education, but you hardly hear a whimper from them over
affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes
with preferences for special interests,'' Powell said to applause.
``It doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable performance considering that Powell was
booed at the 1996 GOP convention when he marshalled the same
defense of affirmative action. It was a testament, perhaps, of a
realization that politics is ultimately about numbers and where
those numbers are now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's declaration to the convention was a challenge, not only
to the GOP delegates assembled in Philadelphia, but also to
Democrats and other political parties who will only survive if they
reach beyond their traditional constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the party's presidential nominee, won
unprecedented support from African American and Hispanic
constituencies in his home state by ignoring ethnic and racial
political boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Though skeptics will argue that's all symbolic, the fact remains
that the only minority statewide candidates on the Texas ballot
this year were Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Guess Democrats couldn't find anyone qualified.
</P>
<P>
   When they meet later this month, Democrats will be challenged to
put on their version of outreach and they are going to have to go
some to match the show in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just politics. Who gets elected and appointed to
whatever directly benefits a very few in the political class. To
get to the issues that effect people, neither party has much room
to brag.
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear politicians in either party talking much about
diabetes _ just to cite one example. This killer, however, touches
15 million lives in the United States _ 5 million of whom don't
even know they have it, according to National Institute of Health
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   There are 789,000 new cases of diabetes reported every year. In
1998, the last year for which statistics are available, the price
tag for diabetes was $98 billion _ $44 million in direct costs of
treatment and the balance in indirect costs that include lost
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes hits women more often than men, but hits especially
hard in minority communities. According to the health institute,
one in 10 Mexican Americans are diabetics as are one in 10 non
Hispanic blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Complications from diabetes are ugly as well as deadly. Diabetes
can lead to strokes, blindness, kidney failure, heart attack and
loss of limbs. A high profile example was the legendary songtress
Ella Fitzgerald, who lost both her legs and then her life to the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who want to talk about compassion can include some
words about funding for research, about access to information and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one way of connecting with real concerns of real
people and a good way of letting folks know that politics can be
more than speeches and balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
