<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GREIG-FILES0807-COX     08-06 2169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-FILES0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The handwriting may be on the wall, but can you read it?
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Did anyone else find it ironic that when
President Clinton signed the electronic signature bill into law, he
used a felt-tipped pen? I, for one, am concerned about signatures
with the power to purchase stock and sell houses floating out in
space _ cyber or otherwise. I am in the minority _ the same
minority that prefers receiving canceled checks, not photocopies in
a bank statement.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting develops fine motor skills. Research at the
University of Washington reveals that the creative process is
enhanced by the mechanical process of handwriting. But alas! Forces
such as the keyboard, the pager and the telephone are conspiring to
make communicating by picking up a pen a less-attractive option.
</P>
<P>
   As a big fan of personal correspondence, this disturbs me. I
like the sensual feel of stationery (Cranes to Pineider) and pens
(fountain to felt) as well as the slower pace of handwriting a
letter. And, yes, I am a lousy typist.
</P>
<P>
   But just knowing how to write is not enough _ it must be
legible, too. Take the misread draft on a Canadian bank account
this May resulting in an $8,000 error, or worse, the doctor whose
poor penmanship cost a patient his life.
</P>
<P>
   Hark back to those tedious exercises on the tri-ruled paper in
third grade. Remember that the girls were always better at this
than the boys? Only an Einstein, pupils were told, could get by
with poor penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal about handwriting in the electronic age?
Can it reveal personality traits? Zero in on the composer of the
JonBenet ransom note? Did you realize some companies use
handwriting analysis as part of the hiring process?
</P>
<P>
   If you love putting pen to paper, then this edition of the Greig
Files will validate the importance of continuing to write by hand.
If you rely on your spell-checker and a keyboard, then this edition
will teach you much about the art of handwriting _ from scratch, so
to speak.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE DID WRITING BEGIN?
</P>
<P>
   The journey from lines in the sand to shorthand and e-mail is a
long one.
</P>
<P>
   Sumerian tribes employed pictograms (about 3500 B.C.), stylized
repof actions, called ideograms (sleep, for example, was
represented by a drawing of a prone person). A little like charades
on paper. Abstract symbols representing sounds rather than objects
or actions enhanced written communication. This writing, known as
cuneiform (Latin, meaning ``wedge''), was written with a
wedge-shaped stylus or pen on clay tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Egyptians (about 3100 B.C.) developed
hieroglyphic writing to annotate religious scenes adorning tombs
and chapels. The Chinese developed pictorial script. The
Phoenicians (2000 B.C.) created symbols with phonetic values.
Voila, the alphabet. This greatly simplified writing.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know more about the history of scribble? Pick up a copy
of ``Panati's Browser's Book of Beginnings'' by Charles Panati.
</P>
<P>
   IS BAD PENMANSHIP A STATUS SYMBOL?
</P>
<P>
   The ability to write legibly has gone in and out of fashion.
Royalty at one time disdained writing. Who needs to write when you
have serfs as scribes and pedestrian merchants to keep track of
wheat bushels and cattle herds? Later, only the educated could read
and write. Clergy devoted lifetimes to copying and embellishing the
Scriptures, priding themselves on perfection. Copies of the Torah
must be error-free.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, penmanship classes were all the rage. Good
handwriting was a sign of breeding and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Penmanship is still part of the grade-school curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   WHO NEEDS GOOD HANDWRITING?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone does.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the electronic age, handwriting is appropriate for a
variety of situations. Thank-you notes (yes, many people still pen
them) as well as correspondence of an intimate nature such as
condolence notes, and oh, yes, love letters. Remember Ronald
Reagan's touching letter sharing his Alzheimer's diagnosis with the
nation? Would it have been as heart-wresting if it had been a typed
letter?
</P>
<P>
   Also, handwritten annotated drafts of literary works are much
more interesting than typed drafts.
</P>
<P>
   IS YOUR LIFE AN OPEN BOOK?
</P>
<P>
   To a graphologist, it may be.
</P>
<P>
   A graphologist studies the characteristics of handwriting and
deduces personality traits from the sample. A parlor game? Maybe,
but not to graphologist Sandra Lynn of Personality Profiles Plus.
Individuals and couples seek out Lynn's services to learn more
about themselves and compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting changes with age, but some parts (how letters
connect, certain flourishes) are steadfast. Somewhere in their
early 20s, an individual sets a handwriting style, breaking away
from the rigors of penmanship lessons, notes Lynn. By this time, a
signature style is also developed.
</P>
<P>
   Does your signature differ significantly from your other
handwriting? Then you tend to have a public self and a private
self. And those of you with squiggles for a signature? Lynn says
either the writer signs things too many times in a day and doesn't
have time to make each one legible or cares little whether anyone
else can read the script.
</P>
<P>
   A forward slant of handwriting, for example, indicates a more
expressive, emotional person than one whose writing slants to the
left. Where a ``t'' is crossed indicates goal setting (High ``t''
cross, higher goals).
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS A FORENSIC DOCUMENT EXAMINER?
</P>
<P>
   A certified professional who studies physical evidence,
including handwriting. Forensic document examiners do not determine
personality traits from handwriting; graphologists do. A
graphologist is to a forensic document examiner as astrologers are
to astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Stobaugh, supervisor of the forensic document section of
the DPS Crime Lab, often compares questionable handwriting to known
handwriting samples. A trained forensic examiner can eliminate
someone as the writer of a signature or determine, for example,
that a questioned suicide note was not written by the suicide
victim.
</P>
<P>
   These examiners employ ink analysis, paper scrutiny, envelope
matching, photocopier identification, wear characteristics, image
restoration, obliteration restoration, latent writing impressions
and even inspecting a document in identifying a writer.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S UP, DOC?
</P>
<P>
   Classes in penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Although the American Medical Association adopted guidelines in
1994 recommending physicians type or print prescriptions to avoid
error, many have failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reduce the annual 98,000 deaths caused by errors
include improving written communications. So doctors in hospitals
such as Cedars-Sinai Medical Center are flocking to classes that
begin with first-grade directions such as ``thou shalt not pinch''
the pen. Saving lives may be the result of these classes, but at
the very least, physicians will receive fewer late-night telephone
calls from pharmacists who cannot read their scrawls.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HANDLES 30,000 LETTERS AN HOUR?
</P>
<P>
   The United States Postal Service MLOCRs. That is the trade
moniker for Multiline Optical Character Readers. In Austin, there
are five of these electronic marvels as well as several Remote
Computer Readers. Automation equipment can process letters at a
cost of $5.20 per thousand. Manually sorted letters cost about
$57.64 per thousand to process. There's a saving!
</P>
<P>
   If these machines cannot decipher your hand, then the letter is
sent to a remote encoding center in Beaumont to be keyed by hand
(not the most direct route across Texas).
</P>
<P>
   These machines are more sophisticated than ever, notes USPS
spokeswoman Barbara Pokorny, but the letter carrier who slips the
mail into the box needs to be able to read your writing. And, no,
putting only the ZIP code plus will not guarantee delivery. The
traditional name and address is still needed. WOULDN'T YOU REALLY
RATHER HAVE A BUTTON GWINETT?
</P>
<P>
   Sure would, because this signer of the Declaration of
Independence died soon after the historic signing. His handwriting
fetches more than $100,000, an exorbitant amount compared with the
$2,000 that John Hancock's brings. Autographs and handwritten
manuscripts are popular and sometimes big-ticket collector items,
according to Sara Willen, senior appraiser of manuscripts at
California's Superior Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Men are more likely to collect handwritten documents than women.
They have the money and the ego, proclaims Willen. So what types of
items does Willen think will rise in value in the near future?
World War I letters and historic signatures as the 100-year
anniversary approaches.
</P>
<P>
   DOES GOOD PENMANSHIP PAY?
</P>
<P>
   It can.
</P>
<P>
   Just win the annual National Handwriting Contest sponsored by
Zaner-Bloser, publisher of handwriting texts. Winners (one for each
grade one through six) are awarded a U.S. Savings Bond, and the
grand champion prize is valued at more than $1,000. The 2000
national winner was Michigan fourth-grader Lauren Spaans, whose
cursive is impeccable. (Imagine the pressure on her mom when a note
to the teacher must be penned!) Schools wishing to participate in
the 2001 contest should call Zaner-Bloser at (800) 924-9233 or
visit www.zaner-bloser.com.
</P>
<P>
   WILL THE QUICK BROWN FOX JUMP OVER THE LAZY DOG?
</P>
<P>
   He could during your next job interview.
</P>
<P>
   Handwriting analysis has been used in the interviewing process.
And it is legal to do so, concludes Chris Knepp, an attorney
board-certified in labor and employment law, ``as long as it does
not screen out people based on protected characteristics.'' An
employer who uses handwriting analysis to uniformly exclude a
certain group could be the subject of a lawsuit. Some jobs, of
course, demand legible handwriting _ teachers come to mind. In
these cases, a handwriting test could be every bit as important as
a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T BEAR TO WRITE THANK-YOU NOTES BY HAND?
</P>
<P>
   Go electronic and please the recipient at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up a copy of vLetter Pro for $149.95. Complete a
handwriting sample form, send it to the company, and within a
couple of weeks you are set (rush available). Install the program
on your computer. You type; it writes. In connective cursive yet!
The program also e-mails missives in your ``hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Signatures are included. Best customers? People doing holiday
mailings and writing thank-you notes, cartoonists and artists
wanting to save manual skills for work, as well as businesses
hoping to personalize correspondence. And, oh, yes, a man from
Texas, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (888) 387-2930 or visit www.vletter.com.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE TWO (OR IS THAT 200?) ASPIRINS AND CALL ME IN THE MORNING
</P>
<P>
   Simple advice _ if legible.
</P>
<P>
   Just this year, an Odessa jury awarded a widow $450,000 after it
decided that her husband's death was the result of poor penmanship
on the part of Dr. Ramachandra Kolluru and the poor interpretation
of his prescription by the pharmacist. Within 24 hours of taking
the wrong dose of the wrong medication, Ramon Vasquez suffered a
heart attack. He died two weeks later of congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   WRITE OR WRONG: THE COST OF POOR PENMANSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Poor handwriting costs American business and taxpayers $200
million annually _ through illegible purchase orders, phone
messages, meeting minutes, application forms and correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 percent of hospital medicine orders are returned by
pharmacists as illegible.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion to hand-held computers in Dade County, Fla., to
issue parking tickets collected an estimated $2 million in fines
annually previously lost because of poor penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   WRITE RIGHT: CONSUMER TIPS FROM DPS CRIME LAB
</P>
<P>
   Your signature should be legible to an uninterested party (i.e.
Not your wife or boss).
</P>
<P>
   Your signature should not be so simplistic that it can be easily
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   Destroy all credit card carbons.
</P>
<P>
   Shred personal documents or at least tear them into bits and mix
with wet, nasty garbage before disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Use a permanent marker when signing checks to foil check
washers.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful when mailing documents and bills. Use the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   Fountain pen signatures are more difficult to forge as they
impart shading in a signature.
</P>
<P>
   Practice good penmanship. A scrawl is easier to simulate than
clean handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN MONROE, BILL CLINTON, MICHELANGELO
</P>
<P>
   What type of menage does this trois make? A left-handed one.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 7-12 percent of the United States population
prefers the left hand to the right. Others among the southpaw ranks
include Babe Ruth, Robert Redford and Oprah Winfrey. More men tend
to be lefties than women; more young people than old. Unfortunately
it is a right-handed world. For more on the trends and tribulations
of left handedness, subscribe to ``Left Hander's Newsletter'' by
calling (800) 511-5338 or visiting www.lefthandpublishing.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
