<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0807-COX     08-06 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To preserve old trees, laws need to get a handle on the ax
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every week I get two or three calls from folks trying
to save trees in their neighborhoods, even though 10 metro counties
and several cities now have tree ordinances requiring developers to
submit tree plans for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's law requires ``no net loss of trees.'' That means when
trees are removed, they must be replaced by other trees that total
the same number of diameter inches. A tree 12 inches in diameter,
for example, can be replaced by three trees that are four inches in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
   So if we've made progress with tree protection ordinances, why
the continuing outcry?
</P>
<P>
   It's simple: People want to save old trees _ the native oaks,
maples, hickories and magnolias that set our city apart from
others. But most tree ordinances don't help with that. They allow
ornamental trees to replace the magnificent white oaks that have
been around since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a Civil War-era oak is the reason DeKalb County enacted
the only ordinance in the region that's effective in protecting
existing trees. Three years ago, the county's second-oldest tree
was cut down in the night (as if nobody would notice) to make room
for a Wal-Mart parking lot. That spurred a group of DeKalb tree
lovers to push for a law _ as Kathryn Kolb, a leader of the group
put it _ ``against killing such a healthy, living piece of
history.'' Now, even private homeowners can't cut an old or
significant tree on their own property without permission from the
county arborist.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent calls from community activists in intown
neighborhoods illustrate why every local government should have a
similar law.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Coffin and her neighbors are trying to save some old
red oaks on property the state Department of Transportation just
sold across the street from the new Freedom Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park's John Lewis Plaza is supposed to be a statement
about history and green space, so why clear-cut across the street
from it?'' said Coffin, who has devoted the last decade of her life
to neighborhood trees. But the city caved in to a condo developer
who didn't want to save the oaks on the 4.4 acres _ even though the
city had an obligation to listen to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 lawsuit settlement over a proposed freeway, Atlanta
neighborhoods entered into an agreement with the city and the state
DOT that gave residents a voice in how the DOT-owned property would
be used. The condo site is included in the property covered by the
settlement, so the neighbors _ who aren't fighting the condo
project, just trying to save a few trees _ went back to court.
Superior Court Judge Elizabeth Long hasn't ruled yet on their
injunction request.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Harvey, an artist who's lived in the city for 18 years,
has been fighting the DOT on a similar issue. DOT could have
preserved a forested dry creek which filters stormwater running
into Lullwater Creek when it sold lots in her neighborhood. But the
agency went for the money instead.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and her husband, Bruce, a high-profile defense attorney,
find special solace in the old trees around them. She derives
textures and colors for her paintings from leaves and bark. ``And I
love that Bruce always reaches out to touch the bark of certain
trees when we walk in the neighborhood,'' Paige said.
</P>
<P>
   Some good things are happening to save trees, although progress
is slow. Atlanta hired four new arborists this summer to handle
citizen demands. Starting next week, developers are required to
post maps of their tree plans on the property for 15 days and mark
the trees to be cut with bright paint. Citizens can appeal to the
tree commission if they think the tree ordinance isn't being
upheld.
</P>
<P>
   But only two things will save old trees: first, a commitment to
tree preservation from the top _ the mayor or the chairman of a
county commission. And second, a law like DeKalb's that won't let
developers be so shortsighted about our signature asset.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
