<HEADER>
A4036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COTTON-GIN0807-COX     08-06 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COTTON-GIN0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birthplace of the Cotton Gin
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Amid the tangled, junglelike growth along the
lower Savannah River, a pile of crumbling bricks is all that
remains of the old plantation house where a young tutor invented a
machine that abruptly changed the course of the South _ and
ultimately the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   It was here, at Mulberry Grove Plantation, eight miles upstream
from downtown Savannah, that Eli Whitney invented the cotton gin in
1793. The simple machine, which efficiently separated cotton fibers
from seeds, ushered in the era of King Cotton and, according to
some historians, gave rise to America's Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the South's frenzy to feed textile mills up North and
overseas with cotton gave rise to a great expansion of slavery,
ultimately engulfing the nation in four years of bloody civil war.
Intensive cotton farming changed the South's landscape forever,
eroding the rich topsoil and leaving behind a red clay the color of
baked sweet potato.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the place that birthed this great upheaval is off-limits
to the public. Although 150 acres of Mulberry Grove are listed on
the National Register of Historic Places, the property sits behind
locked gates. Big black-and-white signs warn that trespassers will
be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings are posted by the property's owner, the Georgia
State Ports Authority, a quasi-governmental board of nine people
appointed by the governor to oversee the operations of the
state-owned docks at Savannah and Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   The ports authority bought the property to expand operations at
Savannah's port, but that project has been on hold for 15 years
while the property has remained vacant. Historic preservationists
are appalled that a place so pivotal to Amercian history has
virtually been forgotten. Now, a major push is afoot to preserve
Mulberry Grove and perhaps eventually restore the old plantation
house.
</P>
<P>
   The ports authority has said it would consider giving up some or
all of Mulberry Grove, but it wants something in return: A swath of
land in the neighboring wildlife refuge to help with improvements
to the port. That's an unacceptable tradeoff, say wildlife
officials, who continue to negotiate. It is a delicate process,
trying to preserve an important piece of the past while also
accommodating the needs of Savannah's port, a powerful economic
engine for the region.
</P>
<P>
   Port officials say they must expand the facility to keep it
competitive. That's why, in 1985, the ports authority purchased
Mulberry Grove and other adjacent property _ about 2,200 acres
altogether _ for potential expansion of the port. A year later, the
authority announced that it intended to pave over hundreds of acres
of the property by the mid-1990s for new berthing space for
ocean-going ships. Ports authority officials now say the expansion
probably won't take place until later this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But another group _ the private, nonprofit Mulberry Grove
Foundation _ is determined that the expansion will never happen.
Instead, the group wants the former plantation to be preserved
forever as a historic park, telling the story of the cotton gin and
its massive impact on America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most historic places in the country, and it
amazes me that it has been so neglected,'' says foundation board
member Mark Yeager, a Decatur, Ga., architect.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Waters of Pooler, a retired Marine colonel who is the
foundation's chief executive officer, has accompanied several
visitors to Mulberry Grove over the years. ``They often tell me
they are awed to stand in the place where the event that changed
America occurred,'' Waters says.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's 12-member board also includes John Berendt, the
author of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' and Augusta
resident Barry Whitney, fifth cousin of Eli Whitney four times
removed.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old group envisions a public place where visitors
stroll along trails with interpretive exhibits at key locations:
where slave cabins once stood, at the piles of brick that are the
only visible reminder of the plantation house where Whitney worked
on his invention and at the site where Whitney and his business
partner built the first ``ginning house'' in America.
</P>
<P>
   Waters says the foundation has shelved for now even more
ambitious plans for Mulberry Grove _ rebuilding the old plantation
house, recontructing a slave cabin or two and perhaps rebuilding
the old ginning house. The cost of that project is an estimated $5
million, a sum the foundation says is far out of reach right now.
</P>
<P>
   But implementing even the scaled-back preservation plans will
require getting the Mulberry Grove property from the ports
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is placing its hopes in the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service, which manages the 27,000-acre Savannah National
Wildlife Refuge adjacent to the authority's docks at Savannah and
across the river from Mulberry Grove. The wildlife service is
authorized by Congress to expand the refuge by more than 14,000
acres if the land can be acquired from willing sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife service's expansion plans include the ports
authority's 2,200 acres that encompass Mulberry Grove. Wildlife
service officials say that if the agency acquires the property, it
would be willing to sign a long-term lease with the foundation to
establish the historic park. The agency also would support the
establishment of a museum on the property to help tell the story of
the cotton gin and the reign of King Cotton and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah refuge manager Sam Drake and ports authority officials
have discussed the federal agency's acquiring the property from the
authority, but so far no agreement is near.
</P>
<P>
   The ports authority has said it would be willing to consider
swapping all or most of its 2,200 acres in exchange for about 500
acres of the refuge directly across the river from the state docks,
where the authority wants to dump spoil from dredging the shipping
channel.
</P>
<P>
   But the wildlife service says the spoil would smother a huge
swath of the refuge's freshwater marshes, which teem with wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, a Yale University graduate, didn't come to Savannah
with intentions of inventing a machine that would change the South.
He came to Georgia to tutor the children of a Savannah River
plantation owner near Mulberry Grove.
</P>
<P>
   When that job fell through, Mulberry Grove's mistress, Caty
Greene, who had become acquainted with Whitney, offered him a job
teaching her children. She was the widow of Revolutionary War hero
Gen. Nathanael Greene, whom George Washington placed in charge of
the Continental Army in the South.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Mulberry Grove, a rice plantation, was
confiscated by the government from its former owner because of his
loyalty to the British Crown during the war. The plantation,
including slaves, then was given to Gen. Greene by an appreciative
state of Georgia for his role in the Revolution. The general died
of a sunstroke in 1786.
</P>
<P>
   When Whitney arrived at the plantation some six years later, he
quickly impressed Caty Greene with his talent for fixing gadgets.
He perfected a frame for her embroidery and repaired her watch.
This delighted her, and she urged him to put his mind to inventing
the greatly needed cotton machine.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for a year on the project in an upstairs room of the
plantation house.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney became partners with Phineas Miller, Mulberry Grove's
overseer whom Caty later married. They formed the Miller and
Whitney Co. to market the cotton gin.
</P>
<P>
   The two business partners had to fight constantly to sustain
their patent, eventually becoming involved in 60 costly, drawn-out
lawsuits. Athough history credits Whitney as the inventor of the
cotton gin, neither he nor Miller derived any great financial
return from the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The Mulberry Grove Foundation's effort is only the latest of
several attempts to preserve the former plantation.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, for instance, the National Park Service
studied the possibility of making Mulberry Grove a national park
because of its historical importance.
</P>
<P>
   The plan never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable for current discussions on the property,
but Waters, the foundation's CEO, says this time there will be no
backing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of if we are going to preserve Mulberry
Grove, it's a question of when,'' he says. ``Mulberry Grove's place
in history is immense, and we can't give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
