<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PROCARE-PHARMACY0807-     08-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCARE-PHARMACY0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CVS offshoot ProCare doesn't fit ordinary drugstore mold
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wil Kinsey delivers more than prescriptions to
patients infected with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsey, who is African-American, delivers prayers, praise and
positive messages. For that, Kinsey has earned the name, ``Black
Moses.'' He does the deliveries voluntarily, even though it's not
part of his job description as billing specialist at the ProCare
Pharmacy in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If Kinsey's approach to his job is unusual, so is ProCare. It's
operated by CVS, the Woonsocket, R.I.-based conglomerate with 4,100
stores nationwide. But ProCare is not your typical chain drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   CVS started ProCare as a separate unit whose stores specialize
in high-priced drugs such as those needed by AIDS, hepatitis C,
cancer, multiple sclerosis, and bone marrow and organ transplant
patients. ProCare coordinates with Emory University Hospital to
stock prescription medicines needed by patients coming out of the
transplant unit.
</P>
<P>
   ProCare pharmacies carry drug quantities typically not stocked
by CVS stores. Sick people who need the drugs often must get them
through special order or by mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very different from the drugstore model,'' said Marie
Griffin, editor of Drug Store News, an industry publicatias a small
selection of supplies found in any drugstore. The local ProCare is
a gallery of sorts, with greeting cards and paintings by local
artists on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ProCare aims to serve consumers with chronic conditions in need
of complex and expensive drug therapies. Stores are staffed with
specialists who have in-depth knowledge of care programs and drug
interactions with other medicines and herbal remedies. They also
help figure out insurance coverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend a few thousand a month,'' Doxtater said.
``Transplant patients max out quickly. In a normal retail setting,
the pharmacists are not as concerned with that. We work with the
available benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   CVS expects strong growth and a healthy payoff from the ProCare
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This niche is growing faster than the overall pharmacy market
is,''said ProCare President Dennis Burton. ``The market is $14
billion nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The specialty pharmacy category, as it's called, accounts for
nearly 11 percent of prescription drug sales nationwide. Burton
predicts the market will blossom into a $20 billion market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you end up at ProCare, something's gone wrong with your
health,'' said Mark Miller, analyst with William Blair &AMP; Co. in
Chicago. ``They have pursued an integrated health care strategy
much more aggressively than their chief competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst David Magee, with Robinson Humphrey in Atlanta, said
both Walgreen's and Eckerd aren't as aggressive in this sector.
</P>
<P>
   Eckerd, for instance, is ``dealing with operation issues that
prevent them from having a real aggressive effort in the near
term,'' Magee said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ryan, chief executive officer of CVS, expects ProCare's
yearly revenue to be $2 billion to $3 billion in the next four
years from a total of 125 locations. That would equate to one-sixth
of CVS' 1999 sales of $18.1 billion. The company has 30 sites now
with plans for another 20 by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Some customers each) spend from $10,000 to $20,000 a year on
prescriptions,'' said Ryan during an earnings-related conference
call with analysts last week. ``ProCare sales are from $4 million
to $6 million a store.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, of Drug Store News, calls the sector the ``holy grail''
of the industry. Managed care companies are motivated to work with
ProCare because it saves them money to deal with one entity rather
than dozens of mail-order and independents, she said. Also, the
type of service at ProCare may encourage patients to stay on their
drug programs, reducing hospital costs.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta probably will get an ``additional two to three
ProCare locations,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   The company could gain another location through an acquisition.
ProCare plans to buy Stadtlanders, a mail-order pharmacy, for $124
million. When the transaction closes this fall, ProCare will gain
several mail-order distribution centers and a database of 50,000
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Stadtlanders has a metro Atlanta site, but it's unclear if that
location would be converted to a storefront.
</P>
<P>
   ProCare has expanded mostly by buying existing drugstores. An
example was its purchase last November of Atlanta Pharmacy, where
Doxtater was an owner. Doxtater stayed on as a pharmacist for
ProCare. Kinsey, the bookkeeper, continued to make volunteer
deliveries to patients who were unable to pick up their
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsey himself is infected with the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a survivor,'' said Kinsey, who has had the virus for 15
years. ``But I get out, and I forget that I'm HIV positive. I just
bought a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
