<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-INFOMERCIAL-CONVENTIO     08-06 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFOMERCIAL-CONVENTION0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Networks shy away from `infomercial' conventions
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They tried.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to come across as ``Republican Party Animals,'' in author
P.J. O'Rourke's phrase, the just-completed GOP convention offered
World Wrestling Federation star The Rock, a rollicking black gospel
choir, ``NYPD Blue's'' Rick Schroder, Comedy Central star Ben Stein
playing ``Win Ben Stein's Money'' with Miss America, and R&AMP;B
crooner Brian McKnight singing ``My body's callin' out your name''
while MTV-style dancers practiced pelvic thrusts behind him.
</P>
<P>
   But virtually none of that made it onto TV, except for C-SPAN.
The broadcast networks had cut convention coverage to its lowest
amount since they started in the convention business in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV is just following the audience. The parties need to make
things more interesting, less boring,'' Linda Schrenko, Georgia
state superintendent of schools, said last week on the floor of the
GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thursday night saw a surge of viewers watching George
W. Bush's acceptance speech, overall Nielsen ratings for the
convention were down last week, as expected. One example: On
Tuesday night, 10 million viewers watched ``Dateline NBC's'' report
on the ``Jerry Springer murder case.'' When NBC switched to Sen.
John McCain's convention speech at 10:30 p.m., more than half the
audience clicked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratings are not great, and it's hardly surprising, because
we have been telling people for days and days and days this is
boring, it's pre-scripted, it is pre-packaged, it is pre-chewed,''
said Howard Kurtz, host of CNN's media roundtable ``Reliable
Sources.''
</P>
<P>
   `A PERVERSE PROCESS'
</P>
<P>
   The political parties, largely acting out of a desire not to
look foolish on TV, have turned their conventions into carefully
choreographed spectacles, as rehearsed and scripted as any sitcom.
ABC, CBS and NBC, in turn, complain there is no news, and abandon
coverage. (CNN folks sometimes complain about the lack of news,
too, but know that the conventions are a place the all-news network
plants its flag, no matter what.)
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican Convention now finished for 2000 and the
Democrats still to come Aug. 14-17, the whole notion of a mass
American audience watching political conventions seems as quaint as
June Cleaver doing housework in hose and high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perverse process,'' said Jeffrey Scheuer, author of
``The Sound Bite Society.'' ``It's an amplified version of what
happens all the time between politics and television, where each is
trying to manage the other side to conform to its imperatives and
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The no-news conventions are due in part to the primary system,
which chooses a candidate earlier and earlier; the last convention
at which there was even a whisper of a doubt was the GOP in 1976,
when Ronald Reagan was challenging Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   COURSE ALTERATIONS RARE
</P>
<P>
   Still there have been times in recent memory when a convention
turned into its own rough, unruly animal, such as the media
freeding frenzy when George Bush picked Dan Quayle as his running
mate in 1988, or the GOP in 1992, when Pat Buchanan gave his
infamous _ and lengthy _ ``culture wars'' speech and pushed former
President Ronald Reagan out of prime time. There were heated
platform debates over issues such as abortion, and political
posturing, such as Democratic efforts to accommodate Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   That's all in the past tense now, as carefully screened
``regular people,'' as ethnically diverse as a UNICEF stamp, speak
perfectly on message and stay on time like Mussolini's trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are party infomercials, attempting to sell a
candidate,'' said CNN political analyst Bill Schneider. One of the
main Republican sales tools was steering away from congressional
Republicans, whom the Bush campaign felt would clash with the idea
of ``a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always some grumbling about lack of news in the sense
of conflict, sparks. We love that stuff,'' says Brit Hume, the
former ABC correspondent who's now chief anchor for cable's Fox
News Channel. ``But the networks are being disingenuous about why
they're not covering the conventions. There are powerful economic
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: When NBC blew off Gen. Colin Powell's speech
Monday night for a rerun of ``Third Watch,'' it attracted more than
10 million viewers. When NBC ran Dick Cheney's acceptance speech
Wednesday night, only 5 million watched.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN BUCKS TREND
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to change the steps in the reluctant dance
between conventions and convention coverage? There are two
competing ideas: toward more entertainment, or toward more news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually these conventions will evolve into something more
appropriate to television, which is basically glitzy variety shows,
like 'The Kennedy Center Honors' with a political twist: novelty
acts, comedy,'' said political analyst Jeffrey Scheuer. ``They've
already ceased to have any political function.''
</P>
<P>
   You could see some of this trend this past week. If you were
watching C-SPAN, that is. CNN and PBS, still dauntless in the
extent and seriousness of their coverage, pretty much ignored the
entertainment interludes the GOP provided, such as Stein and
Schroder, to connect with an audience that views the world through
a totally televisual context.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be even more of the same when the Democrats gather
in Los Angeles. A ``celebrity delegation'' including Ben Affleck,
Ted Danson and Patricia Arquette will attend the convention, and an
off-site fund-raiser Aug. 17 is scheduled to include Barbra
Streisand, Enrique Iglesias and Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   SEEK TO PROMOTE CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   At a roundtable in Philadelphia sponsored by Harvard
University's Vanishing Voters Project, Edward G. Rendell, chairman
of the Democratic National Committee, had a different remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The networks should commit to four hours of coverage a night, he
suggested, but insist that one hour each night be devoted to a
specific controversial topic, with both sides represented. The
result, he hoped, would have conflict, drama and enlightenment.
Historian Doris Kearns Goodwin, part of PBS' coverage team,
suggested more or less the same idea last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, raise the level,'' Rendell said. ``You're the
networks. You can do this.'' Of course, CNN and PBS already offer
such point-counterpoint debates within their coverage, although
never for a full hour on one issue.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News president Andrew Heyward, without endorsing Rendell's
proposal, agreed that ``conflict is educational and I think it
should be encouraged, not for entertainment value, but because it
does help illuminate things.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are party voices who favor letting the conventions
return to a messier format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unpredictability is good,'' said Chuck Clay, chairman of the
Georgia Republican Party. ``We should be less afraid of letting
people say what we don't know they're about to say. It shows the
diversity of our party and lends an air of excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   But any reform of the dysfunctional dance between the broadcast
networks and the parties must fight the reality that both sides
have extremely strong (and, possibly, mutually exclusive) reasons
for leading us to the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks have a serious economic problem,'' said Fox's
Hume. ``(The cable news channels) just need to get the news
junkies. If (ABC, CBS and NBC) only get the news junkies, they lose
money terribly.''
</P>
<P>
   And the political parties ``don't care how many people watch,''
said CNN's Howard Kurtz. ``They care about the images that linger,
that people carry in their heads, the headlines in the paper. They
want to make a nice impression. They are not necessarily in the
ratings game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
