<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0807-COX     08-06 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miracle matches in two organ-donor dramas
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ To have and to hold, in sickness and in health,
Mike and Carol Bracken consummated their marriage in the most
unheard-of way.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that Adam's rib stuff is farfetched, consider: Mike
now has Carol's kidney keeping him alive.
</P>
<P>
   So much for what sour-on-marriage sorts call the old
ball-and-chain. Mike finding Carol, and Carol finding out she was a
tissue match, freed him from a lifetime of misery and dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   One miracle down, countless more to do.
</P>
<P>
   Make that two down. You decide which is more miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   The other one happened between complete strangers, but not by
chance. Tom Warnock was frustrated when he couldn't donate a kidney
to help his buddy, Army Sgt. John Pierce. Tom's wife Valarie,
though she didn't know Pierce, offered a hand. She ended up giving
a kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Generally the rule is that the only person from whom one might
hope to get a kidney is from a corpse or a blood relative. Here are
two exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Miracles like these are becoming less miraculous thanks to
people like Carol and Valarie, and because of medical advances.
Mainly, it helps significantly when the donor is alive and in an
adjacent room.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving from a live donor means almost no inert time for the
kidney compared to an organ that will be on ice for hours.
Seventy-two hours is just about the limit.
</P>
<P>
   So in these two cases, the offerings of Carol and Valarie were
not only customer matches, they were the best merchandise on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   For the Brackens, the transplant June 7 was the end of a
roller-coaster ride. Mike, 57, who runs Waco's Central City Car
Care Center, had been on dialysis for two years. He married Carol,
a widow, last December.
</P>
<P>
   When the ordeal on an organ waiting list became hers by
marriage, she broached the subject of getting her blood tested to
see if she could donate to him. He said no.
</P>
<P>
   She went ahead and did it without telling him.
</P>
<P>
   The unbelievable news that they matched was met with more
resistance from the worried husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I can't accept it,'' he told her. ``I didn't marry you to
hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she convinced him that his welfare was her own.
</P>
<P>
   So, euphoric at the prospects, the couple traveled to San
Antonio in May only to be told that a last-second test of her
antibodies suddenly put the operation on ice. ``You're not a match
any longer,'' they heard.
</P>
<P>
   They returned home crushed. Three days later, with results from
one more test, doctors said, ``It's a go.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery went great. The kidney, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't any time until that sucker was active,'' said Mike,
who knew his bride's gift was giving when he saw his catheter bag
sitting empty.
</P>
<P>
   As for Valarie Warnock and Sgt. Pierce, they knew of each other
indirectly and may have met before briefly, but their first real
meeting was to strike up a relationship of prospective donor and
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, a 34-year-old paratrooper, was injured in a tree landing
while making a jump in combat maneuvers in Panama in 1990.
Subsequent health problems, including a bout of double pneumonia,
caused kidney failure. In 1995 he went on dialysis and onto the
kidney waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   He and Tom Warnock, who works with outpatients at the Veterans
Affairs Medical Center, are good friends. Warnock got tested to see
if he could donate a kidney, but didn't match. When wife Valarie
heard of the situation she knew she was called to help this man, or
someone like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if my kidney isn't for John Pierce it's for somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The kidney was for Pierce. The surgery was done June 16 in
Nashville at a VA hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``A total act of love'' is how Pierce describes it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Valarie shed a kidney, she had to give up 25
pounds, a precaution against late-onset diabetes. Oh, yes. She's a
mother of six. In sum, it was some sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awesome opportunity'' is what she calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Both donors remarked that the procedure, using small
laparoscopic incisions, was amazingly less intrusive than feared.
And both women were on their feet almost immediately, with little
lasting discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Both donors now are ardent advocates of people getting a blood
test for a donor match.
</P>
<P>
   They know of all the kidney patients spending several hours
every week hooked to a machine, waiting for a donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the dialysis patients it just really broke my
heart,'' said Valarie, who doesn't think herself nearly as heroic
as the man who got her kidney, or the people hooked to those
machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just go,'' she said. ``Go get tested.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
