<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRPORT-SMOKING0807-C     08-06 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SMOKING0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smokers light up when they find a bar
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hartsfield is bucking the anti-smoking trend sweeping
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles banned smoking in bars in 1998 and, nationwide,
tobacco companies are settling lawsuits brought by the states for
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But a bar caters to smokers on Concourse A. The Budweiser
Brewhouse has been a successful draw since it opened July 10,
according to managers.
</P>
<P>
   A floor above the gates, the Brewhouse avoids contact with
nonsmokers in the general foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised it was here,'' smoker Ellen Fiorenza said.
``It's actually a pleasant atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiorenza and her husband, Lou Fiorenza, came to Hartsfield to
meet some business acquaintances last week and discovered the
Brewhouse as they came up the escalators from the underground train
station.
</P>
<P>
   They saw the signs to the smoking bar and took a chance that
they could get a cup of coffee instead of a brew at 10 a.m. They
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much nicer than that confined (public) smoking lounge
down the concourse,'' said Lou Fiorenza, who is not a smoker.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield has public smoking lounges on Concourses A, B, C and
E. Two other bars allow smoking: Images Bar &AMP; Grill on E and
Sojourners Lounge, which is the only smoking refuge on Concourse D.
There's not enough room on D for a public smoking lounge, airport
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield had been considering adding a smoking bar for several
years and finally asked joint venture operator Concessions/Paschals
International to create the bar. The bar just leases Budweiser's
name, but the brewery also provided the interior design, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was customer demand and, yes, it's a cash cow,'' said
Denise Kevil of Concessions/Paschals. ``All the smoking lounges
were full all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Open only several weeks, the 56-table bar operates at 45 percent
capacity, said Schree Potts-Ramsey, who manages the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Potts-Ramsey, who managed a restaurant and lounge in Atlanta,
said she had to get used to the ``push'' times at the airport.
Pushes occur several times a day as airline schedules hit peak
periods, then ebb before another push comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 10 minutes with customers,'' Potts-Ramsey said. ``So
customer service starts as soon as they come through the door. They
can get a sandwich, a cold drink and smoke, and all the time
someone is looking after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeat business should also be a strong point. ``We've noticed
people for the second time in just the few weeks we've been open,''
Potts-Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   There's another source for repeat business. Managers have
noticed that they would serve a customer and then an hour or so
later they would be back because of flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GOPCONVENTI     08-06 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GOPCONVENTION0807-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY
 &HT;    Compassionate rhetoric contradicts GOP record
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The George W. Bush of Bob Jones University seemed light years
away from the Bush who brought an upbeat GOP convention to its
climax last week. The Texas governor delivered a well-scripted
speech with conviction and optimism. Except for his pledge of
support for the social agenda of the right and the promise of a
fairy-tale tax cut, Bush stuck to a mainstream agenda of saving
Medicare and Social Security and improving education.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it lasts or not, Bush should be commended for setting a
positive tone and avoiding the harsh partisan attacks of recent GOP
conventions. Philadelphia was not a Republican convention, though _
it was a Bush convention.
</P>
<P>
   And it is that difference that portends the greatest problems
for Bush in the coming months. He will be pressed to explain how
his moderate optimism jibes with the negativism and extremism the
GOP Congress has exhibited on issues like the environment and
health care. He must speak to his differences with the party
platform. He must explain the conflicts between his rhetoric and
his record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The most frequently repeated line at the convention was that no
child will be left behind. Though Bush extolled Head Start, his
vice presidential choice, Dick Cheney, voted against the federal
early education program when he was in Congress. And Bush's pledge
to improve education for poor children is contradicted by a party
platform that rips into the federal program that gives schools
extra money for disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, some children in Texas have been left behind. The
state's child poverty rate stands at 24.2 percent, compared with
20.4 percent nationally. While Bush says all American families and
their children must have access to health care, his administration
opposed matching state dollars for the federal Children's Health
Insurance Program and funds to get more poor families enrolled in
Medicaid health insurance. Today, 600,000 of the state's poorest
children are without guaranteed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received wild applause, especially from the Teenage
Republicans, when he mentioned protecting American's natural
resources. But his spokesmen promised Western state delegates in
Philadelphia that Bush would work to reverse the Clinton
administration's support for saving 43 million acres of dwindling
roadless areas in the national forests. Bush has already promised
to support GOP leaders in Congress who want to open up the National
Arctic Wildlife Refuge to oil drilling.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, emphasized the importance of providing
a safe, nurturing environment for children. But there was no
mention of keeping children and communities safe from guns. Even
the pleas of parents haven't budged Bush from his loyalty to the
National Rifle Association. He signed into law a bill to protect
Texas gun manufacturers from lawsuits by cities and one that allows
people to carry concealed handguns into public places, such as
movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities and women were given leading speaking roles at the
GOP convention, which conveyed an encouraging big-tent message, at
least on stage. But the delegates, the vast majority of them white,
mostly suburban and affluent, will have to reach outside their
traditional communities if the party is to evolve into a more
diverse one.
</P>
<P>
   Only as Bush addresses some of these inconsistencies will the
American people know whether Philly was anchored in the Republican
candidate's true principles or just part of his paid packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
