<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ROMANCE-NOVELIST0807-     08-06 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANCE-NOVELIST0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All about Eva
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Back when Atlanta-born romance novelist Eva Rutland
used a typewriter, she'd sometimes discover that it had run out of
paper. It wasn't that her concentration was so rapt _ or that her
story was so steamy.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Rutland is blind.
</P>
<P>
   She may not be a household name like Barbara Cartland. But this
83-year-old Spelman College graduate and granddaughter of a former
slave is one of the most prolific romantic authors working today.
On Saturday, she came home to pick up a Gold Pen Lifetime
Achievement Award at the African American Online Writers Guild's
first Black Writers Reunion &AMP; Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rutland, who writes with a voice synthesizer on her computer but
isn't on the Internet, has penned 23 books, including more than a
dozen Harlequin Romances and this year's semi-autobiographical
mainstream novel, ``No Crystal Stair'' (Mira, $5.99). That book _
about a strong-willed woman who grows up in the cloistered world of
Atlanta's black aristocracy, only to watch the old order swept away
by the Civil Rights movement _ is a kind of 20th century black
woman's ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the organization that gave the award, Rutland's
greatest contribution was to integrate the publishing world at a
time when black women writers were virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about being a writer until after my children
were born,'' says the Sacramento, Calif., grandmother of six.
``Then I began to be concerned about racial prejudice, and I
thought if black mothers and white mothers could talk together,
just like we are talking now, then they would understand that we
all have the same problems. So I began to write articles and send
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise _ this was the '50s and '60s _ Redbook, Woman's
Day and Ladies' Home Journal published them. Her only non-fiction
book, ``The Trouble With Being a Mama: A Negro Mother on the
Anxieties and Joys of Bringing Up a Family,'' appeared in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '80s, she began writing ``sweet romances.'' At last
count, her books have been distributed in 29 countries. Ironically,
most of her characters are white. She once considered making a
central character black, but a friend told her not to tamper with
success.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the author of ``Her Own Prince Charming'' and ``No
Accounting for Love'' has just traveled 3,000 miles across the
country in an airplane. But she politely sits for a two-hour
interview in the cafe of the Ramada Inn where she's staying.
Nibbling chicken fingers and fries and sipping a glass of white
Zinfandel, Rutland says her daughter Patty-Jo, who traveled with
her, is unhappy with the plain navy shirt dress her mom has chosen.
A former debutante who was once considered one of Atlanta's most
beautiful women, Rutland looks a good 20 years younger than she is.
</P>
<P>
   Talking with this octogenarian is like reading a chapter on
Atlanta's pre-Civil Rights era. Her first story was published by
the Atlanta Daily World when she was about 12. Four years after
Emancipation, her maternal grandfather, Isaac Westmoreland, built
the house in which she was born near what is now Turner Field. ``We
had a very big yard, so everybody played in our yard _ black,
white, Jewish and Gentile.''
</P>
<P>
   The family was one of the few to have its own pew at First
Congregational Church, where a massive stained glass in her
grandfather's memory remains. At Booker T. Washington High School,
Rutland appeared in theatrical productions with actress Lena Horne
_ and she used to hobnob with Josephine Dobbs, daughter of civic
leader John Wesley Dobbs.
</P>
<P>
   And yet as happy as her childhood was, segregation left its
mark.
</P>
<P>
   While in her '20s, a white surgeon working in a private black
clinic damaged her vocal chords while removing her thyroid gland.
``I didn't realize that he was as trapped by segregation as I was.
It may have been because he didn't have the facilities and he
didn't have his regular staff. But he cut my vocal chords and they
were so close together that I wasn't getting much air.'' When she
returned for treatment, she says, he kicked her out of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when she speaks, she must push her gold ``E'' initial
pendant aside to put a finger over the hole in her throat _ a
tracheotomy tube. She believes her blindness, which occurred 30
years ago and was caused by macular deterioration, may be a result
of medication she took for her thyroid condition. Her voice is
raspy, her eyes glassy, and she laughs in little hiccups. Yet she
is a picture of courage, perseverance and good humor.
</P>
<P>
   She has never let her own troubles darken her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the boy meets girl (formula),`` she says. ``They have a
few problems and live happily every after. I love those simple
stories. That's because I like to laugh. I don't want to read about
the tragedies and what they did to us a long time ago and how
deprived we are. I like upbeat stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women would be so much happier, the world would be a
much better place, if men read more romances,'' the author says.
Her favorite novel is Jane Austen's ``Pride and Prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many novelists, she says, ``I don't do the explicit sex.
Some writers do it very very well. If you want to know how to make
love, read some of those romances. I find them boring because the
sex interrupts the story, and they are so repetitive. How many ways
can you make love? They've done them all, so I've read them all.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a momentary pause, a tiny wheeze. ``If I had read those
things when I was younger, I'd have been a much better wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
