   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS (Bazra-Nattis, Ivory Coast) _ How AIDS has deepened
the weaknesses of already troubled educational systems in Ivory
Coast and other African nations. 1,600 words. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-EVOCATIVE-SIGNS (Mexico City) _ The literary masterpiece
that is the street map of one of the world's largest metropolises.
1,100 words. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KARADZIC (Sarajevo) _ The high, forested mountains of
southeastern Bosnia are a place to hide, and, according to the
current local lore, that is exactly what Radovan Karadzic, the man
widely regarded as most culpable for the 1992-95 war in Bosnia, is
doing there. 1,600 words. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran) _ Iranian hardliners and reformists
scuffled in Parliament Sunday after the country's supreme leader
canceled debate over amending a restrictive press law. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-RIGHTS (Cairo) _ Egyptian prosecutors have charged an
Egyptian rights activist who carried an American passport with
having contacts with American intelligence services, a crime
potentially punishable by up to 25 years of hard labor. 500 words.
By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-DONKEY-WAR (Qalqilya, West Bank) _ There were no
casualties in the ``Donkey War'', as one of the Israelis ruefully
called it when the dispute with the Palestinians was over. No
casualties, that is, apart from two mangey donkeys, which ended up
being pulled away from an Israeli animal rescue specialist to be
slaughtered for animal food at Qalqilya's Palestinian-controlled
zoo. The jurisdictional dispute in this mainly Palestinian town
about 20 miles northeast of Tel Aviv told its own story about the
anger that can still flare between Jews and Arabs, Israelis and
Palestinians, as their leaders attempt to negotiate a comprehensive
peace deal to end decades of estrangement and war. Resentments
accumulated over a century and more can invest the least of
disputes, even when the issue involves one of God's humblest
creatures. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CHILDMOLEST (London) _ Britain said on Sunday that it
would ``urgently'' press for stricter laws on child molesting but
resisted widespread calls for public identification of released
violators that have been associated with current vigilante attacks
across the country. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SEMINARY (Heybeliada, Turkey) _ Despite the pleadings of
Orthodox leaders and international allies, Turkish authorities
insist that one of the most historic and important seminaries in
Orthodox Christianity remain closed under a law that gives the
government control over higher education in religious and military
affairs. 800 words. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-RETARDED (Livingston, Texas) _ Oliver Cruz, who was
convicted for capital murder, has spent 11 years on death row here,
and the state of Texas has set his execution for Wednesday, Aug. 9,
at 6 p.m. His execution is scheduled at a time when there is
growing opposition across the country to executing the mentally
retarded. While no one knows how many of the more than 2,000 death
row inmates across the country are mentally retarded, experts say
it could be as high as 10 percent. 2100 words. By Raymond Bonner
and Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   STATUE-SMUGGLERS (San Antonio, Texas) _ A series of thefts of
historic statues from the famous missions of San Antonio is
stirring fears that smugglers are carting away legendary Texas
treasures. 800 words.
</P>
