<P>
   &UR; CULTURE/ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``Magic Terror: 7 Tales,'' by Peter Straub (Random House).
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH-GORE-ESSAY (Undated) _ Margo Jefferson imagines a
Gore-Winfrey ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ART-COLONY-CLOSE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Three years ago, an
experiment in artistic democracy began. And last week it ended. The
Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, a heady mix of summer
camp, artists' colony, encounter group and think tank founded and
directed by the playwright and actor Anna Deavere Smith, closed its
doors on Friday _ at least for the foreseeable future. By Sarah
Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   CLIBURN-MUSIC-REVIEW (Lenox, Mass.) _ James R. Oestreich reviews
Van Cliburn at Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   SANTAFE-OPERA (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ Allan Kozinn on the Santa Fe
Opera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-TALKS (Undated) _ Developments in the contract dispute
between union telephone workers and Verizon Communications. Workers
walked off the job Sunday, replaced by managers, but negotiators
were continuing to talk. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   BARNESANDNOBLE.COM (Undated) _ In the last month, all eyes have
been focused on Amazon.com and its possibly tenuous finances. But
what are the prospects at BarnesandNoble.com? By David D.
Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-TV (Washington) _ When the Federal Communications
Commission started the transition to digital television, Reed
Hundt, the chairman, predicted that it could change the lives of
every American. But now, four years later, many Americans have yet
to grasp digital TV. And the transition is so mired in intractable
problems, squabbles and controversies that some industry executives
now worry that the current plan for the digital rollout could fail.
By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CAMBODIA (Tokyo) _ Bernie Krisher, a retired American
journalist, is helping to wire a Cambodian village for Internet
access, in what he hopes could be a model project for bridging the
so-called digital divide. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALIST-CONFLICT (London) _ Hugo Dixon is the pre-eminent
British financial journalist who gained huge clout by writing the
daily column called ``Lex'' on the back page of The Financial
Times. He made big news when he left the FT to do his own Web site
last October, and he's making big news again by drawing an
investment from Dow Jones and allowing his column to run in the
Wall Street Journal's Europe edition, the FT's archrival. By Andrew
Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   DOMAIN-NAME-DISPUTE (Undated) _ While there have been plenty of
dust-ups over domain names, one now going on may may be the first
to involve two prominent investors who manage billions of dollars.
By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECONOMY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Even as politicians in Washington
are opposing Deutsche Telekom's effort to acquire the wireless
company VoiceStream, the U.S. trade representative is bearing down
on Mexico to give American telecommunications companies a better
break. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ A Web service that distributes press
releases on the cheap; and the rapper Ice-T sounds off, with humor,
on the debate over online distribution of music. By Staff.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Technology vendors see big-money
opportunities in trying to provide the wares and services that will
bring the federal government into the e-commerce era. But getting
the bureaucracies to move at Internet time could take some doing.
By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column, this week on
e-mail. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIA-BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDIANEWS-DOT-ORG (Undated) _ Jim Romenesko, a man much noticed
in his own profession because he notices it back, has begun to
reach out far beyond his humble beginnings. His MediaNews.org Web
site is becoming an online version of the local bar, where
journalists go after hours to argue, to announce their new jobs, to
toast their friends and denounce their enemies. Most recently, it
has put Mike Barnicle back in the news. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-FUTURE-MEDIA (Undated) _ Is the future of news based on
personalized video? A visit to a new ``feedroom,'' which licenses
news segments from the networks and elsewhere. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ How the media handled the sexual
orientation of Dick Cheney's daughter; Julie Chen, the CBS
correspondent who is anchoring the ``Big Brother''show, argues with
her scriptwriters; and other news items from the media world. By
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Each September, many magazines
publish what are their largest issues, fattened by advertisements
for new car models and clothes as well as promotions pegged to the
coming school year and football season. The more ad pages that
appear, the more advertisers strive to be heard above the din. The
result: an increase in nontraditional print ads that fold out, up
or down; come with Post-It Notes or perforations; and require
special devices like 3-D glasses or bar code scanners. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
