A4078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MAGAZINES-AD-COLUMN-N     08-06 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINES-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SELLING BY STUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reverse-bound pullout and a standalone sound like stunts that
gymnasts will attempt next month as they compete for medals at the
Summer Games. Well, those stunts are planned for September, but
look for them from magazine publishers in America rather than
Olympic athletes in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Each September, many magazines publish what are their largest
issues, fattened by advertisements for new car models and clothes
as well as promotions pegged to the coming school year and football
season. The more ad pages that appear, the more advertisers strive
to be heard above the din. The result: an increase in
nontraditional print ads that fold out, up or down; come with
Post-It Notes or perforations; and require special devices like 3-D
glasses or bar code scanners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clutter begets clutter,'' said Charlie Rutman, executive vice
president and managing director at Carat USA in New York, a media
agency owned by the Aegis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people who want to win the game, there are two ways to
do it,'' Rutman asserted. ``Either spend more, and create even more
clutter, or try and be innovative, unusual, impactful, which gets
you beyond the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Two large magazines based in New York _ In Style, part of the
Time Inc. unit of Time Warner, and Glamour, part of the Conde Nast
Publications unit of Advance Publications _ are taking new steps to
help advertisers catch the attention of readers.
</P>
<P>
   In Style will include in its September issue, due out on Aug.
25, a mini-magazine dubbed a reverse-bound pullout because it will
be bound inside the back cover and can be detached to be read
separately. The pullout will be composed of 18 editorial pages and
18 ad pages; the September issue is to run 704 pages, including
about 435 ad pages.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones New York clothing line will solely sponsor the
pullout, titled the In Style Going Out Guide.
</P>
<P>
   And Glamour will publish on Aug. 15 its first standalone issue,
which will be sponsored by three advertisers: Revlon, the Sara Lee
Corp. and the Zale Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-page special issue, expanding a popular monthly Glamour
feature known as ``Dos and Don'ts,'' will be sold separately from
the regular September issue, at a cover price of $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for the pullout was ``word from our readers, and
advertisers, that people are tearing pages of the magazine out and
shopping from them,'' said Louis Cona, publisher of In Style.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was on an airplane in the spring flying back from
Milan, I saw a pullout in Wallpaper,'' he added, referring to a
youthful home and lifestyle magazine published in Britain by the
Time Life Entertainment Group unit of Time Warner, which devoted
its reverse-bound mini-magazine to remodeling bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Cona said he believed that such a supplement ``had never been
done in the U.S. before, but there is a big demand for being
unique, for standing out.''
</P>
<P>
   At Revlon, Cheryl Vitali, executive vice president for Revlon
global marketing in New York, said: ``We evaluate many, many
opportunities and pass on a lot of them. We were intrigued by this
one because it's a smart idea and we hope we'll get to benefit from
that. We like the content; it has value, versus something that's a
throwaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both Glamour and In Style placed their projects under
the supervision of the editorial departments rather than the
advertising departments. That means the contents are composed of
articles, not so-called ``advertorial'' copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been big on advertorials; we've probably done just
two or three,'' Cona said, adding: ``I think they confuse the
reader. Advertisers should take advantage of the power of the
editorial.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the motivation for Jones New York to participate, said
Benny Lin, senior vice president and creative director at the
parent, the Jones Apparel Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones is ``always open to new ideas to set us apart and
raise our brand awareness, we're very selective,'' Lin said. ``The
magazines we partner with need to have good integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cona told Rutman at Carat USA about the supplement, Rutman
recommended it to Lin, who approved it. The sponsorship cost an
estimated $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The three advertisers for the Glamour ``Dos and Don'ts'' issue
are paying a sum estimated at just more than $1 million for their
sponsorships. Besides their ad pages, they will also sponsor a
consumer sweepstakes, a fund-raiser for Goodwill Industries and a
clothing drive, ``Donate Your Don'ts,'' at offices of ad agencies,
Conde Nast, Revlon and Sara Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast will print 600,000 copies of the special Glamour,
compared with a circulation of 2.1 million for a regular September
issue. In Style is printing about 2.3 million copies of its
September issue into which the pullout will be reverse-bound. Jones
New York will distribute additional copies of the pullout to
retailers to give to shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In Style is already planning a second reverse-bound pullout,
Cona said, to appear in the fall; a retailer will be the likely
sponsor, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Fine, publisher of Glamour, said she anticipated
bringing out two standalone ``Dos and Don'ts'' issues in 2001,
increasing that to four a year ``eventually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
