<HEADER>
A4091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-ERMIONE-HNS &LR;      08-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-ERMIONE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SANTA FE OPERA'S `ERMIONE' IS A VOCAL FEAST (Photos available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm.) &HT;    By CHARLES WARD
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The first Santa Fe Opera production of
Gioacchino Rossini's ``Ermione'' may surprise opera fans who know
only his comedies, ``The Barber of Seville'' and ``Cenerentola''
(Cinderella).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ermione'' is a tragedy with a story by the ancient Greek
Euripides via 17th-century French playwright Jean Racine. It offers
a dazzling score _ with three important tenor roles, no less. The
music is unmistakably Rossinian in rhythm and energy, yet
consistently imaginative and engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, the score provoked some equally dazzling
performances led by Bulgarian soprano Alexandrina Pendatchanska as
the title character.
</P>
<P>
   Premiered in Naples in 1819, ``Ermione'' was particularly dear
to Rossini. When Neopolitan audiences responded coolly, he withdrew
it. ``Ermione'' wasn't heard again until 1987, when the Rossini
Opera Festival in Pesaro, Italy, revived it with the great
Monterserrat Caballe in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is Epirus, an ally of Greece, after the 10-year
Trojan War. Pirro (the Italian form of Pyrrhus) holds Andromaca,
widow of the Trojan hero Hector, and her young son Astianatte.
</P>
<P>
   Though engaged to the Greek princess Ermione, Pirro loves
Andromaca. She resists, in honor of her dead husband. He uses every
machination to change her mind _ including threatening to kill
Astianatte (a mute role).
</P>
<P>
   The Greeks would love that, for they are terrified that Hector's
son could grow up to lead a new war. So they send Oreste to Epirus
to demand the boy's execution. Defiantly, Pirro declares he will
marry Andromaca and make Astianatte his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Fatally for Pirro, Oreste loves Ermione. Enraged by Pirro's
passion for Andromaca, Ermione cons Oreste into killing Pirro at
the wedding. When Oreste returns to claim her hand, she sends him
packing, blaming her behavior on her mad love for Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   End of opera.
</P>
<P>
   That final betrayal is typical of ``Ermione.'' In today's terms,
the characters are like politicians with the emotions of American
high-schoolers. When they aren't turning on their allies, they're
either madly in love or about to die _ usually because of cruel
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Immature as these emotions might seem today, they inspired
Rossini to write arias for each of the four protagonists, four
duets and several large ensembles. His music expresses emotions
from deep pathos to grand hyperbole, always couched in challenging
virtuosity, including coloratura fireworks spanning two octaves.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the musical peak occurred in a duet early in Act 2.
Pirro celebrates Andromaca's decision to marry while she vows to
commit suicide as soon as she has secured the safety of her son.
Tenor Gregory Kunde and mezzo-soprano Sara Mingardo were on fire
musically. Their emotions were intense, and the unity of their duet
singing was outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   But neither matched Pendatchanska, who got the canary-fanciers
(vocal fans) talking. Ermione's manic changes of mood were fuel for
this scene-eating dramatic soprano. She raged and ranted
emotionally. Vocally, she ran through the runs and leaps with a
celebratory display. The part was a dream for a singer with a
distinctive stage persona and a fascinating voice of dark, cutting
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Kunde, Barry Banks (Oreste) and Charles Castronovo (as Pilade,
the aide of Oreste) were as good a trio of tenors as could be
assembled today. Currently, the opera world has very few fine
Rossini tenors _ light, agile voices that can throw off high notes
effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Banks was the most daring, even and intense of the three. Kunde
was less consistent in his upper range; otherwise he had a
commanding, almost arrogant presence. Castronovo was sturdy in a
modest part, principally a duet with baritone Michael Krueger (as
Fenicio, an advisor of Pirro's).
</P>
<P>
   Mingardo, an Italian making her American debut, sang with the
dusky intensity of a superior contralto. At times her stage manner
was too impassive; indeed, she was almost implacable when Pirro
announced he would kill her son if she didn't give in to his
marriage proposal. But her fine singing and strong technique
overshadowed that weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The production was split-minded.
</P>
<P>
   Isabella Bywater's set was effective: a simple V-shaped unit
with a break where the two walls met.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jonathan Miller decided to have Bywater dress the cast
in 19th-century uniforms that were vaguely American and Italian.
The choice made no sense; fortunately, it was not a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Italian conductor Evelino Pido led tidily.
</P>
<P>
   In a delight for keen listeners, Pido burnished the range of
colors in Rossini's orchestration, which are far more vivid than
in, say, ``The Barber of Seville.'' But he and the orchestra always
supplied the rhythmic energy that is the defining element of
Rossini's operatic style.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
