<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-ELEKTRA-HNS &LR;      08-06 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-ELEKTRA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
`Elektra' an electrifying close for Sante Fe's Crosby &HT;    Editor's note: The first ``a'' in Klytemnastra takes an umlaut.
(Photos available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm.)
 &HT;    By CHARLES WARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ Fittingly, the founder of Santa Fe Opera is
ending his 44 years as its general director with the best
production of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   With Mary Jane Johnson in the synapse-crossed title role,
Richard Strauss' ``Elektra'' was a riveting story of rotting
personalities at Friday's performance.
</P>
<P>
   In establishing Santa Fe Opera as the country's premiere summer
opera festival, director John Crosby made the operas of Strauss one
of its signatures. Many of the composer's lesser-known works are
staged elsewhere today because of Crosby's advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, his typically understated conducting, which can let
music drift, was perfect for ``Elektra,'' whose musical
characterization of sick people can overwhelm the listener. The
orchestra propelled the drama and painted personalities deftly
rather than bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   Like two other works in Santa Fe's repertoire this season _ Hans
Werner Henze's ``Venus and Adonis'' and Rossini's ``Ermione'' _ the
story of ``Elektra'' comes from ancient Greek history and
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Elektra was the daughter of Agamemnon (whose brother, Menelaus,
married Helen). While Agamemnon was away fighting the 10-year
Trojan War, his wife, Klytemnastra, took up with Aegisth.
</P>
<P>
   When Agamemnon returned home after the war, Klytemnastra
murdered him. Their children _ Elektra, Chrysothemis and Orest _
pledged to kill their mother in revenge.
</P>
<P>
   In the opera, with libretto by Hugo von Hofmannsthal after
Sophocles, Elektra's obsession has turned her half mad. She swears
she will dance triumphantly over the bodies of her father's
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysothemis is a coward. When Elektra tries to enlist her aid,
she shies away, saying she only wants to live in peace as a wife
and mother. Elektra is left to plot the revenge by herself and dig
up the ax she has hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Klytemnastra is so wracked with guilt she either can't sleep or
is consumed by terrifying dreams. She makes endless animal
sacrifices to the gods without relief. She is initially pleased
when Elektra offers advice about the right sacrifice _ but becomes
terrified when the daughter roars out that it should be
Klytemnastra herself.
</P>
<P>
   Word that Orest is dead changes Klytemnastra's mood to joy _ but
that is a ruse. He has snuck into the palace and, after revealing
himself to Elektra, goes off to get revenge.
</P>
<P>
   As Klytemnastra's screams echo from the palace, Elektra is
exultant but, in her frenzy, she dances herself to death,
collapsing lifeless as the opera ends.
</P>
<P>
   A native of the Texas Panhandle, Johnson brought a steely-toned
magnetism to Elektra: on the edge of madness, yet cunning and
consumed. She sang powerfully over the large orchestra as it
vacillated _ like Strauss' artistic temperament _ between the rage
of dissonance and the calm of tonality.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Judith Forst, as Klytemnastra, provided the searing visual
symbol of the production staged by John Copley. She was a
semi-invalid needing hand-held crutches with wrist braces to
balance herself. This pitiful physical condition matched her
tenuous mental state _ and Elektra was quick to take advantage of
both.
</P>
<P>
   In the single most chilling moment of the opera, as the two
women fenced verbally, Elektra finally snatched both of the
crutches away, causing Klytemnastra to topple.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when the mother heard the purported news of Orest's death,
she thought she had triumphed once more and someone found the will
to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Forst's portrayal was mesmerizing vocally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano Susan B. Anthony had childlike longing for normalcy as
Chrysothemis. Bass-baritone Greer Gimsley, an early member of
Houston Opera Studio, brought rich-voiced, single-minded intensity
to Orest.
</P>
<P>
   Tenor Ragnar Ulfung was the besotted Aegisth, who makes a brief
appearance at the end before going off to his death as well.
</P>
<P>
   The new production, designed by Bruno Schwengl, was utilitarian
and stark.
</P>
<P>
   A huge angled wall to the audience's was dominated by
double-doors reached by stairs parallel to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of a former large statue of a man littered the stage.
Presumably the subject was Agamemnon, the way Elektra kept running
to the reclining head.
</P>
<P>
   Copley's direction was sensible for an opera with a lot of
singing and not much action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elektra'' plays again Wednesday and Aug. 17 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
