<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BARNESANDNOBLE.COM-AR     08-06 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNESANDNOBLE.COM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNESANDNOBLE.COM STAKES TURF DESPITE BLOODIED STOCK AND LOSSES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen Riggio remembers telling executives at Barnes &AMP; Noble
that the Internet was the future of bookselling in 1994, before
Amazon.com had even begun. But he has never gotten much credit for
it. By the time he founded Barnesandnoble.com, in 1997, Barnes &AMP;
Noble had become watchwords for letting an Internet upstart eat
your lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Last week should have been heartening. Amazon.com lost its
president, missed its revenue projections and saw its stock plummet
amid doubt of its ability to branch into new markets. One Lehman
Brothers analyst even questioned how long the company would be able
to pay its bills.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnesandnoble.com (www.bn.com) suffered, too. The company
reported a wider-than-expected loss and missed its own revenue
target by more than 14 percent, a sign to some analysts of a
growing saturation of demand for books from people already online.
Investors sent its stock tumbling more than 25 percent to close on
Friday at $3.75 a share, down from a 52-week high last fall of
$23.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   This week should come as a welcome relief from all the bad news
for Riggio, brother of Barnes &AMP; Noble's founder Leonard Riggio and
acting chief executive of its online spinoff. He will enjoy a novel
role reversal. Now it is his turn to play the new media visionary.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com is teaming up with Microsoft on Tuesday to
open the first major online store selling digital books, available
for downloading and reading on a screen or in single paperback
copies printed on demand on high-speed presses _ a technological
capacity that Amazon.com does not yet have.
</P>
<P>
   The launch is a pivotal event for the company and a bellwether
for the industry. Although many consider the idea of reading on a
screen awkward and far-fetched, some publishers hope that
electronic books will provide a new avenue of growth in an
otherwise nearly flat business, just as first paperbacks and then
audio books did in the past. As the first major outlet for digital
books, the new store will assay the depth of consumer demand, the
prices readers are willing to pay and the danger of piracy and
hacking. For Barnesandnoble.com, analysts say, selling digital
books could some day hold out the potential for new, more
profitable sales within the company's traditional franchise _
books.
</P>
<P>
   Partly for that reason, Riggio has been pushing the e-book idea
for years, according to current and former employees. One of
Riggio's first directives when he resumed Barnesandnoble.com's
day-to-day management in January, long before the idea took off
with publishers, was to install a tab for electronic books on its
home page.
</P>
<P>
   The digital-book store is a big bet for a small company,
considering that no one yet knows the size of the potential demand.
To build its presence in the digital book market,
Barnesandnoble.com invested $20 million in MightyWords, which
publishes short digital books. The company spent undisclosed
millions more on technology for downloading electronic books,
providing storage space and processing payments.
</P>
<P>
   For its part on Tuesday, Microsoft will introduce the latest
version of its free software for reading on screens. The new
edition is easier to use than its predecessors and is available for
desktops and laptops as well as expensive hand-held devices.
Microsoft executives say that no skeleton-key code-breaker will be
able to open all of the electronic books available for its
software, but no single electronic book is fully hacker-proof.
</P>
<P>
   The dual launch offers Barnesandnoble.com a chance to benefit
from Microsoft's formidable marketing strength. Microsoft is
backing the new venture with a sizable campaign, and in the process
promoting Barnesandnoble.com. In an unusual boon to authors and
publishers accustomed to begging for attention, Microsoft is
actually paying some of them for the right to advertise their books
with its software. Microsoft, in turn, hopes to make its money in
the form of a small commission on each sale of a digital book for
its software.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com and Microsoft did not disclose the terms of
their agreement. Microsoft expects to work with other Web sites,
and Barnesandnoble.com will continue selling books in other
electronic formats.
</P>
<P>
   The site will begin with more than 2,000 digital titles
available in the Microsoft format, adding about 150 new titles a
week. In addition to selling electronic books, Barnesandnoble.com
hopes to use them to keep its customers coming back, another area
where the company has lagged behind Amazon.com. The company will
offer virtual shelf space to customers, by investing in computer
servers that will store shoppers' digital books online. Customers
can download the same title to the same one or two computers as
often as they like, easing the need to store the electronic texts
on their hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   The digital-book store also sets the stage for a new battle with
publishers. Riggio said the company planned to expand its
long-standing publishing program into digital books. ``Publishers
really add very little value to the distribution of book content,''
he said. ``They are not terribly good at physical book
distribution, and they are not very good at technology. They will
have a place in the digital world, but smaller than it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble, which holds a large stake in the online unit,
previously published its own editions of books in the public
domain, like ``Leaves of Grass'' or ``Middlemarch.'' But now
Barnesandnoble.com has hired a respected former illustrated book
publisher, Michael Fragnito, who has begun meeting with agents to
discuss buying the digital rights to previously published works
still under copyright.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Barnesandnoble.com into direct competition with
traditional publishers, its major suppliers, who are themselves now
scrambling to acquire the digital rights to their authors' back
lists. As Chris MacAskill, MightyWords' chief executive, discovered
when he published some authors' short essays, traditional
publishers can be quite territorial. ``Publishers get very, very
jumpy about digital rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Riggio says the digital rights originally belong to the
author, not the publisher. ``We strongly believe that the author is
entitled to a very big share of the savings that results from the
distribution of digital content,'' he said. What royalty rate
Barnesandnoble.com will offer for digital rights to previously
published titles remains to be set, Riggio said.
</P>
<P>
   He maintains that, in time, Barnesandnoble.com will flourish in
the online world because most of its products _ books, videos and
music _ can be delivered over the Internet. To promote its
products, he says, the site is already becoming an online
broadcaster. Barnesandnoble.com began a network for 16 online radio
stations, soon expanding to 120, along with online video
programming about authors and books, BNTV.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, some analysts say Barnesandnoble.com's most
promising innovation may be more low-technology delivery
techniques, particularly its same-day delivery program. In
Manhattan, any order before 11 a.m. is delivered by 7 p.m., at no
extra charge, by a fleet of Barnesandnoble.com trucks and
messengers. Riggio says the company is evaluating similar services
in other cities. Barnesandnoble.com also lets people return online
purchases at Barnes &AMP; Noble stores. (Until recently, it was even
possible to receive a refund greater than the online price.)
</P>
<P>
   But, although most analysts support Barnesandnoble.com's
investment in electronic books on the chance of a payoff years down
the road, few expect it to help the company's sagging stock price
any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the low share price, rumors have spread through the
industry that Bertelsmann was seeking to buy the online bookstore
outright. Flush with cash from selling a stake in America Online,
Bertelsmann has been buying up struggling Internet retailers to
build an Internet commerce empire under its own brand. Bertelsmann
executives have pointedly declined to comment on the question.
</P>
<P>
   Riggio, too, declined to comment on any talks, except to say
that ``we talk to them about all kinds of things.'' Both Barnes &AMP;
Noble and Bertelsmann are ``committed to the business,'' he said.
The online store expects to begin making a profit in 2002, and
analysts say its profits could help Barnes &AMP; Noble bolster its own
sagging shares. In the meantime, Riggio says, Barnesandnoble.com
has over $350 million in cash and no debt _ plenty of capital to
stay in business till the company turns a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Riggio has a long way to go to restore Wall Street's
faith in the company. For one thing, some say that, after more than
doubling from one year to the next, the days of explosive growth in
online bookselling are over. People already online seem to be
buying as many books online as ever they will, said Mark Rowen,
Internet analyst at Prudential Securities. As a result, he says,
growth in the online book market is slowing significantly, to about
the rate that new consumers hook up to the Internet or a little
faster _ about 20 percent to 25 percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Noto, analyst at Goldman Sachs, said Barnesandnoble.com
faced an uphill battle because it was locked into marketing
agreements with other companies like AOL, limiting its ability to
cut costs when revenue declines. Worse, he said, Barnesandnoble.com
thus far has failed to take advantage of Barnes &AMP; Noble's 544
retail stores to win new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect their customer acquisition costs to be lower than
pure Internet companies, and, the bottom line is, they still are
higher than Amazon's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Noto said, is motivational. The online
store threatens to steal sales from the retail stores, and, except
for the Riggios, Barnes &AMP; Noble executives have no incentive to
work together. Others blame a lack of stable management. Riggio
assumed the title of acting chief executive seven months ago, and
the company still has no replacement.
</P>
<P>
   But Riggio said that the analysts were ``very wrong.'' ``I don't
know the analyst who has been inside the company or met with its
management,'' he said, calling his management team ``one of the
most stable in the sector.'' Cooperation between the chain and the
online store, he insisted, was coming along fine. He declined to
name specifics but promised ``exciting things in the next six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the company's marketing costs would decline, too.
Heavy spending to advertise in print, radio and television is
``behind us now,'' he said, and the company could use its access to
Barnes &AMP; Noble stores to strike advantageous marketing deals, like
its agreement with America Online. ````We'll be around in 10 years,
or 20 years. People are more motivated to work with us now than
with companies in the Wild West shootout that had been the
Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for hiring a new chief executive, Riggio said, his day-to-day
management ensured continuity and the board would make a decision
in due time. ``I am among the candidates being considered,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
