<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-TECHNOLOGY-0     08-06 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-TECHNOLOGY-0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LONG DELAYS KEEP NEW TECHNOLOGIES OFF ELDERLY MARKET
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR USE MONDAY, AUG. 7, 2000
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of elderly and disabled Medicare patients
are potentially denied the latest in medical technology because of
bureaucratic delays and inadequate payments, according to a report
being released today. ((Monday))
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared for the Advanced Medical Technology
Association, which represents medical manufacturers, by the Lewin
Group, an independent analytical firm that specializes in health
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Among its findings, the report said:
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) The time between a new device's approval for medical
use and its acceptance by Medicare can range from 15 months to five
years. Patients rarely receive the new technology during that
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of Medicare coverage for a new device or procedure
restricts patient access,'' the report said. ``Although
beneficiaries may pay out-of-pocket for devices that are not
adequately covered under Medicare, they are rarely in a position to
do so in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Because some devices must be approved by Medicare on a
region-by-region basis, the same technology may not be available
nationwide. Medicare is considering a policy to grant nationwide
approval of new devices. A hearing is likely to be held on that
proposal later this month in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) New Medicare rules will make it tougher for new devices
to be approved for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration, which operates
Medicare, did not have a reaction to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received a draft copy of this report and we're
reviewing it,'' a HCFA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare often pays the same amount for a new device as for
other devices used in a similar manner, even if the new device is
more costly.
</P>
<P>
   That may result in hospitals ``limiting performance of
procedures, eliminating provision of certain services and using
older and less expensive technologies,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, cochlear implants, which stimulate the ear's
cochlea and help restore hearing in some severely deaf individuals,
were approved by the Food and Drug Administration in 1984 and by
Medicare two years later. But Medicare has never adjusted its
payment level even though the implants have been refined over the
past 14 years and are now more costly.
</P>
<P>
   The report said hospitals lose about $9,000 for every cochlear
implant performed on an in-patient basis and $5,500 for outpatient
procedures, resulting in some facilities limiting their
availability. The UCLA Audiology Clinic recently closed its
cochlear implant program, citing the high cost and low
reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of all patients eligible for cochlear implants
are on Medicare, but only about 15 percent of the implants are
performed on Medicare patients, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Approval delays and low reimbursement levels impose substantial
risks on the companies that develop and manufacture medical
devices, with the result that efforts to improve research and
development may be stifled, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high cost and long timelines that may be required to
secure Medicare payment can delay or even prevent new devices with
demonstrated clinical value from reaching the market,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Medical Technology Association: www.advamed.org
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
