<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CHILDMOLEST-N     08-06 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CHILDMOLEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER FUELS `MEGAN'S LAW' CONTROVERSY IN ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Sara in 8th graf is cq) 
By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain said Sunday that it would ``urgently'' press
for stricter laws on child molesting but resisted widespread calls
for public identification of released violators that have been
associated with current vigilante attacks across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Home Office Minister Paul Boateng pledged that the government
would strengthen laws protecting children from sexual abuse, but he
said, ``The decisions about whether or not people are told names
and addresses are not matters for newspapers, they are not matters
for ministers, they are matters for police and the probation
service.''
</P>
<P>
   His newspaper reference was to Britain's top selling tabloid,
The Sunday News of the World, which under the headline ``Name and
Shame'' has been running photographs and whereabouts of men
convicted of molesting children who have been released from prison.
Although the paper had promised to name 100,000, it ended the
practice Sunday after publishing only 82.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch mob attacks and firebombings have occurred in 11 different
communities in England and Scotland since the campaign began two
weeks ago, the majority of them at homes of people wrongly
identified as suspected pedophiles or confused with people with
similar names and appearances as people pictured by the newspaper.
A rioting crowd of 150, many carrying signs with the emotive News
of the World headline, overturned vehicles, smashed windows and
threw stones and rocks at police Thursday and Friday nights in
Plymouth in Southern England.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, which is owned by the press magnate Rupert
Murdoch, has been condemned by police officials and human rights
groups arguing that its campaign has actually further endangered
children by driving sex offenders underground. ``The government's
concern has to be the protection and welfare of children and the
maintenance of public order,'' said Boateng. ``The News of the
World approach to this issue in naming and shaming threatened
both.''
</P>
<P>
   But the newspaper said it was abandoning its effort only because
it had started an ``unstoppable force'' for a law for public
identification of known offenders. It said 300,000 people had
already signed a petition for a law that would let parents see
registers of convicted pedophiles in their area, and it printed
forms for its 4.1 million readers to sign and send to the
government, with the promise of a receiving a ``badge of pride'' to
wear.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after the so-called ``Megan's Law'' in the United
States, the British version is being promoted as ``Sarah's Law,''
in memory of an 8-year-old girl named Sarah Payne, who was abducted
last month near her grandparents' home and later found dead and
naked off a country path after a search that aroused front page
sympathy throughout Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, Sara Payne, 31, made affecting televised
daily appeals for her daughter's return during the two weeks that
police combed fields in Surrey, and she was pictured on Sunday's
News of the World front page endorsing the campaign and helping
count signed petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law, a New Jersey statute that all 49 other U.S. states
have used as the model for similar laws, was created in 1994 in
response to the brutal rape and murder of Megan Kanka, 7, of
Hamilton Township, by a twice-convicted sex offender who was living
across the street unbeknownst to her parents. Under the law, all
sex offenders must register with the police, and community
organizations involved with children are alerted to the presence of
those who are considered to be potentially repeat offenders. The
law counsels a number of preventative steps and explicitly rules
out verbal and physical vigilantism.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Howard, known as a strict law and order official when he
served as Britain's home secretary in the last Conservative
government, warned Saturday that proposals for public surveillance
would lead to vigilantism ``that no civilized society could
tolerate'' and could increase risks to children by discouraging
released sex offenders from registering with police at the high
level they do now. He said the level in Britain was 97 percent _
the highest compliance of any country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Boateng did not detail what steps he was contemplating to redeem
his pledge to tighten up procedures, but the government is known to
be looking at proposals for longer sentencing, including life terms
with no possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   The editor of The News of the World, Rebekah Wade, said, ``As a
result of our naming and shaming campaign I believe the
introduction of Sarah's Law is now inevitable.'' She cited that as
the reason the newspaper had ended the campaign and added, ``Our
job now is to force the government to act _ and we'll name and
shame every politician who stands in our way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TERROR-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     08-06 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGIC TERROR': INTENDED EFFECTS DON'T QUITE WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the clever exercises in horror that compose Peter Straub's
latest work of fiction, ``Magic Terror: Seven Tales,'' the most
successful is the brief ``Ashputtle,'' which takes its title from
the German version of ``Cinderella.''
</P>
<P>
   Here the narrator is Mrs. Asch, ``the Mrs. being entirely
honorific, no husband having ever been in evidence, nor ever likely
to be.'' She is a psychopathic ``female kindergarten teacher in her
50s who happens to be very fat.'' She begins: ``People think that
teaching little children has something to do with helping other
people, something to do with service. People think that if you
teach little children, you must love them. People get what they
need from thoughts like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Asch sees herself as both the victim of a wicked stepmother
and the wicked stepmother, too. During the course of her ramblings,
she reveals that one of her students ``has been lost.'' She
reports: ``A lost child lies deep within the ashes, her hands and
feet mutilated, her face destroyed by fire. She has partaken of the
great adventure, and now she is the same as all nature.'' She may
or may not be aware that she herself is responsible for this loss,
but the reader becomes aware, and the effect is chilling.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Straub is often equally as adept but rarely as
successful. In the much longer ``Bunny Is Good Bread,'' the
psychopathic point of view is 5-year-old Fee Bandolier's as he
watches his alcoholic father gradually battering his mother to
death and is sexual molested by a man in a movie theater.
Inevitably he becomes a serial murderer, joins the Army and is
accepted for Special Forces training. But for all the skill of the
narrative, the conclusion is announced instead of experienced, and
you feel the author's elbow in your ribs.
</P>
<P>
   A similar tendentiousness mars ``Mr. Clubb and Mr. Cuff,'' a
grotesque homage to Melville's ``Bartleby the Scrivener'' that won
a 1999 Bram Stoker Award for Horror. Here a puritanical Wall Street
tycoon who uses $10 words where nickel ones would do describes how
he hired a Gallagher-and-Shean-type vaudeville team of ``private
detectives extraordinaire'' to punish his wife for cheating on him
with his business partner.
</P>
<P>
   The two detectives turn out to be sadistic torturers who move
into the narrator's office and take over his life. But instead of
infusing the story with the inevitable yet indefinable, as
Bartleby's protest does, they merely teach the banal lesson that he
who lives by the pickax and screwdriver dies by them.
</P>
<P>
   For fans of Straub's fiction (``Ghost Story,'' ``The Hellfire
Club,'' ``Mr. X,'' among other novels of terror and the
supernatural), there are many puzzles to work out in ``Magic
Terror'': echoes of his earlier fiction, references to writers the
author admires. ``The Ghost Village,'' a heavy-handed Conradian war
story set in the battle jungles of Vietnam, reintroduces the
characters who first appeared in the novel ``Koko.'' The sexual
molestation in ``Bunny Is Good Bread'' develops a central incident
in ``The Juniper Tree,'' one of the better stories in Straub's
impressive earlier collection ``Houses Without Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet whatever he may be up to with his echoes and leitmotifs, his
main concern here seems to be narrative virtuosity. Repeatedly in
``Magic Terror,'' he clutches the reader by the collar. In ``Isn't
It Romantic?'' a Bond-like operative identified only as N sets out
on a mission in the French Pyrenees entailing good food, fast cars,
esoteric trade talk and sexy women. In ``Porkpie Hat'' a jazz fan
interviews a brilliant saxophonist he calls Hat (based on Lester
Young) and induces him to tell a ghost story from his boyhood.
``Hunger, an Introduction'' seduces with the magniloquence of the
autodidact.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, few of Straub's intended effects quite come off.
The fate of smooth N is obvious almost from the beginning of
``Isn't It Romantic?'' ``The Ghost Village'' sends the not very
fresh message that the violence of Vietnam came home to the States.
The story within the story in ``Porkpie Hat'' is boring and
obscure. ``Hunger, an Introduction'' ends on a lovely, lyric note
without clear meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In the greatest of ghost stories, like ``The Beckoning Fair
One,'' by Oliver Onions, or ``Silent Snow, Secret Snow,'' by Conrad
Aiken, the narrative invades those recesses of your mind that you
don't quite trust and makes the disintegration of something
familiar seem irresistible. In ``Magic Terror'' Straub now and then
entertains you. But his characters are mostly aliens, shadows on
the face of the moon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MAGIC TERROR'
</P>
<P>
   Seven Tales
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Straub.
</P>
<P>
   335 pages. Random House. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
