<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CLIBURN-MUSIC-REVIEW-     08-06 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: VAN CLIBURN DOES A REPRISE AT TANGLEWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ It is not often that Tchaikovsky's ``Pathetique''
Symphony is chosen to open a program, as it was here at Tanglewood
Friday night in a concert given by the Boston Symphony, led by
Seiji Ozawa. The symphony's ominously quiet opening works better if
an audience is already settled, and the desolate conclusion, in an
effective performance, leaves little more to be said or even hoped
for.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it is not often that the soloist of the evening is
of the caliber and reputation of Van Cliburn. Cliburn seldom
performs these days, and when he does, it is almost always in
Tchaikovsky's First Piano Concerto, more or less replicating the
performance that established his career overnight at the
Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was here, with Cliburn inevitably bringing down the
house to end the night with desolation far behind, leaving a
sizable crowd of 11,500 with warm memories. With warmer memories,
in this listener's case, than when Cliburn was last heard, nine
years ago in the same work with the New York Philharmonic as part
of Carnegie Hall's centenary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   On that occasion, Cliburn's first New York appearance in many
years, he appeared nervous and ill at ease. Here he seemed more in
his element despite a few momentary derailments in the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the interpretation was big, broad and raw-boned,
occasionally suggesting, in its awesome power, some of what the
young Cliburn must have sounded like. He positively thundered in
the climactic octave runs near the end. But the voluptuary sound
one might have expected was often undercut by a heavy, percussive
touch, and Cliburn's vaunted lyricism was hampered by a sense of
stop and go rather than ebb and flow.
</P>
<P>
   True, some of that discontinuity, especially in the first
movement, seemed a function of searching, and it was moving to see
Cliburn still trying to plumb depths of meaning in this piece after
so many repetitions. Yet it is hard to know what he expects to
find.
</P>
<P>
   This is, by and large, a young performer's music, preferring
ready sentiment and sheer visceral excitement to profundity of
thought. The excitement Cliburn conjured in his youth may be better
reflected nowadays in a performance like the one Evgeny Kissin
gave, also with Ozawa and the Boston Symphony, to open the Carnegie
Hall season in 1995 (with the ``Pathetique'' also on the program).
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation _ fleet, fluid, playful and mercurial _
could hardly have been more different from the one here. But
Kissin's clear-eyed youthful impetus and the gleeful virtuosity
swept all before it, leaving a tired war horse sounding like a
fresh, clean masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa followed Cliburn's comings and goings with a masterly
hand, insuring a coherence the proceedings might easily have
lacked. And Ozawa's work in the symphony was hardly less
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Pathetique'' is another overworked standard needing
constant revivification, and there was no particular reason to
expect it from Ozawa and the Boston Symphony, whose work together
in recent years has often exuded a sense of weary routine. But here
was a polished performance (almost overpolished at the start) that
looked for depth in all the right places.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa imparted an epic breadth to the first movement, and the
orchestra managed to sustain the line over long spans. The quiet
moments so crucial to this work were just what they needed to be:
dark and oppressive yet intense and charged with mystery. William
R. Hudgins was superb in the clarinet solos, whether singing in
eloquent full voice or murmuring in velvety pianissimos.
</P>
<P>
   When Ozawa announced last year that he intended to leave the
orchestra in 2002, few doubted that the time was ripe for change.
Yet on evidence like this, his tenure still holds the promise of
bearing rich final fruits.
</P>
<P>
   For a music director, lame-duck status may carry more than
diminishing power, as the orchestra, coming to realize that choice
specialties of the collaboration are being revisited for perhaps
the last time, plays with renewed ardor. There may be excitement in
Boston even before 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
