<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PASSACANTANDO-PROFILE     08-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSACANTANDO-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SON OF THE SUBURBS RISES TO THE HELM OF AN EMBATTLED GREENPEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN H. CUSHMAN JR.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not so odd that a graduate of the '80s with a
master's degree in economics and some supply-side credentials
should now find himself negotiating a big merger.
</P>
<P>
   But this merger would combine two environmental organizations,
one obscure and one famous, Ozone Action and Greenpeace. The
buzzwords might be the same as in the world of corporate deals _
``synergy'' comes to mind _ but the objectives could not be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is not a certainty _ the two groups' boards are still
thinking it over. But whether or not it succeeds , John
Passacantando, co-founder and executive director of Ozone Action,
will be moving to Greenpeace USA as its executive director. At age
38, he will take charge of one of the best-known groups in
environmentalism after years of upheaval. Greenpeace's entire board
resigned several months ago amid disputes over the group's internal
organization, staffing and overall direction.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace USA's membership is about 300,000, way down from the
1 million members it claimed several years ago. It has a yearly
budget of about $20 million, raised mostly by costly direct mail
(door-to-door canvassing is a thing of the past). Its staff numbers
about 70, after steep reductions under its former director, Kristen
Engberg.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some cultural similarities, Ozone Action is built quite
differently. Ozone Action has a network of a few thousand
volunteers, but no members; its budget of $1.3 million comes mostly
from family foundations, and its staff numbers about a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups are based in Washington, but Greenpeace reports back
to Greenpeace International in Amsterdam. Ozone Action focuses
narrowly on pollution that causes global warming or thins the
earth's protective ozone layer. Greenpeace's agenda is much
broader, taking in everything from saving whales to opposing
genetically modified crops.
</P>
<P>
   But the two groups share something important, Passacantando
said: an appreciation for attention-grabbing theatrics, carried out
on the streets or on the high seas, in support of their
nitty-gritty policy objectives.
</P>
<P>
   And for this lanky and sincere son of the suburbs, the trip to
the helm of Greenpeace's ship has meant getting used to these
ruckus-raising tactics known in the trade as ``direct action.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Ozone Action's events are moderate in tone _ bringing
ambassadors from small island states to attend town meetings on
global warming or building Web pages that use government data to
illustrate increases in heat waves. But a few months ago,
Passacantando, along with the president of Friends of the Earth and
a few others, was arrested at the headquarters of the World Bank in
Washington during protests of the April meetings of the
international monetary organizations. They tried to hang a banner
denouncing energy development and to disrupt traffic with a
disabled truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow you can find a way that is outrageous and fun, but
still fair and ethical, to speak the truth to power,'' he says of
tactics like this. ``That's a fun job to go to every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't always like this. Growing up in Whippany, N.J., the
son of a father who sold insurance and a mother who left a research
job to raise him and his younger brother and sister, Passacantando
liked to camp, hike and fish with his dad, but wasn't preoccupied
by the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was under the false conviction, well conveyed to me during
the Reagan years, that the era of movements was over. I had missed
the civil rights movement, and I thought, `What a shame.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He sold computer systems, then was hired by Jude Wanniski's
Polyconomics Inc. to do economic research for Wall Street. ``In
fact, very conservative research, supply-side research,'' he
recalled. ``It was pro-development, without any regard for
sustainability.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile he got a masters' degree in economics at New York
University. But his world view was starting to change.
</P>
<P>
   He was reading John Muir and Rachel Carson, farmer-philosopher
Wendell Berry and eco-spiritualist the Rev. Thomas Berry. And he
became involved ``as a minor player'' in a local development
dispute in Morristown.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bill Moyers, the head of the Florence and John Schumann
Foundation in Montclair, took him aboard and gave him the the
assignment of encouraging ``a grass-roots renewal of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The work brought him into contact with environmental advocates _
people like Michael Clark, who was building a coalition to protect
the Yellowstone ecosystem, and Jeff DeBonis, who was organizing
green-leaning professionals in the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that there was, after all, a movement of activists all
over the country; it just did not get through the veil,'' he says.
``There was a wonderful buzz in our democracy, which I had not been
seeing, which I did not see in college. This is my generation's
great battle, and I wanted to be in the trenches.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1993, he co-founded Ozone Action, taking the name from
the crisis over the ozone hole caused by emissions of
chlorofluorocarbons. His co-founder was Karen Lohr, a Greenpeace
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups' styles still differ considerably. Ozone Action
has been training 200 students to report on corporate attempts to
influence the global warming negotiations in the Hague,
Netherlands. Greenpeace, meanwhile, has been driving its boats
obstreperously into the path of a Star Wars missile test.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no real culture gap, says Passacantando, who hopes
his team would fit right in after a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenpeace took what the American colonists did at the Tea
Party and really did develop it to an art form,'' he said. ``And
what you have now is an organization that is stabilized, that came
out of a steep fall for the last decade, and really wants its
leadership to get its creative work going again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
