<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4113 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HARLEM-BAPTISM-ART-NY     08-06 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-BAPTISM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HARLEM, A JOYOUS BAPTISM BY FIRE HOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4, 5 and 6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the heat was beginning to rise from the pavement
late Sunday morning, 115th Street between Lenox and Fifth avenues
was as white as snow. Hundreds of people, dressed from head to foot
in white cotton dresses, slacks and shirts, were arriving by the
bus load and gathering in the center of the avenue for a baptism by
fire hose.
</P>
<P>
   Each August since 1937, the United House of Prayer, a
nondenominational Pentecostal church that claims 3 million
congregants in 28 states, has held mass baptisms on 115th Street in
East Harlem, using a fire hose to spray hundreds of participants
with baptismal waters.
</P>
<P>
   The church holds mass baptisms across the country each summer as
part of a convocation ceremony in which congregants seek holy
renewal. In most places, as many as 2,000 congregants will be
submerged in a local river or a pool. But in New York, where access
to rivers is limited and where pools aren't easy to find, the House
of Prayer has always used the municipal water supply, blessed by
the church's bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptism is a faith thing and has nothing to do with the actual
water,'' explained Apostle H.M. Swaringer, the pastor of Harlem's
chapter, on Frederick Douglass Boulevard and 125th Street. ``In the
scripture in places where there was no water, they used the clouds.
It's all according to the conditions, what's available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many church members travel to different regions of the county
for baptisms that take place throughout the summer. This year,
about 500 congregants gathered for Sunday's New York regional
ceremony, with buses arriving from Washington, Boston and
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Helena and Gracie Myrick, sisters from Baltimore, said they got
up at 3 a.m. Sunday to make the four-hour trip to East Harlem. Both
said they were baptized every year, as their 91-year-old father had
been for years, not just in New York, but in each of the 13 states
that participate in the House of Prayer annual convocations.
</P>
<P>
   The baptism began just before noon, after the church's national
leader, Bishop S.C. Madison, arrived from Charlotte, N.C., and
ascended the stage to rousing Southern swing music played by four
brass bands. Congregants clapped and danced, and waved their hands
in the air, as some put on shower caps and bathing caps, or draped
towels over their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask the Lord to bless the water of the New York reservoir,''
Madison said to the joyful assembly. ``I ask him to change this
water to the water of the river Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a church official unleashed the torrent, and water from a
fire hose attached to a city hydrant sprayed high into the air,
pouring down on congregants for a 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Some people shook their heads and grimaced at the cold spray,
others danced to the music of the brass bands, some dropped to the
ground and a few threw their hands in the air as if to grasp the
falling blessing. When the deluge ended, drenched participants
straggled off, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel good, relaxed,'' said Rose M. King, 41, a
Harlem resident, shivering in a soaked T-shirt. ``It takes all the
evil away.''
</P>
<P>
   From the 1920s until almost midcentury, the House of Prayer's
church stood on 115th Street between Lenox and Fifth avenues. It
was demolished in 1947 to make way for a public housing
development, the Martin Luther King Jr. Houses.
</P>
<P>
   Church members return to the street every year to honor their
old house of worship, and some who live in the surrounding
neighborhood have come to see the convocation ceremony as part of
their own tradition.
</P>
<P>
   George A. Donaldson, who moved into the King Houses with his
family in 1951, when only half the project had been completed, said
he and his former neighbors planned their annual reunion each
summer to coincide with the House of Prayer ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who grew up on 115th Street and Fifth is naturally
going to want to come out for this,'' said Donaldson, who greeted
old neighbors as he watched the convocation from the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a group of tenements across the street and
most of the residents there were members of the church, so you can
imagine how it used to be. Since then, everyone has scattered. But
this has such a strong pull that it brings everyone back every
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
