<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the southwest will deliver much warmer air to the
Middle Atlantic states and most of the Northeast. Cool, damp
conditions will be slow to leave parts of eastern and northern New
England. A broken area of strong thunderstorms will erupt during
midday in the humid air from the Ohio Valley to the central
Appalachians. Scattered thundershowers will reach the Northeast
coast by evening.
</P>
<P>
   Very warm air will cover a large area from the interior West
across the southern and central Plains to the Southeast. A few
thunderstorms will form near the periphery of the hot air mass from
the northern Rockies to the Dakotas. Meanwhile, a slow-moving
disturbance will promote clouds and scattered thundershowers in
Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Alberto with winds of 80 mph will continue moving west
1500 miles east of the Windward Islands.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DOG DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Daytime temperatures in the 90s, hazy skies hiding random
thunderstorms, sticky, still nights with patches of dense fog add
up to the dog days of summer. The term comes from the ancient
Egyptians who thought the intense heat of this season was caused by
the extra warmth of another morning star. Sirius, the Dog Star of
the constellation Canis Major, is visible just before sunrise from
July 3 to Aug. 10. This period coincides with the highest average
temperatures for Egypt and much of the Northern Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
