   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MIDWEST _ Story follows Bush on the last day of his
whistlestop tour through the Midwest. (Heath, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-TECHNOLOGY _ WASHINGTON _ Thousands of Medicare
patients may not receive the latest in medical technology because
of bureaucratic delays or underpayments, according to a report
being released today (MONDAY). (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   INFOMERCIAL-CONVENTION _ ATLANTA _ They tried. Eager to come
across as ``Republican Party Animals,'' in author P.J. O'Rourke's
phrase, the just-completed GOP convention offered World Wrestling
Federation star The Rock, a rollicking black gospel choir, ``NYPD
Blue's'' Rick Schroder, Comedy Central star Ben Stein playing ``Win
Ben Stein's Money'' with Miss America, and R&AMP;B crooner Brian
McKnight singing ``My body's callin' out your name'' while
MTV-style dancers practiced pelvic thrusts behind him. But
virtually none of that made it onto TV, except for C-SPAN. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED in (a) General News and (e)
Entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-PREGNANCY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sixteen, pregnant, and
she didn't want to have an abortion. Glenda Dowis' daughter
couldn't foresee that her mother would react violently, threaten
her at gunpoint to get an abortion and wind up in jail. The high
school senior was simply following a growing tendency among
pregnant teenagers: going through with the pregnancy rather than
end it, despite parental disapproval. Nationwide, the rate of
teenage pregnancies is dropping, even as more youths are becoming
sexually active and at younger ages. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COTTON-GIN _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Amid the tangled, junglelike growth
along the lower Savannah River, a pile of crumbling bricks is all
that remains of the old plantation house where a young tutor
invented a machine that abruptly changed the course of the South _
and ultimately the entire nation. It was here, at Mulberry Grove
Plantation, eight miles upstream from downtown Savannah, thatEli
Whitney invented the cotton gin in 1793. The simple machine, which
efficiently separated cotton fibers from seeds, ushered in the era
of King Cotton and, according to some historians, gave rise to
America's Industrial Revolution. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS - ONLINE _ A metro Atlanta school district will be
offering a few on-line classes for high school students district
wide in the fall. (Lezin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TREASURE _ WEST PALM BEACH _ A Virginia federal appeals court
ruling, upholding Spain's legal ownership of a long-lost galleon
sunk in U.S. waters in 1750, has infuriated Florida's underwater
salvors, who fear the decision may deprive them of the thrill and
profit of one of the most exciting jobs imaginable: seeking sunken
treasure. (Browning, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBUGGY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Tom Sines boasts that
his custom-made electric car can turn on a dime, he's not
exaggerating. Driving down a narrow country road near his home in
Okeechobee, Sines slows the car to a near stop, then whips it
around and heads in the opposite direction with the flick of his
wrist. Sines' ``Sunbuggy'' looks a bit crude with its unpainted
fiberglass body and seats covered with carpet remnants, but it has
technology that may be the wave of the future. (McGinness, Palm
Beach Post) WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-GOPCONVENTION _ The Bush of Bob Jones University
seemed light years away from the Bush who brought an upbeat GOP
convention to its climax last week. The Texas governor delivered a
well-scripted speech with conviction and optimism. (The Atlanta
Constitution). 10. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Every week I get two or three calls
from folks trying to save trees in their neighborhoods, even though
10 metro counties and several cities now have tree ordinances
requiring developers to submit tree plans for approval. Atlanta's
law requires ``no net loss of trees.'' That means when trees are
removed, they must be replaced by other trees that total the same
number of diameter inches. So if we've made progress with tree
protection ordinances, why the continuing outcry? It's simple:
People want to save old trees _ the native oaks, maples, hickories
and magnolias that set our city apart from others. But most tree
ordinances don't help with that. They allow ornamental trees to
replace the magnificent white oaks that have been around since the
Civil War. (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Those who thought this year's
Republican convention would be the same ol', same ol' were proven
wrong from opening night. Say what you will about the demographic
makeup of the delegates, they rocked to African and Latino rhythms
and listened to the nephew of the candidate address them in two
languages _ the English of his father and the Spanish of his
mother. They might not have liked everything they heard, but this
convention had a different tone to it. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ To have and to hold, in sickness
and in health, Mike and Carol Bracken consummated their marriage in
the most unheard-of way. If you think that Adam's rib stuff is
farfetched, consider: Mike now has Carol's kidney keeping him
alive. So much for what sour-on-marriage sorts call the old
ball-and-chain. Mike finding Carol, and Carol finding out she was a
tissue match, freed him from a lifetime of misery and dialysis.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-INTERNET _ BellSouth today will announce plans to
build a high-speed Internet system near Miami that will carry huge
amounts of data arriving from overseas, helping to relieve
congestion in much of the equipment now used by Internet companies
in the Southeast. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PROCARE-PHARMACY _ ATLANTA _ Wil Kinsey delivers more than
prescriptions to patients infected with the AIDS virus. Kinsey, who
is African-American, delivers prayers, praise and positive
messages. For that, Kinsey has earned the name, ``Black Moses.'' He
does the deliveries voluntarily, even though it's not part of his
job description as billing specialist at the ProCare Pharmacy in
Atlanta. If Kinsey's approach to his job is unusual, so is ProCare.
It's operated by CVS, the Woonsocket, R.I.-based conglomerate with
4,100 stores nationwide. But ProCare is not your typical chain
drugstore. (DeGross, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SMOKING _ In what seems to be a reverse of a societal
trend, there's a new smoking bar at Atlanta Hartsfield
International Airport, the Budweiser Brewhouse and Smoking Lounge
on concourse A. It's a new smoking bar. The wrinkle is, it's
upstairs to avoid drawing the ire of non-smokers. (Hendricks,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GLADIOLUS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mazzoni Farms in Delray is
the very last gladiolus farm in the area, which once was host to
dozens. They're one of the four major growers of this flower in the
United States, and do 25 million bulbs a year. But NAFTA is giving
them pressure, they say: This year, Mexican gladioluses bit into
their profit margin. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-FILES _ If you love putting pen to paper, then this
edition of the Greig Files will validate the importance of
continuing to write by hand. If you rely on your spell-checker and
a keyboard, then this edition will teach you much about the art of
handwriting _ from scratch, so to speak. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-QUIZ _ Take this little test to see if you're ready for
school to start _ 'cause we're thinking you probably forgot
everything you need to know over the summer. (Malley, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ROMANCE-NOVELIST _ Eva Rutland is being honored with the
lifetime achievement award at a writer's conference in Atlanta this
coming weekend. A romance novelist, she has written for Harlequin
for the last 15 years. In February, she published her first
mainstream novel, No Crystal Stair, a semi-autobiographical work
that covers 60 years in a Black Atlanta based family. Mrs. Rutland
is 83 and has been blind for the last 30-plus years. She was born
in Atlanta and raised in the house that her grandfather (a former
slave built). She is a 1937 graduate of Spelman College. (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
