<SLUG> BC-SUNBUGGY0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunbuggy of the future
 &HT;    By Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Tom Sines boasts that his
custom-made electric car can turn on a dime, he's not exaggerating.
</P>
<P>
   Driving down a narrow country road near his home in Okeechobee,
Sines slows the car to a near stop, then whips it around and heads
in the opposite direction with the flick of his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   To further prove his point that his car can out-maneuver any
other four-wheel vehicle on the road, he makes it spin in circles,
like a stomach-churning ride at the county fair.
</P>
<P>
   Sines' ``Sunbuggy'' looks a bit crude with its unpainted
fiberglass body and seats covered with carpet remnants, but it has
technology that may be the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a steering wheel, it has a joystick.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you drive a car, you have to do a certain amount of work
to steer. With this car, it's just like using the joystick on a
(Sony) Playstation,'' he said. ``It's just a lot easier to drive
and a lot more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto manufacturers have been experimenting with joysticks, or
electronic ``drive-by-wire'' controls for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Mercedes-Benz unveiled its F200 concept car, with
``sidesticks'' or joysticks in the interior door panels and center
console that the driver uses to steer, accelerate and brake. Cars
with a more open cockpit have proven to be safer in front-end
collision tests because there's no steering column or foot pedals
pushed toward the driver.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG spent $1.3 million to create a research
vehicle with twin sidesticks that look like they came out of an
airplane. The manufacturer says it will be several years before the
cost and regulatory problems can be worked out, and even then there
are concerns if consumers will be ready for such future-orientated
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In the evolving world of non-polluting, alternative energy
vehicles, it seems like Sines has developed something that's quite
different, said Kara Flynn, spokeswoman for the Electric Vehicle
Association of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to say it hasn't been done elsewhere, but I've never heard
of it,'' said Flynn, whose Washington-based organization includes
vehicle manufacturers, electric companies, research institutions
and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sines, 59, actually started working on his vehicle as a hobby
about 25 years ago, after the Arab oil embargo of 1973 led to
increased gas prices and long lines at the pump. Rather than
complain about the situa The idea for the joystick started out as a
novelty, Sines said. The more he worked on it, the more he realized
how much easier it is to operate a car with a joystick, he said. He
has applied for a patent on his design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing is a slow, meticulous, trial-and-error thing. You
try lots of things. Some work, some don't,'' he said. I think we
have something great here.''
</P>
<P>
   High gasoline prices and government regulations to increase fuel
economy and reduce emissions in new cars, trucks and SUVs have
sparked a renewed interest in electric vehicles and hybrid-electric
cars, said Flynn of the Electric Vehicle Association. Honda's
Insight and Toyota's Prius _ hybrid passenger vehicles that use
both gasoline and electric motors _ hit the U.S. market this year.
Ford plans to debut a hybrid electric version of its new small
sport utility vehicle, the Escape, in 2003. General Motors Corp.
will begin building a version of its Chevrolet/Silverado/GMC Sierra
pickups in 2004 that are powered by a gas-electric hybrid system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see a lot more of these alternative-energy vehicles on
the road in the next few years,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Sines would like to be part of the resurgence, but it depends on
finding investors to help set up a small manufacturing plant and to
market his car.
</P>
<P>
   He believes there are dozens, if not hundreds, of motorists in
South Florida who share his dislike for ``Big Oil'' and his love
for the environment and would want a Sunbuggy of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, this is such an exciting car,'' he said.
``It's just incredibly fun to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
