<SLUG> BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Numbers of pregnant teens dropping
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sixteen, pregnant, and she didn't want
to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Dowis' daughter couldn't foresee that her mother would
react violently, threaten her at gunpoint to get an abortion and
wind up in jail. The high school senior was simply following a
growing tendency among pregnant teenagers: going through with the
pregnancy rather than end it, despite parental disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who give birth also choose to keep their babies,
rather than place them for adoption as was the custom for previous
generations.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that started with the sexual revolution of the
1960s, faltered in the 1970s-80s under the novelty of legal
abortion and the self-involvement of the ``me generation,'' then
surged as single parenthood went from anomaly to norm in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the rate of teenage pregnancies is dropping, even as
more youths are becoming sexually active and at younger ages. Fewer
pregnancies mean fewer ``outcomes,'' as the statistics keepers call
births, abortions and miscarriages, and the numbers show abortion
on a steeper decline than the other outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, girls in Dowis' daughter's age group _ 15 to
17 _ became pregnant at the rate of 71.6 per 1,000 and had an
abortion rate of 30 per 1,000, according to the Alan Guttmacher
Institute, a reproductive study arm of the Planned Parenthood
Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   The last complete year of data for pregnancies and abortions was
1996, and by then the pregnancy rate was down to 61.5 per 1,000 and
the abortion rate was 19.
</P>
<P>
   Teen birth figures for 1998, the last available year, show the
rate had fallen 18 percent during the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the numbers dropped for several reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Fear of AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread education about contraception, plus newer and more
reliable methods such as implants and injectable contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   More conservative attitudes, making casual sex less acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Abstinence and safe sex practices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the declines, four of 10 American girls still become
pregnant at least once before they reach age 20, resulting in 1
million teen pregnancies a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Guttmacher Institute's figures show white and Hispanic teens
choose birth over abortion more often than their black
counterparts. Data from 1995 show 67 percent of white pregnant
teens gave birth to live babies, while 16 percent had abortions.
The remaining pregnancies ended in miscarriages or stillbirths.
</P>
<P>
   Among blacks, 49 percent gave birth, and 38 percent chose
abortion. For Hispanics, the figures were 66 percent births, 22
percent abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The number of teens who place their babies for adoption is hard
to determine, because money for studies is lacking and many women
choose to place their babies for adoption privately, according to
the National Council for Adoption.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience of the Children's Home Society of Florida
indicates a strong trend toward parenting rather than placing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of domestic adoptions of newborns has decreased
because it's so much more acceptable in society for teenagers and
single parents of any age to parent than before,'' said Amy
Garvin-Liddell, adoption supervisor for the society's local office.
</P>
<P>
   The office may work with 20 to 30 birth mothers a year, but have
only a fraction of them decide to put their children up for
adoption, Garvin-Liddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinics that provide abortion and contraception services say the
most disturbing element they encounter now is the increasing
numbers of barely pubescent girls engaging in sex. They show up
with their mothers or ``way older boyfriends,'' one clinic worker
said, because they're too young to drive and they have no money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
