<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TREASURE0807-COX     08-06 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURE0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salvors fight to keep precious treasure
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A Virginia federal appeals court ruling,
upholding Spain's legal ownership of a long-lost galleon sunk in
U.S. waters in 1750, has infuriated Florida's underwater salvors,
who fear the decision may deprive them of the thrill and profit of
one of the most exciting jobs imaginable: seeking sunken treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The decision involved the wreck of the Galga (''Greyhound,'' in
Spanish) off the Virginia coast. Diver Ben Benson of Sea Hunt Inc.
had located the Galga, along with another wreck, the 1802 Juno.
Armed with a state permit, Benson was exploring the Galga and
salvaging its cargo of gold and silver coins, when the government
of Spain stepped forward in 1998 and claimed both wrecks as its
property.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court ruled that the Juno belonged to Spain, but that
the Galga did not, because the 1763 Treaty of Paris ceded ``all
that Spain possesses on the continent of North America, to the East
or South East of the river Mississippi'' to Great Britain. Spain
appealed, saying the treaty applied to land, not warships. In late
July, a federal appeals court overturned the lower court decision
and ruled in Spain's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could mark a sea-change in the legal status of
shipwrecks, precisely at the time underwater technology is making
them easier and easier to find.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is especially rich in wrecks of all periods, so many
that Florida State University offers a program in marine
archaeology. Sunken ships in thousands lie along the state's
1,200-mile-long coast, though few contain treasure, and the ones
that did have mostly been found and stripped of their precious
cargoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible that Spain made this claim,'' said Taffi
Fisher-Abt, who is the daughter of the late Mel Fisher, discoverer
of the fabulously rich wreck of the Nuestra Senora de Atocha in
1985. Fisher salvaged $400 million worth of gold, silver and
artifacts from the Atocha and waged a successful legal battle
against the state of Florida all the way to the Supreme Court, to
hold onto his treasure. His daughter today runs the Mel Fisher
Museum in Sebastian.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher died in 1998, but his company, managed by his son, Kim,
continues to search for sunken gold. The firm is currently
exploring a fleet of 12 Spanish vessels that sank in 1715 off Vero
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for us salvagers, there wouldn't be anything to
fight over. I don't see Spain putting up the money to search for
any ships anywhere, but when we find one, all of a sudden they get
interested,'' Fisher-Abt said.
</P>
<P>
   New finds emerged from the Atocha wreck only last month, and the
wreck's riches may be far from exhausted. Kim Fisher displayed
three solid gold bars, 120 silver coins, several gold chains, a
gold medallion that may be of Aztec origin, and other pieces of
Indian jewelry from South America. The latest finds may be worth as
much as $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher-Abt said she doubts the Virginia decision will affect her
family's rights to the Atocha and its contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that, whatever happens, we would be
grandfathered in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia salvor Ben Benson, whose Sea Hunt firm got a permit to
search for the Galga in 1992 and located it in 1996 after sinking
$2 million into the search, could not be reached for comment.
Others welcomed the federal court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of happy doubloon-hunting have been running out for
some time now,'' said Florida state archaeologist Jim Miller.
``This is just one more stage in the never-ending saga of legal
complications about shipwrecks, but the court's decision
reestablishes a fundamental principle of law and sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   Key West admiralty attorney Edward Horan disagreed. Horan's firm
successfully represented Mel Fisher in his fight to keep the Atocha
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just muddies the waters, if you will pardon a figure of
speech,'' Horan said. ``This case begs to be taken to the Supreme
Court, and I hope it will be. This decision completely changes the
way admiralty law has traditionally viewed an abandoned vessel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia court decision hinged on an obscure point of
admiralty law and the principle of ``abandonment.'' There are two
types of abandonment, implied and express.
</P>
<P>
   The law grants more leeway to salvaging commercial vessels,
because after a long period of time their abandonment is implied.
</P>
<P>
   But military vessels fall into a different category. To be fair
game for salvagers, the court ruled, a military vessel like the
Galga must have been expressly abandoned, by some formal act or
expression on the part of its owner. The Spanish government argued
in court that the Galga was a warship, that it had never been
expressly abandoned, and that it was therefore still Spanish
government property. The federal appeals court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The Galga case pitted Benson and the state of Virginia not only
against the government of Spain, but those of the United States and
Great Britain as well. Both countries filed briefs supporting
Spain's claim to the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater technology is locating ships of all ages at fantastic
depths. The Titanic, the Lusitania, the Bismarck, the Britannic and
the U.S. aircraft carrier Yorktown have all been found within the
past few years. In 1999, Gus Grissom's Liberty Bell 7 Mercury
capsule was found and retrieved from the bottom of the Atlantic
Ocean, where it had rested for 31 years at a depth of nearly 3
miles _ a mile deeper than the wreck of the Titanic. It only took
two weeks to locate the capsule on April 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The salvors' position is simple: Finders keepers. Underwater
treasure-hunting is a gamble, risking both money and life. Fisher's
quest for the Atocha cost the lives of four people, including a
son, when a search vessel capsized in the middle of the night.
After he found the ancient hoard, worth $400 million, he gave one
artifact to Spain as a gift to Queen Sofia: a single cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Ben Benson fights it. I hope he appeals it all the way
to the Supreme Court. It's kind of a tragedy,'' Fisher-Abt said.
</P>
<P>
   Another treasure hunter, Peter Leo of Sebastian, responded to
the ruling with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hell with the U.S. government, and the hell with Spain,''
said Leo, who has located the 1659 wreck of the San Miguel de
Archangel off Jupiter Inlet. ``Why don't we just give all the gold
back to the Indians of Bolivia, Peru and Colombia? It came out of
their homeland, after all. They're the ones the Spaniards stole it
from.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Leo has salvaged 10,000 silver coins, 30 gold coins, two
4-pound gold bars and one 80-pound silver bar. Under an agreement
with the state of Florida, 80 percent of the treasure belongs to
Leo's for-profit company, Jupiter Wreck Inc., and about 20 percent
belongs to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all the best stuff goes to the state. They get first pick
of the primo, pretty stuff, the nicest coins and so on. I'm not
complaining, though. We've got a good agreement, and I am hoping to
find the mother lode. If that happens, I can keep duplicates of the
coins we've already handed over to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo, who works full-time as a lifeguard and part-time as a
treasure hunter, discovered the wreck in 1987. He saw only vague
outlines in the sand to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no wood, just imprints. It was a shallow beach
wreck, buried under about 10 to 15 feet of sand. As the sand washed
away, I saw the remnants of cannons and anchors. Then as we blew
more of the sand away, we found more and more things.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are highly variable around the wreck, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days, the water is gin-clear. Some days, you can't see
your finger in front of your mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo takes a cynical view of Spain's interest in its old wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typical. If we were talking about clay pots, nobody would
be interested. But you put gold and silver out there, the rats come
out to guard the cheese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
