<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MIDWEST0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush appeals to farmers and union members on last leg of Midwest
tourBy Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLIET, Ill. _ Gov. George W. Bush wound up his three-day
whistle stop train tour through the Midwest on Sunday, telling
crowds in steamy central Illinois that he is on the side of farmers
and union members as he worked to win over the state's key swing
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to hear us loud and clear. Even though the economy
is changing, there are certain things that are really important and
won't change,'' Bush said at a rally in Joliet, the first of three
Sunday. ``One of them is the ability to feed ourselves, feed our
family, feed our world. This is an administration that will never
forget the American farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   In shirtsleeves with wife, Laura, by his side, he looked into
the crowd and said: ``I appreciate the man down there carrying the
union sign. We welcome you to this camp. We know you're a
hard-working man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and running mate Dick Cheney rode the Victory 2000 Express
through Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan last week before winding up
their tour in Illinois. On Sunday, the train took them through the
corn and soy bean fields of central Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, the crowds were enthusasitc and large. In
Normal, 8,000 people came out to hear Bush and Cheney talk for
about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush heads west for another train tour, this one
through California. He will travel with Arizona Sen. John McCain,
the man who delivered a blistering challenge during the primaries
and who is now working to help Bush win over wavering Democrats and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started off Sunday morning attending services at Sharon
United Methodist Church, a small, three-story church in Plainfield,
Ill. Cheney and his wife, Lynne, and House Speaker Dennis Hastert
and his wife, Jean, also attended. Afterward, Bush said he intended
to win Illinois, a state no Republican has carried since his father
won the state in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   A Chicago Tribune poll taken July 19-23 had Gore with 42 percent
and Bush with 40 percent. Released July 30, the poll of 900 likely
registered voters had a margin of error of three percentage points.
Nationally, the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll had Bush at 54
percent and Gore at 37 percent. The poll of 653 likely voters was
taken Friday and Saturday and had a margin of error of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Across Illinois on Sunday, Bush told the sign-waving crowds
gathered in tiny towns that he wanted to share his ideas. On
Sunday, as he traveled to a rally in Normal, a woman in the tiny
town of Odell let him know loud and clear what she was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   As the train pulled into town, Bush caught sight of the woman
bent over, her pants pulled down and the phrase: ``Raise the Min
Wage'' scrawled across her buttocks. Bush favors raising the
mininum wage so long as states can opt out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' Bush said. ``You just got on national TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right!'' the woman responded, as she pulled up her pants.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, Bush turned to a cameraman filming the scene and said:
``Did you get her?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes, asked if reporters had
seen the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we asked people to get behind Gov. Bush, that's not
exactly what we had in mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
