<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MISSOURI-POLITICS-NYT     08-06 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTHRIGHT AN ISSUE IN ST. LOUIS FREE-FOR-ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ William L. Clay, who created a stir more than 30
years ago when he became Missouri's first black congressman, is
creating another one by retiring, setting off a free-for-all for a
seat that hasn't been open since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, the senior member of his state's congressional delegation,
is working feverishly to help his son, state Sen. William L. Clay
Jr., succeed him in Missouri's 1st Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Clay, who is widely known by his middle name,
Lacy, is confronting a crowded field of competitors in this heavily
Democratic district, which includes the largely black north side of
St. Louis and large swath of St. Louis County, a predominantly
white suburban area.
</P>
<P>
   While there are five candidates in next Tuesday's Democratic
Party primary, the two considered the most serious _ and who are
spending the most money _ are Clay and Charlie Dooley, a member of
the St. Louis County Council, the governmental body in the area
just outside the city. Of the five, only Clay and Dooley hold
elective office.
</P>
<P>
   The race is being eagerly watched because it could affect how
Missouri's congressional districts are redrawn next year,
particularly as they relate to the adjacent district represented by
Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   But it also being watched because it is a contest where race
provides a subtle but profound undercurrent, even though both major
contenders are black.
</P>
<P>
   Black residents make up slightly more than half of the district,
but about 60 percent of registered voters are white.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley has maintained that the Clay campaign is trying to
energize the black electorate against him by asserting that
Dooley's role as a county official makes him less concerned about
blacks in the city of St. Louis. At the same time, the Dooley
campaign has made nepotism an issue, asserting that while the
father has been a suitable congressman, the seat is not the
birthright of the son.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it,'' Dooley said, ``there is a
racial dynamic here. Because I'm from the county and most of my
political allies are from the county and white, it's been portrayed
by the other camp that I'm not black enough. That's stupid talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay vehemently denies the accusation. ``I have never engaged in
racially divisive politics and I never will,'' he said. ``That's
not my style.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clay, who has been in the Missouri legislature for 17 years,
bristles at the suggestion of nepotism. ``No one is trying to
inherit anything,'' Clay said. ``I am going in front of the voters
like I have eight previous times. I am asking for their vote based
on my record and my accomplishments. I find that suggestion
insulting.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Clay name is well known in the St. Louis area, and the
congressman has worked hard to pass along much of his support and
campaign organization to his son, the younger Clay's election is by
no means assured.
</P>
<P>
   Clay's base is in the city of St. Louis, from the trim brick
homes along Fairground Park to the dilapidated storefronts along
the north side and the stylish restaurants and stores in the
Central West End. While the city of St. Louis once made up all of
the district, the area has been bruised by an exodus of people and
jobs. The decline in the population has pushed the district's
boundaries far into the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   That means Clay must work harder to get votes from an area where
Dooley has far greater influence.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been other problems for Clay in a race that has
grown increasingly acrimonious. For one thing, though his father
has long been known as a champion of organized labor, Clay has not
won the support of the state AFL-CIO. For the first time in recent
memory, the union declined to make an endorsement in the race,
saying instead that its affiliate labor organizations should make
their own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Dooley camp has accused Clay of a series of ethical
lapses. Most prominently, it has attacked Clay because he once
worked for a medical supply company operated by two brothers who
have been charged with Medicare and Medicaid fraud in Atlanta. And
Dooley's aides have charged that Clay failed to include his
relationship with the company on financial disclosure forms.
</P>
<P>
   Clay acknowledged that he worked for the company as a sales
representative, but ended his relationship with it two years ago.
He added that there had been no hint that the business had done
anything improper in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   And Clay has sued Dooley, charging that his campaign established
a special committee to illegally evade the limits on campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   While the candidates' character and fitness have emerged as
central themes, the two major candidates agree on virtually every
significant issue. Both want to use more federal money to hire new
teachers, and agree that health care should be more widely
available. They oppose the death penalty and support abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Their styles are hardly similar. The 52-year-old Dooley, a thin,
well dressed man who recently retired after 30 years with the
Boeing Corp. as a manager in the microfilm department, often
appears serious and earnest. Lacy Clay, 43, in contrast, is a
gregarious legislator who was seems as comfortable slapping the
backs of his fellow senators as dancing with school children at an
outdoor festival in his district.
</P>
<P>
   The contest could well have broader long-term implications on
Missouri's congressional districts. Since the cardinal rule of
redistricting is to protect incumbents, a victory by Clay would
likely put pressure of the legislature to preserve the district's
St. Louis neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But if Dooley wins, legislators will most likely shift the
district's boundaries farther into the suburbs of St. Louis County.
That would enable legislators to extend Gephardt's district north,
into the heavily black _ and securely Democratic _ terrain of St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading candidates are working tirelessly, each
portraying himself as the front-runner. Many politicians suggest
that Dooley will benefit from a strong showing in the county and
from the support of many of its elected officials and some labor
groups.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Clay can expect strong support from other
union locals as well as by the endorsement of most elected
officials in St. Louis. And while Clay insists that the
congressional seat is not an inheritance, he shows no reluctance to
invoke his father's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father has been very involved in this race,'' Clay said.
``And I admire and revere my father. In politics, they say, you
inherit your father's friends and enemies. Fortunately, he has more
friends than enemies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
