<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GLADIOLUS0807-COX     08-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADIOLUS0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gladiolus grower keeps ``plugging away''
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When residents of the Winston Trails
development decorate their homes with fresh gladioluses from
Publix, they probably don't know the popular cut flowers once grew
where their homes now sit.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban site is just one of many parcels of land used over
the years by Mazzoni Farms Inc., which has grown gladioluses in
southern Palm Beach County for nearly six decades.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were dozens of gladiolus growers in the area in
the 1940s and 1950s, Mazzoni is the only one that has hung on as
the others dropped out. Today, Mazzoni Farms, is the only gladiolus
farm in Southeast Florida and one of a handful of growers in the
state, which is the nation's largest producer of the tall, flowered
stems.
</P>
<P>
   But President Bill Mazzoni, whose father started the business
here in 1941, said his day is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a life expectancy now, too,'' said Mazzoni, 52, who
predicts he'll have to get out of the business, maybe in only five
years.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scenario facing farmers of all types in Palm Beach
County: Development pressures, coupled with threats from imports
produced with low-cost labor, are conspiring to push them out.
</P>
<P>
   For most local growers of other types of cut flowers, the
shakeout happened earlier, as imports from Colombia and Ecuador
began pouring into the United States in the mid-1980s. Lower labor
and regulatory costs meant foreign producers could pay to ship
flowers to the United States and still sell them for less, said
Bill Schall, a nursery extension agent for Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   As a gladiolus grower, Mazzoni was somewhat insulated because
the sheer weight of the long stems made them too expensive to
transport by air, eliminating South American growers as
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The business remained in good shape even as the North American
Free Trade Agreement went into effect in 1994, hammering Florida
vegetable growers with cheap imports from Mexico. That's because
Mexico did not produce gladioluses _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is just beginning to get into the business, Mazzoni said,
which means trucking across the border will become economically
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a serious nail in the coffin,'' he said. ``Once
they figure it out, they will be so cheap it won't pay to grow
flowers in the United States anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As development moves closer to fields and leasable land becomes
more scarce, ``the writing is on the wall,'' Mazzoni said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it has become more profitable to build homes on southern
Palm Beach County farmland than to grow vegetables or flowers, said
Bob Blankenship, an economic researcher for the Florida Department
of Agriculture. ``With that squeeze, and then with NAFTA coming
along, it speeds things up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, Mazzoni plugs away, planting about 25 million
bulbs a year on 900 acres he leases from rancher Billy Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Planting season begins next month and runs through the middle of
March. Machines drop the bulbs, which are harvested from the
previous year's crop and stored at 38 degrees in the off-season.
Workers follow behind to space them and turn them upright.
</P>
<P>
   The mature stalks are harvested by hand also, between November
and June, with workers walking the rows day after day and cutting
only those spikes that are just about to open.
</P>
<P>
   Gladiolus bulbs have a three-year life, growing tall
asparagus-like spikes that love sun and temperatures in the 70s.
After that, new bulbs are used and fields typically are rotated to
help replenish nutrients. During the season, Mazzoni employs about
150 workers, mostly migrants, some of whom are housed in a camp
across from the company's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Mazzoni Farms employed more than 200 during the
season, but that also included people who worked for the company's
nursery business. Mazzoni said he left the foliage business in the
early 1990s, after losing millions because of plant damage from
DuPont Co.'s Benlate fungicide and watching volume chains such as
Wal-Mart push prices lower and lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep plugging along,'' Mazzoni said of his
gladiolus business. ``There is no intent to quit, but economics
will say when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   During the harvest season, Mazzoni ships 150,000 stems a day to
wholesale florists and grocery chains throughout the country.
Publix is his largest customer, though he will not disclose
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Florida growers received an average of 28.4 cents for each
gladiolus spike from wholesale buyers in 1999, according to data
from the Florida Department of Agriculture. Prices aren't much
higher on the retail end, with Publix supermarkets typically
selling a 10-spike bunch for $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   With 25 million bulbs in the ground, Mazzoni's goal is to sell
25 million spikes in a year. Each bulb typically produces one
spiked stem. Florida's two other major gladiolus growers are in the
Fort Myers, Bradenton and Palmetto areas.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzoni, whose father died two years ago, still owns about 480
acres. Most of that he leases to other farmers, preferring to lease
Bowman's 900 contiguous acres for his own operation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
