<HEADLINE>
GLYNN STRIKES A CHORD
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
TORONTO _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates has been almost begging his
young starters to throw more strikes. Ryan Glynn heard the
manager's plea and took the advice to heart.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glynn survived a three-run homer by Dave Martinez in the first
inning and pitched the Rangers to an 11-6 victory against the
Toronto Blue Jays at SkyDome yesterday. After Martinez went deep,
Glynn retired 20 of the next 24 batters he faced, giving his
teammates a chance to go to work on the Blue Jays' pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had real good stuff today,'' Glynn said. ``I felt strong.
That's not exactly the way you want to start. After losing the
first three games here, I wanted to give my team a chance to win. I
knew the guys didn't want to get swept.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn's effort and 16 hits from his teammates, including three
doubles by Mike Lamb, allowed the Rangers to avoid a four-game
sweep at the hands of the Blue Jays. In the clubhouse afterward,
the manager rejoiced, not about avoiding the sweep but by the sight
of one of his young pitchers going after hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him so, too,'' Oates said. ``Maybe it will set the tone
for everybody else. It can be done. He did it extremely well. Down
3-0 before you crack a sweat, pitching the way he did, that was a
veteran performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also praised the work of backup catcher B.J. Waszgis, who
made his first major-league start. Waszgis had two hits, and Oates
said he worked well with Glynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very composed,'' Oates said. ``When I went to the mound, he
knew exactly what he wanted to do. Glynn and Waszgis did a super
job working together. They came right after hitters, saying: `Here
it is. Hit it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Glynn: ``What I worried about last year was about throwing
strikes and not walking hitters. What I'm doing now is just make
the hitters hit the ball. My defense is doing a great job. When I
get into trouble is when I start trying to strike people out. I get
overaggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn said that's what happened in the seventh after he struck
out Craig Grebeck for the second out. The Rangers were leading 7-4,
but Shannon Stewart and Alex Gonzalez both singled and Glynn walked
Martinez to load the bases, bringing up Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my team in a position where it could lose the game,''
Glynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Venafro bailed Glynn out, getting Delgado to swing at a
first-pitch fastball and ground out to second base to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's hit that pitch out of the ballpark 10 times this
year,'' Venafro said. ``He just got on top of it this time.''
</P>
<P>
   With Glynn keeping the Blue Jays at bay, the offense was able to
come back against Blue Jays starter Kelvim Escobar and three
relievers. They erased the early damage with three runs in the
third on Ricky Ledee's two-out, run-scoring single and a two-run
double by Scott Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went ahead for good in the fifth on a run-scoring
single by Rusty Greer. Rafael Palmeiro followed that with a double
into the right-field corner that made it 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon, giving Royce Clayton a day off at shortstop, continues
to show his value as a utility player. He went 2-for-5, with a
run-scoring single in the ninth inning and is now hitting .295.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a lot of work and a lot of preparation,'' Sheldon
said. ``I try not to do much when I get in there. The tendency is
to try and impress or do something really good. I just try to swing
at good pitches and put a good swing on the ball.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
