<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-RDP-810&AMP;ADD-NY     08-06 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-RDP-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CONFLICT EXPECTED AT REFORM PARTY'S CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Months of bickering and conflict are expected to reach a
crescendo of sorts this week, when the Reform Party gathers to
nominate a presidential candidate at its national convention in
Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the tame and carefully planned Republican convention that
anointed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas on Thursday, the four-day
meeting of Reform Party members promises some sharp skirmishes as
the delegates choose between Pat Buchanan and John Hagelin for the
party's presidential nomination and the $12.6 million in federal
campaign funds that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   The party has moved into such contentious terrain that Ross
Perot, the party founder and two-time presidential candidate, has
had virtually nothing to do with it in the last few years. So far
as anyone can tell, he has made no plans to attend the convention.
Nor has Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, the only Reform Party
member ever elected to such high office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a war over the direction of the Reform Party,'' said
Russell J. Verney, the party's former chairman and a leading force
against Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders on both sides of a dispute over Buchanan's candidacy
agree that what happens in Long Beach will go a long way toward
defining the party's future _ either one based on governmental
reform as envisioned by Perot or, if Buchanan wins the nomination,
one based on the conservative positions he has championed for
years, like opposition to abortion, affirmative action, illegal
immigration and homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   That Buchanan has made his fight against those issues the
hallmark of his presidential campaign represents the major source
of conflict within the party.
</P>
<P>
   While Perot's brand of Reform Party was always silent on those
issues because they were divisive and exclusionary, Buchanan has
brought them to the fore, as he did again Sunday on a round of
morning talk shows, offering further evidence to his opponents that
he intends to transform the party into a haven for social
conservatives and disaffected right-wing Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the Republican Party for excluding conservatives at
its nominating convention last week, Buchanan said on CBS' ``Face
the Nation'' that ``there wasn't a single voice up there for the
unborn, there was nobody that got up and spoke about right to
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Colin Powell, the former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff and a major speaker at the Republican convention,
Buchanan said on ABC's ``This Week'': ``Affirmative action, quotas,
racial preferences are wrong. They're unjust discrimination against
white folks because of the color of their skin or where their
ancestors came from, and I don't care if General Powell gets up and
says they're right. For heaven's sakes, why did not a single
Republican get up and say `That is wrong'?''
</P>
<P>
   After a lifetime as a Republican, Buchanan joined the Reform
Party last year and set off to re-energize it by recruiting voters
and party organizers. It worked. But the stronger his forces
became, the more he worried longtime party members, especially
Perot supporters, who feared their founding principles would be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on several programs Sunday, Buchanan accused them of
trying to destroy the party by blocking his efforts and ``simply
mixing the Kool Aid for the party,'' as he said on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The feuding factions will not even wait until the official start
of the convention, on Thursday, to open fire.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it all starts Tuesday morning, when the party's
national committee _ three people from every state and the District
of Columbia, plus the 11 members of the executive committee _ meets
to consider challenges over who has the right to serve on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan campaign, which called for the meeting, has
challenged as many as 30 people, the seating of whom would have a
huge bearing on who wins the nomination. By party rules, the
Buchanan supporters need a two-thirds majority on the national
committee _ they say they need just a simple majority _ to settle a
dispute over who is chairman of the convention credentials
committee.
</P>
<P>
   That is important because if the Buchanan forces prevail, their
man, Frank Reid, the Ohio state chairman, would oversee the
convention credential process and play a persuasive role in
settling more than 40 delegate challenges, which affects the
seating of hundreds of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   By party rules, a candidate can ask that the primary vote, which
began last month and concludes this week, be set aside so that the
delegates, by a two-thirds vote, can choose the party nominee.
</P>
<P>
   By controlling the delegates, Buchanan would not have to worry
about the possibility that Hagelin, a quantum physicist who has run
for president twice before on the Natural Law Party ticket but has
uncertain support within the Reform Party, would win the popular
vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The national committee is also scheduled to resolve another key
issue: whether a recent vote by the executive committee to
disqualify Buchanan from the primary should stand.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin has accused the Buchanan campaign of corrupting the
primary process by submitting the names of ineligible voters to be
sent ballots. A panel was appointed to review the charge, and it
asked both campaigns to provide material that proved the legitimacy
of the names they submitted.
</P>
<P>
   After Buchanan's campaign refused, the panel recommended that he
be disqualified, a decision that the executive committee supported
by vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan forces assert that the executive committee vote was
improper, sending the dispute before the national committee.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tension and conflict, Buchanan seems not to be
affected in the least. He has boldly predicted that he will win the
nomination, saying Sunday on ``Fox News Sunday,'' ``I think you
will see at Long Beach the fact that this is a Buchanan party, a
conservative party, reform party and populist party, and you will
be surprised at the unanimity.''
</P>
<P>
   One who certainly will be surprised if there is unanimity is
Hagelin. He said last week that if Buchanan won the nomination by
any spurious means, he would sue him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
