<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEWS-FUTURE-MEDIA-NYT     08-06 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-FUTURE-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING ONLINE AUDIENCES NEWS THEY WANT 
</HEADLINE>
  By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is how Jonathan Klein, a former high-level executive at
CBS, sees the future of news:
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will click on video reports they want to see, when they
want to see them. Computerized news services will learn users'
viewing habits and offer them news bits tailored to their tastes.
Advertisers will aim at viewers based on their supposed news
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Klein is so sure that his vision of the future is accurate that
he is staking $35 million in venture capital on a new Web site,
FeedRoom, which is to make its public debut later this month.
</P>
<P>
   FeedRoom is one of a handful of new Web sites offering users
television-style news reports on the Internet, in digestible bits
that can be put together into personalized newscasts. Yahoo has a
similar offering, as does Zatso.com, a new company from San
Francisco. Another site, called Jagfn.com, posts video reports
about financial news.
</P>
<P>
   These services are based on the new-media assumptions that
consumers want information and entertainment on demand and that
high-speed Internet connections, offered by broadband services, can
finally give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to watch good news, you'll watch good news; if you
like to watch crime news, you'll watch crime news,'' said Klein,
who was executive vice president of CBS News from 1995 to 1998.
``It's putting the clicker in the viewer's hand and saying, `You
decide.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the not too distant future, Klein predicts, this new
style of newscast will replace the traditional news fare of the
major networks and local TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that prediction is an accurate one and whether it would
be a step forward or back for journalism are matters of heavy
debate in the television news industry, which is struggling to hang
on to viewers amid increased competition.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Klein is right, analysts say, it is not clear that
sites like his would be well received by people not yet accustomed
to watching anything resembling TV on computers that, for the most
part, have poor pictures and make for uncomfortable viewing.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Klein's news service is among the most ambitious
attempts yet to recreate a television news experience on the
Internet. Though the concept has been around for a while, it has
been slow to take off because of inadequacies in Internet
technology.
</P>
<P>
   And the more established news providers have been hesitant. They
are waiting to see which business models will survive and how
viewing habits will develop, once more people have broadband, or
high-speed, Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   FeedRoom, which will require users to have broadband
connections, is meant to be user friendly, with a central video
window occupying one-quarter of the computer screen (currently,
video windows occupy only about one-sixteenth). The main window is
flanked by smaller ones advertising the available reports. A
separate box offers viewers links to different types of reports
under categories like health, entertainment, finance and sports.
</P>
<P>
   The reports will be provided by local stations around the
country that have struck deals to provide video to FeedRoom, which
in return will share advertising revenue and design the stations'
individual Web pages. Last week, Klein announced two such
agreements with the NBC television station group and Tribune
Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   What stops these major media companies from doing it themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a very large, successful broadcast business that
we have to continue to run and grow,'' said Jay Ireland, president
of the NBC station group. ``These guys had a combination that
proved very valuable, and it gets us out there quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   With the NBC and Tribune deals in place, FeedRoom now has ties
to 32 TV stations that reach 45 percent of the country's television
markets. Klein said he hoped to complete similar deals with other
big television networks by the end of the year. Although no major
advertiser is signed yet, he said he had enough financing _ from
investors like Warburg Pincus, Ridgewood Capital and Intel _ to
operate for two years without ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But FeedRoom is designed with advertisers well in mind, and
Klein said he expected to close some deals soon. The site is
equipped with software that can identify users and, based on what
segments they tend to select, aim specific banner ads at them. The
system is also programmed to give on-screen prominence to the types
of segments an individual viewer tends to choose.
</P>
<P>
   The automatic winnowing is worrisome to many journalists and
media experts, who fear that the proliferation of personalized news
will enable viewers to filter out information that is important but
may not be sizzling entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business model might do a very good job of supporting
narrow content for things like sports or business or health,'' said
John V. Pavlik, executive director of Columbia University's Center
for New Media. ``But I'm not so confident that the business model
will support public affairs journalism. Who, exactly, is going to
be the sponsor for that type of news?''
</P>
<P>
   Some network news executives said last week that they shared
that concern, especially in light of the low TV ratings for last
week's Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has potentially enormous implications for not only how we
do our business, but also for our democracy,'' said Andrew Heyward,
president of CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   But while ``it has implications for the citizenry that might be
disturbing, that doesn't mean you can stop it,'' he added. ``This
is where the technology is heading.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, big-network news executives like Heyward seem satisfied
to sit back and monitor expensive experiments like Klein's. ``The
FeedRoom is one of what are going to be numerous experiments in the
early days of broadband,'' Heyward said. ``No one knows which is
going to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have little research on which to base forecasts because
of the embryonic state of broadband Internet access _ whose 31
million users so far are mostly office workers and college
students, according FeedRoom's research.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not stop analysts from debating whether computer
users are ready for personalized, TV-style, online newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to do broadband video right now,'' said David
Card, a media analyst with Jupiter Communications. ``Point one:
There aren't a lot of people who have broadband. Point two: Even in
broadband, it's not a beautiful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein acknowledged the challenges. ``It's an enormous risk,'' he
said. ``But the rewards are enormous if this thing works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 1913EDT &QL; 
