<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     08-06 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD DOESN'T GET IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield is losing his grip on reality.
</P>
<P>
   He believes he actually has a right to fight for the world
championship Saturday when he faces John Ruiz, and he contends he
should be champion anyway because he should have been given the
decision against Lennox Lewis in their second bout.
</P>
<P>
   OK, technically, he's right on the first count. He and Ruiz
!ital!are fighting for the WBA version of the title that was
stripped from Lewis when he refused to fight the No. 1 contender,
Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   However, everyone knows that Lewis _ holder of the IBF and WBC
belts _ is the man no matter what happens Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Holyfield-Ruiz is a sham of sorts. Lewis twice
beat Holyfield (once officially) and without question is the top
heavyweight in the world while Ruiz, a journeyman heavyweight, was
once knocked out in 19 seconds by David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Holyfield was among those who lobbied to have Lewis
stripped of his title even though he knows a divided heavyweight
championship is bad for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Holyfield disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't follow the rules, you lose your title,'' he said.
``I follow the rules. I fought (mandatory challenger Vaughn) Bean.
I would've had to fight (Henry) Akinwande (before the fight fell
through) or I would've been stripped of the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, we'll give him that point on a technicality. However, in
no way did he win his second bout with Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield barely concedes he lost their first bout, one which
almost all impartial observers saw as an easy victory for Lewis
that lousy (corrupt?) judges scored a draw.
</P>
<P>
   The second bout was closer but still a clear victory for Lewis,
whose combination of size and talent is too much for the smaller
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it sounded a bit absurd when Holyfield said:
``Anybody who watched (the second) fight knows I did beat Lennox.
They always talk about the first fight. . . . The next fight, they
thought, 'We corrected it and made it right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no complaint. I understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems as if Holyfield really !ital!doesn't
understand. For the sake of Lewis and the sport, at least the rest
of us do.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hype begins: Fernando Vargas tried to keep focus on his Aug.
26 bout with Ross Thompson during a teleconference call last week _
but he didn't try too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he's thrilled at the prospect of fighting Felix
Trinidad in December and couldn't keep his enthusiasm in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everything I've ever wished for, everything I've prayed
to God for,'' said Vargas, a resident of Oxnard, Calif..
</P>
<P>
   The deal's not done yet, although both sides say they're very
close to an agreement for Dec. 2 in Las Vegas. If it happens, it
could be the best matchup yet among a rich pool of fighters in the
welterweight and junior middleweight divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the first question is about Vargas' relative lack of
experience: 19 pro fights. One wonders whether he'll experience a
fate similar to that of David Reid, another young fighter whom was
beaten unmercilessly by Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, 22, said he heard similar things before title fights
with Yory ``Boy'' Campas, Raul Marquez and Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think David Reid had the mentality to deal with the
crowd, the magnitude of the fight,'' he said. ``He respected
Trinidad too much. I definitely believe he was thinking, `Oh, my
God. I'm fighting Felix Trinidad.'
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I'm comfortable at this level, I've been able to perform
at this level. I feel I'm ready for Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious question mark is Trinidad's undeniable power:
What will happen when Vargas gets tagged?
</P>
<P>
   Vargas contends he has a good chin _ ``My trainer (Eduardo
Garcia) says I have the jaw of a mule'' _ and results support that
contention: He's never been knocked down or seriously hurt.
However, he doesn't plan to allow Trinidad's power to become a
significant issue: He won't engage Trinidad in a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an intelligent fighter,'' he said. ``If you go to war, you
get busted up and you have a good chance of getting knocked out
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight a smart war.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he doesn't believe Trinidad has any more power than he
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, he has power,'' Vargas said, ``but he has no
more power than I do and he's not a stronger junior middleweight
like some people think. I'm going to show that Aug. 26.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More Vargas: Some experts believe Vargas has surpassed Oscar
De La Hoya as a fighter, particularly after Vargas' impressive
victory over Ike Quartey and De La Hoya's losses to Trinidad and
Shane Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas won't come out and say as much, but he certainly won't
argue with the prevailing thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just analyze it. Putting it simple, I make adjustments to beat
fighters, whatever that might be,'' he said, referring to De La
Hoya's inability to adjust when Mosley took control of their fight
in the final six rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas went on: ``I don't think you should blame the trainers
(for De La Hoya's performance). At the end of the day, you're the
one in the ring fighting. It's all up to you. You have to think,
`I'm getting blistered all over the place. I might as well change
up something,' maybe feint and come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane Mosley had a great fight plan, he fought a great
intelligent fight. He made Oscar fight his fight. I definitely
think De La Hoya went in a one-dimensional way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see when I fight, I box when I have to box and punch
when I have to punch. I beat everyone at their game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Friday is a busy day for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Robinson faces Vivian Harris in a 10-round lightweight bout
in Atlantic City, N.J., on ESPN2, which should be a typical
action-packed Robinson fight.
</P>
<P>
   And, in Las Vegas, Tim Austin defends his IBF bantamweight title
against Arthur Johnson on Showtime. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Lacierva takes on David Vasquez in a 12-round bantamweight
bout Sunday in Reno on Univision. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
