<P>
   HARLEM-BAPTISM (New York) _ Each August since 1937, the United
House of Prayer, a non-denominational Pentecostal church that
claims 3 million congregants in 28 states, has held mass baptisms
on 115th Street in East Harlem, using a fire hose to spray some 500
to 800 participants with baptismal waters. The church holds mass
baptisms across the country each summer as part of an annual
convocation ceremony in which congregants seek repentance and holy
renewal. By Nina Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-PLANETS (Undated) _ Where there is one planet around a star,
there are likely to be more. At least, that is the view of
astronomers at the University of California at Berkeley. The reason
astronomers have not sighted more multiple-planet systems, they
say, is simply that they have not looked long enough. Dr. Debra A.
Fischer, a postdoctoral fellow at Berkeley, re-examined data from
12 stars known to have one planet to see if they contained
unnoticed evidence of other planets. ``Five of them showed extra
wobbles,'' Fischer said. ``That indicates the presence of some
other thing there.'' The findings were presented Sunday at the
International Astronomical Union meeting in Manchester, England. By
Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
