<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-QUIZ0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All I really need to know I forgot during the summer
 &HT;    By Rich Malley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Summer's too short! Still, kids have had plenty
of time to engage in their favorite warm-weather activity: blanking
out everything they learned during the previous school year. So
before they head to class, they should take this pop quiz, which
will give them a clear picture of . . .
</P>
<P>
   1. The sum of the angles of a right triangle is . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. 180 degrees
</P>
<P>
   B. 200 degrees
</P>
<P>
   C. 260 degrees
</P>
<P>
   D. Irrelevant to my future career as a dot.com entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   2. The War of 1812 was fought over . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Land.
</P>
<P>
   B. A pretty girl.
</P>
<P>
   C. Control of the TV remote.
</P>
<P>
   D. A period of time which almost certainly included all or part
of the year 1812.
</P>
<P>
   3. The legislature of the U.S. government is called a bicameral
system because . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two houses of Congress: the House and the, uh,
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   B. It takes a two-camera security system to make sure the
legislators don't steal the treasury blind.
</P>
<P>
   C. It was supposed to be called bi-mackeral but it got
misspelled in the original rulebook.
</P>
<P>
   D. There are two branches of government in addition to the
secretarial branch.
</P>
<P>
   4. Ohm's law states that . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Amperage over voltage equals ohmage.
</P>
<P>
   B. If you plug 4 ohm speakers into your cousin's 8 ohm car
stereo, your chances of survival increase with your distance from
his house when he gets home from work.
</P>
<P>
   C. You cannot transport an underage ohm through a wire that
crosses state lines.
</P>
<P>
   D. All good things shall accrue to Ohm.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``The Great Gatsby'' was about . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. A horse named Gatsby and the boy who loved him.
</P>
<P>
   B. A man named Gatsby who made his living in the 1920s selling
bootleggings.
</P>
<P>
   C. A man named Gatsby who was better than good.
</P>
<P>
   D. The last thing I emptied out of my locker into the trash when
school let out last May.
</P>
<P>
   6. The lowest common denominator is . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. A very important thing to know when dealing with fractions.
</P>
<P>
   B. The number that goes either above or below the line in
fractions.
</P>
<P>
   C. Very possibly the most important term in fractions.
</P>
<P>
   D. Probably who I'll be hanging out with again this year.
</P>
<P>
   7. Chromosomes are . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. The thread of life that is used to sew your genes.
</P>
<P>
   B. The basic tinkertoys of life.
</P>
<P>
   C. Secreted by certain glands, making me unable to concentrate
on anything but the girl who sits across from me in third period.
</P>
<P>
   D. Typically mutated in the members of our football team's
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   8. The 19th Amendment . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Gave women the right to wear slacks.
</P>
<P>
   B. Was necessary because even after the first 18, there was
still more amending to do.
</P>
<P>
   C. Was approved by a jury of its amendment peers.
</P>
<P>
   D. Will finally grant statehood to Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   9. The word ``gerund'' refers to . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. A word beginning with the letter g and ending in e-r-u-n-d.
</P>
<P>
   B. Things which collectively are known as gerunds, but
individually as a gerund.
</P>
<P>
   C. Horst Gerund, the inventor of gerunds.
</P>
<P>
   D. That thing or things described by the word gerund.
</P>
<P>
   10. The publication of Upton Sinclair's ``The Jungle'' had a
major impact on...
</P>
<P>
   A. Suppliers of floor sweepings to Chicago's turn-of-the-century
sausage factories.
</P>
<P>
   B. The Tandem Printing Co.
</P>
<P>
   C. People who had to work in unsafe jungle conditions.
</P>
<P>
   D. How much Mrs. Sinclair could spend at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   11. Ponce de Leon explored Florida in search of . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. The Fountain of Juice.
</P>
<P>
   B. A quiet, safe place to retire.
</P>
<P>
   C. The guy who nicknamed him ``Ponce.''
</P>
<P>
   D. A motel vacancy on I-4 near Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   12. Francis Scott Key wrote the lyrics to ``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. While delirious with fever.
</P>
<P>
   B. On the side of his sneaker.
</P>
<P>
   C. On a dare.
</P>
<P>
   D. Before he fully mastered the English language.
</P>
<P>
   13. Austrian botanist Gregor Mendel's 19th century work with
common garden peas led to the development of . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. A callus on his pea-picking hand.
</P>
<P>
   B. Papa Mendel's Laboratory-Style Frozen Dinner Peas.
</P>
<P>
   C. The dance craze known as the Garden Pea Waltz.
</P>
<P>
   D. An affair with the Widow Schnenken who worked at the local
nursery.
</P>
<P>
   14. A quadratic equation is . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Best used to express the relationship between quadrates.
</P>
<P>
   B. How you know that PE has ended and you're in algebra class
now.
</P>
<P>
   C. Like one of those bad dreams where you're running from
something scary but no matter how fast you move your feet, you
don't get anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   D. Always lesser than and/or equal to and/or more than zero.
</P>
<P>
   15. One of Newton's laws states that an object at rest . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Tends to miss the school bus.
</P>
<P>
   B. Should never be disturbed if it's Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   C. Will usually get called on in Mr. Salinas' physics class.
</P>
<P>
   D. Is likely to be stolen at this school.
</P>
<P>
   16. Eugene V. Debs and Samuel Gompers were important leaders in
. . .
</P>
<P>
   A. The American Flava movement.
</P>
<P>
   B. The Tour de France who were eventually overtaken by Lance
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   C. Something that we talked about in civics class last year.
</P>
<P>
   D. The movement to shorten the school year to three months.
</P>
<P>
   17. A mortgage with a fixed APR of 10 percent is an example of .
. .
</P>
<P>
   A. A topic that is discussed in business classes in American
high schools.
</P>
<P>
   B. The kind of responsibility I will never be entrusted with
unless I start getting better grades soon.
</P>
<P>
   C. A loan that's probably about 1 3/4 points too high based on
the current national average.
</P>
<P>
   D. Something I hope the person I eventually marry will know how
to take care of.
</P>
<P>
   18. Einstein's Theory of Absolute Relativity states that . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. The speed of light gets slower when it gets dark.
</P>
<P>
   B. Hey, it's all relative, so just chill.
</P>
<P>
   C. E &QC; MC2, where E, M and C all mean something.
</P>
<P>
   D. It's absolutely necessary to see your relatives during the
holidays
</P>
<P>
   19. The massive population growth of California in 1849 was
spurred by . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. A lot of people moving to California all at once.
</P>
<P>
   B. The discovery of gold rushing down the California River.
</P>
<P>
   C. The invention of the minivan. vvc
</P>
<P>
   D. Good jobs at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   20. The six commonly used trigonometric functions are . . .
</P>
<P>
   A. Sine, cosine, tangent, cotangent, donner and blitzen.
</P>
<P>
   B. Sleepy, Happy, Doc, Sneezy, Grumpy and, uh . . . um . . .
</P>
<P>
   C. Addition, subtraction, multiplication, percentage, On and
Off.
</P>
<P>
   D. Sine, cosine, tangent, cotangent, secant and . . . Dopey!
</P>
<P>
   SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Tabulate one point for every ``A'' answer, two points for every
``B'' answer, three points for every ``C'' answer and four points
for every ``D'' answer.
</P>
<P>
   RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   0-19 points _ A score below 20 means you weren't able to give
even incorrect answers to all of the questions. That's really
scary.
</P>
<P>
   20-29 points _ The good news is that your score indicates you
forgot nothing you learned in school last year. The bad news is
your score indicates you learned nothing in school last year.
</P>
<P>
   30-49 points _ If you can curtail your Slushie habit now, your
brain may thaw by the time classes start with little or no
permanent damage
</P>
<P>
   50+ points _ Boy, are you smart! You should drop out of school
immediately and find a lucrative job writing back-to-school quizzes
for the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
