<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. ECHOES EUROPEANS IN A PHONE MARKET FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   While the European Union contends that opposition by U.S.
lawmakers to Deutsche Telekom's $50.7 billion offer for VoiceStream
Wireless violates commitments that the United States made to the
World Trade Organization to keep its telecommunications market
open, the United States is making similar arguments against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, says there
is no doubt that Telefonos de Mexico, the former state-owned
monopoly, is thwarting competition and that Mexico is thus not
living up to its WTO commitments.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT'S BUSINESS GOES ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Now that the only year 2000 disaster has turned out to be the
stock prices of dot-com businesses, Internet executives and federal
bureaucrats are taking a much closer look at each other. Thanks to
the year 2000 scare, the government is much smarter about
information technology systems and processes, and it is directing
that knowledge to Internet purchasing efforts. Internet companies,
meanwhile, are looking for any market that can deliver revenue and
keep their businesses afloat.
</P>
<P>
   `BIG BROTHER' HOST SEEKS CREDIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Julie Chen, the news reader on ``The Early
Show,'' as a host of the reality program ``Big Brother'' on CBS
touched off a renewed debate over whether the lines between network
news and entertainment were becoming blurred. Now, executives close
to the program say, Chen is doing what she can to maintain her
stature as a newscaster, fighting with ``Big Brother''
scriptwriters, who have been handing her lines that are hardly the
stuff of news people.
</P>
<P>
   RIVAL HAS MONEY MANAGER'S NAME
</P>
<P>
   Even though Thomas F. Marsico, a money manager at Janus Capital,
left three years ago, his domain name has found its way back to his
old employer. The name tommarsico.com was registered by James P.
Goff, manager of the Janus Enterprise fund. While there have been
dust-ups over domain names before, this may be the first to involve
two investors who manage billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A MEDIA FORUM WIDENS ITS REACH
</P>
<P>
   The MediaNews.org Web site expanded its portfolio with the
publication of a revisionist history of the 1998 controversy
involving the columnist Mike Barnicle of The Boston Globe, who
resigned after accusations that he plagiarized a comedian's jokes
and that he had inadequately verified a story.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSCASTS TAILORED FOR INDIVIDUALS
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Web sites are offering users television-style news
reports on the Internet, in digestible bits that can be put
together into personalized newscasts. These services are based on
the new-media assumptions that consumers want information and
entertainment on demand and that high-speed Internet connections
can finally give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD ACCORDING TO ICE-T
</P>
<P>
   At an industry conference, the rapper Ice-T, a self-described
``conspiracy theorist type of guy,'' shared his views on the
recording industry and the controversy over Napster, the service
that lets people swap music files over the Internet: ``Napster will
resurface in one of these major record companies as a way to share
files. Once they figure out how to take the technology and get paid
off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   BID CONSIDERED FOR SEAGRAM UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bronfman, the uncle of Edgar Bronfman Jr., president of
Seagram, is considering a bid for the liquor division of Seagram,
the family-controlled company that is being sold to Vivendi of
France.
</P>
</TEXT>
