<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SWEPT IN CLEVELAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Anaheim Angels remained 0 for August, and oh so
close to letting a promising season slip away, after a 5-2 loss to
the Cleveland Indians on Sunday before 43,133 at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians completed a three-game sweep of the Angels, who have
lost five in a row _ their longest losing streak of the season.
They are looking for their first win in August and fell eight games
behind first-place Seattle in the AL West, their largest deficit of
the season. They are only five games out in the wild-card race but
trail four teams (Oakland, Boston, Cleveland and Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, however, continue to say they will work things out,
that it's no time to panic. There are 50 games left in the season,
plenty of time to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still early enough to look at the big picture,''
Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Obviously we're not going to
be complacent, thinking we're going to win playing the way we are
now. But we're too good a ballclub to stay in this rut.''
</P>
<P>
   The rut _ 11 losses in 15 games _ has been caused by a lack of
good starting pitching. The staff has been ravaged by injuries, but
even those who are healthy are not throwing well.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's starter, Brian Cooper, has been trying to correct a
mechanical flaw in his delivery, but apparently he has work to do.
He lasted only 3 innings, allowing five runs and seven hits. Four
of the seven hits were home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper threw a three-hit shutout against the A's on June 30 but
has struggled since then. In his last six starts, he is 1-5 with a
9.42 ERA. He threw only one good game during that stretch, beating
the Padres on July 17 (6 innings, 2 runs, 4 hits).
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he regressed a little bit with his command,''
Scioscia said. ``He couldn't locate the ball, he couldn't put
hitters away. For a sinker-ball pitcher to get hit like that is not
what we're looking for. But he'll get it ironed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he hopes Cooper (4-7) can get his problems fixed
in the majors, but a trip back to the minor leagues in not out of
the question. Ramon Ortiz has pitched well in Triple-A and Kent
Mercker should be ready in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four tough (starts) in a row, it's pretty easy to dwell on the
negative aspects,'' Cooper said. ``But if I stay away from that and
focus on the things I'm doing right, it should carry me from start
to start. . . . As long as they have confidence in me, I'll have
confidence in myself. Hopefully something will spark and get me
rolling in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper retired the first two batters he faced, then surrendered
back-to-back home runs to Roberto Alomar and Jim Thome. The Angels
tied it with two runs in the second, but Alomar homered again in
the third for a 3-2 Indians lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Einar Diaz followed a single by Bill Selby
with a two-run homer. Cooper didn't make it out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels bullpen pitched well, throwing 4 scoreless innings.
But the Angels offense couldn't get back in it.
</P>
<P>
   Indians starter Bartolo Colon (10-8), who hit 99 mph on the
Jacobs Field radar gun several times, gave up two runs and six hits
in seven-plus innings, striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Colon also walked five batters, but the Angels failed to take
advantage. The Angels went 1 for 10 with runners in scoring
position, the only hit being Kevin Stocker's RBI double in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a pretty good disciplined approach with
(Colon),'' Scioscia said. ``We had plenty of opportunities early in
the game but couldn't get the key hit that would have changed the
complexion of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
