<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY ADVOCATE IN EGYPT ACCUSED OF ESPIONAGE  

</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ A state prosecutor on Sunday expanded the list of
accusations against Saad Eddin Ibrahim, a prominent democracy
advocate, to include espionage for the United States, his lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim, who has been detained since June 30 without being
formally charged, is accused of revealing Egyptian security secrets
while speaking at a 1994 conference on Egyptian-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   Farid al-Deeb, one of his defense lawyers, said the new
accusation was raised in the latest interrogation of Ibrahim, a
sociologist who also holds American citizenship and who has been
active in human rights work and election monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Spying is the most serious of the complaints brought against him
so far and carries a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are baffled by this new accusation,'' said his wife,
Barbara Ibrahim, in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   No one in President Hosni Mubarak's government has commented
publicly on the case. But Ibrahim, and his supporters, have said
they believe he is being punished for his plan to set up
independent monitors for the parliamentary elections scheduled for
November.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak's National Democratic Party holds 97 percent of the
seats in the People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim's case has drawn considerable international attention at
a time of rising tensions between Egypt and the United States over
the faltering Palestinian-Israeli peace efforts. Clinton
administration officials have accused Egypt of being uncooperative
by not pressuring Palestinians to accept an offer on the status of
Jerusalem, a charge that officials here vehemently deny.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, every government-subsidized newspaper has run
editorials attacking President Clinton, accusing him of being
biased in favor of Israel and insensitive to Egypt's foreign policy
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The continued detention of Ibrahim has only intensified the
friction. The State Department, questioning Egypt's commitment to
human rights, has urged authorities to clarify the charges against
him or release him.
</P>
<P>
   No formal charges have been brought against Ibrahim, but the
State Security Court has twice extended his original 15-day
detention period.
</P>
<P>
   To keep him imprisoned longer without charge, authorities would
have to resort to Egypt's emergency law, which permits detention of
up to six months without charge. The law, generally used to detain
suspected terrorists and political prisoners, has been in effect
since 1981, when former President Anwar Sadat was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   In previous interrogations, according to his lawyers, Ibrahim
has been accused of defaming Egypt by producing a get-out-the-vote
film, of misusing foreign funds in his social research
organization, of sowing sectarian hatred through his research into
Muslim-Christian relations and of having unauthorized contacts with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen employees of Ibrahim's Ibn Khaldun Center Development
Studies in Cairo have also been imprisoned. The center itself has
been closed by security forces, as has a related center that was
promoting women's electoral participation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the playwright who wrote the script for the film on
voter participation, Ali Salem, has been charged with threatening
national security because of his connection with Ibrahim. The film,
which has never been released, was financed with a grant from the
European Union and urges Egyptians to shed their apathy and vote.
</P>
<P>
   The espionage accusation concerns a conference that was attended
by Ibrahim and a number of diplomats from the Egyptian Embassy in
Washington _ a present Egyptian government minister, Ali el-Din
Hilal; members of a research organization financed by the Egyptian
government; the former Egyptian ambassador to Canada, Tahseen
Bashir; and representatives of the U.S. Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Deeb said that Ibrahim spoke at the conference about his
research into Islamic extremism in Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
