A4158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-INTERNET080     08-06 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-INTERNET0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth to create high-speed Internet system
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth today will announce plans to build a
high-speed Internet system near Miami that will carry huge amounts
of data arriving from overseas, helping to relieve congestion in
much of the equipment now used by Internet companies in the
Southeast. Construction will be done by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting in a 20-lane cloverleaf,'' said Susan
Campbell, director of Internet strategy and business development at
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Most data traffic in the United States passes through one of the
seven public ``network access points.'' Some large data carriers
have their own private access points, accessible only to companies
who contract to connect.
</P>
<P>
   But no public access point has been built since 1996 _ and
Internet traffic has been doubling every two or three months. So
like a transportation system in a growing economy, the spectacular
growth of the Net has outpaced those systems' ability to carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Internet-transmitted video often appears jittery
and jerky, because congestion has slowed transmission of the signal
to a relative crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration with that flaw is bound to increase as home Net
users plunk down more money to get high-speed access _ broadband _
only to find their use can be disrupted by jams in data traffic
hundreds of miles distant, Campbell said. ``The Internet really has
got to move to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Addition of an eighth public access point could help relieve
that congestion, at least in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, BellSouth will use fiber optics _ a faster, more
reliable technology than that of any other public access point, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company knows of no other public access point planned with
optical technology, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has for years been pouring resources into fiber and
now manages more than 2.8 million miles of fiber in its nine-state
region.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has not decided whose equipment to use, and says only
that the project has a ``multimillion- dollar'' cost.
</P>
<P>
   The $26 billion-a-year company will reap revenues from the
companies that connect, with fees based on how much data is
handled. Signed up so far to connect with the BellSouth system are
the Internet service providers run by FPL FiberNet, Qwest,
International Wireless, UUNet, Intermedia, NetRail and Diveo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GUNS-2TAKES(TRIM     08-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA, MANY GUN OWNERS SEE BUSH AS A FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ark., Maine, Ill., N.Y.)   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One expectation of anyone running for governor
of Texas is that he or she must grab a gun and shoot something. So
in 1994, George W. Bush, then the Republican candidate for
governor, borrowed a 20-gauge shotgun and invited a group of
reporters on a dove hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the dawn mist, Bush fired seven times, bagged a bird for the
cameras, and then left to continue campaigning. But the dead bird
turned out to be a killdeer, a protected species, and a photo
opportunity meant to underscore Bush's kinship with gun owners
instead became an embarrassment, as he paid a small fine and
apologized for his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the eyes of gun owners in Texas and national gun-lobbying
groups like the National Rifle Association, Bush's illegal shot was
the last mistake he has made. The NRA's chief lobbyist in
Washington, James Jay Baker, could not recall a single instance in
which Bush, as governor, had opposed the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I can remember,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record has been decidedly sympathetic to gun owners. He
has signed far-reaching pro-gun legislation, including a 1995 law
making it legal to carry concealed weapons, an expansion of that
law in 1997, and a 1999 law making it extremely difficult for
cities to sue gun manufacturers. One national survey by a
gun-control group found that only three states _ Louisiana,
Arkansas and Maine _ had looser gun laws than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This stance has earned Bush many admirers in Texas, where guns
are entwined in the culture. But it has also galvanized his
opponents in this presidential campaign, from gun-control groups to
Vice President Al Gore, who have eagerly tried to cast Bush as a
willing pawn of the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are using the gun issue to pursue broader
themes of attack. Gore has cited Bush's pro-gun record to try to
marry the Texas governor to his party's right wing, and, in
contrast, has offered a string of gun-control proposals. Bush's
aides, noting that Gore once opposed gun control, only to change
his position, have used the issue as part of their effort to depict
Gore as opportunistic.
</P>
<P>
   Both the rifle association and the leading gun-control group,
Handgun Control Inc., are treating this election as historic.
Handgun Control ran commercials attacking Bush during the
Republican National Convention and will continue to do so. Baker,
who said the NRA would spend $15 million in this year's election
campaigns, said that the candidates' divergent views on guns made
this presidential race the most important in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's supporters say he has put Texas in the national
mainstream with the 30 other states that have similar laws allowing
the carrying of concealed weapons. But his critics note that
several other Republican governors, including George Ryan in
Illinois and George Pataki in New York, have pushed for stronger
gun laws. Bush supports better enforcement of existing laws, as
does the rifle association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a Texas governor that compares to Bush in
carrying water for the NRA,'' said Nina Butts, president of Texans
Against Gun Violence, a gun-control group.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a high-ranking NRA official was videotaped telling
supporters that in a Bush presidency, ``we work out of their
office.'' The official said the association and Bush would have
``unbelievably friendly relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush bristled at that remark and has sought to signal his
independence from the association by endorsing ideas that include
background checks on the buyers of firearms at gun shows and
raising the minimum age for buying handguns to 21 from 18. This
spring, when the Million Mom March on Washington was held in
support of gun control, Bush announced that he would spend $1
million a year of state money to to hand out free trigger locks to
handgun owners. He said that if elected president, he would support
a similar national program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be times when we agree and times when we
disagree,'' Bush said of the NRA in an interview in March.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's critics are skeptical that he has been converted.
They note that Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, has long opposed
gun control. As a Republican congressman from Wyoming, Cheney was
among only 21 House members who voted against banning so-called
cop-killer bullets. In 1988, Cheney voted against a ban on plastic
guns that could pass through airport security.
</P>
<P>
   And the critics note that Bush declined to put his clout behind
gun-show background checks in Texas even though he is now
supporting them nationally. ``Bush is out on the campaign trail
running for president in a country where parents are very concerned
about gun violence,'' Butts said, ``and he's making promises that
have nothing to do with his record in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Texas residents recall that Bush ran for governor on four issues
in 1994 _ juvenile justice, tort changes, and overhauling education
and welfare. But guns were also an issue. The incumbent Democrat,
Ann Richards, had vetoed a 1993 bill to permit a statewide
referendum on allowing Texans to carry concealed weapons. Bush
pledged to sign such a bill, and gun lobbyists now say the issue
was critical to his victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush ran against Ann Richards largely on the
right-to-carry issue,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Legislature again passed a concealed-weapons bill.
Many law enforcement agencies, including the Texas Association of
Police Chiefs, opposed the bill, but Bush, as he had promised,
signed it into law. The law, which did not require a referendum,
allows residents to carry hidden weapons if they undergo a
background check and 10 to 15 hours of training. Two years later,
Bush signed an amendment that allowed people to carry concealed
weapons into previously excluded institutions, including churches,
nursing homes and hospitals, unless those institutions expressly
prohibited it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters were pleased, but if they regard Bush as
an ally, they do not consider him a soul mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is being given the mantle of the pro-gun zealot and he's
really not,'' said Jerry Patterson, a former Republican state
senator who was a chief sponsor of the concealed-weapons bills in
1995 and 1997. Guns had ``never been a hot button issue'' for the
governor, said Patterson, who claimed that some ``pro-gun people
are not comfortable'' with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   He said of Bush: ``He made a commitment and lived up to his
commitment. This issue is not high on his list of priorities. I
would say it's probably not even on his list of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control supporters were outraged, particularly by the
provision involving churches. Patterson said it had been in
response to complaints from pastors who could not carry their
weapons onto the grounds of their own churches. As of July 3, state
statistics showed that 212,969 Texans had licenses to carry
concealed weapons, and Bush has argued that the law has made Texas
safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that Texans supported,'' said Bush's
spokesman, Dan Bartlett, of the overall legislation, noting that
the crime wave predicted by opponents never materialized. ``It's a
rigorous process to go through. Law-abiding citizens should have
the ability to protect themselves and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates say crime has fallen in Texas because of
larger national trends, not concealed weapons, and point to studies
that show that many gun owners with concealed-weapons permits have
committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 report by the Violence Policy Center, a national
gun-control group, showed that Texans with licenses to carry
concealed handguns were arrested in connection with 2,080 crimes
from 1996 through 1998, from drunken driving and burglary to rape
and murder.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle association shifted emphasis in 1999, beginning a
nationwide effort to blunt lawsuits filed by cities against gun
manufacturers. In Texas, which includes three of the nation's 10
largest cities, the Legislature passed a bill prohibiting such
municipal lawsuits, though it did allow the state attorney general
to file such suits. Bush signed the law and has suggested that he
would sign similar federal legislation if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't consider that in the gun-control debate,'' Bartlett
said. ``That is a tort reform measure.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When asked about gun control, Bush often repeats the theme that
government should enforce existing laws, not restrict the rights of
law-abiding citizens. As part of his juvenile-justice package, Bush
increased the penalties for minors committing crimes with a gun. In
1999, he helped institute the Texas Exile Program, which helps
local law enforcement agencies prosecute gun crimes under stricter
federal sentencing guidelines. In 1995, he signed the Texas Child
Access Prevention law, which holds adults criminally responsible
for not keeping loaded guns out of the hands of children.
</P>
<P>
   But while gun-control advocates applauded the child access law,
they noted that it included something for the NRA _ a provision
that ``strongly encouraged'' school districts to provide gun-safety
programs beginning in kindergarten. And the provision instructed
schools that the safety program must comply with the rifle
association's safety course for children, with the cartoon
character Eddie Eagle, essentially allowing the association to
dictate the curriculum. Critics equate the Eddie Eagle program with
the cigarette industry's use of Joe Camel to entice teen-agers to
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, gun-control advocates in Texas say Bush should be
judged not only by what he has done, but what he has not. Last
year, Debra Danburg, a Democratic state representative from
Houston, introduced a bill to close the loophole that allows people
to buy weapons at gun shows from unlicensed sellers without a
background check. Texas has the most gun shows of any state, with
472 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Columbine High School shootings, Bush said that
a popular culture that romanticizes violence had been partly to
blame. But in remarks to reporters, Bush endorsed the idea of
background checks at gun shows. This stunned Danburg. Just hours
before the governor's comments, Danburg's bill had died in a House
committee. Bush had done nothing to get the bill passed.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure quickly built for Bush to revive the Danburg bill, but
he refused, declaring it dead and telling reporters that ``it
really needs to be worked out at the federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides and pro-gun lobbyists say the Danburg bill was
flawed and would have essentially closed down all gun shows.
Danburg said she would have amended the bill and could have passed
it, if Bush had helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he supported it, he should have put his money where his
mouth is,'' she said. Danburg, who sponsored a resolution in
support of the Eddie Eagle program, calls herself a moderate on the
issue. But she said the governor was listening to only one side of
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made enough promises to extremists who are pro-gun that
they have passionately adopted him,'' she said. ``Yet he doesn't
talk with people who are concerned with gun safety. We're not
invited inside the big tent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
