u i BC-ARGENTINA-SUICIDE-NYT     08-06 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEON'S SUICIDE LEAVES ARGENTINES MOURNING AND PONDERING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ It has been more than a week since Dr.
Rene Favaloro, Argentina's most esteemed surgeon and a pioneer in
heart bypass surgery, committed suicide. But the outpouring of
grief seems to be growing more intense day by day, opening a
channel of despair so deep that Argentines are raising the deepest
of questions about themselves and their country.
</P>
<P>
   As wreaths of flowers pile up in front of Favaloro's research
foundation, newspapers are publishing extra columns of letters to
the editor in a deluge of long, sorrowful and often bitter
diatribes blaming the entire society for the suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Favaloro's photograph is on the cover of seemingly every
magazine, and articles are recounting the suicide in gruesome
detail, while the country's most important writers speculate about
what Favaloro's death means. There has been blanket television
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Argentines, especially Portenos as residents of this capital are
known, are among the most psychoanalyzed people in the world.
Depression is a topic of everyday conversation of people of all
classes, and Argentines are not shy about complaining about
everything from the weather to the pressures of their jobs.
Funerals and cemeteries are elaborate, and suicide is not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something so distinctive about Favaloro's death
that it goes well beyond the national fixation with neurosis and
death. Some analysts say that the national mourning could be just
the epiphany Argentines need to kick themselves out of their
lethargy and the long decline the nation has suffered since its
economic and cultural heyday in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Sabato, Argentina's leading novelist, noted that it was
``profoundly tragic'' that one of Argentina's most creative sons
would feel so ``desperate and impotent'' that he would end his own
life. But he added, ``I ask myself if this sadness that is draining
all of us might just jolt us out of our inertia. Perhaps that was
his final wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking may well be wishful in the extreme, an example of
what one newspaper article characterized as an Argentine propensity
to swing from despair to euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of smoke-filled cafes here these days is about how
Favaloro's death is just one more symptom reflecting a country in
which a deep two-year recession has ravaged the middle class,
forcing the best and brightest to stand in line at the American,
Spanish and Brazilian embassies seeking visas to work elsewhere. It
has also spurred a debate about health care in Argentina, and how
the country does not put enough resources into scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay titled ``The Sad Land of Psychoanalysis and Tango,''
published Sunday in La Nacion, the country's most prestigious
newspaper, Favaloro's death was linked to a deep national
melancholia. ``Millions of Argentines, trapped by unemployment and
recession, are confronting an insecure future with anguish,'' wrote
Claudio Ivan Remeseira in the essay. ``The death of Rene Favaloro
marked a transcendent moment in this climate of frustrated
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Fernando De la Rua has been put on the
defensive, as reports emerged that the surgeon sent him a letter
crying out for help just days before he shot himself in the chest.
It was more than awkward, and some said it was heartless, when the
presidential palace put out a statement early last week denying
that the government was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The 77-year-old heart surgeon had a rags to riches life story.
The son of a seamstress and carpenter who grew up in the provincial
city of La Plata, Favaloro managed to become one of the world's
best known doctors. While working at the Cleveland Clinic in 1967,
he performed a bypass around a deadly coronary blockage. Although
other doctors had performed a similar surgery earlier, those
procedures were done under emergency conditions after patients
deteriorated on the operating table.
</P>
<P>
   Favaloro's procedure was planned, and he became the first to
report on it in a medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   After his success in America, he returned to Argentina and
founded a foundation dedicated to heart transplants and research.
It is among the most important medical facilities in South America.
Beloved and respected, Favaloro was repeatedly mentioned over the
years as a possible presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But along with the Argentine economy, the Favaloro Foundation
had fallen on hard times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Favaloro was found dead by his brother and secretary in a
bathroom of his apartment in the upscale Palermo neighborhood on
July 29, a .38 caliber pistol beside his body. No foul play has
been suggested.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, the press has revealed that the Favaloro
Foundation was being sued by the government because it was behind
in paying Social Security contributions to its employees even while
the government reportedly owed the foundation a more substantial
sum of money for unpaid services to a public retirement institute.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of the government suit came from a federal judge,
Julio Cruciani, who bitterly complained that ``this is a country
that comes down hard on people who are doers.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's handling of the death has been criticized as clumsy
and is at least partially fueling all the hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   His immediate response to the news of the suicide was to issue a
special decree expressing that the nation was in mourning. But over
the next few days, the Argentine press revealed that before his
death Favaloro had made a desperate appeal to the president to help
him solicit financial support for his foundation from businesses.
De la Rua said he received the letter only a day before the
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has no guilt to wash off its hands nor does it
want to enter the debate over whether or not someone is to blame,''
Jorge De la Rua, the president's brother and chief of staff, was
quoted as saying in the local press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unjust to attribute to the government of Fernando
De la Rua the responsibility for these tragedies _ the emigration
of so many young people, the worsening poverty, the suicide of an
exceptional scientist,'' wrote Tomas Eloy Martinez, one of
Argentina's leading writers. ``But all these things are alarming
symptoms that we cannot pretend not to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
