<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ COMEBACK SPOILED AS MARINERS ROUT YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez has a familiar pose whenever a game
starts to crumble around him. He slouches his body, pins his right
hand on his waist like someone who is impatiently waiting in line
for a driver's license and peers out to where another damaging hit
has just landed. ``How did that happen?'' El Duque seems to be
saying to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck the pose often on an overcast day at Yankee
Stadium, a day that did not last too long for the sluggish pitcher
or for the Yankees. El Duque had not started a game in 24 days, he
had difficulty throwing strikes and he wondered why the Seattle
Mariners were pummeling the strikes he did throw in coasting to an
11-1 victory. ``How did this happen?'' El Duque surely said to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It happened because the Mariners were patient. They made a rusty
Hernandez work deep into counts and then they treated a pitcher who
was considered one of the best in American League in April like an
impostor. Hernandez trudged back to the dugout after the fourth
inning as if he were walking over land mines, knowing that his
long-anticipated return to the rotation ended in an 85-pitch
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was very frustrated because, like he does most of
the time and like we do, when he goes out there, we expect him to
shut down the opposition,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``He wasn't
able to do that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was on the disabled list with a sprained right elbow
and back spasms, but he did not blame the five earned runs on eight
hits and three walks on any physical discomfort. Hernandez had a
strong fastball and a decent slider. He simply did not locate his
pitches precisely and the Mariners waited, pounced and then rode
Paul Abbott's eight excellent innings to the rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to battle,'' Jorge Posada said about Hernandez.
``You could see that he was in a battle. He was frustrated with
himself. They were laying off some tough pitches and I think he got
frustrated a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Torre and Posada both called Hernandez frustrated and
although El Duque's body language revealed exasperation, he
bristled when he was asked about being frustrated after matching
his second-shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't win and we didn't win,'' Hernandez said through Leo
Astacio, his interpreter. ``Frustration is for the weak and I don't
consider myself weak.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a lost weekend for Hernandez, who returned from
rehabilitating in Tampa, Fla., on Friday and immediately created a
controversy by asserting that one of the Yankees' coaches
supposedly said he was not ``as hurt as much as I thought.'' Torre
was understandably upset with Hernandez's charge, which the pitcher
tried to minimize by apologizing to the coaches on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for making them feel bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Torre admitted that Hernandez's words would probably not
evaporate. Hernandez said it to reporters and, regardless of his
retraction, everyone knows what he said after returning from
working under Billy Connors, the Yankees' vice president and
pitching instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will always be that little thing out there, that
element of question,'' Torre said. ``Sometimes we magnify things.
As far as I'm concerned, he has had so much support from everyone
here.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hernandez and Allen Watson were drilled, Abbott used a
fastball and a change-up to disarm the Yanks and win for the second
time in seven starts. The Yankees began three innings with runners
on first and second, but Abbott induced double plays each time.
After Bernie Williams homered in the fourth, the Yankees loaded the
bases and stranded all three runners. Abbott did not give up a hit
in eight at-bats with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a buzz saw,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Hernandez never looked comfortable. He wore a
blue, long-sleeve shirt on a 76-degree day and jogged out to the
mound seconds before the national anthem began. After Hernandez
went ahead 0-2 on Stan Javier, he threw three straight balls before
Javier singled to right field for his first of five hits. One out
later, Alex Rodriguez looped a single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had a 1-1 count on Edgar Martinez when he threw a
fastball up and in to give Martinez a different look or maybe get
him to foul off the pitch. But Martinez's quick, compact swing
enabled him to hammer a pitch that was near his eyes over the
left-field fence, giving the Mariners a 3-0 bulge and giving him a
major league best 103 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems like he can hit a ball over his head,'' Posada said.
``He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   When the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre visited the mound after
Martinez's homer, Hernandez looked perturbed. Hernandez walked two
batters in the third, but he escaped unscathed from a bases-loaded
situation. He could not escape more danger in the fourth when four
of the first five batters slapped hits and the Mariners surged to a
5-0 lead, leaving Hernandez looking frustrated and wondering what
had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, I feel good,'' Hernandez said.
``My elbow is fine. My back is fine. All the rest will solve
itself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
