<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOMAIN-NAME-DISPUTE-5     08-06 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMAIN-NAME-DISPUTE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND MANAGERS AT ODDS OVER USE OF DOMAIN NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas F. Marsico was a star money manager at Janus Capital
before he left three years ago to form his own company. But his
name, it seems, has found its way back to his old employer. Or at
least his domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Web site called FundAlarm.com disclosed that Janus,
the United States' fifth-largest mutual fund manager, had
registered the domain name tommarsico.com. Actually the name was
registered by James P. Goff, manager of the $8.7 billion Janus
Enterprise fund. Goff, 36, said he registered it on his own last
December and not on behalf of Janus.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been plenty of dust-ups over domain names
before, this may be the first to involve two prominent investors
who manage billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were big shareholders of Network Solutions,'' Goff
explained, referring to the Internet company that until last year
controlled the registry of domain names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on there and got jimgoff.com,'' he said. ``Just for
kicks, I looked up Tom's and was surprised they hadn't reserved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsico, the 45-year-old chairman and chief executive of Marsico
Capital Management, which manages more than $15 billion, said he
was not aware until last week that the domain name had been
registered. He was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people go out and buy domain names like that, they're
usually trying to do it for some benefit, selling it for a higher
price,'' he said. ``I was dumbfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Marsico managed the Janus Twenty fund and
was one of the industry's most prominent fund managers, appearing
often on the covers of financial magazines. He also helped recruit
talent to the firm, including Goff. Both men worked previously for
Fred Alger Management, a New York investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Since his departure from Janus, Marsico has said little about
the firm. He and his former colleagues have had plenty on their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Bank of America bought the half of Marsico Capital
Management that it did not already own, for a total price of $1.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Janus, meanwhile, lost a bitter dispute with its corporate
parent, Kansas City Southern Industries, which spun off Janus as an
entity called Stilwell Financial, over the objections of Janus
executives.
</P>
<P>
   What will be the fate of tommarsico.com?
</P>
<P>
   The World Intellectual Property Organization has ruled against
several companies that operated registered Web addresses
incorporating the names of Yahoo, AT&AMP;T and Microsoft. But the
Marsico case seems more likely to be settled on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who belong to the same Denver-area country club,
met by chance last Wednesday. Goff said he apologized and offered
to return the domain name free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for fun, and it was a bad decision,'' Goff said,
adding that he had never set up any Web site at the address.
</P>
<P>
   Marsico was skeptical of Goff's explanation: ``This is a guy who
I brought to Janus. I got him into a country club he lives right
on. He doesn't say, `It's nice you sold your business,
congratulations.' It was, `By the way, since The New York Times
called me, I bought your domain name.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marsico did once try to register marsico.com, but he said it had
already been taken by a Pittsburgh company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a man named Marsico there,'' he explained. Marsico
Capital uses the address marsicofunds.com as its home.
</P>
<P>
   As for tommarsico.com, Marsico said it had never occurred to him
to register the name.
</P>
<P>
   Will he take up Goff's offer and claim the site? When Goff
approached Marsico in a buffet line at the golf club, Marsico said
he was more interested in hitting the links than hearing about a
domain name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm protected,'' he said. ``If I ever wanted my name,
I could get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
