<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone but the Los Angeles Lakers seems to have come to grips
that he's leaving.
</P>
<P>
   There probably won't even be a press conference today, and if
there is, Jerry West promises he won't be there.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will team owner Jerry Buss, who's somewhere in Europe
slipping Deutsche marks down the top of some 19-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The coach? If his one-room shack in Montana is rockin', don't
bother knockin'. He's either writing another autobiography or
compiling his latest manifesto about the evils of modern
technology.
</P>
<P>
   That'll leave poor ol' Mitch Kupchak to answer for the eminent
signing of free agent Kendall Gill _ a nice pickup, but who needs a
10-year veteran guard who can't shoot any more on a team well
stocked in awful-shooting guards?
</P>
<P>
   So Mr. Clutch is outta here (taking Glen Rice with him?), maybe
coming back in a year or two after his inner demons are properly
squashed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers can stay in denial, but it'll only hurt more later. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ What makes Pat Riley so sure that EJones will be around at
crunch time? He's not, but it sure beats P.J. Brown taking the last
shot. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ WNBA stat of the week: The Miami Sol has won 11 of its 30
games this season _ even though it's the league's worst-shooting
team. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Once Darryl Strawberry deals with his latest cancer treatment
this week, he'll go back to having to face no means of income,
$22,000 in the hole in child support payments and possible legal
action if it's found that he violated current drug-related
probation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Ray Guy, picked last week to the all-time All-NFL team of the
Century, isn't even in the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Which continues to rankle the white jumpsuit of Raiders boss
Gentleman Al Davis, so we continue to endorse the oversight. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ We'll take John Elway to lead our team. You can have Johnny
Unitas and Joe Montana. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Notre Dame, outta the AP Top 25 preseason poll? Gettin' back
into the loop will be tougher than Jack Lemmonhead making the cut
at Pebble Beach. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ How big you think Cecil Fielder is these days? ...
</P>
<P>
   __ The Mike Fetters version of the bobble-head doll _
spring-loaded to snap only to the left. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The gradual deterioration of ``Hollywood Has-Beens Night'' at
Dodger Stadium at least gives the producers of ``Politically
Incorrect'' a one-stop recruiting trip. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The reason Fernando Valenzuela's mural of honor hasn't made
it up on the outfield wall _ he hasn't officially retired, meaning
he could return as an opponent. Which wouldn't look cool. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ In an attempt to counter constant allegations that its
athletes cheat by using drugs, Chinese sports officials proclaimed
in the state-run newspaper last week that its doping record was far
better than international norms.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide rate of positive doping tests was 1.8 percent in
1998, but China's rate has fallen from about 1.6 in the early 1990s
to near 0.6 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   But then, 0.6 percent of a billion is. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ And there's some despondent kickball fans in the city of
Houston, which found out that the Major League Soccer doesn't
consider it a priority for an expansion team until at least 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Want our team?
</P>
</TEXT>
