u i BC-CHINA-JAPAN-535&AMP;ADD-N     08-06 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-JAPAN-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT IS SYMBOL OF CHINA'S HOSTILITY TO JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ When Tang Weijiang slid a promotional compact
disc into his friend's computer last month, what he saw ruined his
day, and now he is asking Canon Inc. to pay $12 million in
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Tang, 29, said he was furious that the Japanese company implied
on the disc, which promoted Canon's bubble-jet printers, that
China, Hong Kong and Taiwan are three separate countries. He said
he suffered mental distress from what he alleged was a deliberate
effort by Canon to undermine China's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Behind what outsiders might see as a quixotic lawsuit is a
deeper reason for Tang's reaction: China's long-simmering anger
toward Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong trade ties between the two countries, Japan
remains suspect in the eyes of many Chinese because of the Imperial
Japanese Army's horrendous behavior in China during the 1930s and
1940s, which included beheading contests and the mass rape and
murder of civilians in Nanjing. China estimates that as many as 35
million people died during the Japanese occupation.
</P>
<P>
   So visceral is China's animosity toward Japan that anything
short of demonizing wartime Japan is considered unpatriotic. Many
Chinese say openly that they hate the Japanese, though they don't
say so to the Japanese directly.
</P>
<P>
   The director Jiang Wen has been criticized for depicting the
Japanese too sympathetically in his film ``Devils on the
Doorstep,'' which won the Cannes Film Festival's Grand Prix in May
but has been banned in mainland China. The term ``devils'' refers
to Japanese of that period.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility creates a difficult environment for Japanese
companies operating here, even as Chinese are fast embracing
Japan's powerful popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese women, even in remote cities, teeter on cakelike
platform shoes and carry Hello Kitty handbags, all icons of Japan.
Casio G-Shock and Baby-G watches are the rage among teeny-boppers,
and sushi is an increasingly fashionable meal for the
sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   But that shallow love affair can evaporate quickly when the
Chinese feel slighted.
</P>
<P>
   During demonstrations at Zhejiang University following NATO's
bombing of China's Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, last year, the
mood quickly turned from anti-American to anti-Japanese when a ball
being kicked around by a group of Japanese students playing soccer
inadvertently hit a student banner. The Japanese had to be
evacuated by police.
</P>
<P>
   And a university in the central city of Wuhan has banned the
rental of kimonos and Japanese swords to people posing for pictures
beneath blossoming cherry trees that were planted on campus by
Japan during the war. The university said the once popular practice
upset students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of propaganda have conditioned Chinese citizens to sense
slights regarding Taiwan, and the fact that the insult came from a
Japanese firm intensified Tang's reaction _ in Beijing's view,
Taiwan is a province of China, while Hong Kong, once a British
colony, is now a Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company mixed it up intentionally,'' said Tang, who sells
airline tickets in the central Chinese city of Chongqing. ``It hurt
the feelings of the Chinese people, and I felt hurt personally.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Japan has never fully apologized to China for its wartime
crimes. It maintains a shrine in China for fallen Japanese
soldiers, including seven class-A war criminals who were hanged.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori said Sunday that he would
not make an official visit to the shrine this month on the
anniversary of the end of World War II, although he did so last
year. His defense minister will visit it this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has never confessed its wrongdoings, from the 1894
Sino-Japanese War to the war in the 1940s, and now it is using
another approach to invade _ economic penetration,'' said Lu Lei,
Tang's lawyer, who is also suing Canon after finding similar errors
on the company's Web site. ``The country has political goals,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba Corp. is fighting an anti-Japanese media campaign that
accuses it of treating Chinese as second-class customers because
the company has offered to compensate American buyers of faulty
laptops but not Chinese buyers. The U.S. compensation was necessary
to avoid a costly legal case.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese consumers are now also suing Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   Canon was quick to issue a recall of the discs that led to the
current lawsuit and offered its Chinese customers an apology,
blaming an editing error.
</P>
<P>
   But Tang is unappeased, bolstered by the stone-faced seriousness
with which his case has been treated in the press. His vow to spend
the $12 million he is suing Canon for on schools in impoverished
areas of China, if he wins his case, has made him something of a
local hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't accept Canon's apology,'' said Tang. ``We need Canon
to apologize to all Chinese people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
