<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 ACE-TEX 
12-YEAR-OLD BUTTERFLY SPECIALIST SWIMS INTO OLYMPIC TRIALS (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jeff Caplan 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ With dolphin-like swiftness and ease,
12-year-old Dana Vollmer has propelled herself from Granbury's
summer swimming league to a shot at the Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Amid 1996 Olympic gold-medalists Jenny Thompson, Beth Botsford
and Andrea Beard, all of whom will converge on Indianapolis for
this week's U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, Dana is rapidly revealing
herself as a rising star. Sporting a lean frame of nearly 5-foot-9,
she is sharp, focused and bursting with talent.
</P>
<P>
   She regards Thompson, a two-time Olympian, as her ultimate hero
_ Thompson is the world record-holder in Vollmer's top event _ yet
her path to this point mirrors Botsford and Beard. Those two, both
sophomores at Arizona, rocketed onto the Olympic scene in Atlanta.
Beard was 14; Botsford was 15.
</P>
<P>
   Dana has a chance to eclipse that when she takes the water
Wednesday in the 100-meter butterfly, though she is more likely a
serious contender for the 2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try really not to think about it because I get myself worked
up and nervous before the meet,'' Dana said Friday morning after
completing her final practice session at the Forest Park pool.
</P>
<P>
   A family play day at Hurricane Harbor was up next, only two days
before her scheduled arrival in America's heartland and braving a
new world: elite Olympic competition.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic-caliber swimming is unlike gymnastics or figure skating,
where younger often means better. Adolescent swimmers face an
upstream battle against fully developed athletes who have been
training and competing at a world-class level around the calendar
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like Botsford and Beard were, Dana appears to be a prodigy
in the making. Until recently, Dana didn't register a blip on the
selective radar of the Fort Worth Area Swim Team (FAST), an
extension of USA Swimming and a year-round elite swim club. That is
a major difference from her youthful predecessors, who began
year-round training years before making the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Dana, remarkably, joined FAST only last September. Her parents,
Les and Cathy, a longtime swim coach who has tutored her daughter
for years, chose to forgo the life-changing commitment of full-time
training for a couple of reasons. The drive to Fort Worth and the
nearest Olympic-sized pool is 50 minutes from the Vollmers in
Granbury, but the drive was only part of the reason they didn't
make the trip regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coaching a long time, and I've seen a lot of young
kids that were really good get burned out really early and then
they quit,'' Cathy said. ``As soon as you switch over to full time,
it's full time from now until after college, and that's a lot. You
do have to keep reminding yourself that she's just 12, that she
needs to be a kid and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the switch to full-time training _ about 11 practices a
week for two-hour sessions twice a day, starting at 5:30 a.m.
coming up in the fall _ has come as naturally to Dana as the
butterfly stroke she started to perfect at age 5 when mom toted her
around in a backpack when she coached.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been people really good at 12, but not at the level
she is,'' said Ted Murphy of FAST, Dana's instructor since joining
the club. ``She is basically one-in-a-million. She is swimming in
senior national events. The top 1 percent of all swimmers are in
those meets.''
</P>
<P>
   Proof is in her times. In the past six months, Dana has set
three national age-group records in the butterfly. Two of those
records, the 50-yard and 50-meter butterfly had belonged to
Botsford, set in 1993. Dana's third record, in the 100-meter
butterfly, blasted an 18-year-old mark set by Jennifer Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Dana is so advanced that she doesn't swim against competitors
close to her own age. Instead, she is routinely blowing away
college-age swimmers at high-level meets.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dana: ``I don't think they really realize \Rmy age\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana's 100-meter national butterfly record of 1:03.07, set July
15 at the Junior National Southeast meet in Orlando, Fla.,
qualified her for the Olympic trials by two-hundredths of a second.
It is about four to five seconds off the pace she probably will
need to make the Olympic team, which carries two swimmers in each
event.
</P>
<P>
   She has two primary goals this week. Making the Olympic team is
the ultimate. On a more realistic level, Dana said she wants to
make the semifinals, which would put her in the top 16. Also, a
time of 1:02.21 would automatically place her on the U.S. National
Junior team, a squad that competes internationally and is the next
logical step on the road to the 2004 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Her rapid rise hardly seems to affect Dana, who will soon have
to make some athletic choices. This month, she will enter seventh
grade, the first year students can participate in scholastic
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play volleyball, basketball and track,'' she said.
``Right now, it sounds kind of weird, but I love basketball as much
as I love swimming. I hear things like, `But you're going to the
Olympic trials.' I've always dreamed of playing in the WNBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Calm and mature, the significance of her supersonic success and
a blazing bright future might be more incomprehensible right now
for Dana's parents than for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of ignoring it because it could be so big that it
would overwhelm me and therefore influence her,'' Les Vollmer said.
``This trip to Indianapolis, we are trying to find a bunch of
things to do, call it a vacation, and, oh by the way, on Wednesday
you're going to swim for a spot on the U.S. Olympic team.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
