<HEADLINE>
A POSSIBLE BID TO KEEP SEAGRAM IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Bronfman, the co-chairman of the Seagram Co., which is
being sold to Vivendi of France, is considering making a bid for
his company's liquor division, home to brands like Absolut vodka,
Captain Morgan rum and Chivas Regal scotch.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge Investments Ltd., Bronfman's privately held investment
group, has retained investment bankers at Bear Stearns to examine a
possible bid. Vivendi, a French conglomerate, is building its
entertainment and communications operations, but plans to sell the
liquor business.
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to Bronfman said Sunday that he was still
considering how to structure an offer, if indeed he bids at all.
However, his grandfather, Samuel, founded Seagram as a liquor
company. His nephew, Edgar Bronfman Jr., the chief executive of the
company, expanded it into entertainment properties.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi has no interest in the liquor business and wants to shed
it to help reduce its debt of about $6.6 billion. Analysts have
speculated that the liquor operations could raise more than $7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reports have said that Charles Bronfman has hoped
that the business will remain family-owned. Phone calls to Claridge
and Bear Stearns were not returned Sunday. A spokesman for Seagram
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But a person informed of the discussions said Charles Bronfman
was mulling how to put together a deal, including strategies that
involve joining with Bacardi-Martini, the privately held owner of
Bacardi rum, or with the owner of Absolut vodka, to which Seagram
already owns the worldwide distribution rights.
</P>
<P>
   Absolut's distribution deal stipulates that if Seagram is sold,
the Swedish distiller, the state-owned Vin and Spirit A.B. of
Stockholm, has the right to break its contract. One person
speculated Sunday that the Bronfmans might have some advantage in a
sale because the company and the family already have a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Other large liquor companies that could join the bidding for
Seagram's liquor operations are Diageo of Britain, which just sold
Pillsbury to General Foods for $10.6 billion, prompting analysts to
speculate that Diageo was raising money for a bid. Allied Domecq,
which owns brands like Beefeater gin and Ballantine's scotch, is
also expected to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those companies would have some economies of scale in
making an offer for Seagram that could make it easier for them to
raise their bids beyond the $7 billion to $8 billion that analysts
say the company is worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
