<HEADER>
A4175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FARMER-NEIGHBORS-NYT     08-06 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMER-NEIGHBORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNYARD SHOWDOWN: NEIGHBORS SAY ARTIST IS CREATING A CRASS
MENAGERIE
</HEADLINE>
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Gines Serran-Pagan has a farm. And on this
farm he has some barns. And in those barns he kept some pigs and
chickens and rabbits and sheep and goats. And a llama. But the pigs
got loose and ate the neighbor's grass. The chickens flew the coop
and ate the neighbor's flowers. The rooster crowed at all hours and
disturbed the neighbor's sleep. The llama, the neighbors said, just
plain stunk.
</P>
<P>
   So now Pagan, an internationally renowned artist, gallery
proprietor and the sole owner of livestock in Southampton Village,
has a court date.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors and officials claim that he has violated section
116-9.8 of the village code, which bans ownership of barnyard
animals within village boundaries. Pagan insists that he has found
a loophole in the code that allows people to keep livestock for
pets or meat as long as they own a barn.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has pitted Pagan and the coterie who visit his salon
des artistes _ The Red Bar Atelier _ against his neighbors, the
Gadomskis, a married couple who have lived in the same little house
on Layton Avenue for nearly 50 years. The Spanish-born painter
insists that he is not another out-of-towner with outlandish and
grandiose dreams. Rather, he said, he is a preservationist who is
trying to restore the old character of Southampton; a character
that has been torn down and paved over by a development craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to re-create a colonial feeling here,'' said Pagan, a
quixotic 50-year-old with a shock of curly hair and a goatee. ``The
neighbors, they're an old cranky couple who just don't appreciate
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex and Genevieve Gadomski said they are not cranky people at
all. And as for nature, they grew up on farms in rural Poland.
Their position, they said, is a simple one: Animals are good, just
not in the middle of a subdivision. More than 30 of their neighbors
agree, as does the mayor of Southampton Village, Joseph P.
Romanosky Jr., who happens to be their son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living with a lot of noise and a lot of smell and I'm a
wreck,'' said Mrs. Gadomski, 79. ``I've lived here a long time and
always thought it was residential. If it's not, then I'm buying a
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that the problems started as soon as Pagan
purchased the acre of property in 1997. The parcel is said to be
the oldest collection of barns in the village, dating back to the
18th century. Pagan remodeled the buildings in a Mediterranean
style, with an outdoor bread kiln and palazzo, and turned the place
into a nonprofit gallery space and a petting zoo for school
children.
</P>
<P>
   Pagan planted more than 100 trees around the perimeter to
obscure the view of the Gadomskis' plastic fencing, which he
thought was ugly. The trees began to grow over and through the
fencing, dropping pine needles in the elderly woman's garden.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the spring of last year, the first animals were brought
in: crowing roosters, wandering rabbits, flying chickens, baa-ing
sheep. And the uncastrated llama.
</P>
<P>
   When two chickens flew into his yard last year and tore up his
flowers, Mr. Gadomski 80, brought out a pellet gun. A teenager who
was sent by Pagan to retrieve the chickens said the man threatened
to shoot the birds. ``I admit I had the gun,'' Gadomski said. ``But
I wasn't going to shoot anything. I'd like to wring that guy's
neck, but I'd never shoot anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Gadomskis' complaints, the village took Pagan
to court in July 1999, contending that he violated the animal
disturbance law. The case was dismissed with the caveat that Pagan
put his barn in order and keep the animals quiet. He got rid of the
llama. ``He was very aggressive anyway,'' he said. ``He was
spitting on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But this spring, Pagan bought three pigs. The list of the
menagerie now read: 20 chickens, 20 ducks, six goats, three pigs,
four sheep, sundry rabbits and guinea hens. At some point, the pigs
dined on the Gadomskis' lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Pagan has been summoned to court again and is scheduled to
appear on Sept. 7. Mayor Romanosky wants all of the animals gone
before then and has instructed the sheriff to fine Pagan $250 every
day the animals remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fascism,'' the Spaniard said. ``It is a total abuse of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanosky bristled at the suggestion that he is harassing Pagan
to placate his in-laws. ``It's not as basic as he bought three
little pigs and we're the wolf trying to blow his house in,'' the
mayor said as he was joined in his office by Jonathan Foster, the
village building inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not because it's my in-laws. It's because he's got a
ranch going on over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a llama!'' blurted the building inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Bowed by the $250 fines for the trespassing chickens, Pagan
clipped their wings. He got rid of everything but the goats and
ducks and chickens. He even reinforced the fencing that surrounds
his property. Still the village and the Gadomskis are determined to
close his barn doors.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation, Pagan has launched an all-out ``save the farm''
campaign. He has purchased time on the local radio stations to
plead for justice. He has 500 names on a petition (some local, some
not). His supporters routinely call the mayor. He has taken to
hiding his animals behind the barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make peace, I tried to meet them half-way,'' Pagan
said while standing in the rain, surveying his hacienda. ``But I'm
ready to go to jail for my animals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
