u e BC-SANTA-FE-OPERA-REVIEW     08-06 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-FE-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: GREEK TRAGEDY RESURRECTED IN SANTA FE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALLAN KOZINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ One has to admire Santa Fe Opera's willingness
to gamble. After all, in an eight-week season offering only five
productions, every questionably bankable show accounts for a
significant portion of the schedule. This summer the company is
staging two high-risk works, the American premiere of Hans Werner
Henze's ``Venus and Adonis'' and Rossini's ``Ermione,'' a rarity
that lay unperformed from its 1819 premiere until its modern
revival in 1987. A third work, Strauss' ``Elektra,'' though not
uncommon, is well down the operatic hit parade.
</P>
<P>
   The Henze and Rossini works have a constituency among opera
obsessives who travel the world in search of fresh works and are
the majority of the Santa Fe audience. And ``Elektra'' draws
admirers of the estimable Strauss tradition established here by
John Crosby, the company's founder and general director. But these
constituencies are not huge: only this season's bread-and-butter
offerings, Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' and Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro,''
are sold out.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Ermione,'' the company enlisted Jonathan Miller to direct,
and he transported the piece from the Trojan War era to the
American South just after the Civil War. It is difficult to imagine
what in this work suggested such a peculiar, historically
incongruous move. Perhaps the idea was picked out of a hat.
</P>
<P>
   In this operatic reduction of Racine's ``Andromaque,'' Pyrrhus,
the Greek ruler of defeated Troy, has resolved to dump his wife,
Hermione (Ermione), in favor of the Trojan princess Andromache,
Hector's widow. She considers the offer only as a way to save her
son Astyanax, the heir to the Trojan throne. Orestes, sent by
Greece to demand Astyanax's execution, mostly pants after Hermione,
who dispatches him to murder Pyrrhus and then excoriates him for
doing so when she has a belated change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   A few trenchant moments are scattered through the
2-and-a-half-hour work, but ``Ermione'' is mostly Rossinian
boilerplate: chirpy tunes with scant connection to the words being
sung, much less the emotions they evoke, and plenty of florid
stuntwork for the soloists. That puts a heavy burden on the
soloists: not only must they have the range and agility to meet the
music's demands, but they must sing thrillingly enough to make the
work's vacuousness seem beside the point. The Santa Fe cast worked
valiantly on Thursday evening, with inconsistent results.
</P>
<P>
   In the title role, Alexandrina Pendatchanska wobbled shrilly
through the first act, but after the intermission she settled into
the role sufficiently to give an admirably ornamented account of
Hermione's final scenes. Barry Banks' Orestes was a bit overwrought
and his timbre veered on reediness. But he has the power and range
for this music, and a taste for bel canto heroics.
</P>
<P>
   There was also much to admire in Sara Mingardo's vocally
dark-hued and dramatically dignified portrayal of Andromache. But
Gregory Kunde was an awkward Pyrrhus, stretched well beyond his
limits.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra, conducted by Evelino Pido, seemed to be having
fun with the music, even after Pido toned it down enough to let the
singers be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Orestes reappears in ``Elektra,'' this time to avenge the death
of his father, Agamemnon, by slaughtering his guilty mother,
Clytemnestra, and her new husband, Aegisthus. The Strauss work,
heard on Friday, is being offered in a strikingly direct production
by Copley. The set, by Bruno Schwengl, is the courtyard of
Aegisthus' palace, littered with fragments of a fallen statue of
Agamemnon.
</P>
<P>
   Schwengl's costumes mirror the spirit of the characters: black
for Elektra, light, muted colors for Chrysothemis, a blaze of red
for Clytemnestra and Aegisthus, and cool blue armor for Orestes.
More crucially, the production has a uniformly strong cast. As
Elektra, Mary Jane Johnson was the picture of madness about to
break loose, but under control for the moment. She was undaunted by
either the acrobatics or the virtually unrelieved intensity of
Strauss' vocal line, and in its best moments, her performance was
hair-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Susan B. Anthony's Chrysothemis was paler dramatically, but she
sang with a power and range that matched Johnson's. Judith Forst
played up Clytemnestra's malevolence and magnified her decrepitude,
but was also equal to the considerable vocal demands of the short
role. And Greer Grimsley's sonorous bass was perfectly suited to
the patiently vengeful Orestes.
</P>
<P>
   The company's championship of the Strauss operas, nearly all of
which have been played here, has its roots in Crosby's fascination
with the composer, and the company's tradition is that when Strauss
is on the stage, Crosby is in the pit. His devotion to this music
and his deep knowledge of it were clearly a motivating force, and
the orchestra responded with the lush string textures, burnished
brass sound and, most important, the carefully modulated tension
that ``Elektra'' requires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
