<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KARADZIC-A     08-06 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-KARADZIC-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARADZIC STILL PLAYS HIDE-AND-SEEK WITH U.N. IN BOSNIA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The high, forested mountains of
southeastern Bosnia are a place to hide, and, according to current
local lore, it is there, in the steep gorges or trails and high
passes into neighboring Montenegro, that Radovan Karadzic has been
hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic, the former leader of the Bosnian Serbs twice indicted
by the Hague war crimes tribunal on charges of genocide and crimes
against humanity, took refuge, according to media reports in Bosnia
last month, in the village of Celebici, right on the border with
his native Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   A onetime psychiatrist who led a campaign of extreme nationalism
and instigated a lethal war of ethnic cleansing, he has been
closely guarded since the war ended.
</P>
<P>
   Even men who were once his close associates say they have not
seen him for two years. His influence over the Bosnian Serb
republic, which he founded, is said to be waning, as officials
close to him have been moved out of office, left the country or
been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Karadzic, widely regarded as the man most culpable for the
1992-95 war in Bosnia, is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   His unrepentant presence glowers over every issue in this ruined
society: The return of displaced people to their homes, the rule of
law, cooperation of local officials and politicians with the
international administration, and the failure or unwillingness of
the U.N. peacekeeping force in Bosnia, known as SFOR, to arrest
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me he is the central one,'' said Thomas Miller, the U.S.
ambassador in Bosnia, who insists that arresting Karadzic is still
a priority. ``For my government, if I had one single wish, it would
be to get Karadzic. He's a war criminal, responsible for terrible
things, but to his people he symbolizes resistance. If he goes, it
collapses that wall of resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Karadzic has eluded the special squads who have steadily
picked up lesser suspects _ almost one a month in the last 10
months _ and he has continued to move around the region, if with
great caution and even more warily since NATO troops seized his
close associate and partner in war, Momcilo Krajisnik, in April.
</P>
<P>
   It is five years since Karadzic was indicted, and local
journalists and officials fear that despite all foreign promises,
he may get away for good, sneaking into Montenegro and then Serbia,
where many other war crimes suspects have found refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Georgios Vlachogiannis, the international governor of Foca, the
Serbian nationalist stronghold closest to Celebici, said he did not
believe that Karadzic was still in the area. ``There are rumors
that he is moving through the Montenegrin border,'' he said. ``Some
think he is moving into Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pale, the ski resort town outside Sarajevo that Karadzic made
his capital and wartime headquarters, his daughter has reportedly
been looking for a buyer for her television and radio station,
Astra. That could indicate that the family is preparing to move to
Serbia, one local journalist said. Karadzic's son, a businessman
reputed to have ties to the widespread smuggling networks developed
during the war, has lived in Belgrade for some years.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic's wife, Ljiljana Karadzic, still heads the Red Cross in
the Bosnian Serb republic and in July attended the celebrations in
Pale marking the 10th anniversary of the founding of her husband's
Serbian Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   She appears to live apart from her husband for security reasons
but remains a standard bearer and praised the achievements of his
party.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Karadzic in Pale remains outwardly strong.
``Everyone still supports him,'' said a 24-year-old who gave only
his first name, Mladan. ``I think no one would betray him, despite
the big reward. If he were arrested, blood would be spilled and
there would be attacks on SFOR.''
</P>
<P>
   But others doubt that there would be unrest, pointing to the
muted reaction after the arrest of Krajisnik. ``People are only
interested in jobs,'' said Mayor Dragoljub Pipovic of Foca, a Serb.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The governor, Vlachogiannis, says the thugs who made Foca
notorious _ 12 men from Foca alone have been indicted on war crimes
charges _ have gone and the atmosphere in the town has changed.
``My feeling is that after Krajisnik's arrest they left,'' he said.
``They are probably living in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why NATO peacekeepers would not arrest indicted war crimes
suspects before they crossed the border, a spokesman for the force,
Col. Tom Beginnes, said that it was not the force's task to pursue
suspects and that they could be arrested only when encountered in
the course of peacekeeping activities.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic's top general, Ratko Mladic, has been living in
Belgrade since the end of the Bosnian war and has been sighted
there several times in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Serbia may not provide a safe refuge for some men _ as
Dragan Nikolic, a Serb wanted by the Hague tribunal for crimes
alleged to have been committed in a camp for Muslims near Vlasenica
in 1992, found out. Nikolic, the first man indicted by the war
crimes tribunal, was abducted from his home in the town of
Smederevo in central Serbia in April, driven to the border with
Bosnia in the trunk of a car and handed over to U.S. troops. His
abduction is said to have been organized by Serbian bounty hunters
tempted by the cash reward, who have since been arrested in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has posted a $5 million reward for
information leading to the arrest of the three most notorious men
indicted by the tribunal, Karadzic, Mladic and President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia, who was charged for crimes committed by
his troops in the Kosovo war last year.
</P>
<P>
   If the reward has not brought any results so far, it has
certainly raised the stakes. Wolfgang Petritsch, who heads the
international administration in Bosnia, said the steady stream of
arrests had increased the pressure. ``The big shots are still at
large,'' he said, ``but I can feel a heightened sense of
nervousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic has gone to extreme lengths to protect himself. He
never shows his face, but people know he is in Pale when they see
members of his entourage around, one journalist in the town said.
That last happened two to three months ago, the journalist added.
Former associates say Karadzic went underground two years ago after
the murder of the young deputy police chief, Srdjan Knezevic, in
Pale in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic is widely believed to have been behind the killing,
since the influential deputy had defected to join Biljana Plavsic,
then president of the Bosnian Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
   Plavsic, once an extreme nationalist, turned her back on
Karadzic and threw in her lot with the Western officials running
Bosnia before losing the presidency in late 1998. She reacted by
withdrawing Karadzic's government bodyguards, according to his
former defense minister, Milan Ninkovic.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few close associates of Karadzic still openly in
circulation in Bosnia, Ninkovic remains the most powerful
politician in his hometown of Doboj in the north of the country.
Yet the threat of a secret indictment clearly nagged at him. He
complained that peacekeepers' helicopters had started flying over
his house on the outskirts of Doboj.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often fly over the house and hover, and there is some
indication that they are photographing my house,'' he said. ``I
consider that there is no war crime in my past and the only problem
is that I am an obstacle to my political enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   He served as defense minister for the last year of the war in
Bosnia, and so was in office during the worst massacre of the war,
at Srebrenica. He insists that he had little authority and that
Karadzic and Mladic frequently bypassed him when they issued orders
to the army.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed Mladic, with whom he had frequent disagreements, for
Srebrenica. He was careful in his comments about Karadzic, saying
the only order he had seen was for the army to surround Srebrenica,
not seize it.
</P>
<P>
   Ninkovic, like Karadzic, defends the actions of the Bosnian Serb
leadership during the war. An interview with him runs like a speech
in his defense, and one that takes little account of the recent
arrests and indictments of some of the most notorious Bosnian Croat
war crimes suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only mistake was that I wanted to defend my own people,''
Ninkovic said, accusing the Muslim side of war crimes too. ``Who
killed the 30,000 Serb war dead?'' he asked. ``Yet it is only Serbs
who go to the Hague.''
</P>
</TEXT>
