<HEADLINE>
OFF THE TOP SHELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   __ The book: ``All Things Possible: My Story of Faith, Football
and the Miracle Season.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The author: St. Louis Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, with
Sports Illustrated writer Michael Silver.
</P>
<P>
   __ The essential info: $24; HarperSan Francisco; 269 pgs.
</P>
<P>
   __ The real-life message: Inspirational on many levels, Warner's
story goes well past Hollywood-scripted tripe often passed off as
``Field of Dreams'' material. This reads, and feels, more real.
</P>
<P>
   What he calls ``one of the wildest slingshot rides you'll ever
see in sports or anywhere else'' _ specifically, ending up as the
MVP of the Super Bowl after working his way up from the bottom _
seems even more improbable. As he tells it, starting with his
childhood bedwetting problems and broken home, moving along to
marrying single-mom Brenda and stocking shelves at the supermarket,
it's still stuff that's already been chronicled, but it all seems
richer as he adds his humor and personal anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he writes about trying to avoid the trappings of
success: ``A few years ago, we were eating ramen noodles and peanut
butter-and-jelly sandwiches for dinner, and now that we can go out
to a restaurant and afford to buy anything on the menu, a lot of
times they won't even bring us a check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have to roll my eyes at the special treatment we
receive. People who wouldn't give us the time of day . . . now act
like we're the best thing since squeezable ketchup bottles.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The religion angle: It's an important part of his life, but
he explains how: ``A lot of people are turned off when athletes
talk like this, so let me come right out and clarify my position:
I'm not trying to preach or be overly judgmental, and I'm not in
any way claiming that God is some sort of football grand pooh-bah
who hands out touchdowns and sacks to the faithful like winning
lottery tickets. I'm just trying to give people a sense of what
works for me. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
