<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FOLO0807-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcon's preseason victories make for tough decisions
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Atlanta Falcons discovered in Tokyo that they have
problems _ good problems.
</P>
<P>
   Players are making it very difficult to decide who will stay and
who will go.
</P>
<P>
   The two preseason victories have shown that competition is
intense at the wide receiver, running back and secondary positions.
And four-year veteran quarterback Tony Graziani muddled the
quarterback race with a solid performance in Saturday's 20-9
victory against Dallas in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be a good football team, you're going to
have to turn some good football players out on the street,'' vice
president/football operations Ron Hill said. ``Competition makes
everybody better because people push each other and improve faster
working against better players.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves has made it clear that rookie free agent
quarterback Doug Johnson stands a good chance of staying as a
developmental project. In limited action against Dallas, Johnson
didn't lose any ground, completing three of four passes for 44
yards.
</P>
<P>
   But Graziani was the story.
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that he has little chance in competition
with Danny Kanell for the backup spot, Graziani, a seventh-round
draft choice in 1997, completed nine of 14 passes for 134 yards and
two touchdowns. He threw touchdown passes to 6-foot-5 wide receiver
Brian Finneran, who's pressing for a permanent job, and rookie free
agent Maurice Smith, who also is opening eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell completed nine of 15 passes, including touchdowns to
Finneran and tight end Brian Kozlowski, during last week's victory
against Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical about Tony going to Barcelona (to play in NFL
Europe) instead of staying here in our offseason program, and
working with the new guys,'' Reeves said. ``But he got to play a
lot, and that's really what he needed more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson, whose comeback from right knee surgery should
continue with his first preseason action Friday at home against the
Bengals, isn't the only issue at running back. Smith, who gained 24
yards on eight carries against Dallas, Ron Rivers, Byron Hanspard,
Gary Downs, Ken Oxendine and Winslow Oliver are competing for two
or three running back spots.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams will be a very important consideration for reserve
running backs, and Downs and Oliver, who have not carried the ball
in in the preseason, are valuable there.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith and Rivers (nine carries for 25 yards) have run well
in the past two games. Oxendine also had a strong performance
against the Cowboys with 53 yards on 16 carries. Smith lost a
fumble, but also caused one on a Dallas kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   At wide receiver, Terance Mathis, Tim Dwight and Shawn Jefferson
are locks. Finneran, who had three receptions for 36 yards, Eugene
Baker, who had two catches for 45 yards, Jammi German (20-yard
reception) and special teams ace Ronnie Harris (three for 34) are
vying for two or three spots.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran had a 41-yard reception called back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
