<HEADLINE>
RED SOX IN A CYBERSERIES? GET SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   __ The game: World Series Baseball 2K1, featuring Boston Red Sox
pitcher Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   __ The essential info: By Sega, for Sega Dreamcast, suggested
price: $49.95, rated E (for everyone). This is the first baseball
game made for Dreamcast since the platform was introduced last
September.
</P>
<P>
   __ The pros: Easy to control with five levels of play (amateur,
rookie, veteran, All Star and legend); excellent job incorporating
real player faces onto the cyberbodies with more than 1,500
motion-captured animations, especially with batting and running
motion.
</P>
<P>
   __ The cons: Each defensive play looks anything but fluid, crowd
noises are annoying, and the game announcer is more stiff than
Geoff Witcher in real life.
</P>
<P>
   __ The commercial: Might be the best part of the package right
now. It's with cover boy Pedro Martinez lovingly talking about
``his kids'' and then changing his tune, describing how he'll beat
them at the game because he has ``more pitches than a used-car
salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Keep in mind: It uses rosters that all 30 teams had at the
beginning of the 2000 season, so it's already kind of outdated,
only because of all the trading.
</P>
<P>
   __ A reason to doubt its realism: In a Dodgers-Mets game we
played, Carlos Perez got out of the first inning without giving up
a run.
</P>
</TEXT>
