<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN.COM RESTORES JERUSALEM TO ISRAEL  
 LEWINSKY INTERVIEW DID HAVE ITS COSTS  
 `BIG BROTHER' HOST SEEKING CREDIBILITY  

</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February, executives at CNN.com made a change to their
weather home page that at the time, they said, seemed innocent
enough. On a list of cities that allows users to click on a heading
to get weather reports around the world, they moved Jerusalem out
from under the heading of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Users, who once would have found Jerusalem listed with other
cities in Israel, now found it standing alone.
</P>
<P>
   The executives made the move, they said last week, in keeping
with their editorial position that Jerusalem is a disputed
territory and that to list it as part of Israel would portray
CNN.com as taking sides in the debate. ``CNN is a news-gathering
organization. It does not take editorial stances,'' said Edna
Johnson, a spokeswoman for CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN.com changed its stance last week, after it received an
angry letter from Phil Baum, executive director of the American
Jewish Congress, who wrote that it was exercising ``politically
biased news judgment that Jerusalem is now an international city.''
He demanded that the network change its Web site and put Jerusalem
back under Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Baum's letter was followed by a flood of phone
calls and e-mail messages making the same demand. ``They saw it as
a political statement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After some internal discussion, CNN changed its Web site again
on Thursday, and listed the city as Jerusalem, Israel, once again.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that while the executives at CNN, a unit of Time
Warner, were reacting to the political accusations when they made
the change, they were also, in part, considering complaints from
users who said that by moving Jerusalem out of the Israel section,
they had made it hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Still, executives have not caved in altogether. The CNN.com
weather listing for Jerusalem is marked with an asterisk, which
leads users to the following message: ``The status of Jerusalem,
the seat of Israeli government, is the most contentious issue in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. Palestinian and Arab leaders
consider part of Jerusalem the capital of the prospective
Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky Interview Did Have Its Costs
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, ABC News struck gold: Monica Lewinsky, after
flirting with other news organizations, agreed to give her first
interview to Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing the coup, Walters and ABC News repeatedly
stated that they had not paid Lewinsky for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean that the interview did not cost ABC News.
The organization paid Theodore Olson, a Washington lawyer, to help
it ``secure access to Lewinsky,'' says a profile of David Westin,
the ABC News president, in the issue of The New Yorker that is out
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ABC needed help from the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. The
interview with Lewinsky was delayed for months because of
Lewinsky's immunity agreement with the prosecutor. It required
Lewinsky to get permission from Starr before giving any interviews.
Starr had been withholding that permission.
</P>
<P>
   Starr gave his blessing to the interview in February 1999. The
article does not establish whether Starr gave his permission
because of any efforts by Olson, whom the article describes as a
friend of the prosecutor. Westin told the magazine that the
arrangement did not violate the network's policy against paying for
interviews, since the money was paid to a lawyer, not to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday an ABC spokeswoman said Olson was hired for his
``specialized knowledge and expertise in immunity agreements'' and
took issue with what she called the implication that ABC was paying
for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker article had been widely anticipated among
executives at all of the major news organizations. In part, that
may be because it has been a slow summer in terms of news (yep,
that includes the convention), and an even slower one in terms of
grist for the network chattering classes.
</P>
<P>
   `Big Brother' Host Seeking Credibility
</P>
<P>
   CBS' announcement earlier this summer that Julie Chen, the news
reader on ``The Early Show,'' would be a host on ``Big Brother,''
one of the network's two summer reality programs, sent ripples of
anger through the network's news division.
</P>
<P>
   There was grumbling that it was inappropriate for a news
personality like Chen to participate in ``Big Brother,'' a
prime-time game show that is managed by CBS Entertainment. Her
appointment to the program kicked off a renewed debate over whether
the lines between network news and entertainment were becoming
blurred. Andy Rooney, the ``60 Minutes'' commentator, publicly
called her role in the program ``a further deterioration of news
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, executives close to the program say, Chen is doing what she
can to maintain her stature as a newscaster, heatedly fighting with
``Big Brother'' script writers, who have been handing her lines
that are hardly the stuff of network news people.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after the first episode of ``Big Brother,'' Chen
was heavily criticized by TV critics for uttering the following
decidedly un-newsy statement: ``Wow. That was intense.'' Earlier,
Chen had told the audience, ``Wow, that's wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the lines seemed to have been ad-libbed by Chen,
executives revealed that the words were scripted. Chen, they said,
was deeply embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, they said, she has been engaging in long, tense
arguments about scripts with her ``Big Brother'' producer, Michael
Horowicz, over lines that she thinks will sully her image. Though
Chen is said to have won some battles _ knocking out the more
embarrassing lines _ she has only been able to do so much, and some
have remained from week to week.
</P>
<P>
   Chen and Horowicz both declined to comment on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' runs on CBS six nights a week and made its debut
in July, when 10 contestants were placed in a house together and
put under constant surveillance. Once a week the contestants
nominate one another for elimination or the audience votes one of
them out. Chen is the host of the weekly shows and she interviews
contestants about the week's developments.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said that to give Chen more time for those
interviews, in which she can act more like a newscaster, they have
eliminated the role of the co-host, Ian O'Malley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
