<HEADLINE>
GORE AND ADVISERS GATHER TO SELECT A RUNNING MATE
</HEADLINE>
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ With just hours to go until his self-imposed
deadline of noon on Tuesday, Vice President Al Gore huddled with
close aides and family members Sunday night to make his decision on
a vice presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation continued to center on four Democrats in the Senate
_ John Kerry of Massachusetts, John Edwards of North Carolina,
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and Evan Bayh of Indiana _ although
Gore raised the possibility last week that he might pick a ``wild
card.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president met here Sunday afternoon with Warren
Christopher, the head of his vice presidential search committee, to
discuss his choices. Also in the meeting were Gore's wife, Tipper;
his brother-in-law, Frank Hunger; William Daley, his campaign
chairman; and Donna Brazile, his campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   At every opportunity Sunday, Gore said he had not made a
decision. ``I have not decided yet,'' he said at an afternoon
fund-raiser in New York. ``But I will, and shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley appeared on several talk shows Sunday morning, determined
not to tip Gore's hand but he did discuss how the campaign might
respond to concerns that have been raised about each of the
possible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Edwards' tenure of just a year and a half in the
Senate showed sufficient experience, Daley noted on CNN's ``Late
Edition'' that Abraham Lincoln had served only one term in Congress
before he became president.
</P>
<P>
   Of Kerry, whom some Republicans have branded a Massachusetts
liberal in the Kennedy tradition, Daley said he was a patriot and a
decorated Vietnam veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Of criticism from abortion-rights groups that Bayh was not
committed enough to abortion rights, Daley said that Bayh's record
as a former governor of Indiana showed his leadership and that his
position on abortion would not disqualify him from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the country was ready for a Jewish president _
referring to Lieberman _ Daley acknowledged that some people might
have a problem with that, but he noted that several states have
elected Jewish senators.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rendell, chairman of the Democratic Party and former mayor of
Philadelphia, told reporters on Saturday, ``I don't think anyone
can calculate the effect of having a Jew on the ticket.'' Rendell
is Jewish, but his comments drew criticism Sunday from Jewish
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Diament, political director of the Union of Orthodox
Jewish Congregations of America, said that Rendell was giving
legitimacy to ``whatever anti-Semitic views are out there.''
Diament said he was worried that commentary on Lieberman, whose
Orthodox faith precludes certain activities on Saturdays, was
``feeding a perception that Sabbath-observant people aren't capable
of doing certain jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, speculation centered as much on when the selection might
be leaked to the news media as much as it did on whom the candidate
might be.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman, said, ``There is no firm
timetable, but it's unlikely that any phone calls will take place
until later on on Monday or early Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said that the process was being run in the manner that
Gore had insisted upon. ``We haven't engaged in soliciting
Democrats by sending out questionnaires, we haven't held a series
of press conferences with possible candidates, and you haven't had
a range of names put out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, who has been helping Gore in the selection process,
said Sunday afternoon that he thought Gore had conducted his search
in ``a professional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not brought up any names publicly, but officials close
to the campaign have confirmed a list of six. Besides the four
senators, the list included Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire
and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, both of whom
have said they are not interested.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whom Gore may pick for his running mate has
dominated political talk here and wherever Gore appeared over the
weekend. When he arrived in Nashville from New York on Sunday
afternoon, his hotel was swamped with camera crews and reporters,
and Gore tried to turn the focus of attention from speculation on
his running mate to his campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began the day at a church service in Sag Harbor, N.Y., on
the east end of Long Island. He had asked to speak to honor the
35th anniversary of the signing of the Voting Rights Act of 1965,
which gave the federal government the authority to oversee voter
registration and elections in counties that had used literacy tests
and other unconstitutional means to determine voter eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion allowed Gore to reflect on his, and his father's,
support for civil rights, although, as a U.S. senator from
Tennessee, his father, Albert Gore Sr., had voted against the Civil
Rights Act of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also showcased more of his biography, a goal that is
becoming more urgent as he heads toward the Democratic National
Convention next week in Los Angeles, where his advisers hope he can
make the most of his chance to re-introduce himself to voters.
</P>
<P>
   He used the spotlight over the weekend to appeal to the base of
his party, including blacks and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Sunday from the pulpit of Christ Episcopal Church,
beneath a revolving fan on the arched wooden ceiling, Gore said
that the congregation of about 70 people, who included several
African-Americans, ``looks like America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
