<HEADLINE>
KELLY SAYS HE'S STAYING TWO MORE SEASONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Sophomore wide receiver Kareem Kelly wrapped up
summer school a day early and will unexpectedly join his teammates
today when USC opens training camp at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more important for the Trojans, Kelly has already
decided he will not turn pro after this season, no matter how
successfully he might follow up last season, when he was named the
Pacific-10 Conference Freshman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NFL teams call out at me, I'll turn them down,'' Kelly
said Sunday. ``I want to make it at least until my junior year. I
still have a lot to learn. It's evident that I always get better
every year. But coming out after my sophomore year is too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's announcement means he and sophomore quarterback Carson
Palmer have publicly stated they will both stay at USC for at least
two more years. Kelly said if Palmer turns pro following the 2001
season, he would most likely also leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who caught 54 passes for 904 yards and four touchdowns
last year, said he will be used in a more unconventional manner
this season, in part because teams will probably double-team him
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan a lot of trickery and I'll even be in the backfield a
little,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   __ High expectations: Beginning with Saturday's first team
meeting, it's evident USC enters the year with higher expectations
than any season since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team last night, in all my years of coaching, I
don't know if I've ever been more excited about a group,'' USC
coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is the Orange Bowl, but we'll settle for the Rose
Bowl,'' quarterback Carson Palmer said, referring to the national
championship game in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   __ Freshmen report: Hackett said strong safety Matt Grootegoed
and offensive tackle Joe McGuire stood out in the freshmen-only
practices held on campus this week. He also singled out wide
receiver Keary Colbert, quarterback Matt Cassel and tight ends Alex
Holmes and Gregg Guenther.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the surprise would be (defensive lineman) Jamaal
Williams,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Position switch: Sophomore Scott Huber, who switched from
tight end to linebacker last spring, has decided to move back to
tight end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
