<SLUG> BC-SUIT-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-SUIT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    LAWSUITS TARGET MINE INSPECTOR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CRAIG HARRIS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona State Mine Inspector's Office received just one
anonymous complaint in five years about unsafe conditions at
Asarco's Mission underground copper mine, but the family of Jose
Villanueva blames state officials for the January accident that
took his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now they want $10 million from the state and say they will sue
if the state won't pay.
</P>
<P>
   A suit in the Villanueva death would be the latest in a string
of court battles for the small agency that was created by the
Constitution that accompanied statehood in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Since settling a wrongful-death suit in 1998 for $90,000, the
mine inspector's office lost a trial in April, after a person died
from a fall into an abandoned mine shaft near Payson. The jury
awarded $811,576 in damages after a trial in which the Mine
Inspector's Office alleged the victim had been drinking at the time
of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Another mining wrongful-death case from 1997 is scheduled for
trial this week in Pima County Superior Court in Tucson. In
addition, Mine Inspector Doug Martin, who was elected in 1988 but
had avoided suits until the past few years, faces another
wrongful-death suit involving a concrete facility in Huachuca and a
personal-injury suit from a mine in Morenci.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the jury award and settlement, Martin believes the
lawsuits are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me think I have some people out there who want
monetary compensation, and they don't care where it comes from,''
Martin said. ``They want it from any source they can. {hellip} What
can I say? It is a litigious society.''
</P>
<P>
   When Arizona loses a mining case or agrees to a pretrial
settlement, the money comes from the state's risk management fund.
That money, of course, comes from taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Millea, the Phoenix attorney representing the Villanueva
family, said those victimized by mining accidents have no one to
sue but the state Mine Inspector's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Millea said Arizona's workers' compensation laws make it nearly
impossibly to sue an employer unless an accident victim can prove
willful misconduct. He also said federal laws make it difficult to
sue the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration, the other
government agency responsible for protecting miners.
</P>
<P>
   The Villanueva family contends that the state Mine Inspector's
Office is responsible for Jose Villanueva's death because it acted
in a ``grossly negligent manner'' as it inspected and regulated the
mine, which is 18 miles south of Tucson in the community of
Sahuarita. Millea contends that if the state had done its job,
inspectors would have seen the same kind of unsafe mining
conditions that killed Villanueva.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing if it truly was an unavoidable accident, but
this is not what happened here,'' Millea said. ``It's sad when you
see how this guy (Villanueva) was so concerned about his safety,
and that is why his family is so angry. And that is why we are
going to ask the state for a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva was killed Jan. 31, when a 9-ton slab of copper ore
fell on his crane while he and two partners were loading explosives
into the roof of a cave. He fell at least 20 feet to his death,
while Joe Olson and Javier Vargas were severely injured.
Investigative reports from Martin's office and the federal mine
safety agency said Villanueva and Olson's failure to properly
secure their safety belts contributed to the accident's severity.
</P>
<P>
   During the entire 13 months Villanueva worked at the mine,
neither he nor anyone from his family complained to the state,
according to Phil Howard, assistant mine inspector. In fact, no one
had complained to the state about the mine since 1996, when a
person anonymously complained about poor ventilation and unsafe
work conditions. A state report found those complaints were
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Villanuevas had not called the state mining office
to complain about conditions at the Mission mine, Millea said,
``I'm not sure they understood exactly how mines are regulated.''
He said Jose, his wife and their two youngest children had moved to
Arizona from New Mexico about a year before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Then Millea added, ``I can tell you it is my impression that
miners don't think the Arizona mine inspector does anything. They
report (problems) to the federal agency because they thought they
were more likely to get results.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident, Villanueva's widow, Amparo, has received a
$5,000 burial benefit and roughly two-thirds of his salary from
Asarco's insurance carrier, both of which are required under state
workers' compensation laws. The insurer also has covered all the
medical costs for Olson and Vargas and has paid them nearly
two-thirds of their salary as they recover from severe injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But in each case, the miner or his family is receiving
approximately $200 less every two weeks because the state caps
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is pretty good if you are the employer, but not too
good if you are the employee,'' said Olson, who said he felt boxed
in by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona allows a worker to sue an employer for an on-the-job
accident only if the employee files written notice rejecting
workers' compensation. The notice must be filed before the employee
suffers an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is rarely done and very few people opt out ahead of
time,'' said Brian I. Clymer, a Tucson attorney who wrote a
handbook on the state's workers' compensation system.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Industrial Commission does not keep records as to how
many of the state's 2.36 million workers opt out of the coverage
and therefore retain the option to sue their employer.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas said he had no idea he couldn't sue Asarco now that he
has accepted worker's compensation.
</P>
<P>
   On July 19, Tucson attorney Patrick Butler filed notices of
claim against the state for both Vargas and Olson. Butler claimed
that competent state inspections would have revealed ``that the
mine consistently employed mining methods which resulted in
unnecessary exposure of miners to unstable ground conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The notice of claim for Olson and his wife demands $2.5 million,
claiming that in the accident he suffered a spinal cord injury,
nerve damage and fractures to his sternum, left wrist and left
elbow, as well as four fractured ribs. The claim for Vargas and his
five children demands $3.5 million for injuries to his legs so
severe that he lost several inches of one leg and ``will continue
to require assistance and care.''
</P>
<P>
   Millea said the Villanueva family might sue the federal Mine
Safety and Health Administration if there is proof federal
inspectors failed to investigate safety complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arizona's workers' compensation laws are not all that
different than the rest of the country, said Cheye Calvo, who
studies the issue for the bipartisan National Conference of State
Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trade-off and in most states it benefits employees,''
Calvo said. ``You could go to court, wait five years and not get a
dime. But (under workers' compensation) if you are injured, it will
take care of you Day One and you are compensated for lost wages.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvo also said every state but Texas has a mandatory workers'
compensation system.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, workers' compensation language was written into the
1912 state Constitution at the urging of an attorney who
represented the railroads and Phelps Dodge, a major mining company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, voters changed the Constitution to require an injured
worker to take workers' compensation benefits unless it's rejected
prior to an accident. In 1980, voters changed the law again by
giving co-workers immunity from lawsuits. And language was added to
protect employers from suits unless they ``knowingly and
purposely'' injured workers or engage in a ``willful disregard of
life,'' according to Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   Now with all the suits filed against his office, Martin plans to
ask the 2001 Legislature to give his office absolute immunity from
suits. An effort this year to get the office partial immunity
failed.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at craig.harris(a)arizonarepublic.com or
602-444-8058.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
