<HEADLINE>
CHENEY GIVEN CRUCIAL ROLE IN KEY STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAL, Ill. _ In stump speeches that echoed his combative
address to the Republican National Convention, Dick Cheney on
Sunday repeated his promise of a ``tough fight'' to ``restore
honor, integrity and decency to the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he acknowledged in an interview that House
Republicans bore some responsibility for the ``partisan bickering
and backbiting'' in Washington that he rails against in his
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't deny it has been a two-way street,'' said Cheney, the
Republican vice presidential nominee, on the third day of a rail
trip across middle America with Gov. George W. Bush. ``The process
by which we Republicans took control in '94 left some scar
tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the second-ranking House Republican until he became
defense secretary under President George Bush, also denied waging a
specific offensive against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've attacked President Clinton at this
stage,'' he said. ``We've made it clear what we want to bring to
the White House. If it implies any criticism of the Clinton
administration, that's their problem, not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the lower-key style of Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois was more in sync with Bush's ``compassionate
conservatism'' than the scorched-earth tactics of former Speaker
Newt Gingrich, a friend of Cheney, were. ``Denny Hastert is
probably more suited to the kind of thing we're talking about now
than Newt,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, of course, is a name that most Republicans are running
away from these days. There is little mention of the hard-edged
politics of confrontation that predated Bush. And Cheney fits that
mold of the conservative pragmatist who brings the campaign depth
in foreign affairs and the business world.
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Bush describes his 59-year-old running mate as
``humble,'' ``strong,'' ``steady,'' and someone who has brought
``nobility to public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their rail tour, Cheney has stuck to his role as the
solid, substantive but colorless understudy, the intellectual
ballast who would never upstage the top of the ticket. And that is
how Bush wants it, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what's involved is to get reoriented back into the
political world,'' said Cheney, who until two weeks ago was
chairman of Halliburton Co., the big oil services company. ``All of
this has happened so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace is about to get even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking tradition with the role of previous vice presidents,
who typically were dispatched to shore up their voter base, Cheney
said he would spend most of the campaign in key battleground states
that will be decisive in the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Republicans are so united, we have the freedom to send
him to swing states,'' said Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush will campaign in California and the Pacific Northwest
later this week with his former rival, Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
Cheney will hit the stump on his own in Missouri, Michigan, Ohio,
Kentucky and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   To cover as much electoral ground as possible in the next three
months, the two running mates will run apart, with Cheney saying he
would campaign four or five days a week, depending on the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we'll try from time to time to get together, for joint
appearances, but most of the time we'll have separate schedules,''
Cheney said in an interview Sunday aboard his train, which was
rolling through Illinois cornfields. When Cheney campaigns solo, he
said, he will hammer home the same issues _ education, Social
Security reform, tax cuts and rebuilding the military _ that are
staples of Bush's stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotional undercurrent of Cheney's message is a call to
Republicans to evict what they call a scandal-tainted Democratic
administration. ``It will be a tough fight, but it's absolutely
essential for us to do whatever has to be done in order to restore
honor, integrity and decency to the Oval Office,'' he said at a
rally in Joliet, Ill., on Sunday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The two candidates' body language at rallies on this four-state
jaunt suggests that Bush is comfortable with Cheney, but not close
in the way the chemistry clicked between Bill Clinton and Al Gore
on their first postconvention bus tour in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney, for example, usually just shake hands after the
introductions. On Sunday, for the first time, each threw an arm
around the other's waist, and they waved together to a cheering
crowd in Joliet, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are opposites in other ways. ``Mr. Cheney has
a wry sense of humor,'' Hughes said. ``The governor's is more
rambunctious.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney did have a rare moment of playfulness as his campaign
train pulled into Akron, Ohio, the other day. When he spotted some
photographers on the platform, he threw his arms up in a
Nixon-esque victory pose, grinning until his wife, Lynne, nudged
him to quit clowning around.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it always takes time for two candidates to mesh. At
times Cheney seems more appended than integrated into the
well-oiled Bush campaign. The 13-page press schedule for the
campaign's whistle-stop tour repeatedly listed when ``the
governor'' arrived at or departed from events. But Cheney was
mentioned only once _ when he and his wife were to get off the
campaign plane in Dallas, one stop before Bush flies on to Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his hamming for cameras in Akron, Cheney still doesn't
seem completely at ease on the podium. He introduces Bush usually
in two minutes or less. Two lines from Cheney's convention speech _
``It is time for them to go'' and ``Help is on the way'' _ are
among the biggest applause lines. The former 10-year congressman
from Wyoming delivers them in a matter-of-fact monotone.
</P>
<P>
   When the more dynamic Bush speaks, Cheney tends to fidget on
stage, folding his arms, then jamming his hands in his suit pants,
and then clasping his hands behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   None of this bothered Republicans who turned out to see their
candidates. ``Cheney just seems very sincere,'' said Teri Almy, 55,
an Iona County clerk who came out for the rally in East Lansing,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Cheney insisted that he is running for ideals
developed over three decades of public service. When Bush asked him
to run, Cheney said he had no good reasons other than personal
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, look at what he gave up: a great CEO's job, making
millions of dollars a year, he had his own private airplane; now
he's out here running for public office, what the hell's wrong with
him,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the crowds on the trail have already vindicated his
decision. ``Mostly what people say is, thank you, we really
appreciate you're willing to take this on,'' said Cheney. ``That
counts for a hell of a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
