<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE METS' ONLY GOOD NEWS COMES AT A HOSPITAL IN SCOTTSDALE 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The New York Mets' only victory Sunday came at a
hospital in Scottsdale, where Mike Piazza's left knee was examined
and found to not be seriously injured. There was not much happening
at Bank One Ballpark, where the Arizona Diamondbacks stopped the
Mets, 9-5, in a lackluster game that snapped the Mets' seven-game
winning streak against their rivals from the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had won four straight and 10 of their previous 11
games, their only loss coming when Cincinnati beat Glendon Rusch
last week. Rusch (7-9) was the losing pitcher Sunday, when he
missed his locations at critical moments and the Diamondbacks made
him pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had two of their best hitters out of the lineup.
Piazza, who sprained the medial collateral ligament in his left
knee after crossing first base on a close play Saturday night, will
miss three to five games, and Todd Zeile was given the day off.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets mounted a rally in the ninth inning, helped by Jay
Payton's fourth single of the game. The Diamondbacks, who started
the inning leading by 9-3, had to summon their closer, Matt Mantei,
with two runs in, two runners on and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   The next two hitters were the first baseman and the catcher, but
with Zeile and Piazza out, those hitters were Matt Franco and Todd
Pratt. Franco struck out to end the game, leaving Pratt on deck and
earning Mantei a save.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's home run off Mantei last October clinched the Mets'
victory in the division series over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a great ball team,'' Mantei said. ``Their lineup
is solid one through eight, and even some of their pitchers can
hit. There's not a thing I don't like about the Mets. I like the
way they play, I like the way they hustle; they play hard. Just to
get a win and get an edge on them a little bit is nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to pitch in this series. After the home run last
year, I wanted to go out and pitch well against them again.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Mets traveled to Houston, where they will
play at Enron Field for the first time, in a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very dangerous situation,'' Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine said of playing the Astros, who have baseball's worst
record (42-69). ``They're still good players without a good
record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, of course, were supposed to be the more
formidable opponent on this two-city, seven-game trip. But since
Arizona beat the Mets in the second game of last October's division
series, the Mets had won seven consecutive games between the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks won Sunday behind the efficient pitching of the
former Met Armando Reynoso (8-7) and some big hits by Matt Williams
and Greg Colbrunn. Williams had three hits, including a two-run
homer, and Colbrunn had two, including a three-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   For Rusch, the four-inning outing was his shortest start of the
season; he had lasted at least five innings in each of his first 19
starts. The trouble began in the second inning, when Rusch fell
behind in the count to Colbrunn, 3-1. Rusch rarely issues a walk,
and his next offering was over the plate. Colbrunn ripped it down
the left-field line for a double, and a single and a sacrifice fly
followed to give the Diamondbacks a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tied the score the next inning, with a big assist from
Colbrunn. With the bases loaded and one out, Robin Ventura hit what
should have been an inning-ending double-play grounder to Colbrunn
at first. But he bobbled the ball and could get only one out,
allowing a run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch retired the first two batters in the third, but Luis
Gonzalez singled and Williams came up. Williams is a productive
home run hitter, but he has lost much of this season to injuries to
his right foot and right quadriceps and had only three homers
coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did not miss a high fastball from Rusch. He lined it
into the bleachers in left-center field for his first home run in
more than three weeks. The Diamondbacks led, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the Diamondbacks' fourth, a walk and a single put two runners
on with one out. A sacrifice accounted for the second out, and
Rusch got ahead of Tony Womack, 1-2. He had retired Womack on a
breaking ball earlier, and he tried one again. But the pitch hung
in the strike zone, and Womack whacked it up the middle, scoring
two runs and increasing Arizona's lead to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of games, one pitch is going to make or break the
ballgame,'' Rusch said. ``You need to identify that point in the
game and make quality pitches there. If you don't, it could cost
you the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   After a walk, the pitching coach Dave Wallace came to the mound
to visit Rusch. The left-hander stayed in and retired Gonzalez to
end the inning, but he left for a pinch-hitter in the fifth, having
allowed five runs, seven hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch's opponent was the right-handed Reynoso, who has not lost
against the Mets since leaving them as a free agent after the 1998
season. Reynoso, who beat the Mets twice last year, gave up five
singles through six innings, but he faltered in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and a runner on, Mike Bordick drove a pitch just
over the fence in left field for his second home run as a Met. That
cut Arizona's lead to 6-3, and it chased Reynoso from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer and Greg Swindell finished up the inning, and the
Diamondbacks put the game away in the seventh, when Colbrunn bashed
a three-run homer off Dennis Cook. Cook had allowed only one run in
the second half of the season before giving up three in one inning
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
