<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: YANKEES TOO SUCCESSFUL FOR THEIR OWN GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trapped in the Bronx, or thoughts from the deepest,
darkest recesses of George Steinbrenner's mind:
</P>
<P>
   I just can't believe what's happening. What's wrong with these
people? I tried for years to warn them of the dangers of coming to
Yankee Stadium, and for years they heeded my warnings. Remember
1996? I did some of my best work that year. We won the World
Series, but we had only two and a quarter million fans come to the
old ball yard in the Bronx. It was no coincidence that it was
during that year that my friend the mayor released a report
recommending the construction of a new park on the West Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   I have only myself to blame. I dragged my feet and didn't let
Rudy know what I wanted to do. I kept saying I'd announce my
decision after the season. I just never said what season. I never
said I'd take Manhattan, forget the Bronx and Staten Island, too.
If I had, maybe I wouldn't be in this quandary. Look at what has
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Another crowd of 50,000-plus showed up at the Stadium Sunday for
the game with Seattle that we played so badly I should have offered
them tickets for another game. That makes 11 crowds of 50,000 or
more in the first 53 home dates, four more than last year for the
same number of dates. (I don't keep these things in my head; I just
tell my PR people to get me the information and they jump.)
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Yankees history, not just my history but
the Yankees' entire history, we are averaging 41,000 fans a game.
If we just maintain that average _ and I'm afraid we're going to
exceed it as we get closer to another championship _ we'll finish
with a total attendance of 3.32 million. Last year we reached 3
million for the first time, and we would break that record.
</P>
<P>
   So how on earth am I supposed to convince anyone that we need a
new park? Why would the city and the state be willing to spend a
billion dollars or more on a new park when we're doing better than
ever at the old one? Not just better than ever, really, better than
anyone would have ever expected.
</P>
<P>
   We got too good for our own good. We are a prisoner of our own
success. In the mid-70s we went to the World Series three years in
a row and won two in a row, and in those three seasons we had a
total of 6.44 million fans. We'll have more than that just for this
season and last.
</P>
<P>
   We have become too attractive. The fans find us too
irresistible. We're like a human magnet that is pulling people into
the Bronx despite the dangers. At this point, we probably couldn't
even justify renovating Yankee Stadium for three-quarters of a
billion. That's what the 1996 study said it would cost. Today it
would probably cost closer to a billion. Rudy's a lame duck. He
probably couldn't even push that plan through.
</P>
<P>
   My luxury boxes, will I ever get my luxury boxes? Baltimore,
Cleveland, Seattle and Detroit have luxury boxes. Colorado, San
Francisco, Houston and Arizona have luxury boxes. For heaven's
sake, Pittsburgh and Milwaukee are going to have luxury boxes. And
George Steinbrenner isn't going to get luxury boxes. I get the
Grand Concourse that hasn't been grand for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   But now that I'm thinking about this, maybe I should forget
about it. Who needs a new park with luxury boxes if those other
incompetent owners are going to take my money? Yeah, remember that
blue-ribbon report? Those guys want to take half of my local
revenue and give it away. They want to play Robin Hood and rob me
of my hard-earned money and give it to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   I can just see my good friend Bud wearing green tights and
riding from place to place dropping off bags of my money. One for
the Expos and one for the Twins and one for this team that never
wins.
</P>
<P>
   This year they're going to take about $25 million from me and
spread it around to those so-called small-market clubs. Right. When
did the Angels and the Phillies become small-market clubs? Next
thing you know, they'll be giving some of it to the Mets, too.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs to generate more revenue just to give it away? If I
want to give money to charity, I can send a check to the Little
Sisters of the Poor. It'll cost me a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   That report said we already have the most local revenue _ $650
million for the past five years, it said. With our local television
money going up in a new deal, way up _ I have to be careful and not
talk out loud about it because we've been sued over it _ our total
local revenue will go up. So we will already be giving away more of
my money. Why should I sweat out construction of a new park or
renovation of the one we have just so those greedy guys can get
their hands deeper into my pockets?
</P>
<P>
   I have no intention of operating the George Steinbrenner
Foundation for Wayward Baseball Teams. I gotta call Rudy in the
morning and tell him I've made my decision. No more
procrastinating, no more fence-sitting. Rudy, we're not going
anywhere. But you better reserve your seats for the rest of the
season. They're flocking to the Stadium. What a wonderful place to
see a ballgame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
