<SLUG> BC-TEN-MANHATN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTYLE.COM EVENT WILL PREP PLAYERS FOR U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Some of the world's top women tennis
players will be looking for a bit of a bounce when the estyle.com
Classic begins today at the Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, in its 19th year, boasts one of its top singles
fields ever, with many of those star players feeling as though they
have something to prove this week after recent disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis and Lindsay Davenport, ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in
the world and seeded the same way, both suffered stunning
early-round defeats last week at the Acura Classic in Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, winner of four career Grand Slam
titles, has advanced past the quarterfinals just four times this
year, and Serena Williams must worry not only about matching her
breakout 1999 season, when she won five tournaments, but also about
matching her older sister, Venus, who won Wimbledon and the Acura.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'm not very happy with the way I've played this
year,'' said Serena Williams, the defending champion who has just
one victory this year. ``I think I could have won a few more
tournaments and done a little better here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I still have the rest of the year left, and we're
going into the last part of the season. So I feel that I'm going to
do a lot better. The second portion of last year, after the U.S.
Open, I was really focused.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open, which begins in three weeks, will be on all the
players' minds. Manhattan Beach serves as a chance to restore
confidence heading into the final Grand Slam event of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, 19, earned her first Grand Slam title last year
at the U.S. Open and hopes that Manhattan Beach will once again be
the jump-start that will carry over to New York later this month.
She missed two months of this season with a knee injury but reached
the semifinals at Wimbledon, where she lost to her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm practicing really hard,'' Williams said. ``I'm not taking
hardly any time off. I'm really going for it. I really feel I'm
going to do well (at the U.S. Open) again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Williams, Davenport or Hingis stumble again this week,
there are plenty of other players capable of winning.
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, Monica Seles is one of the oldest players among the
tour's elite but has won three singles titles this year and reached
the Acura final. Seles is ranked No. 5 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Conchita Martinez, thought to be on the downside of a long and
consistent career, rebounded earlier this year by reaching the
Australian Open final. Amy Frazier upset Hingis is the
quarterfinals of the Acura Classic, and wild card Alexandra
Stevenson reached the Wimbledon semifinals in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-player tournament begins today at 10 a.m. and concludes
with the championship match Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
