<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-RING-REVIEW-SPI &LR;      08-06 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RING-REVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE OPERA RETURNS TO ITS ROOTS WITH RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By R.M. CAMPBELL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its third production of Wagner's ``Der Ring des Nibelungen''
over the past 25 years, Seattle Opera has returned to its roots: a
concern for Wagner's text and evocation of the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   The latest edition, premiered in part this past weekend at the
Opera House, employs technological advances in stagecraft, as well
as imagination on a high order and some of the best singers plying
the composer's treacherous waters today.
</P>
<P>
   The result is thoroughly engrossing _ visually and musically and
dramatically _ with an excitement both visceral and intellectual.
For the first two operas in the cycle, ``Das Rheingold'' and ``Die
Walkure,'' Seattle Opera general director Speight Jenkins has
assembled an extraordinary cast which is, at the least, equal if
not superior to most ``Ring'' casts in the world. As a group, they
have handsome tone and startingly electricity and the requisite
power to fill the nearly 3,100-seat house. And, directed by Stephen
Wadsworth, they make Wagner's drama, often static in less inventive
hands, a vivid theatrical enterprise. Swiss conductor Armin
Jordan's conducting is a revelation of detail and sensuous beauty.
Thomas Lynch's set design _ ``green'' to the core at Jenkins
insistence _ is often awesome, in a sober way, and surprisingly
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   With all the contemporary ``Ring'' cycles afloat on the world's
stages, it is more fashionable, even glamorous, to do something
radical than something traditional: for instance the ``Ring'' that
premiered last week at the Bayreuth Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Opera sought a ``Ring'' traditional in concept but not
traditional in execution, a production with values Wagner would
recognize: the naturalistic world the composer envisioned but did
not have the means to realize.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's set design is remarkable in many ways, at times so real
one forgets it is a theatrical illusion. The opening Rhine scene is
the cycle's coup de theatre, with Rhinedaughters ``swimming'' in
midair. It is spectacular and enchanting and really works. The
forests in ``Rheingold'' and ``Walk &UR; gfumlaut &LR; ure'' are not pretty _
they are hungry for air and light _ but they are telling. The first
is sparse and the former gnarled and tight. The wild and rocky
mountainside in ``Walk &UR; gfumlaut &LR; ure'' is magnificent and
awe-inspiring; so is Loge's fire. Making the first scene in Act II
the same as Act I will raise eyebrows because it is such a
departure from Wagner's directions, but it makes dramatic sense.
Martin Pakledinaz's costumes are quiet in design but immensely
clever in the ways they drape the singers, make the extended drama
coherent and spark new ideas. Peter Kaczorowski's lighting design
is also notable and totally integrated.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's stage direction is a marvel of detail that
elucidates relationships and keeps the action moving. One could
cavil about occasional gestures, but their sum total is a
revelation of character and motivation, even unexpected humor and
theatrical pizzazz.
</P>
<P>
   The cast was astonishing, especially the women singing
Brunnhilde, Fricka and Sieglinde. Jane Eaglen sang very well
indeed, a substantive growth of musical expression and confidence
in the four years since I heard her do Brunnhilde at Lyric Opera of
Chicago. With Wadsworth directing her, she has never appeared more
as an actress. Stephanie Blythe, in her Seattle debut as Fricka,
has huge reserves upon which she can draw. There is a shiny glint
at the top of her voice and depth and character at the bottom. She
is not merely big in voice: She sings the music, colors and phrases
it with discretion and a sense of theater. Another local debut was
Margaret Jane Wray, singing Sieglinde. Her performance, in a word,
was thrilling. With a brilliant soprano totally at her command,
Wray conveyed the torment of her character as well as her
exhalation. The voice has steel in it, but the kind of metal that
glistens and glowers.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Maultsby is one of the few to remain from the second
``Ring.'' Her Erda has become greater in dimension and her voice,
richer and more resonance. Marie Plette was a good Freia,
attractive and appealing. The three Rhinedaughters _ Lisa Saffer,
Mary Phillips, Laura Tucker _ were amazing because they sang well
while flying in mid-air and doing somersaults in two directions.
The valkyries looked terrific _ handsome women in handsome
costumes, well-directed. I have never seen the scene better staged.
</P>
<P>
   The men were also impressive. Phillip Joll is a committed,
persuasive Wotan, although more in ``Walkure'' than ``Rheingold.''
He is a character difficult to like, yet Joll made him sympathetic.
Stephen Milling's Fasolt in ``Rheingold'' was moving and Hunding in
``Walkure'' terrifying. Whereas he was sympathetic in
``Rheingold,'' he was horrific, in presence and voice, in
``Walkure.'' Again, he is a singer with a big, impressive voice who
doesn't just sing loud. Mark Baker's portrait of Siegmund was
engaging and persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Paul Fink was a menacing Alberich, who actually sings
the music, which many don't. He was also an ardent suitor of the
Rhinedaughters, slipping and sliding at his own peril, or so it
seemed, at the bottom of the Rhine. Peter Kazaras sang a
calculating Loge, dispensing bolts and bits of fire wherever he
went. James Courtney was a good Donner and Thomas Studebaker
equally so as Froh. Thomas Harper's Mime is well-known here, and no
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's conducting was a singular revelation of tonal splendor
and carefully judged dynamics. Balance in the orchestra was
exemplary. When clarity when required, it was there, shimmering and
translucent, but Jordan had no difficulty in summoning Wagner's
awesome demands for sheer sonic power. Orchestral textures
resembled silk, smooth and luxurious in sensibility but solid
muscle supporting it. Even soft, tender passages were firm and
focused. The orchestra, many of whom are members of the Seattle
Symphony, played well for its conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Dean's new supertitles have rendered Wagner's old
German into something poetic, dignified and illuminating, often
with a dollop of archaic English to give it the right historical
feeling and alliteration to mirror the composer's predilection for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities to see, and hear, the ``Ring'' are limited: The
three cycles of Seattle's complete ``Ring'' next summer are already
approaching sold-out status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
