<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-THOMPSON-2TA     08-06 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-THOMPSON-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 THOMPSON HOPES TO TOUCH GOLD AT END OF THE POOL
</HEADLINE>
  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is tied with the speedskater Bonnie Blair for most Olympic
gold medals won by a U.S. woman _ five _ but Jenny Thompson's
swimming career carries the slight whiff of unfulfillment. This
sense of incompletion is barely perceptible, but it hovers about
the pool, wafting like a trace of chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter and Summer Games have always celebrated individual
achievement over team accomplishment, and all of Thompson's gold
medals have come in relay events. So, at 27, she will enter her
fourth Olympic swimming trials, which begin Wednesday in
Indianapolis. It is not a singular medal itself she is chasing next
month at the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, or rather not the
gold-plated hardware, but instead a sense of goals achieved,
potential consummated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to me, because I feel I'm capable of doing
it,'' Thompson said. ``If this is my last Olympics, I can know that
I'm ending the closest I can get to my potential.'' She added: ``If
I stopped now, I would feel disappointed, not because I didn't get
a gold medal, but because I didn't try. I feel I owe it to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her career will follow the same arc as that of Pablo
Morales, the world record-holder who failed to make the U.S. team
in 1988 and won the 100-meter butterfly in 1992. Except Thompson
has five gold medals. Still, she feels some small inadequacy, one
gold medal lost in what surely was an undetected Chinese doping
scandal, another missed because she found herself trapped in an
undertow of nerves and stress.
</P>
<P>
   Four months before the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona, Spain,
Thompson set a world record in the 100-meter freestyle, becoming
the first swimmer outside East Germany to set a world mark in the
event in two decades. At the Barcelona Games, though, Thompson
finished second to Zhuang Yong of China. ``Zhuang immediately
became the focus of a growing suspicion that the Chinese women
swimmers were taking steroids and other prohibited substances,''
David Wallechinsky wrote in ``The Complete Book of the Summer
Olympics. ``With her deep voice, heavy muscles and bad acne, she
fit the profile of a steroid user.''
</P>
<P>
   Many athletes and coaches also became incensed that all
medalists, including Zhuang, were not being tested for drugs after
swimming events, as they were in other sports. Thompson voiced her
concerns, and like Shirley Babashoff before her, she was criticized
for fermenting her skepticism into sour grapes. But, just as
Babashoff had been right about the East Germans in the 1970s,
Thompson was correct about the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 female Chinese swimmers have been caught cheating
in the last decade, including Yuan Yuan, who was found with 13
vials of human growth hormone in her luggage at the 1998 world
championships in Perth, Australia. China has vowed to crack down on
drug cheats, and its female swimmers have lost their dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Wu Yanyan, the 200-meter individual medley world
champion, was removed from China's training camp for the Sydney
Games after testing positive for a muscle-building steroid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have said what I said if I didn't think it was
accurate,'' Thompson said. ``I don't mind being criticized if I'm
saying what I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the medical commission of the International Olympic
Committee approved testing for EPO, an endurance drug believed to
be widely used in swimming. But there will be no test for human
growth hormone, a steroid, and other banned substances in Sydney.
Thompson continues to question the desire of Olympic officials to
catch drug cheats.
</P>
<P>
   Women's swimming, perhaps more than any other Olympic sport, has
been tarnished by the specter of drugs. Every East German
performance from 1968 through 1988 _ including all 32 gold medals _
has been discredited by revelations in court of the country's
state-sponsored system of doping. Cheating by the Chinese has been
thoroughly documented, and suspicions about three gold medals won
by the Irish swimmer Michelle Smith at the 1996 Atlanta Games
gained credence last year when she was banned for spiking a drug
test with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there could be a test for growth hormone,'' Thompson
said. ``It makes me angry. The drug is being abused. The technology
is there for a test, but IOC officials are worried about looking
bad. If there is a test and 50 percent of the athletes test
positive, it makes the IOC look really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago at the Olympic trials, Thompson created problems
of her own doing. On opening day, she finished third in the
100-meter freestyle _ only two swimmers qualify in each event _ and
she began suffering from insomnia and self-doubt. The trials
spiraled into the worst meet of her career, and she did not qualify
in any single event for the Atlanta Games. She won three relay gold
medals in Atlanta, but individual gold remained elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media pressure was getting to me,'' Thompson said.
``I was putting too much pressure on myself. I was worried about my
competitors. I wasn't being myself. I wasn't enjoying the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson began to reassess her career, realizing that she was
too serious and obsessed, narrowed by a kind of tunnel vision that
left her with little besides swimming. ``Winning was the only
important thing,'' she said. ``I really wanted to kill my
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Atlanta, she said, she recovered a joy that she
experienced as a child in Dover, N.H., swimming because she loved
to be in the water and to race with her friends and to do frivolous
things, like eating Jell-O from a box. That childlike joy is
leavened by a wider world view. Swimming is no longer the only
thing in her life. A 1995 graduate of Stanford, Thompson has been
accepted into medical school at Columbia University, which she
plans to enter next August.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had had the dream Olympics I wanted to have in Atlanta, I
wouldn't be here,'' Thompson said of the trials. ``I think, in a
large way, it was a blessing. I learned so much about myself and my
swimming.'' She added: ``I've never lost the desire to win a race,
but I do see it with a different perspective. Now I have much more
joy. I enjoy the whole process, the crowds, the kids, my teammates
cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   And she has been swimming faster than ever, using weight
training, yoga and stretching exercises to increase her strength
and flexibility. Last year Thompson set a world record in the
100-meter butterfly, 57.88 seconds, breaking a mark by Mary T.
Meagher that had stood for 18 years. Last month Thompson broke her
own U.S. record in the 100 freestyle in 54.27, set a personal best
of 1 minute 59.49 seconds in the 200 freestyle and came within
two-hundredths of a second of her best in the 50 freestyle, 25.20.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the trials, Thompson will wear a version of the so-called
Fastskin bodysuit made by Speedo, which mimics sharkskin and
decreases drag in the water. A number of world records have been
set in similar suits this year. U.S. officials banned the suits
from the trials, saying they were not available to everyone, then
reversed themselves after one manufacturer threatened to file a
grievance. Thompson said she would wear a version that covers her
legs but not her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my legs are raised higher in the water; it doesn't take
as much energy to stay afloat,'' the 5-foot-10-inch, 160-pound
Thompson said. ``I'm a densely muscular person. With the suit, it's
easier. It streamlines the body so it can flow through water
easier. It's like control-top pantyhose.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, winning an individual gold medal may not be any easier in
Sydney than it was in Barcelona and Atlanta. Inge de Bruijn of the
Netherlands has set blistering records in the 50 and 100 freestyle
this year and has twice lowered the 100 butterfly record. It stands
now at 56.64, a stunning 1.2 seconds below Thompson's old mark,
bringing inevitable public suspicion about doping, which de Bruijn
has vehemently denied. The old Jenny Thompson might have become
bitter, unnerved. The new one has not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I feel her times are skeptical is irrelevant,''
Thompson said. ``They are real world records. I don't feel like
they're impossible times for me to do. They are real times for me
to shoot for and surpass.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the race she really wants in Sydney, the 100 butterfly,
perhaps to break yet again a record that was once considered
unbreakable. There could be no greater validation of her longevity
and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really motivated, this being the end of the road and
wanting to live up to my potential,'' Thompson said. ``An Olympic
gold medal would be nice.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
