<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, AUGUST 7 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-NYT (moved Monday, July 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 31
about preparations by Dutch and Scottish officials for the trial of
two Libyans accused in the Lockerbie bombing used an outdated name
for a soft drink reputed to replace whisky among Scottish officers
barred from using alcohol while armed. It is Irn-Bru. While it was
first marketed as Iron-Brew in 1901, manufacturers adopted the
phonetic spelling after World War II because the drink was not
brewed and did not meet labeling regulations.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-SHLOMO-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary of Grand Rabbi Shlomo
Halberstam of the Bobover sect, sent on Wednesday, August 2,
misstated the title of a documentary in which he is shown dancing.
It is ``A Life Apart: Hasidism in America,'' not ``A World Apart:
Hasidic Life in America.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-PEARSON-NCS-NYT (moved Monday, July 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 31
about the purchase of National Computer Systems Inc. by Pearson
P.L.C. misstated Pearson's relationship to Simon &AMP; Schuster.
Pearson acquired Simon &AMP; Schuster's educational publishing
operation in 1998; Viacom owns the Simon &AMP; Schuster trade
publishing operation and the name.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-NYT (moved Wednesday, July 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July 19
about a University of Tennesee professor who made charges about
improprieties in academic work by varsity athletes misstated the
number of students at the Knoxville campus. It is 26,000, not
40,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
