<SLUG> BC-PHONE-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS BEGIN STRIKE AGAINST VERIZON AS TALKS CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va. to Maine)  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of workers fanned out to picket sites throughout the
East Sunday as negotiators for Verizon Communications and its
unions pressed forward with efforts to end a strike by about 86,000
telephone employees.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly affecting routine services, the labor dispute at
Verizon, the nation's largest local and wireless telephone company,
disrupted operator-assisted services, repairs and installations for
25 million residential and business customers from Maine to
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the strike, over issues including the outsourcing
of work and the unionization of employees in the wireless business,
may help to define the role of organized labor in some of the most
rapidly growing high-technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could open the door for unions to move not only into
wireless but into other high-tech parts of the economy as well,''
said Paul Osterman, professor of management at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was able to limit the immediate impact of the strike by
deploying about 30,000 managers to cover tasks normally performed
by the striking employees. Automated services on Verizon's network
and wireless services were not disrupted. But delays in repairs and
operator-assisted services could become more common as the workweek
begins.
</P>
<P>
   While members of the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers picketed at several
hundred Verizon facilities in several East Coast cities, there was
progress in the talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Verizon offered concessions that would
allow the unions to organize more easily in the company's
fast-growing wireless division, a central bargaining issue that
could have a substantial effect on labor relations in the entire
wireless communications industry, said people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was formed by Bell Atlantic's acquisition of GTE and its
venture in wireless communications with Vodafone AirTouch. But
while it operates the nation's largest wireless carrier, only a few
dozen of the wireless company's 32,000 workers are union members,
compared with 80 percent of the 120,000 employees in Verizon's
local telephone division.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the company and the unions approached compromise on
the wireless issue, job security and Verizon's practice of
outsourcing work in fast-growing areas like the installation of
high-speed Internet lines, they appeared to be far apart on other
issues Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokeswoman from the Communications Workers of
America, the unions and the company remained most divided over
forced overtime and job stress.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side appeared optimistic that an agreement could be
reached late Sunday, although the unions and Verizon said they were
ready to continue negotiations throughout the evening and into the
morning if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, striking workers in 13 Eastern states and the
nation's capital dug in for a walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I figured it out: three days,'' said Roger
Doucette, 53, when asked how long he could afford to be on strike
from his job as a trainer at a Verizon service center in Braintree,
Mass. But he said he was ready to strike as long as necessary,
given his particular concern over the company's policy of
outsourcing work in the installation of high-speed Internet lines.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, only a scattering of union members could be
found at Verizon facilities, perhaps because of the progress in the
talks. At the company's headquarters in Midtown Manhattan, six
protesters, clad in red for union solidarity, stood behind police
barricades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to sabotage. We just want more money,'' said
Shirley Harris, 33, an administrative assistant. ``It's very
expensive to live in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cities, the strike generated greater tension between
workers and management.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, striking employees blockaded entrances to
Verizon's main switching facility in Philadelphia, effectively
keeping managers from entering the building. In Delaware, some
strikers also blocked access to facilities. The company was seeking
court injunctions to deal with these cases, said Eric Rabe,
Verizon's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 740 union workers out of 3,100 scheduled to work in
the strike region Sunday showed up. Most of those were in New
Jersey and not covered under the same contract as the striking
workers, according to Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   Managers were expected to work 12-hour shifts to provide stopgap
service while the strike continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while I'll probably get tired of this,'' said
Stephenne L. Bell, who normally does budget tracking analysis in
Verizon's marketing and communications department. On Sunday, she
was working a 5:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. shift at a customer service
center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, where about 2,500 telephone lines were put out of
service Sunday because of a cut line, Verizon said repairs could be
delayed because of the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Verizon deals with an average of 2,600
requests for telephone installations and 4,500 requests for repairs
each day, said Steven Marcus, a spokesman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   As the company moved to handle potential service problems and
talks continued, the negotiations were of particular interest to
employees in Verizon's largely nonunionized wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being treated like a second-class citizen within
the company,'' said a customer service representative from a call
center in Woburn, Mass. She declined to provide her name, she said,
because Verizon had told employees at the call center that they
would be fired if they discussed joining the union on work
premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a union contract, I'd have chances for better pay,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the union, customer service representatives at
Verizon's wireless unit who are not union members in Massachusetts
make about a third less than unionized employees who do virtually
the same job in other parts of the company. The company says pay
differences are much smaller than the union's claim.
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking assurances from Verizon that the company
would not interfere with or actively discourage organizing
activities at the wireless division, making it easier for the union
to sign up employees. Because Verizon Wireless controls nearly 30
percent of the wireless market, the outcome of the strike could
affect labor relations throughout the wireless industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If labor can't penetrate the new economy, they will be
assigned to its margins,'' said Stanley Aronowitz, a sociology
professor at the City University of New York. Aronowitz compared
the situation to union efforts in the 1930s to organize in the
automotive and steel industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going after the biggie with the idea that the others
will fall in line,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
