<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS PROVES TOO POWERFUL FOR SELES
</HEADLINE>
 By MICHAEL ARKUSH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ The seeded players have yet to be announced
and the sages have yet to weigh in. Even so, with the U.S. Open set
to begin in three weeks, a favorite has emerged among the women.
Her name is Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams started her run last month at Wimbledon, of course,
with an impressive victory over Lindsay Davenport in the final, and
has not slowed down since.
</P>
<P>
   With her 6-0, 6-7 (3), 6-3 triumph over Monica Seles on Sunday
in the Acura Classic at the La Costa Resort and Spa, Williams
captured her third tournament title and 15th match in a row.
Despite 14 double faults in the match and a loss of focus during
the second set, the third-seeded Williams continued to serve notice
that she can dominate a match against a quality opponent even when
she is not at her most formidable. Although she committed 34
unforced errors, she recorded 38 winners, using the powerful ground
strokes that have made her so successful.
</P>
<P>
   For her opponents, there is almost no defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play my best tennis,'' said Williams, who, bothered
by the sun, had 10 double faults in the second set. But, she added,
``I'm still winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first set, Williams rolled past Seles in 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hitting the ball with some pace,'' Williams said. ``I
was hitting it deep.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Seles picked up her first-serve percentage
and came through at several key moments.
</P>
<P>
   Although she squandered a 5-2 lead, and it appeared as if she
might lose the match in two sets, the fourth-seeded Seles played
well in the tie breaker _ aided by three double faults from
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Seles could not maintain the momentum in the deciding set. She
rebounded from a service break to record her own, putting the match
back on serve at 4-3. But the resilient Williams immediately broke
back to seize control once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a key game for me to hold,'' said Seles, who is now
0-3 against Williams. ``If I could replay something, that would be
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles realized she was in trouble from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feet were dead out there,'' said Seles, who has been unable
to practice because of a blister on her left hand. ``I felt asleep.
I thought I better wake up or it would be over in 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Waking up is exactly what Anna Kournikova seems to be doing in
time for the United States Open. Although Kournikova was defeated
by Seles here in the semifinals Saturday and is still searching for
her first tournament victory, her list of conquests at this event
included Davenport and Nathalie Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   The Open also affords a great opportunity for Williams to assert
herself as the game's new premier player.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged on Sunday that there are aspects of her game
that she still needs to improve. She was unhappy with her footwork
in the Seles match, for instance. Before the Open begins, Williams
will have an opportunity to work on improvements to her game at the
Pilot Pen tournament in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   But she may not need to play any better than she did on Sunday.
As Seles said, ``The way she's playing now, by far, she's the
favorite.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
