<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   File under ``D'' for dogs and ducks, or perhaps ``C'' for
Central Park and Cheyenne, the wayward Australian shepherd mix who
captivated crowds at Turtle Pond one steamy weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began at 8:15 a.m., well within the park's 6-to-9
a.m. window for dogs to romp off leash. Heading down the path from
Belvedere Castle with her guardian and two canine siblings,
Cheyenne suddenly broke away and bounded into Turtle Pond, home of
snapping turtles, ducks and loons.
</P>
<P>
   An astute mother mallard directed her ducklings toward the tall
grass to the north, and proceeded to quack and flap her wings
wildly. Cheyenne began a hot pursuit and although her clunky paddle
was no match for the duck's easy glide, she was not deterred. Pleas
from her agitated owner, a tennis ball thrown in her path and the
gathering crowd failed to distract her from the task at hand.
Cheyenne was no ordinary dog.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes later, the police and park staff arrived.
Someone suggested that the owner herself be sent into the pond to
catch the dog. The owner, at wit's end, shed her sandals and made
her way into the snapping-turtle-infested waters. Thus we saw a
duck followed by a dog followed by a wild-haired woman wearing a
life preserver provided by the Park Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear that the woman had no more chance of catching
the dog than the dog did of catching the duck. Finally two police
officers took off on the pond in a rowboat. The capture was swift.
The last thing we saw was the owner standing over Cheyenne, shaking
her head and shouting, ``Cheyenne, how many times have I told you
not to chase ducks!''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA MORRISON
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Holzwarth's friend Debra Sweezey of Stone Mountain, Ga.,
was preparing Jessica, her 4-year-old daughter, for her first trip
to Manhattan. Sweezey mentioned some of the sights they would see,
and said they would ride the subway, ``a train that runs under the
ground.'' Wide-eyed, Jessica asked: ``But how do we get down to the
train? Do we have to dig?''
</P>
<P>
   THE IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you have seen me _ strolling in front of the Plaza or
exercising in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   I was born beautiful! How many times have I heard it! Life is
never easy when an image must be preserved. As we grow older, it
gets harder. If you really look closely, there are some signs of
change. I still look good _ from a distance?
</P>
<P>
   My hair was always my best feature. Now it takes twice as long
to get it the way it used to look. The daily manicure is a
nuisance. Borderline starvation is the only way to keep my
slimness. If that goes, I'm finished. I've always prided myself on
my figure.
</P>
<P>
   How I envy you average-looking females, gaining weight, letting
yourself go. Rollers, old bathrobes, you are still loved. No hours
in the beauty salon for you, listening to boring females.
</P>
<P>
   I still love the attention. I never tire of being admired. I am
superior. But the price is getting too high.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I'll say goodbye to it all, let my hair go, keep late
hours, gorge myself until I'm sick, run around my back yard, roll
in the leaves and mud. I'll be free. Free to be myself, just
another Yorkie.
</P>
<P>
   _ R. WINIFRED BYRNE
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has introduced so many new words, like ``e-mail''
and ``e-commerce,'' that I wonder if we'll have to redefine some of
our current vocabulary. Can we look forward to:
</P>
<P>
   e-go _ to start a Net search.
</P>
<P>
   e-on _ synonym for ``online.''
</P>
<P>
   e-motion _ Web-surfing.
</P>
<P>
   e-mission_ a commitment to Internet research.
</P>
<P>
   e-quip _ a clever remark in a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   e-gret _ an electronic sympathy card.
</P>
<P>
   e-bullience _ lying about yourself online.
</P>
<P>
   e-cology_ getting an online B.A.
</P>
<P>
   e-clipse _ online movie scenes.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLARE HIGGINS
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER LAMENT
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to climb a Rocky
</P>
<P>
   Back a Saratoga jockey
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to roam the nation
</P>
<P>
   So why did I take a winter vacation?
</P>
<P>
   _ BERNARD DILBERT
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Like many, I am annoyed by people's supposed needs to have phone
conversations wherever they are. Recently, my perspective shifted.
</P>
<P>
   I was taken by ambulance, in the middle of the night, to Beth
Israel Hospital North with severe abdominal pains. In the morning,
I began to worry about my outside appointments for that day and the
next. I had no money with me, but I soon discovered that Beth
Israel provides a cellular phone in the emergency room for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   I called my neighbor, who has my keys, told her whom to call in
my address book and got that worry off my mind. Later in the day,
another cell phone came to my rescue as my neighbor took hers into
my apartment and I directed her from room to room, telling her
where to find things I needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ RETTA BLANEY
</P>
<P>
   While on the subject of cell phones: Judith Nochimson Stein was
on a Wall Street-bound subway on a weekday when it stopped for
almost an hour because of a fire in the station ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes, as the passengers sat frustrated and restless,
fretting about missed appointments and irate employers, a lone
entrepreneur made his way through the cars, yelling, ballpark
style: ``Call your offices, call your families. One dollar a minute
on my cell phone.'' He wasn't discouraged when Stein's car produced
smiles but no takers. He just went on to the next.
</P>
<P>
   R. Michael Wirin parked on 36th Street recently, and when he
returned a few hours later, his one-touch ``keyless'' key holder
wouldn't open his car.
</P>
<P>
   After thinking of paying a streetwise kid to break into the car,
or throwing himself on the mercy of a police officer, he hailed a
nearby parking attendant, hoping the man wouldn't hold it against
him that he hadn't entrusted his car to the lot.
</P>
<P>
   The attendant took the clicker in hand and said, ``Empire State
Building.'' Wirin explained that he wasn't a tourist looking for
that skyscraper. The attendant scrambled under the car and voila,
the locks magically opened as he reappeared and said again,
``Empire State Building.'' At this point, Wirin asked him to
explain.
</P>
<P>
   It was common knowledge, the man said, that the huge transmitter
atop King Kong's perch often disables electronic devices in the
neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-NYT     08-06 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN'S REAL ESTATE MARKET NOW SIMMERING, INSTEAD OF BOILING 
</HEADLINE>
  By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thrill is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's over-the-top real estate market, on a fast roll for
more than four years, has lost its frenzied upward momentum _ at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be buyers, who this spring seemed caught up in a
grab-it-now-before-it's-gone panic, suddenly have lost their
desperate urge to buy. In the last two months, real estate brokers
and statisticians say, bidding wars have declined, apartments have
stayed on the market longer before being sold, and hundreds have
even been marked down. Manhattan real estate prices are finally
leveling off.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things everyone is beginning to feel is that the
market is flat,'' said Deborah Beck, executive vice president of
the Real Estate Board of New York. The board measured a 22 percent
drop in the number of city apartments sold in the quarter ending
June 30, compared with the same period last year _ a figure Beck
called ``a significant slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The edge is off the market,'' said Jonathan Miller, president
of Miller Samuel, the appraisal firm that compiles citywide
statistics for Douglas Elliman, the city's biggest brokerage firm.
Especially during the last month, Miller said, ``we're seeing much
more modest appreciation, more of a return to normalcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts, including Miller, are quick to warn that the changing
statistics, which mirror a national trend, may not signal the start
of a downward spiral like the one in the late 1980s and early '90s.
But one thing is certain: One of the biggest sellers' markets in
New York history has suddenly tilted more toward the buyer _ and
the buyers are noticing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his two years of looking, Tom Pappas, a
Midtown lawyer, has spotted the same properties showing up week
after week on his Internet searches. But he is not biting until
their prices go down. Then, he vowed, ``I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts call it a simmer, no longer a boil. Sales volume is
down, and prices are no longer soaring. While brokers insist that
no one is grasping at low-ball offers, most brokers concede that
more sellers now are accepting modest reductions off the asking
price than were doing so earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Many link the chill to the Nasdaq plunge that began on April 14,
and to the last interest rate increase _ the half-point in May. In
interviews, the brokers and statisticians said that today's buyers
were more cautious, that they spent more time looking, but that
many did, in the end, buy _ and at a good price.
</P>
<P>
   In a report Miller is just finishing, he found that the average
property spent 28 percent more time on the market than it did
during the same period a year ago, 118 days versus 92 days.
</P>
<P>
   These changes reflect a national trend. Fred Flick, the vice
president for research at the National Association of Realtors,
said the real estate market nationally was down 6 percent in
volume; by the end of the year, the association estimates that
volume will be down 9 percent. And while it still predicts average
price increases at 2 percent to 3 percent this year, that is less
than last year's 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The national slowdown was confirmed on Thursday, when the
Commerce Department reported that across the country, new home
sales fell 3.7 percent in June to the lowest level in two and a
half years. Median prices fell slightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
