<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-COLONY-CLOSE-ART-     08-06 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-COLONY-CLOSE-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS CRUSADE FOLDS ITS TENT AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Three years ago an experiment in artistic
democracy began. And last week it ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, a heady mix of
summer camp, artists' colony, encounter group and think tank
founded and directed by the playwright and actor Anna Deavere
Smith, closed its doors on Friday _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer for the last three years the institute assembled a
group of artists and scholars for six weeks of what Smith called
``artistic boot camp.'' The artists presented their works in
progress _ pieces of theater, dance and music intended to induce
dialogue about civic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars were invited to jump into the fray. And a core audience
of people who had agreed to go to every performance had been
gathered to join in the discussions after each performance.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year program, with the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for
Afro-American Research at Harvard University and the American
Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., as joint hosts, cost $4.2
million and was paid for largely by a grant from the Ford
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is best known for her one-woman plays ``Fires in the
Mirror,'' about the conflicts between blacks and Jews in Crown
Heights, Brooklyn; ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' about the riots
after the first Rodney King verdict; and ``House Arrest,'' a
multivoiced meditation on the American presidency and particularly
on Thomas Jefferson's relationship with his slave Sally Hemings and
Bill Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   For those plays, Smith interviewed hundreds of people of
different races and ages, somehow managing to internalize their
expressions, anger and quirks enough to be able to portray them
with astonishing verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue was, in some sense,
like an Anna Deavere Smith play writ large. She said she was trying
to ``create a frame'' that would hold ``many different voices and
histories and expressions in the same place and still be
coherent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of performances, a 22-year-old Rwandan
playwright, Hope Azeda, presented her play about hatred and
reconciliation between the Tutsi and Hutu; the singers Suzzy Roche
and her sister Maggie sang prayers written by audience members;
Sheila Kennedy, a professor of architecture at Harvard, pondered
the cultural fear of hollow spaces; Patricia Williams, a law
professor at Columbia University, and Oliver Lake, a jazz
saxophonist, riffed on cloning, shadows, the apocalypse and the
subjunctive; Smith screened ``Twilight: Los Angeles,'' a movie
based on her play; and on the final night a multiracial cast
performed ``Piano,'' her play about the Cuban insurrection against
Spain in 1898. The art was not there for art's sake, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art is a mask'' for social issues, Smith said. The point,
she suggested, is not to fasten on the mask but ``to get behind
it,'' to ``engender discussion.'' And ``the audience is a critical
part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Smith's play ``Piano'' was a prime example.
Before the performance, Smith told the audience that her aim was to
write a play that would throw many classes and races together in
one living room and that would allow the actors to act in their own
skins.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of ``Piano'' is a plantation house owned by Spanish
colonials. Little do they know that the people who clean and cook
for them every day are insurrectos, revolutionaries planning to
free Cuba from Spain and to free themselves from domestic slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna, an African, is the head of the staff and has adopted an
African girl to clean the floors and to be her revolutionary
protegee. She trains her by telling her that the piano is an angry
lion whose paws she must clean without stirring the beast.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese cook makes African food. His wife is a smiling
Chinese hostess and the mistress of the Spanish master of the
house. The music teacher seems to be part Spanish, part African.
</P>
<P>
   The drama begins when some visitors arrive: a rich and liberated
American woman traveling with her African-American boyfriend, and a
brutal Spanish general, the brother of the man of the house, who
has come to defend Spanish interests against the insurrectos and
rape some women along the way. The house is a revolutionary
tinderbox, ready to explode.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant as it is, the play was not the thing. It was merely
the mask. The final act belonged to the audience. A woman asked why
some of the audience members who remained grave at moments when
race was discussed had laughed at japes about rape and male
anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   A man from the core audience piped up, ``It's a democracy.''
Someone else tried to break into the conversation, only to be
hushed. Donald Byrd, a choreographer who had been at the institute
for all three years, said it was the ``laughter of recognition.''
And the dialogue ended with one of the institute artists, Margo
Jefferson, who is also a columnist for The New York Times, saying
she trusted laughter as a response a lot more than sobriety. The
crowd dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   The response that Smith wanted to evoke, she said, was not a
standing ovation, which she got, but rather an audience full of
people who rise to their feet and say, ``What can I do?'' That was
not what she got.
</P>
<P>
   In her final week at the institute Smith said, ``It has been an
extraordinary laboratory.'' More than anything, she said, the
institute has set her thinking about three words, ``We the
people.'' In this world, there is ``no single great explainer,''
she said. `` `We the people' means something different than it did
in 1968. We still haven't figured out how `we' is a big `we.' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the easy part was dealing with the artists. She
recalled some of her favorite moments and most had to do with a
melding of voices. She thought of Ysaye Barnwell of Sweet Honey in
the Rock getting 200 people singing and rocking to four different
spirituals at the same time. She thought of Suzzy Roche singing a
Vietnam veteran's private prayer, which Roche called a ``melting
experience.'' And there were Williams and Lake, creating what
Williams called ``an allusive conversation'' between music and
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part, Smith said, had to do with the audience. The
first year there were about 160 in the core audience, but they had
only four performances to go to. The crowd was unusually varied.
Williams recalled a performance where some people in the audience
had once been homeless or in prison. But at the end there were 15
performances and the core audience, about 90 people, was not as
mixed as it might have been. Although there was a mix of races and
ethnicities _ 58 white, 24 black, four Hispanic, two Asian, two
Indian, one Arab _ the great majority were middle-aged or older and
middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps part of the difficulty had to do with being on the
Harvard campus. Of course, there were some obvious advantages.
Cornel West, a professor of Afro-American studies and religion at
Harvard, showed up and ``blessed'' almost every performance.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of professors, including Henry Louis Gates Jr.,
the chairman of the Afro-American studies department at Harvard,
and Charles T. Ogletree, a Harvard law professor, were often there,
ready to leap into the civic debate at a moment's notice. But there
were disadvantages too. ``People conflate Cambridge with Harvard,''
Smith said. It was hard to draw people from other neighborhoods in
the Boston area consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has been at the institute for three years, said,
``We didn't reach every last person in Roxbury.'' And that may have
had something to do with being at Harvard. ``I'm from Roxbury,''
Williams said, ``and when I went to law school at Harvard I was
self-conscious about whether I had the right to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is not so different from the practical difficulty
presented in ``Piano'': the insurrectos must plan the revolution
while living in the house of the Spanish masters. Are they really
free to talk as they please? Where else could they meet? Can any of
the masters be trusted? How big can ``We the people'' be?
</P>
<P>
   Smith was given a standing ovation after the screening of the
movie ``Twilight: Los Angeles,'' in which she herself had taken the
roles of dozens of people, including a Beverly Hills real estate
agent, the trucker Reginald O. Denny, one of his assailants, a
looter, a Korean woman whose husband was killed, a pregnant
Hispanic woman who was shot in the crossfire, the former police
chief Daryl F. Gates, the diva Jessye Norman and Professor West
drinking cognac.
</P>
<P>
   She took the opportunity to ponder the question of bigness and
to compare herself to a surgeon who was asked why he had chosen to
operate on children with cancer. Expected to say something about
saving children's lives, he simply said, ``It gave me the
opportunity to do a bigger operation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
