<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     08-06 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROSH WILL REPORT TO UCLA TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Size doesn't matter _ or so UCLA hopes in regard
to its Napoleon-sized freshman football class of just 14
scholarship players, which reports to the coaching staff today.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, at least five true freshman have played each season
and Bruins coach Bob Toledo doesn't expect this year to be any
different. He said five true freshman have a good chance to play
right away: linebacker Brandon Chillar, defensive back Ben Emanuel,
punter/kicker Chris Kluwe, receiver Tab Perry and Valencia High
running back Manuel White.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 185-pound Emanuel, from Clear Brook High in
Friendswood, Texas, and the 6-foot-3, 218-pound Perry, from
Milpitas, were recruited nationally and walk into situations in
which the Bruins could use some help.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel, whose cousin Bert came to UCLA as a quarterback before
transferring to Rice and becoming an NFL receiver, could make an
impact at safety, which is the team's most unsettled position.
Sophomore Lovell Houston is coming off surgery on both shoulders
and won't be ready to practice Saturday, Toledo said. Jason Zdenek,
a little-used fifth-year senior from Chaminade High in West Hills,
and former strong safety Audie Attar are among the other
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, meanwhile, could help at a position that is short on
playmakers beyond starters Brian Poli-Dixon and Freddie Mitchell.
Kluwe, from Los Alamitos, could push sophomore punter Nate Fikse
and White, a 6-foot-2, 229-pound tailback from Valencia, would be
the biggest in the Bruins' stable.
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the class, offensive tackle Paul Mociler, from
Bellflower St. John Bosco, was considered among the top prospects
in the country at his position before he tore knee ligaments last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen check in today and go through orientation before
starting workouts Tuesday afternoon. The upperclassmen report
Thursday and begin practice Saturday for the Sept. 2 season-opener
against No.3-ranked Alabama at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
