<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- OBIT-GUINNESS -- Sir Alec
Guinness, the elegant and versatile British actor known to older
audiences for films like "The Bridge on the River Kwai" and to a
whole new generation for his role as Obi-Wan Kenobi in "Star Wars,"
died late Saturday at a hospital in West Sussex, England. He was 86.
Alec Guiness, who played the Jedi guru Obi-Wan Kenobi in the original
''Star Wars'' trilogy, with George Lucas in 1981. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LOS ALAMOS, N.M. -- Aug. 6, 2000 --
HIROSHIMA-ANNIVERSARY -- The 55th anniversary of the American atom
bomb attack on the city of Hiroshima, Japan, was marked Sunday in
Japan and elsewhere. Takashi Tanemori, a bomb survivor, draped a
chain of folded paper cranes on a sculpture to peace at a ceremony in
Sante Fe, N.M., near the Los Alamos laboratories where the weapon was
developed. (Steve Northrup/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HEYBELI ISLAND, Turkey -- Aug. 6, 2000 --
TURKEY-SEMINARY --  Despite the pleadings of Orthodox leaders and the
urgings of Turkey's allies, most recently President Clinton, Turkish
authorities insist that the Holy Theological School remain closed
under a law that gave the government control over higher education in
religious and military affairs. Greek Orthodox nuns take in the view
from the courtyard of the Holy Theological School, which the Turkish
government closed in 1971. (Staton R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- HARLEM-BAPTISM-4 -- Each
August since 1937, the United House of Prayer, a nondenominational
Pentecostal church that claims 3 million congregants in 28 states,
has held mass baptisms on 115th Street in East Harlem, using a fire
hose to spray hundreds of participants with baptismal waters. The
church holds mass baptisms across the country each summer as part of
a convocation ceremony in which congregants seek holy renewal. About
500 congregants gathered Sunday for the New York regional ceremony,
with buses arriving from Washington, Boston and Philadelphia.
(Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN-2
-- Al Gore returned to his home state of Tennessee on Sunday as he
neared a final verdict on who his vice presidential running mate
would be. Three senators -- John Kerry, 56, of Massachusetts, John
Edwards, 47, of North Carolina and Joseph Lieberman, 58, of
Connecticut -- were considered the top contenders. Gore greeting
members of the Tennessee National Guard after leaving Air Force 2 at
the Nashville, Tenn. airport. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN-1 --
Six weeks after taking charge of Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign, William M. Daley, the former commerce
secretary, seems to have significantly revived the once flagging
morale of the campaign, both in Nashville and beyond. Daley has freed
Gore to focus on essential decisions rather than on the power
struggles back home, and he has reassured Democratic partisans that
the campaign is back on track. Daley arriving in Nashville for a
campaign strategy session, Sunday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- BARNESANDNOBLE.COM --
Barnesandnoble.com is teaming up with Microsoft on Tuesday to open
the first major online store selling digital books, available for
downloading and reading on a screen or in single paperback copies
printed on demand on high-speed presses -- a technological capacity
that Amazon.com does not yet have. In Manhattan, Barnesandnoble.com
delivers books the same day on orders received by late morning via
its own fleet of trucks. (Jack Manning/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- E-COMMERCE -- Internet
companies are looking for any market that can deliver revenue and
keep their businesses afloat as the dot-com consolidation continues.
The goal is not only to sell goods to the government to help build
its e-commerce systems, but to provide goods that government
purchasing agents can buy through those same systems. Steven Tinchak,
right, of the General Services Administration's federal technologies
service, listening as David Arnold of MobShop, left, explains his
Internet company's group purchasing system during a technology
exhibit at the Ronald Reagan World Trade building in Washington.
(Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- HARLEM-BAPTISM-3 -- Each
August since 1937, the United House of Prayer, a nondenominational
Pentecostal church that claims 3 million congregants in 28 states,
has held mass baptisms on 115th Street in East Harlem, using a fire
hose to spray hundreds of participants with baptismal waters. Bishop
S.C. Madison, the national leader of The United House of Prayer,
blessing some 500 congregants gathered Sunday in Harlem for the New
York regional ceremony, with buses arriving from Washington, Boston
and Philadelphia. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- HARLEM-BAPTISM-2 -- The
United House of Prayer, a nondenominational Pentecostal church that
claims 3 million congregants in 28 states, holds mass baptisms across
the country each summer as part of a convocation ceremony in which
congregants seek holy renewal. Since access to rivers is limited and
pools aren't easy to find in New York, the House of Prayer has always
used the municipal water supply, blessed by the church's bishop.
About 500 congregants gathered Sunday in Harlem for the New York
regional ceremony, with buses arriving from Washington, Boston and
Philadelphia. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- HARLEM-BAPTISM-1 -- Each
August since 1937, the United House of Prayer, a nondenominational
Pentecostal church that claims 3 million congregants in 28 states,
