(Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) JOLIET, Ill. -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-CAMPAIGN
-- George W. Bush, campaigning by train from the suburbs of Chicago
through verdant farmlands, on Sunday pledged to revive a vetoed tax
cut for married people if elected. The Republican presidential
candidate and his running mate Dick Cheney spent the day touring
Illinois by train, wrapping up a three-day whistle-stop swing through
key battleground states that began at the end of the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia. Bush with his wife Laura, left,
and Cheney and his wife, Lynne. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) JOLIET, Ill. -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- CHENEY-INTERVIEW --
In stump speeches that echoed his combative address to the Republican
National Convention, Dick Cheney, the vice presidential nominee, on
the third day of a rail trip across middle America with Gov. George
W. Bush, repeated his promise of a "tough fight" to "restore honor,
integrity and decency to the Oval Office." At the same time, he
acknowledged in an interview that House Republicans bore some
responsibility for the "partisan bickering and backbiting" in
Washington that he rails against in his speeches. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 6, 2000 -- LABOR-UNION-ART -- Moe
Foner, an official of union 1199, has tried to improve the image of
labor unions and help members identify more closely with them and
feel prouder of their work lives. Foner, who presides over the arts
activities of 1199, with a poster designed  by Milton Glaser. (Maxine
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
