<SLUG> BC-PALM-HANDHELD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEWEST PALM IS STREAMLINED AND SIMPLIFIED  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reaching out to less-technical users, Palm Inc.
will today add a new low-cost member to its popular series of
handheld organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm m100, like the low-end IIIe model it will replace, will
be priced at $149. But the m100 offers several new features
designed, the company says, to make it more attractive to shoppers
who aren't especially computer-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are new tutorial software, an on-screen digital clock
visible through a hole in the unit's protective cover, and a new
Note Pad program that allows users to scribble names and numbers on
the screen of the device even before they master Palm's Graffiti
writing system. The Note Pad, which may eventually be offered on
other Palm models, in effect saves a picture of the handwritten
data in a format known as ``digital ink.''
</P>
<P>
   The new model also introduces a new look for Palm: In addition
to the clock hole, it has a rounded base, and it's narrower across,
making it easy for women in particular to grip, according to John
Cook, the Santa Clara, Calif., company's director of consumer
product marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The standard unit is black, but customers will have the option
of adding snap-on faceplates, priced at $19.95 each, in silver
green, ruby, or light or dark blue.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a cradle to hold the device while it's synchronizing
data with a PC or Mac, the m100 will ship with just a cable for
sharing data with a full-size computer.
</P>
<P>
   The new design might help Palm regain some business from
Handspring, which since last fall has offered low-cost,
bright-color organizers based on software licensed from Palm.
According to PC Data, a Reston, Va., market research company, in
June the Handspring's Visor Deluxe became the single best-selling
handheld computer model in U.S. retail channels, with a market
share of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Visor represents a moral victory for
Handspring, which is led by executives who originally founded Palm
and then left it. Overall, however, Palm continues to dominate the
handheld arena, with a market share estimated at about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Palm will also announce several other changes to its product
line today:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Palm VII, which has wireless messaging and
Internet-access capabilities, will be replaced by a new version
called the VIIx, which offers four times as much memory (8
megabytes) and additional software. The VIIx will be $449, while
remaining VII units will be reduced to $399.
</P>
<P>
   -- The company will offer the Palm Vx, its slimmest, sleekest
model, in two new colors, ``Champagne Gold'' and ``Millennium
Blue.'' Priced like the standard silver Vx at $399, the ``Limited
Edition'' color configurations will be sold only on Palm's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Palm announced another special version of the Vx, the
``Claudia Schiffer Edition,'' which will be offered exclusively on
the supermodel's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   -- An Ethernet cradle, announced in October, is finally
available. The $249 device, installed in lobbies, labs, meeting
rooms and other public areas on corporate campuses, will let
roaming employees update the information on their handhelds over
the company network without having to return to their desks.
</P>
<P>
   Palm also reduced the price of the IIIc, its only color-screen
model, from $449 to $399.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
