<HEADER>
A4235 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BRAND-LICENSING-SFCHR     08-06 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAND-LICENSING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DOT-COMS MARKETING LOGO-CLAD PRODUCTS  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The alarm goes off at 7 a.m. and Dot Consumer
sleepily climbs out of bed and puts on her Pets.com sock puppet
slippers to pad to the shower, drying off with a Bikini.com towel.
</P>
<P>
   After donning a pair of jeans and deciding among 37 T-shirts
with computer logos, she downs a bowl of sugary flakes in a
Hamsterdance bowl, then stuffs her AskJeeves calculator into her
Yahoo backpack and heads out the door, clicking her Autobytel
electronic car remote to unlock her new Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   That's the logo-clad future _ the very near future _ as a
variety of Internet companies envision it.
</P>
<P>
   Internet brands are moving into the real world as dot-com
companies realize that easy cash _ and even more important, brand
awareness _ can be had by licensing their names and mascots for
everything from clothing to electronics to toys.
</P>
<P>
   Only a trickle of products has hit the market so far, but by
Christmas, consumers will be able to stock up on many of the goods
mentioned above, plus a variety of other dot-com goods.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking board games, watches, calendars, clocks, musical
instruments, postcards, puppets, stuffed animals, pillows,
dinnerware, key chains _ tchotchkes up the wazoo.
</P>
<P>
   Make that up the Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Yahoo, the most popular site on the Web, was an early,
enthusiastic convert to licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo first licensed its name to Ziff-Davis for Yahoo! Internet
Life magazine, which started in 1996, and has long had a variety of
third-party-produced Yahoo gear, such as sweatshirts and mouse
pads, available on its site.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's getting into watches, eye wear, stationery, board and
card games, computer reference books, a ``dot-com racer'' toy car,
even a guitar. And it's not neglecting PC-related products: Various
models of speakers, mice and keyboards from Sakar International, as
well as a digital camera from Tiger Electronics, are now in
production.
</P>
<P>
   The royalties on this merchandise are immaterial for the Santa
Clara company, which had $588.6 million in 1999 revenues. What
matters is the branding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been our goal to make Yahoo a tangible brand,''
said Karen Edwards, vice president of brand marketing. With
Yahoo-brand consumer products, ``people have the opportunity to
actually touch and hold Yahoo; it becomes more personal, more part
of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Edwards is realistic about how much consumers actually
like living in a logo world. ``Very few people want to be walking
billboards for brands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing is a natural evolution from the promotional items Net
companies already give away. ``Internet companies have spent a
fortune on premiums. They give away polo shirts, hats, beach balls
with their dot-com address on them. They want people to wear them,
use them, see them and go to the address,'' said Richard Mark
Blank, chief operating officer and co-founder of
NetNameLicensing.com, a New York company that hopes to help dot-com
firms land licensing deals online. ``Boom, the consumer loves their
favorite dot-com merchandise just like they love their favorite
offline brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Licensing is pure gravy for companies lucky enough to have a
compelling brand. The T-shirt or toymakers bear all the expense and
risk up front, paying royalties to the licenser, anywhere from 3 to
18 percent of the wholesale price. The manufacturers have to
guarantee a minimum fee to ensure they won't park a slow-moving
product on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Not many Net companies have gotten in on the action yet. For
that matter, only a handful of online firms have the huge brand
awareness of Yahoo, which is the 53rd most-recognized consumer
brand name, according to Interbrand Group (Coca-Cola, Microsoft and
IBM being the top three). But some people say the potential is
vast, especially since Net-savvy consumers have the young, hip,
affluent demographics companies crave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a great opportunity and the market could be
huge for a select group of dot-com companies,'' said Charles
Riotto, president of the International Licensing Industry
Merchandisers' Association in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But ``select'' is the key word. Only very well-known companies
will attract manufacturers to make goods bearing their brand. ``You
have to establish your core brand before an effective licensing
program can be put into place,'' Riotto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a place where brands are just being created,''
said Marty Brochstein, executive editor of the Licensing Letter in
New York. ``Computer access by consumers is not yet ubiquitous.
There are limitations at this point as to the visibility of
anything that exists only on the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential market is huge: Brochstein said retail sales of
licensed merchandise in the United States and Canada hit $74.15
billion in 1999. Corporate trademarks and brands were the biggest
chunk of that.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some dot-com players whose wares are starting to hit
the market:
</P>
<P>
   -- Pets.com. After carpet-bombing prime time over the past year
with commercials featuring its goofy sock puppet, Pets.com realized
it had a pop culture hit on its hands, along the lines of the Taco
Bell Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   The online pet-supply firm says consumer demand drove its
decision to engage a licensing agent. The sock puppet, a finger
puppet and smaller stuffed replicas of it are on store shelves now,
with slippers, posters, T-shirts, key chains and greeting cards
coming soon.
</P>
<P>
   Again, branding is the main objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of licensing is that by putting your character in
various retail stores, whether on T-shirts, greeting cards or in
the gift section, it literally extends the presence of your
brand,'' said Chris Deyo, president of Pets.com. ``Each puppet will
have a hang tag to drive consumers to our Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Deyo said he expects licensing royalties to represent ``a strong
complementary revenue stream'' that will account for under 10
percent of overall sales. However, he noted, ``the revenues flow
right to the bottom line. Royalties are a nice item because they
don't have any cost of goods sold, so they help the overall
economics of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The sock puppet's popularity mirrors that of another recent
advertising icon, the Taco Bell Chihuahua. But there's a cautionary
tale attached: Despite selling 13 million plush toys and creating
national catchphrases such as ``Drop the chalupa,'' Taco Bell has
seen sales stall and recently gave the doggie the boot.
</P>
<P>
   Pets.com says sales have increased twelvefold since it started
the sock puppet campaign. Its situation differed from that of Taco
Bell, because Pets.com was just starting up when the campaign
began.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the sock puppet and its product progeny will drive
people to the Web site long-term remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people know about the sock puppet who don't need
to know because they're not ever going to buy dog food,'' Rebecca
Nidositko, a senior analyst at the Yankee Group, said last month.
</P>
<P>
   -- AskJeeves. The know-it-all British butler from AskJeeves will
soon materialize in the realm of consumer products. AskJeeves.com
of Emeryville, whose primary product is a search engine that
answers Web surfers' questions, has hired two people to help Jeeves
make the leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to just slap him onto a T-shirt. We would
never do just a standard plush doll,'' said Mary Kean, licensing
manager for AskJeeves. ``We want to combine the character and the
technology to make really interesting products.''
</P>
<P>
   Since AskJeeves is about finding answers and educating people,
she said, Jeeves will appear in educational milieus such as board
games and electronic organizers for children. He'll have his own
calendar with a question of the day; he's already featured in two
self-published books.
</P>
<P>
   Kean, who landed her job by suggesting it to AskJeeves' vice
president of ideas, already has experience with placing brainy
Europeans in consumer products. She previously handled licensing of
Albert Einstein's name and image on behalf of Hebrew University of
Jerusalem. Jeeves and Einstein ``are both great thinkers,'' she
noted.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bikini.com. Modeling itself on ``lifestyle brands'' such as
Martha Stewart and MTV, Bikini.com calls itself ``an online beach
party'' with content and commerce about ``wholesome swimsuit and
California beach lifestyle entertainment,'' according to CEO and
co-founder Gail Sonnenschein. She hopes to branch beyond being
merely a dot-com company, and into television, movies and theme
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1997, the New York company built licensing into its
business model from the beginning. One of its first employees was a
licensing director; today it has four (out of 25) employees
handling licensing.
</P>
<P>
   That approach has paid off with 15 deals so far for beach-themed
products and trinkets bearing its logo: swimwear, of course, and
also towels, totes, jewelry, calendars, music CDs, sandals,
sunglasses and magnets. Half of Bikini.com's revenue derives from
licensing, according to Sonnenschein, and most of the products have
yet to hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenschein waxes lyrical about the benefits of licensing. It
has allowed her firm to spend barely a nickel on advertising, she
said, noting that appearances by Bikini.com models on TV shows have
also helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Wrestling Federation sold $1 billion of licensed
products with ugly wrestlers, so imagine what we can sell with our
Bikini.com supermodels and the boys of summer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other dot-coms exploring licensing include online car site
Autobytel.com, which is now talking to manufacturers about
Autobytel-branded car accoutrements, such as jumper cables,
wrenches, safety kits and security systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hamsterdance2.com, custodian of the jiggling rodents, has a
music CD out now and plans to have T-shirts, plush toys, lunch
boxes, dinnerware, pens and pencils, children's bags, bendable
figures, book covers and key chains.
</P>
<P>
   But all the companies getting into licensing need to observe
some cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern would be: Who's the steward of the brand?''
said Jon Callaghan, a partner with CMGI &LR; Ventures in Menlo Park.
``Brands are fleeting. Every customer interaction makes a brand
over time. I would be concerned about the potential downside of no
longer controlling the customer experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's Edwards agrees. ``It's an incredible risk for the
brand,'' she said. ``I never want to see something with the Yahoo
brand in the bargain bin where it's been marked down four or five
times.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
