<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-FORBES-REPUBS-665(     08-06 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FORBES-REPUBS-665(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP AIMS FOR REVENGE ON DEFECTOR IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKHAVEN, N.Y. _ Rep. Michael P. Forbes didn't want to talk
about it initially: the television advertisement that his
Republican foes spliced together to try to humiliate him. Why
dignify it?
</P>
<P>
   Then he reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's silly, and it's part of the hate-vengeance campaign, and
a very childish approach they are taking,'' said Forbes, the
Democrat who defected from the Republican Party in disgust last
year, and in so doing became the most despised Democrat _ on a very
long list _ among many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats are engaged in one of their fiercest
fights ever this year over control of the House, where the
Republicans have a precarious majority that would be wiped out by
the loss of six seats.
</P>
<P>
   But no individual race quickens the pulse of House Republican
leaders as does Forbes'. In fact, his Long Island seat appears
almost irrelevant to them; it is revenge they seek, payback for the
embarrassment he caused them and the trouble he sowed. On their
list of targets, Forbes, who has served three terms in the House,
places first.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the television advertisement they are considering running.
The ad, which pokes goofy fun at Forbes throughout, ends with the
congressman's clowning around and pretending to make rude sounds by
squeezing his hand under his armpit in the fashion of adolescent
boys.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was an outtake, clipped from a moment of horseplay
after he taped an ad as a Republican, and someone with a long
memory unearthed it for the House Republicans' campaign committee.
So far they haven't broadcast it, although they did treat
themselves to a private screening.
</P>
<P>
   As hard as Forbes and his opponent, Felix J. Grucci Jr., the
fireworks manufacturer, who is the town supervisor here, try to
make their campaign about local issues and local politics,
Washington power brokers cannot resist joining in the rumble and
trash-talking.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him what he thinks of Forbes, and Rep. Thomas M. Davis III
of Virginia, chairman of the House Republican Campaign Committee,
eagerly tosses out, yet again, his standard quip: ``Have you ever
heard of the movie `Dead Man Walking'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hit him pretty hard,'' Davis said. ``Forbes is
the most vulnerable Democrat in the House. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republican leaders have pumped $45,000 so far
into Grucci's campaign coffers from their personal political action
committee funds and have sent Sen. John McCain to stump for Grucci.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are doing their part to help shore up Forbes'
campaign. President Clinton held a fund-raiser in New York City
that raised $500,000 for Forbes, even though Forbes voted to oust
him on all four articles of impeachment. Several Cabinet
secretaries plan to visit Forbes' district, in eastern Suffolk
County. One of them, Bruce Babbitt, the interior secretary, has
already made an appearance there.
</P>
<P>
   One conservative political organization, the Republican Majority
Issues Committee, which is headed by a former member of the staff
of Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the Republican whip, turned on one of
its own icons for political benefit and ran an advertising campaign
tying Forbes to Rep. Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker and a
favorite Democratic target.
</P>
<P>
   And the New York Democratic Party made its own ad, tying Grucci
to ``special interest'' allies, which it said were ``big polluters,
big tobacco companies and big-deal wheeler-dealer Texas
politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The race also pits two archfoes _ big business, which is
generally supporting Grucci, and labor unions, which are helping
Forbes with grass-roots campaigning _ against each other.
</P>
<P>
   To date, according to the candidates, Forbes has raised $1.2
million, and has $850,000 in the bank; Grucci has raised $800,000,
and has $500,000 on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts do not single out Forbes as the most vulnerable
Democrat in the House, but they agree that his race is a tossup and
one of the quirkier battles of the year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Forbes is in a singularly unenviable position this
political year,'' John Kohut wrote in July in The Rothenberg
Political Report, a nonpartisan newsletter that handicaps political
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some in his newly adopted party who care less about
the Democrats' `big picture' in Washington, and can only regard him
as an old adversary,'' the report notes. ``Then there are Forbes'
old allies in the GOP who see him as the worst type of turncoat and
want to see him humiliated and defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Forbes, 48, stunned his colleagues when he
announced he was leaving the Republican Party _ the party in power
in the House _ to become a Democrat. Standing outside his home in
Quogue, on Long Island, Forbes, a product of Republican machine
politics, unleashed a blistering assessment of his former party,
calling it ``angry, narrow-minded, intolerant, uncaring, incapable
of governing at all, much less from the center.''
</P>
<P>
   The move all but guaranteed a scorched-earth campaign for his
seat this year, and Republican leaders lost no time preparing for
it. They described him as petulant and unprincipled, a man who fled
only because he felt unloved.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes had already drawn their ire in 1996, when he became the
first Republican to say that he would oppose Gingrich's second term
as House speaker. But Gingrich was re-elected, and Forbes, a
one-time Gingrich disciple, was snubbed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Forbes, who won his first two terms with 53
percent and 55 percent of the vote, was re-elected in 1998 with 64
percent. The 1st District, home to the Hamptons, Brookhaven
National Laboratory and military plants, is politically Republican,
but Clinton carried it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at his defection, Forbes says he harbors no regrets
and describes those Republican labels as bunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to be purely political and fake, clearly I
wouldn't have done what I did a year ago,' he said. ``I was in the
majority, in the top committee in the House. I was, in most
people's estimation, a shoo-in for re-election. But there has to be
more to this business than just raw politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Election years, though, thrive on raw politics, and Forbes faces
a nasty race, full of hurdles, all of them rooted in his party
switch.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were naturally not happy about supporting a former
rival candidate, especially one who opposes abortion rights and
voted to impeach the president. With help from national party
leaders, Forbes persuaded almost all of them to overcome their
reluctance, although he faces a nominal primary fight against a
Democrat who is an abortion-rights advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a public tiff, Forbes further unnerved Democrats by
seeking the endorsement of the local Right to Life Party. The
endorsement went to Grucci. Forbes was also rebuffed by the
Conservative Party and the Independent Party, which supported him
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called regular Democrats _ the apparatchiks _ are
fairly solidly behind him,'' said Brad O'Hearn, a spokesman for the
Suffolk County Democratic Party. ``There are some interest groups
that still have bones to pick with him. But he is meeting with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Grucci campaign portrays Forbes as an
out-of-touch Washington politician who betrayed Republican
principles. ``Mike Forbes will say or do anything for his own
political expediency,'' said Grucci, who handily won re-election
twice as supervisor of Brookhaven, the largest town in Suffolk
County.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has not stayed silent, though. He and other Democrats
portray his opponent as out of his league in Washington and
question how much he knew about a political scandal that sent a
local Republican chairman to prison.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns about town, Forbes makes a simple pitch: He is
the same man he was before.
</P>
</TEXT>
