<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ONLINE INVESTING: MORNINGSTAR SERVICE OFFERS AT-A-GLANCE ANALYSIS  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Finding good stocks is always a challenge.
Morningstar ( &LR; www.morningstar.com &LR; ) recently introduced an analysis
tool, Market Radar, to help you uncover investment candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Market Radar displays information graphically, rather than
requiring you to interpret numeric data. It's also a free service.
You don't even have to register. Here's how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Select ``Market Radar'' under Tool Box on the left side of
Morningstar's home page to display a graph showing the year-to-date
return of stocks making up the S&AMP;P 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   I'll use the S&AMP;P data to explain Market Radar's display format,
and then show you how to search for investment candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A dot ranging in color from red to dark green represents each
stock of the S&AMP;P index.
</P>
<P>
   The dot colors indicate the value of selected data, which, in
this case, is the year-to-date return.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks with the highest returns are dark green, while those with
the worst returns are red. Move your cursor over a dot to see the
stock symbol and the data value (year-to-date return).
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar overlays the stock dots onto its ``style box''
format, comparing valuation to company size. A stock's ``value
score,'' which is based on price-to-earnings and price-to-book
ratios, determines its placement on the horizontal axis.
</P>
<P>
   Companies on the left are considered value priced, and those on
the right, growth stocks. Stocks in the middle are considered a
``blend'' of value and growth. Stocks on the far right are momentum
priced.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says value stocks are less risky than growth
stocks, while momentum stocks carry the highest risk.
</P>
<P>
   However, these traditional relationships between value and risk
have not held true in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The vertical axis represents company size (market cap). The
larger companies (large-cap) are near the top, smaller companies
(small-cap) toward the bottom, and in-between (mid-cap) in the
center.
</P>
<P>
   A stock's value and size ratings determine its placement.
Large-cap, value-priced stocks, for instance, will be clustered at
the top left, while small-cap, momentum stocks near the bottom
right.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked last week, the best performers of the S&AMP;P 500 were
large-cap growth stocks. Mid-cap value and mid-cap blend stocks had
the worst returns.
</P>
<P>
   I determined that using the color bars below the graph. Each bar
corresponds to a dot color. Clicking on a bar eliminates the
corresponding dots from the graph. Clicking again restores the
dots.
</P>
<P>
   I eliminated all except the dark green dots to view the
distribution of the best performers, and then I displayed the red
dots by themselves to see the stocks with the worst returns. Move
your cursor over a dot to see the ticker symbol and the data value
(YTD Return).
</P>
<P>
   Here's how you can use Market Radar to find investment
candidates. You first need to identify a group of stocks to
analyze. You can select stocks belonging to a particular index,
trading on a specific stock exchange, in a certain economic sector
or industry group, or from a variety of other categories.
</P>
<P>
   Then, pick data points you want to graph from one of five
categories: Performance, Owners Dividends, Growth Rates, Earnings
Projections and Profitability. Each category includes
subcategories.
</P>
<P>
   Let me demonstrate the process by researching one of the hottest
industry sectors: wireless communications stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``Select a Universe,'' then ``Stock,'' ``Industry,''
``C-D,'' and finally ``Cable/Wireless Equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   You should see the selected group: ``Stock Universe Industry
</P>
<P>
   Cable /Wireless Equipment,'' displayed near the top. You will
still have the S&AMP;P 500 displayed until you click on ``Select a Data
Point'' to pick a category such as ``Growth Rates.'' And then
select a subcategory such as ``EPS Growth One-year'' and finally
click on ``Graph'' to display the results.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier than it sounds. Start by clicking on ``Select a Data
Point'' and then select ``Performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Select ``One-year Return'' and click the ``Graph'' button to see
the one-year returns of all stocks in the cable /wireless sector.
The stocks with the highest returns are shown in dark green.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in the best performers, use the color bars
to turn off all dots except dark green.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, you may want to eliminate the highfliers and
focus on stocks that haven't taken off yet.
</P>
<P>
   If so, turn off the dark green dots. Also, turn off the red and
orange dots to exclude dogs that may never recover. On the other
hand, value investors may want to focus on the red and orange
underperformers.
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits say you will do best picking stocks with scant
mutual-fund ownership. That's because you can enjoy the ride when
funds finally discover the stock and drive its stock price up with
their heavy buying.
</P>
<P>
   Others, myself included, say it's best to pick stocks with heavy
mutual-fund ownership, indicating the pros have analyzed the
company and like what they see. Whatever your outlook, you'll find
stocks to suit your needs by selecting ``Fund Ownership'' in this
category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., teaches investment classes and
publishes the Winning Investing newsletter. You can read his
columns at  &LR; www.winninginvesting.com &LR;  or e-mail him at
 &LR; hdomash(AT)winninginvesting.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON &LR;      08-06 2099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH21: TURNING OFF IDLE PCS COULD HELP END POWER CRUNCH  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With luck, the heat wave gripping the West as I
write will have broken before you read this. But the electricity
shortage the summer sun has brought to light will be with us, in
the best of cases, for years to come. And because increased
computer use is one factor in the crisis, we owe it to ourselves as
well as the rest of society to make sure we're operating our
systems as energy-efficiently as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the amount of power consumed by high tech is still
pretty small compared with applications such as lighting, air
conditioning and industrial production. According to the
Environmental Protection Agency, all office equipment accounts for
about 7 percent of electricity used in business.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency estimates that a typical desktop computer
uses about 45 watts and a monitor an additional 110 watts. And even
those relatively modest numbers may be on the high side: A
spokesman for Dell, the largest PC vendor in the United States,
told me it figures an average of about 40 watts for its PCs and 70
to 80 watts for a 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, roughly speaking, a working computer system
consumes no more than a couple of light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   But when you figure that there are well over 100 million PCs in
this country, and you factor in the printers, networking gear and
other devices that go with them, the load starts to add up.
</P>
<P>
   And because very little of this stuff existed a decade ago, it
amounts to a big chunk of the increase in demand, even if it's
still not an overwhelming percentage of overall consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at an ``energy summit'' convened in June by the Silicon
Valley Manufacturing Group, one speaker alleged, according to the
Associated Press, that ``computers and computer peripherals now
consume about 13 percent of the nation's available power, a figure
that has soared from less than 1 percent since 1993.'' On its Web
site, the SVMG also declares that ``energy consumption attributed
to Internet usage alone climbed from essentially zero in 1993 to 8
percent in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the record, some experts have told me they consider those
numbers exaggerated, but even so, the trend is clear. There's no
dispute that ``office equipment, computers in particular, is the
fastest-growing source of electricity consumption in businesses and
homes,'' as the EPA puts it.
</P>
<P>
   STARRY EYED: Few of us, I suspect, are about to cut back our
computer usage just because there's not enough juice to go around
right now. But the reality is that much of the energy that goes
into our tech gear goes to waste, particularly in offices, where
computers are usually left on all day _ and often all night and on
weekends, too _ even though, according to the EPA, they're actually
used only about four hours per workday on average.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long run, the evolution of technology may alleviate the
problem: LCD flat panels consume less than half the power of
conventional CRT monitors, and stripped-down network computers use
much less than full-featured PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you're not quite prepared, financially or otherwise,
for these cutting-edge technologies, there are some simple steps
you can take, both at home and at work, to address the power
problem without causing yourself any real pain or even
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   One is to make sure any new hardware you buy carries the Energy
Star logo. A voluntary partnership between the EPA and industry,
the Energy Star program has been around since 1992. It sets
energy-efficiency targets for some 3,400 types of products in 25
categories, from appliances to windows.
</P>
<P>
   Products that meet the criteria for their category can bear the
Energy Star logo. Certification is required for many government
procurements, as well as some corporate purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The program classifies all computers and peripherals, regardless
of actual location or use, as office equipment. In this category,
the standards focus not on the products' power draw when in use,
but on making sure they're capable of dropping automatically into a
low-power ``sleep'' mode after a period of idleness.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules, which are updated from time to time,
computers are entitled to the logo if they consume no more than 15
percent of their maximum power usage when they go to sleep.
Monitors must power down to 15 watts or less after 15 or 30 minutes
of inactivity, then to 8 watts or less after a total of 70 minutes
of inactivity. There are similar standards for printers, fax
machines, copiers, scanners and so on.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information, check out the .pdf documents listed at
 &LR; www.epa.gov/appdstar/esoe/index.html &LR; , especially one called ``A
Buyer's Guide to Purchasing Energy Star-Compliant Office
Equipment.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, EPA spokeswoman Christine Sansevero told me, about 90
percent of all new monitors sold in the United States are Energy
Star compliant. But for computers, she said, the figure is only 50
to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies offer only Energy Star systems (that seems to be
the case with Apple at the moment, though last year's
blue-and-white G3s weren't compliant), but most sell a mix of
compliant and noncompliant models; often it depends on the details
of the particular configuration you order.
</P>
<P>
   If you're buying a standard ``shrink-wrapped'' PC or peripheral
from a retail dealer, you should be able to tell whether it is
Energy Star-certified by looking for the logo on the box.
</P>
<P>
   But things get trickier if you're ordering from a catalog or the
Web, or having your system configured to order.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you can tell from the tech specs most manufacturers
post on their Web sites, but the information isn't always there.
According to Brian Zucker, a technology evangelist at Dell, the
corporate side of the company maintains lists of Energy
Star-certified models, but consumers and small-businesspeople
checking out products such as the popular Dimension PC line will
find no indication as to which models and configurations are
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're careful to buy only Energy Star-certified
products, it won't do much good unless their power-saving features
are activated. Energy Star rules, according to the EPA, require
that these capabilities be enabled when the product leaves the
factory, but users can override the default settings.
</P>
<P>
   Most home users probably don't do that. But many corporate
information-technology departments replace the software preloaded
on new systems with a standard ``image'' containing licensed
applications and approved configuration settings. In this process,
according to the EPA, power-saving features are often disabled _ in
part, it seems, because years ago, when Energy Star was new, PCs
used to lose their network connections when they went to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That problem has long since been corrected, but many IT
departments still disable power-saving features _ including even
monitor sleeping, which has nothing to do with network connections.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry to say that seems to be the case at The Chronicle. The
Energy Star features on all our PCs seem to be disabled, and when I
stay late or drop in on a weekend, I'm surrounded by humming PCs
and glowing CRTs.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to check your own PC's settings, there are at least
two places to do so in Windows 98: in the Power Management
properties (click the Start button, then Settings, then Control
Panel, then double-click Power Management) and in the Display
properties (same routine, except choose the Display icon in the
Control Panel window, or simply right-click on the desktop and
choose properties; either way, you should find the Energy Star
settings for your monitor by clicking on the Screen Saver tab).
</P>
<P>
   Note that even if your computer and monitor don't have an Energy
Star logo, odds are, unless they're genuine antiques, they do have
a sleep or low-power mode option, and it's worthwhile to enable it.
If it doesn't reduce power as far as the EPA program requires, it
will almost certainly cut your consumption significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ON OR OFF? That brings us to one of computing's eternal
questions: Should you shut off your computer when you're not using
it?
</P>
<P>
   This old chestnut came to my attention again back in June, even
before the California electricity crisis surfaced, when David
Einstein, author of The Chronicle's almost-weekly Computing Q&AMP;A
column, addressed a question about the risk of screen ``burn-in,''
the alleged danger that screen images could get burned permanently
into a CRT's phosphors if a monitor is left on but idle for too
long.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of arguing that modern monitors are ``practically
impervious to screen burn,'' Einstein noted that he'd had a
computer at work that he'd left on, displaying the Windows desktop,
for two whole years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he ended his answer by suggesting that the reader
configure his or her PC to shut off the monitor after 15 or 20
minutes of inactivity, Einstein's two-year comment elicited a howl
of outrage, e-mailed to me among other journalists at The Chron and
elsewhere, from a reader signing himself
`` &LR; pups(AT)dog-patch.com. &LR; '' Leaving a computer on all the time,
pups yelped, amounted to ``wasting energy ... in the most moronic,
slothful way imaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a special interest in this dispute, not only because I
consider myself an environmentalist, but also because that monitor
Einstein left on for two years is now mine. (Though he now writes
his Q&AMP;A column on a free-lance basis, he was for many years on The
Chronicle staff, and I happen to sit at the desk he used to
occupy.)
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the monitor doesn't show any sign of burn-in, but
I'm with pups on the larger issue: It simply doesn't make sense to
me to leave your PC running overnight _ especially if you don't
have Energy Star-certified equipment or have the power-saving
features disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the immediate power crunch facing California is mainly
during the workday, so I can't argue that shutting down at night
will help much with that. But electricity is electricity, whenever
it's consumed, and the more you consume, the more fossil fuel is
likely to be burned to generate it, with all the attendant
pollution and greenhouse-gas issues.
</P>
<P>
   It probably doesn't come as a surprise that the EPA sides with
pups and me on this one: ``Absolutely, no question about it, people
should shut down their office computers at the end of the day,''
Matt Haber of tHe agency's San Francisco office told me. ``In a
crisis situation (such as the hot-weather days we had last week),
it may make sense to shut down even when you leave for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   The main argument against Haber's position is the time required
for boot-up and log-in. For that reason, I haven't followed his
advice about lunch, but I have started shutting off my monitor
whenever I expect to be away from my desk for an hour or more.
Surely no one can argue that hitting a single switch is a major
burden.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly true that having to wait for my PC to start up
every morning is annoying, but here's one more argument for why
it's worth the trouble, even if you don't give a damn about the
environmental issues: When I have left a Windows system running
overnight, I've found that the odds of a crash the next day are far
higher, thanks to the ``memory leaks'' and other anomalies that
continue to plague Microsoft's operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: Booting up and logging in every morning may be a pain,
but it's not half as bad as having to do so after a crash in the
middle of the day, when you lose unsaved work and have to wait for
DiskScan to run its disk-integrity checks.
</P>
<P>
   One last point on energy saving: Screen savers, whatever else
they may do, don't save energy. Your computer has to be up and
running to float the Windows logo, a flying toaster or anything
else across your screen. Depending on your software and settings, a
screen saver may even prevent your system's power-management
features from engaging when they otherwise would, negating the
effects of Energy Star compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT ONLINE: For those interested in news about the
environment, one Web site to check out is the Environmental News
Network's portal ( &LR; www.enn.com &LR; ). Much of its content is
wire-service reports and press releases from green groups, but it's
convenient to have those in one place, and the site also delivers
some interesting and apparently original features.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
