<SLUG> BC-ADS-DOTCOMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AD AGENCIES EXPECT CONTINUED GROWTH  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With all of the churn in Dot-Comville,
advertising agencies that cater to Internet companies should be
suffering from headaches of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But while most San Francisco agencies have taken some hits since
the April dot-com implosion, a surprising number say they are on
track for robust growth this year, with new business coming from
both dot-coms and not-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We doubled in size last year (to $200 million) and we expect
to double again'' in 2000, said Tom Bedecarre, chairman of Citron
Haligman Bedecarre in San Francisco, which specializes in
Internet-related accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all local agencies saw a dramatic slowdown in
new-business solicitations after the April meltdown in Internet
stocks, which particularly hurt sites catering to consumers. Quite
a few e-tailers lost their funding or at least put marketing
efforts on hold.
</P>
<P>
   But phones started ringing again by June, agency executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new clients are business-to-business Internet firms,
infrastructure providers and wireless communications companies. And
of course, non-tech companies continue to spend record amounts on
advertising, particularly with the Olympics coming up.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, advertising spending this year is expected to grow a
healthy 9.4 percent, according to McCann-Erickson Worldwide, a New
York ad shop.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few local agencies have escaped the dot-com meltdown
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Exile on Seventh, a San Francisco firm that specializes in
online ads, just won three high-profile accounts _ eBay, Webvan and
People PC, with total annual billings estimated at $20 to $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency, whose clients are all Internet-related, recently
lost five other accounts worth about the same amount, said chief
executive Michael McMahon. ``I went on vacation in June and three
of them completely gave up while I was gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exile's revenues will be flat for the quarter, compared with the
10 percent monthly increases it has seen in the past. ``It's not
terrible, but we're not used to having to worry about it,'' McMahon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't made our first cold call ... but we are going
to start to have to take a more proactive stance toward generating
new business,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Gardner Geary Coll has seen three dot-com
clients stop advertising altogether or ``cut way back'' since
April, said agency President Bob Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com billings have fallen to about a quarter of the agency's
total from approximately a third, Gardner estimated. Still, the
agency continues to hire more staff and he expects overall billings
to increase this year by 15 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 21, which creates online campaigns for clients such as
Tupperware and Bank of America, has seen two of its 15 clients
defunded. But the agency still expects billings to grow by several
multiples over 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Much of its new business is coming from established offline
companies, such as Tupperware, that are just beginning to advertise
online, said chief executive Kate Everett-Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 21 is using the April downturn to its advantage by
recruiting staff from agencies whose stocks are underwater,
Everett-Thorpe said. The agency is trying to add 100 additional
employees to its current roster of 150, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the volatility, some agencies are relieved that they
didn't make an all-out push into dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we're very smart or we're very stupid,'' said Rich
Silverstein, co-chairman of Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, which
is known for consumer-product advertising such as the ``Got Milk?''
campaign. ``We're careful not to have one kind of industry take
over the entire agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's e-tailing clients, which include E-Trade, eLuxury
and a new client, Hotwire, are spending healthily on advertising,
Silverstein added.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, client volatility remains an issue among not-coms as
well as dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of Young &AMP; Rubicam lost 25 percent of
its billings last year when its biggest client, Clorox of Oakland,
consolidated its accounts with another agency.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R expects to replace the lost revenues ``almost exclusively
with tech and dot-com clients,'' said chief executive Austin
McGhie.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
