<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIDS-ASIANS-NYT &LR;      08-06 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-ASIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURAL BARRIERS HINDER EDUCATION OF ASIAN-AMERICANS ABOUT AIDS
</HEADLINE>
  By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The diversity of cultures and languages among
Asian-Americans may cause headaches for schoolteachers and census
takers, but rarely does it affect matters of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   One glaring exception is in the prevention and treatment of HIV
and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts needed to educate Asian-Americans, especially recent
immigrants, about the disease are greater than for any other ethnic
group, say scholars and outreach workers. That is because of the
variety of languages spoken and because of cultural beliefs that
discourage discussion about sex and death, let alone about sexually
transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that they are years and years behind in terms of how
the illness is treated and the social perceptions of the illness,''
said Dr. Ezer Kang, a clinical psychologist at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan who is studying
HIV-positive Asian-Americans. ``There's a lack of acceptance and
lack of awareness of HIV in the general community.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health agencies have not been very effective in directly
tackling these problems, and the task has been left to community
groups, said Kang and other experts. For example, two groups were
passing out fliers and condoms at a Chinatown street fair Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of knowledge about HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
among many recent Asian immigrants is a problem nationwide, but is
of particular concern in New York, which has the highest number of
Asian-Americans with AIDS of any metropolitan region in the
country, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. At the end of 1997, the latest year for which
information is available, they accounted for 306 out of 39,625
people with AIDS in New York. (Outreach workers say that number is
an undercount because many Asian-Americans with AIDS never report
it.)
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies also show that as an ethnic group,
Asian-Americans have the highest rate of late intervention, meaning
that patients are already infected with an AIDS-related disease by
the time they get a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The latest study, released in February by the New York City
Department of Health, shows that of a sample of 118 people made up
mostly of Asian-Americans and a few American Indians with AIDS in
1997 and 1998, 44 percent were cases of late intervention. That is
in contrast to 28 percent for blacks, 24 percent for Hispanics and
21 percent for whites.
</P>
<P>
   The main reasons for that, experts say, are a dearth of
materials about the disease in Asian languages, an unfamiliarity on
the part of public health agencies with Asian cultures, and
cultural beliefs that may hinder an understanding of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Huang, 31, of Brooklyn, ran into that problem with his
father. ``When I told him I had AIDS, and I told him I was gay at
the same time, he said, `Well, what is that?' '' Huang said. ``I
was very angry. We still really don't talk about it much.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, federal and local governments have recognized
the need for outreach, and have given funds to most of the half
dozen or so community groups in the city that provide services to
Asian-Americans. Those groups in turn have found a need to employ
an array of strategies including handing out multilingual fliers at
street fairs and giving away condoms stuffed in envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   A top priority is to make outreach efforts specific to language
and culture. To that end, the Asian and Pacific Islander Coalition
on HIV/AIDS, known as Apicha, has 75 peer educators fluent in a
dozen languages, from Bengali to Tagalog to various Chinese
dialects. The group plans to buy multilingual subway advertisements
this fall using grant money from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Other outreach groups have made educational videotapes that show
Chinese- and Korean-Americans in dramatized situations dealing with
HIV. The actors speak in Asian languages, and the situations are
set in immigrant neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the experts say that merely presenting materials in
different languages isn't enough. Each culture has a different
attitude toward sex and HIV that has to be addressed individually.
</P>
<P>
   Thai immigrants, for example, are more receptive to learning
about HIV because the high rate of infection in Thailand has led to
relatively open discussion, said Prescott Chow, a program director
at the Asian and Pacific Islander American Health Forum, based in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic Filipino-Americans often shy away from discussing
safe sex practices because of church teachings on birth control and
on abortion, said Therese Rodriguez, executive director of Apicha.
</P>
<P>
   Many East Asian immigrants come from societies that avoid open
talk about AIDS or sex. For years, the Chinese government refused
to acknowledge that AIDS existed in China. In Japan, the news media
covered the epidemic ``like witch hunting,'' and high school sex
education still revolves around ``flowers and pollen metaphors,''
said Yoshiharu Muto, a journalist based in New York who has written
about AIDS for a Tokyo newspaper and who heads the Japanese AIDS
Workshop Series.
</P>
<P>
   Apicha has found that private meetings work better than public
lectures with them, said Faraz Ahmed, a Pakistani-American outreach
worker.
</P>
<P>
   Educators talk about HIV at house parties, and Ahmed rides
around in taxis to teach drivers. Those cabbies who take customers
to sex establishments can pass on the information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, the Chinese-American Planning Council has begun a program
to educate prostitutes in Chinatown. Many came from China or
Southeast Asian countries with no intention of becoming
prostitutes, but now work out of massage parlors or apartments to
pay debts, said ManChui Leung, an outreach director at the planning
council. The peer educators often talk to the women one on one in
their homes or where they work and accompany them to be tested for
H.I.V.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very successful program for us, but tough, because
a lot of people are undocumented,'' Leung said. ``It's tough
dealing with the police, and with a lot of the businesses shutting
down and opening up.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching out to church congregations can be just as difficult.
Religious beliefs _ from Islam to Catholicism _ often play a large
role in the silence surrounding sex. In Korean- and
Chinese-American communities, Christian churches would be ideal
places for HIV and AIDS outreach because they often draw recent
immigrants, but ministers rarely allow sex education in their
houses of worship, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
   Seongho Kim at Korean Community Services said many ministers had
rejected his offer to set up HIV lectures. In January, the youth
director of a church in Flushing agreed, but the minister balked.
</P>
<P>
   For Kim and many health educators, their greatest hope is that a
new generation _ liberated from the cultural beliefs that their
more traditional parents hold _ can accept and pass on these
lessons about sex, life and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to grow healthy both mentally and physically,''
Kim said. ``At the same time, I want them to keep their own
culture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
