<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATSKILLS CASINO PLANS FOUNDER AMIDST BROKEN DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four months after the federal Interior Department approved plans
for an Indian casino in Monticello, N.Y., various developers and
tribes are battling to bring gambling to the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, none of the partnerships between the developers
and the tribes have been approved by the Interior Department. And,
after decades of futility, many proponents are becoming
increasingly worried that their best shot at bringing casinos to
the Catskills may be on the brink of slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the window of opportunity is closing,'' said Anthony
P. Cellini, supervisor of the Town of Thompson in Sullivan County.
``I think people are getting sick and tired of being promised
something that comes and goes, comes and goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents were counting on casinos to provide thousands of
jobs and bring back the tourists who until the 1970s used to flock
to the now crumbling hotels and bungalow colonies scattered across
the wooded mountains. With the prospect of gambling, politically
connected developers have been buying property in the area in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the Interior Department approved a four-year-old
proposal by the St. Regis Mohawks and a company, Catskill
Development, to build a $500 million casino on 30 acres at
Monticello Raceway, about 90 miles northwest of New York City.
Although casinos are illegal in New York, a federal law would
permit gambling on sovereign Indian land.
</P>
<P>
   But eight days after gaining federal approval, the Mohawk tribal
council spurned Catskill Development and signed a secret agreement
with Arthur M. Goldberg, chief executive of Park Place
Entertainment, the world's largest casino company. The tribe
granted Park Place the rights to develop and manage tribal casinos
in New York in return for a $3 million loan for the Mohawks' small,
nearly bankrupt casino on the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg then announced plans to build a huge casino-resort with
the Mohawks at the old Kutsher's resort, about five miles away from
the racetrack, but soon discovered that he could not simply
transfer the federal approval from the racetrack to Kutsher's.
Federal officials said it would take more than two years for a new
application to wend its way through the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   Furious about the last-minute sabotage, Robert A. Berman and the
other partners in Catskill Development refused to meet with
Goldberg, leaving one side with an approved site and the other with
an approved tribe. In May, Gov. George E. Pataki, whose approval is
needed for any Indian casino deal, said he would not make a
decision on the Sullivan County proposal until the dust cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side has something the other needs,'' Sen. Charles E.
Schumer (D-N.Y.) said. ``I'm trying to get both sides together. My
goal is to bring gaming to this area, which needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal surfaced recently about 10 miles south of
Monticello in Mamakating, where a group has been quietly
negotiating to build a casino-resort on a 720-acre parcel owned by
Crescent Heights Investments, a development company. According to
two people involved in the talks, Crescent Heights has been meeting
with David Flaum, a developer from Rochester, and Len Wolman,
managing partner of a gambling company owned in part by Sun
International, about building a casino-resort with the
Stockbridge-Munsee band of Mohicans. The tribal band, which is
based in Wisconsin, has a 24,000-acre land claim in central New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal got a warm reception from officials in Mamakating,
but the prospective partners hit a snag in mid-July. The three
sides resumed negotiations recently but may work with a different
tribe. One person involved in the project said MGM, another
gambling company, had expressed interest in a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Local political leaders say they now fear that the prospects for
a casino are dimming. Politicians in Albany are expected to
resubmit a bill requiring legislative approval of any Indian
casino, making any gambling project, proponents said, highly
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Goldberg has spent an enormous amount of time
successfully convincing officials like Cellini, Schumer and Pomeroy
that he truly intends to build a major resort.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, in turn, met for months with leaders of the Cayuga
tribe, which has a 64,000-acre land claim in central New York,
about building a casino at the track. Both parties talked with John
F. O'Mara, Pataki's chief negotiator on Indian land claims, and
tthe outline of a deal came together: The state would give the
Cayugas $130 million to settle their land claims and allow the
tribe to buy about 10,000 acres in their ancestral lands.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration would also approve a Cayuga casino at
Monticello Raceway, while the tribe agreed to revenue-sharing and
to work out a tax arrangement. But shortly before the Cayugas went
back to court in Syracuse on July 17 for their land claim, state
officials suddenly broke off all contact. A jury already awarded
the tribe $37 million in damages and Judge Neal McCurn is now
determining whether to increase the award to as much as $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal was done,'' said Martin Gold, a lawyer for the
Cayugas, ``but it's nowhere now. The state walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Goldberg has told local officials that he would
be able to obtain federal approval within 11 months for a proposal
to transfer land at the Kutsher's resort to the Mohawks for a $500
million to $750 million resort and casino on 66 acres, Cellini
said. But federal officials said it was unlikely that Park Place's
application would be completed within a year. ``That's optimistic
and not in keeping with our previous record on these matters,''
said Kevin Gover, the assistant secretary for Indian affairs at the
Interior Department. ``Traditionally, it's taken two to three years
on a new application.''
</P>
<P>
   The project could lose momentum during that time, so Schumer,
Cellini and Goldberg have prevailed on Berman's group to sit down
with Park Place officials to work out a deal for at least a
temporary casino at the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hoping that the two parties can find a way to
resolve their differences and move forward with a project at the
Monticello Raceway,'' Pomeroy said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Bernstein, a partner in Catskill Development, said
that even if his group did agree to meet with Goldberg, there was
no way that they could trust the man who he said had stolen their
project. If they do not work out a deal with another tribe, he
said, Catskill Development will sue Park Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our case against Park Place is worth more than a casino,''
Bernstein said. ``We either get the Cayugas or go to court. There's
no way you can do a deal with a guy who stabbed you in the back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
