<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NURSING-HOMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ACCEPTABLE NURSING HOME CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   For decades, hundreds of thousands of frail older Americans have
suffered unnecessary neglect, injury, abuse, malnutrition and even
death while in the paid care of licensed nursing homes. Congress
and the states have passed laws in response, and the federal
government, which spends $39 billion a year on nursing home care,
has subjected the industry to a complex web of regulations, annual
inspections and an exhaustive reporting system designed to govern
the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress has never established how many nurses and nurses'
aides are needed to give adequate _ much less good _ care for the
number of residents in a home, and it has never required
substantial training or competitive wages for the aides.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Congress asked the executive branch to report by 1992
whether there should be a defined ratio of staff to patients in
nursing homes, but it was not until 1997 that the study got
priority, and not until 11 days ago _ in a labor market grown so
tight that 41 states have reported that nursing homes cannot hire
or retain the staff they need _ that the Health Care Financing
Administration finally delivered draft copies to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The study, of 1,800 nursing homes in New York, California and
Ohio, determined that conditions like bedsores, malnutrition and
weight loss increase when staffing falls below a certain level.
Fifty-four percent of nursing homes do not meet minimally adequate
staff levels, and 92 percent have less staff than necessary to give
optimal care.
</P>
<P>
   The facilities with the highest staff levels and wages are the
nonprofit homes. The ones with the lowest ratios and wages are the
for-profit homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which has made a serious effort in
the last several years to regulate nursing homes and crack down on
abusers, has now given Congress a report that makes the case for a
new definition of acceptable care for older Americans. Achieving
competent levels of care could mean huge increases in staffing and
staff expense for nursing homes, requiring greater government
financing. Each nursing home has a different mix of residents, with
different infirmities and different needs for care.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive overhaul of the system should wait a year for
the study to complete its second phase: the construction of
formulas to suggest what staff ratios are appropriate for different
caseloads in different homes. But Congress should in this session
restore some of the Medicare money that it cut from nursing homes
three years ago, and it can endorse the concept of tying such money
to staff ratios in nursing homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
