<HEADER>
A4273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-06 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON WALKOUT DISRUPTS SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thousands of striking telephone customer service
representatives and technicians walked picket lines outside Verizon
Communications centers along the East Coast Sunday, demanding an
agreement that would permit the unionization of wireless workers
without interference from management.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout resulted in telephone service delays and a temporary
loss of directory assistance for customers as both sides continued
to discuss job security and other key issues.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's two unions _ the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers and the Communications Workers of America _ said
a majority of the company's 85,000-member work force will not
report to work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout at Verizon, the company formed by the merger of Bell
Atlantic and GTE, could affect 25 million customers in 12 Eastern
states, from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The company confirmed that service in Washington and parts of
New York was disrupted by rainy weather, and that managers at a
Philadelphia center had difficulty reporting to work when pickets
blocked their building entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rabe, a vice president for communications at Verizon, said
the company's 30,000 managers had been dispatched and would be
working 12-hour days, seven days a week to prevent lengthy
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Pickets began gathering early Sunday morning, several hours
after the unions formally announced a strike at midnight Sunday.
Several hundred strikers were posted at various sites around
Massachusetts, including Andover, Brighton, and downtown Boston.
Many said they were primarily concerned about layoffs and the
impact of new technology on their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the key words are respect from the company and job
security,'' said Thomas J. Flynn, 49, of Cambridge. The cable
maintenance technician and chief steward at the International
Brotherhood of Technical Workers Local 2222 was among dozens of
pickets who marched outside a company maintenance garage in
Brighton Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the major concern is the company's ability to move the
work at will,'' said Steve G. Smith, a 48-year-old cable splice
service technician and picket captain who monitored pickets in
Burlington and several other sites Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that even if the work is being done here in
Massachusetts, the company could move it someplace else,'' he said.
``They might offer me work in another state, but that wouldn't work
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the company and the CWA, which represents 72,000
customer service workers in the East, and the IBEW, the
representative for some 13,000 technicians and maintenance
employees, began June 26.
</P>
<P>
   However, the two sides deadlocked over the unions' demands for
contract language that would guarantee job security in the
fast-paced telecommunications industry. Union sources said the
company initially refused to discuss the unions' proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe confirmed that discussions are continuing and said the
company is hoping for a resolution soon, but declined to discuss
details of the talks or the company's contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In what the unions are calling the most positive development
since talks began, the telecommunications giant is now talking to
union negotiators about organizing rights at Verizon Wireless this
weekend, a union representative said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of progress made late Saturday night on
developing a process that would protect the rights of nonunion
workers at Verizon Wireless who want to join a union,'' said Steve
Early, a CWA international union representative in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an exchange of proposals about the details of a
card check agreement. We do not have an agreement or even a
tentative agreement,'' Early said. ``But Verizon now recognizes
that to settle this strike it must address this issue. We are
intent on building up our base on the wireless side.''
</P>
<P>
   A key sticking point is a proposed neutrality or voluntary card
check agreement that would permit the unions to organize Verizon
Wireless, the company's cellular subsidiary, through the
distribution of union cards.
</P>
<P>
   Under such an agreement, wireless workers would become part of
an IBEW or CWA bargaining unit after more than 50 percent sign
union cards.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, unions are turning to such agreements in an effort
to avoid lengthy labor-management court battles over union election
results.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, just 42 of the wireless unit's 3,500 workers are
unionized. CWA organizers contend technical and service workers at
the company's wireless unit receive fewer benefits, work longer
hours and, in some cases, receive less pay than their union
counterparts in other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The unions are also seeking protection from layoffs, provisions
that would allow workers in traditional wireline jobs to move into
the wireless division, and a cap on the percentage of workers who
may be transferred from the Eastern division to other units within
the company's newly expanded service area.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bell Atlantic Corp.'s merger with GTE this summer, its
service area has grown from the District of Columbia and 12 states
in the Eastern region to include an additional 18 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
