<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU QUARTERBACK ISN'T WORRIED ABOUT LOFTY EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 QB-TEX 
 t60b:SEASONED SOPHOMORE (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Arthur Garcia c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram FORT WORTH _ Birth
certificate?
<TEXT>
<P>
   May 16, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   School transcript?
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Extracurricular activities?
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning'' starter at quarterback on the ``Star-Telegram's''
17th-ranked college football team.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, go over Casey Printers' essentials again. It doesn't seem
possible that a 19-year-old, without the benefit of a redshirt
season, could be ready for so much so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Casey Printers, one of the best freshmen in the nation last
season, isn't the average sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey is a sophomore in eligibility only. He's much wiser
emotionally and mentally,'' TCU coach Dennis Franchione said.
``He's firmly entrenched in the program as a leader at a very young
age, and players look up to him. They respect his commitment to the
game, his commitment to the team and commitment to being good. And
he works hard at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this would be hard for a normal sophomore, but he's not
normal. In 28 years, he's the best freshman I've ever coached at
quarterback. I think he relishes the part of being a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Printers is ready for the role. As a freshman in 1999, the
former DeSoto standout played in 11 games for the Horned Frogs.
Taking over for an injured Patrick Batteaux in the third quarter of
the second game, Printers went on to start the last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Printers passed for 1,213 yards and eight touchdowns over the
regular season. He added another 173 yards and a touchdown in the
Mobile Alabama Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated'' tabbed him one of the ``Top-10 True
Freshmen in the Country,'' and ``The Sporting News'' selected him
third-team All-American at quarterback. Michael Vick of Virginia
Tech and Wisconsin's Brook Bollinger, first- and second-team,
respectively, were both redshirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really high on Casey Printers,'' said tailback LaDainian
Tomlinson, TCU's Heisman Trophy hopeful. ``He showed a lot of
leadership coming in as a true freshman last year and starting 10
games for us. With more experience, he's only going to get better,
and by the time he's a senior, he's going to be one of the top
quarterbacks in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Printers had an 8-2 record as the starter, though for much of
the regular season he split time with Batteaux. Against East
Carolina in the Mobile Bowl, however, Printers nearly went it
alone. Showing poise and maturity beyond his years, Printers took
home MVP honors after leading TCU to a 28-14 upset of the
20th-ranked Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence is carrying over to his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm on the level of a senior, because I understand
the offense totally,'' said Printers, who's switching to jersey No.
1 this season after wearing No. 11 in '99. ``I know what we're
trying to accomplish, and all we have to do is execute.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty on the Frogs' wish list for 2000, starting with
an outright Western Athletic Conference championship in their final
season in the league. Printers' plans for the season, starting Aug.
15 with two-a-day practices, are a little loftier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go in and work my butt off, help LT win the
Heisman and hopefully we'll go 11-0,'' he said. \Nsubheds:The new
Casey \Nbody:Though Printers completed 57.3 percent of his passes
last season, coaches began tweaking his technique as soon as spring
drills began in March.
</P>
<P>
   They noticed Printers' habit of lining up his left foot, the
lead foot, in the wrong direction when he's throwing to the left
side of the field. Franchione said his form is perfect when
throwing right, but because Printers is a good off-balance passer,
he was able to overcome the flaw when going to his left.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione and new offensive coordinator Les Koenning Jr. ironed
out the kink with Printers over the 15 spring sessions. Printers
noticed the difference as soon as he compared film from the Mobile
Bowl to tape from the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I look like a totally different player,'' he said.
``I look stronger, more athletic and versatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coaches were always on me. Coach Koenning did a good job of
staying on top of me and showing me what to do. I'm no longer
throwing off my back foot. I also feel more comfortable running the
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux excelled in the option, a staple of Franchione's
multiple-attack offense. Printers has the size (6-foot-3 and 205
pounds), strength (bench presses nearly 400 pounds) and the speed
(4.6 in the 40-yard dash) to be dangerous running the option, but
Franchione said Printers has been too tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to just let it fly and not be so much of a
start-and-restart guy,'' Franchione said. ``Pat could do a little
bit more of that. Casey is best when he just keeps going and runs.
In the bowl game he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Franchione doesn't want to change is Printers' feel
for the game. Franchione compares Printers favorably with Stoney
Case, his star quarterback at New Mexico and now a backup with the
Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stoney was such a fierce competitor,'' said Franchione, who
left New Mexico for TCU after the 1997 season. ``During his junior
and senior years, we would make changes during the game that you
might have to work a week on in practice. Casey is already like
that. He's such a student of the game that he'll bring you ideas
and thoughts, and a lot of times they're really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Printers has clued in the coaching staff on potential recruits
and offered ideas on how to better utilize current personnel.
Against Hawaii last season, Printers made a check with receiver
Mike Scarborough after noticing how the Warriors overplayed a hitch
earlier in the game. It turned into a 48-yard touchdown pass that
broke open the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what they were going to do,'' Franchione
said. ``When he launched it I said, `Oh, what in the hell is going
on here?' And then it's, `Good throw, good throw.' That's the kind
of player he is.'' \Nsubheds:Dreams for 2000 \Nbody:Printers
understands the unique opportunities awaiting the Frogs this
season. Ranked in The Associated Press preseason Top 25 for the
first time since 1960 at No. 20, TCU is not only the overwhelming
WAC favorite, but the Frogs are looking at a possible berth in the
Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, TCU must finish the season ranked among the
top six. The Frogs' schedule is favorable; they play WAC contenders
Fresno State and Hawaii at Amon Carter Stadium. However, the
schedule's overall lack of strength could make a major jump in the
polls difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think we have a chance \Rat the BCS\S,'' Printers
said. ``If we just take it one game at a time, I think we'll be
just fine ... 11-0, 10-1, that's the goal for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RBeing ranked is\S a great honor for us. It's good for our
recruiting and things like that, but we want more respect. We're a
team that's hungry. We still have a point to prove, and we're going
to go out and prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Hawaii and Fresno State, Printers figures the Frogs
will get stern tests from Rice and SMU in the WAC, and Northwestern
in nonconference play. Printers also remembered his struggles
against Arkansas State, a 24-21 victory in his first start, and
said Tulsa could be a sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get started. We're very excited,'' Printers
said. ``Everybody is just prancing around waiting for the season to
start, but we're a very focused football team. Coach Fran keeps the
pedal pressed down on us pretty good. We have our eyes set on the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione can't see anyone other than the 19-year-old sophomore
leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade him for anyone right now,'' Franchione said.
``If we were drawing 'em up, we'd draw 'em about like Casey
Printers.'' .MDBU/ nn
</P>
