<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AMERICA-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AMERICA IN THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 7:
</P>
<P>
   These are heady yet baffling times for the world's sole
superpower. Less than a decade after the demise of the Soviet
Union, the United States is a military and economic colossus. No
nation in history has possessed the wealth, military might or
technological edge over its rivals that America has today. Yet as
the presidential campaign enters its final months, the country
seems uncertain about its role and perplexed by the changing array
of threats that it faces. There should be vigorous debate about
these matters in the days ahead, starting with an assessment of
America's critical national interests.
</P>
<P>
   There are clear and important differences between Gov. George W.
Bush and and Vice President Al Gore on Russia, China, missile
defenses and other pressing issues. We intend to return to some of
these matters as the campaign unfolds. But specific policies cannot
be developed or evaluated in isolation. They should flow from
principles that reflect the nation's core values and interests.
</P>
<P>
   It is harder today than during the Cold War to define U.S.
interests and to determine how best to defend them. Contamination
of the world's air and water or a currency crisis in Asia can
threaten U.S. security as much as a fleet of Russian bombers. The
free flow of information across national borders may be a more
potent force for advancing democracy than dispatch of U.S. aircraft
carriers to a distant sea.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some core national interests remain unchanged. The
physical defense of America's territory, people and economic
lifelines is paramount. The Pentagon can safely eliminate thousands
of nuclear weapons left over from the Cold War, but must maintain
enough to discourage attack. America also needs highly trained and
mobile military forces, adequately paid and equipped with advanced
weaponry. Washington must also guard against international
terrorist groups. Effective intelligence gathering is an essential
first line of defense. Washington should provide adequate financing
for these purposes, but spending must be based on realistic needs,
not inflated threat assessments or parochial congressional
interests.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a powerful enemy like the Soviet Union, the
country has found itself with few established guidelines to decide
when military intervention abroad is warranted. Clearly,
self-defense and the protection of allies and economic lifelines
are reasons to use force, as Washington did when oil supplies were
endangered by the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   But as recent upheavals in Africa and the Balkans have shown,
ethnic conflicts can escalate to imperil the stability of an entire
region, and genocidal attacks on civilians sometimes can be stopped
only by outside force. Washington should consider intervening in
such conflicts if it is clear that force can make a difference and
sufficient military resources are available to assure success, the
case in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the last decades of the 20th century showed, the defense of
U.S. security is no longer primarily defined by sending military
forces into combat. The United States is uniquely suited to
encourage peacemaking in troubled regions like the Middle East.
President Clinton has used U.S. influence constructively in the
Middle East and Northern Ireland, and his successor should continue
the work he has begun. It may also be appropriate, as in Bosnia, to
send U.S. troops overseas to serve as peacekeepers once warring
parties have laid down their arms and agreed to a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the country's security and prosperity are connected to
the global movement of goods, capital, information and people.
Keeping these channels of commerce and technology open can be as
important as defending a foreign border. Washington should advance
these interests through trade agreements that lower barriers to
imports and investment. But the preservation of a stable global
economic order, a vital U.S. interest, cannot be accomplished
without spreading prosperity's benefits more fairly. Three billion
people, or half the world's population, live on less than $2 a day.
Bettering their lives requires more effective governance, increased
private investment and expanded access to education and health
care.
</P>
<P>
   America also makes its own democracy more secure by promoting
democracy elsewhere. The evolution of Russia and China into
enduring democratic states would make the world a far safer place
and erase two of the greatest potential threats to U.S. security.
Encouraging democracy and the rule of law in these nations should
be among the primary goals of the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting health and the environment are central U.S.
interests. Epidemics and climate change know no borders. Strong
environmental treaties and efforts to make medicines more widely
available must be a high priority for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush and Gore engage foreign policy, they should spell out
their thoughts about these broad national interests. Bush has so
far taken the more creative approach to the question of nuclear
weapons reductions. Gore has been more forward looking on
environmental issues and has shown a more nuanced appreciation of
the role U.S. troops could play in halting regional conflicts. But
the debate between them has not moved much beyond rhetorical
flourishes. Voters deserve a serious discussion of how this
country's power should be used to advance the global interests of
its people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
