<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS MISS BOAT AT TRADING DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A poll commissioned by The Sporting News and published
last month asked baseball general managers, assistant GMs and
personnel directors to name the top 30 current players, regardless
of position or team.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez was No. 2, behind Boston ace
Pedro Martinez. No. 3 was ex-Mariners pitcher Randy Johnson. No.6
was ex-Mariners center fielder Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, Sporting News asked: How did the Mariners fail to
win a championship with three of the top six players?
</P>
<P>
   Any Mariners fan over the last five years can provide the
answer: This isn't pro basketball, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Three superstars in the NBA is one more than necessary to win,
say, six championships in eight years. But baseball is so
pitching-dependent and the Mariners were so pitching-light after
the Big Unit that they have managed a just a single playoff-game
win over the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The reason they were pitching-light was because ownership was so
preoccupied with cutting losses and building a new ballpark that
investment in player payroll took a distant backseat.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after the Great Squandering and the departure of two
the game's best players, the Mariners have sufficient pitching.
They also have profits, thanks to the taxpayer-financed Safeco
Field and its high-spending hordes who will likely set a
single-season club attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the Mariners lead baseball's tiniest division,
which is absent any ownerships who are reckless with a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   So the 2000 season represents a splendid chance to answer The
Sporting News and pay back the millions of Northwesterners and
their millions of dollars with a World Series appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the results from the initial trading deadline a
week ago were for discerning Mariners fans a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-game lead instead of six games in arrears, the
Mariners were not in a panic. And it's true that the club's big
moves, nearly all of which have worked, were done in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   But Al Martin? He's not a bad pickup, but a guy who's been on
three teams in five months and with two wives simultaneously is not
exactly the emotional bedrock upon which to fan a pennant drive.
</P>
<P>
   He's a left fielder, and a mediocre one at that, coming to a
position already filled by recent newcomer Rickey Henderson. That
has meant Martin in his first week has played more center field and
right field than he has in his eight-year major league career
combined, in order to avoid sending Henderson into one of his
legendary pouts over playing time.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that leads the major leagues in runners left on base,
he represents the teensiest of solutions. He's a left-handed bat
who can run a little and will help the lame pinch-hitting, but he
rarely hits breaking pitches and probably couldn't gun down at
second base a shopping cart with a bad wheel.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mariners have invested $8 million in left field ($5
million for Martin, $3 million for Henderson) when they already
have a capable backup outfielder in Stan Javier, who has more RBI
than Martin in 100 fewer at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In utilityman John Mabry and minor league pitcher Tom Davey, the
Mariners didn't give up much. But they didn't get much, which
contrasts heavily with what happened with the contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mariners are assured of no less than a split of
the big four-game series against the Yankees _ thanks to Sunday's
11-1 clobbering _ that ends today, the Yankees repaired themselves
over the past month with the additions of David Justice and
Glenallen Hill and pitchers Denny Neagle and Dwight Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox pulled off a seven-player trade that added pitcher
Rolando Arrojo and second baseman Mike Lansing. Boston's staff
leads the American League in ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays traded for three veteran pitchers, and Oakland
added set-up reliever Jim Mecir, whose virtue as an ex-Mariner is
that he is almost guaranteed to do what ex-Mariners always do
against Seattle _ star.
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced by their 23 runs over the weekend at Yankee
Stadium, the Mariners are a solid team. But it also demonstrates
that the Yankees are as vulnerable as they have been in their
half-decade of dominance. With less than two months of the season
remaining, there isn't a formidable team in the AL, and only seven
real contenders for the four postseason spots.
</P>
<P>
   It's a season of rare opportunity, and the Mariners are on the
verge. But with a 13-11 mark after the All-Star break, a little
personnel lightning last week could have been decisive. Instead, it
appears they are in a summer-long swordfight with Oakland, whose
$32 million payroll _ about $30 million less than Seattle _ is a
giant egg aimed right at the faces of Mariners ownership.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his reluctance to part with prime minor league
pitching talent for immediate batting help, Mariners GM Pat Gillick
sounded wise when he said his plan is to create enough personnel
depth to win at least 90 games every year for 10 years and take his
chances in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Gillick is coming up against a lot of bad
Mariners history (they have won as many as 90 games in a season
just once, in 1997) and a tempting present _ an AL more winnable
than any time in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mariners can be happy to have survived the trades of
Johnson and Griffey, they need the franchise's best season to keep
Rodriguez and the fickle part of the fan base, which in
major-league sports is increasingly large and vulnerable. Ask the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   There is always logic and comfort in prudence. But the Mariners
in their new ballpark are rich and successful enough to be done
with the phony small-market conservatism and engage in a little
swashbuckling.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
