r a BC-PRISON-AZR &LR;      08-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PRISON-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    STATE'S FEMALE INMATE POPULATION IS SOARING(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, the number of women behind bars in Arizona was
barely enough to fill one prison wing.
</P>
<P>
   But their ranks have swollen so much that female felons now
warrant their own prison, proof that crime is an equal-opportunity
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Female inmates are still scattered among five prisons throughout
the state. But by October, they all will move to the Arizona State
Prison at Perryville in Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   The move is necessary, according to officials with the Arizona
Department of Corrections, as a cost-cutting measure in the face of
a booming female prison population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite clearly, our female population is growing at a faster
rate,'' said Camilla Strongin, a DOC spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The number of female inmates has exploded since 1980, when just
171 women were serving time. The number has risen tenfold since
then, and is expected to top 2,000 by next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade alone, the number of female inmates has more
than doubled. The rate of increase even eclipsed the 84 percent
growth in male inmates, whose numbers over the past decade soared
to 24,494, from 13,272.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's growth in prisoners mirrors a national trend during
the 1990s, in which the overall prison population boomed, and the
rate of female incarceration rose even faster. Nationally, prison
ranks doubled in the past decade, according to a recent
congressional study.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office also found that the majority of
women were held for non-violent crimes. Tough new laws covering
drug offenses are largely credited for the explosion of prison
populations.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, as elsewhere, the growth continues.
</P>
<P>
   The DOC projects the number of female inmates will rise to 3,615
by 2008 based on the number of crimes being committed by women,
nearly double again the number in Arizona prisons today.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Perryville, which affects 1,867 women, involves a
series of complicated transfers of male inmates to other prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have to juggle male bed space to make room for the
women,'' said Ellen Kirschbaum, DOC's female programs
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``During all this, not only do we have to move men out, we have
construction that has to go on,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   That construction involves adding beds for inmates with
disabilities to comply with the federal Americans with Disabilities
Act. Workers also are repainting the facility, which is nearly 20
years old.
</P>
<P>
   The move seems to be sitting well with female prisoners, even
though some have been overwhelmed by the size of the Perryville
facility and its larger prison population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot more staff than we were used to dealing
with,'' said Paula Reynolds, 49, who has served 91/2 years of her
20-year sentence for killing her abusive boyfriend. She had been
housed in a different unit at the Perryville complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are a totally different breed - more emotional and maybe
more mouthy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The prison department expects to save money by housing female
inmates in one place, rather than having to transport them among
facilities as far away as Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also know more than 60 percent of our females come from
Maricopa County, although half have been housed in Tucson,''
Strongin said. ``So this move has an added benefit for their
families and for their release back into the community from where
they came.''
</P>
<P>
   Consolidating female prisoners in Arizona is part of a larger
trend of grouping prisoners by the crimes they committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a move to consolidate certain
populations,'' Strongin said. ``A couple of years ago, we started
consolidating all the sex offenders together because it eliminated
the risk to them of being housed with other types of prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   Although overwhelmed by the size of her new unit, inmate
Reynolds said it is better than her former accommodations - a tent
with swamp coolers, fans and nine roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an optimal kind of living,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow inmate Tracy James agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so thankful to get out of the tents,'' said James, who
has spent the past three years of her nine-year sentence at
Perryville prison. She was convicted of killing her fianci in a
domestic violence situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have put me in a massive place or a minute one. I
didn't care. All I know is that I have running water in my cell and
my own restroom. And they gave us our TVs back.''
</P>
<P>
   James, 32, is also glad the prison eventually will be occupied
only by women, because it means more jobs for female prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of jobs will be opening up,'' possibly at the Hickman
Farms and in telemarketing, she said. ``Pretty much the women are
going to run the prison.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at kerry.fehr-snyder(a)arizona republic.com
or (602) 444-8975.
</P>
