<HEADLINE>
FLIGHTS OF THOUGHT ON COWBOYS' PROGRESS _ OR LACK OF IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get one thing straight.
</P>
<P>
   There's no such thing as a good 12-hour flight.
</P>
<P>
   However, the excitement of going to a foreign country made the
front end of this round-trip to Tokyo somewhat palatable.
</P>
<P>
   The return was nothing but a beat down _ somewhat akin to the
ones the Cowboys routinely take in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   But back to yesterday's tedious flight home. The movie choices
were ``My Dog Skip'', an updated version of ``Lassie'', and the
sassy ``Erin Brockovich''. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   A manly action flick would have been nice, considering the
inaction from the Cowboys in the second half of Saturday's 20-9
loss to the Falcons. Four turnovers on six second-half possessions?
</P>
<P>
   What better time then to ponder what we've learned about the
Cowboys after two weeks of training camp and two preseason games?
</P>
<P>
   So here are some random thoughts from ``somewhere over the
Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you realize that if Randall Cunningham hadn't fallen in the
Cowboys' lap then Paul Justin, who looks the second coming of Hugh
Millen, would be the team's backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Justin's two turnovers against the Falcons give him six in two
preseason games. It's downright hilarious that the Cowboys still
insist that they are comfortable with Justin.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only that Justin has made mistakes, it's that he's done
it by forcing the issue. Generally, you want your backup
quarterback to play within himself and be a caretaker, such as
Jason Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that theory doesn't hold with Cunningham. But not
even the Cowboys are comparing Justin with Cunningham. The fact
that the Cowboys signed Cunningham speaks volumes _ about the
two-time MVP Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys should get credit for not only getting Cunningham,
but for how they are using him. Cunningham basically has three
playbooks, the conventional one that starter Troy Aikman uses, the
special plays that the Cowboys inserted for him and the free-lance
plays that he makes up.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is the real reason the Cowboys signed him.
Ironically, for much of Cunningham's career, he has been criticized
for improvising too much, running too much and not running the
offense enough.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 37, the Cowboys want him to run _ and do whatever _
as much as he wants. His ad-libs have been impressive so far.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about the Cowboys' inability to get in the end zone
against the Falcons. Remember the first-team offense played without
running back Emmitt Smith and guard Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the NFL all-time leader in rushing touchdowns, and Allen,
the league's best offensive lineman, know a little something about
getting into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't worry about linebacker Dat Nguyen not being able to
handle the middle. Sure, the Cowboys are going to get creased at
times for big plays up the middle because of Nguyen's size.
However, he's a playmaker. And he's going help you a lot more than
he's going to hurt you.
</P>
<P>
   Other players who put smiles on the Cowboys faces when their
names come up are tight end Jackie Harris, guard Kelvin Garmon and
defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   Do, however, worry about the cornerbacks. Not because the
Cowboys do not have Deion Sanders, but because of who they do have.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ryan McNeil is a proven veteran, but he is three
years removed from when he was considered among the league's top
cornerbacks. While he's the best on the Cowboys, can he get back to
the higher level?
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Smith is healthier than he's been in a couple
of years. But aren't his best days behind him?
</P>
<P>
   And rookie second-round pick Dwayne Goodrich is, so far, living
down to expectations in the vein of previous busts Shante Carver
and Kavika Pittman. His body language is worse than his play. How
can the Cowboys feel comfortable about playing him when he looks so
beaten down.
</P>
<P>
   That being said, confidence and swagger are not a problem for
the other two rookie corners. Both Kareem Larrimore (fourth round)
and Mario Edwards (sixth round) have been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they've been beaten on plays. But they always come back
raring for more. While Larrimore is part of the first nickel group,
look for the chatty Edwards to get the first shot at starting if
Smith falters.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if Erik Williams is not back by the start of the
season, look for him in Week 7.
</P>
<P>
   Whew, just 10 more hours to go.
</P>
<P>
   Brokovich or sleep?
</P>
<P>
   Both. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
