<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK DEPTH STILL QUESTIONABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Ray Buck 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that the Cowboys have been outscored by a 3-1 margin in
preseason losses to Pittsburgh and Atlanta is pertinent only if you
believe that the third-team quarterback is going to play a role in
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Or that the No. 3 quarterback is going to play this season,
period.
</P>
<P>
   If it gets down to either the much-maligned Paul Justin (six
turnovers in two games) or rookie Clint Stoerner needing to deliver
when the games begin to count Sept. 3, then the season isn't going
to be worth much anyway. That's just how the NFL works.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, 0-2, have more reason to fret with five turnovers
and 10 penalties which occurred in their 20-9 loss to the Falcons
at the Big Egg in Tokyo, because that reflects a lack of both
discipline and focus that Dave Campo preaches every day in training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are back in Wichita Falls tomorrow after returning
yesterday from Japan and completing their second 12-hour flight in
four days.
</P>
<P>
   What has come out of the quarterback play in the first two
exhibitions is that the Cowboys no longer see Troy Aikman's
thirtysomething backup as someone who is better-suited to coach the
quarterbacks than to be one himself.
</P>
<P>
   That's what really chased away longtime backup Jason Garrett,
who defected in February to the NFC East rival New York Giants,
where he is Kerry Collins' backup. That opened the door for Randall
Cunningham to come to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your second quarterback doesn't get the work that he needs in
the offense to stay with the game plan,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
said of Cunningham. ``What Randall brings to the table is an
`impromptu ' approach. He doesn't need the \Rextensive\S
preparation during the week to make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Steelers, Cunningham turned a potential coverage
sack into a 21-yard gain when he pulled the ball down and
scrambled. Against the Falcons, the 37-year-old veteran completed 3
of 5 passes for 45 yards, relying on Wane McGarity and Chris
Brazzell, not Joey Galloway and Rocket Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also believe that \RCunningham\S, with a full week to get
ready for a game, can be able to run all of our offense,'' said
Jones, who can quote Cunningham's 8-4 career record against the
Cowboys. ``And Randall actually is more suited to the three-, five-
and seven-step drops in our offense than he has been in the West
Coast offense.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the job that the Cowboys wanted Garrett to take is now
filled by Wade Wilson, who retired after 19 NFL seasons. And
Garrett's job as Aikman's backup now belongs to Cunningham, who was
released by Minnesota for salary-cap purposes only two years after
he was the NFL's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cowboys so far, Cunningham is 2-for-2 in putting points
on the boards: two field-goal drives.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and Cunningham are responsible for all five of the
Cowboys' scoring drives. Aikman has completed 70 percent of his
passes for 158 yards and has engineered one touchdown and two field
goals in his four series.
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 3 quarterback candidates, Justin and Stoerner, have
combined for eight turnovers and no scoring drives.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, a 58-percent NFL career passer with only 10
interceptions in 380 NFL pass attempts, already has had more
interceptions (six) than completions (four) for the Cowboys. Justin
also has lost two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner has completed nearly 58 percent of his passes for 126
yards, but he has had two interceptions. Each time, he forced the
ball to make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   What matters most to the Cowboys is that Aikman and Cunningham
have game.
</P>
<P>
   Justin has slipped badly after being Aikman's backup before
Cunningham's arrival June 8. Now Justin probably gets the fewest
number of snaps in practice _ and it shows. Since Justin knows the
Cowboys' basic system from his past connections to Mike Martz
(Arizona State and St. Louis Rams), he usually gets fewer practice
reps than Stoerner, who has no background in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early,'' to give up on Justin, said Jones, adding, ``Paul
has always been willing to take chances; it's a part of his game.
But I think he's taking risks that he wouldn't normally take in a
regular-season game.''
</P>
<P>
   But keep in mind that the No. 3 quarterback job isn't a tall
order of business in making up a 53-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   That works for Justin, as well as it works against him. The
rookie comes cheaper. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
