<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL AMERICAN BOWL TRANSLATES INTO A FARCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Gil LeBreton 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A news dispatch last week from league headquarters reminded us
that Saturday night's Cowboys-Falcons skirmish was the 10th NFL
exhibition game to be played in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   My response is, shhhh _ I won't tell the United Nations if you
guys won't.
</P>
<P>
   Let me get this straight. They send us dependable cars, raw
fish, state-of-the-art TVs and ``Iron Chef'' reruns.
</P>
<P>
   And we send them Tony Graziani at quarterback and Emmitt Smith
in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a bad exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL persists in calling these international matches of
mystery the ``American Bowl,'' as if this was Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue's annual entry in the Nobel Peace Prize sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, lest anyone forget, played in the original American
Bowl, circa 1986. They practiced in London's Hyde Park, posed with
the palace guards, and played the Chicago Bears in a game that was
a novelty until, oh, the third quarter, when the Wembley Stadium
crowd began doing soccer chants.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys lost that night, 17-6, and have squandered every
foray onto foreign soil since _ no wins, seven losses, one tie.
Despite that, owner Jerry Jones issued the obligatory ``proud to
serve as ambassadors'' pronouncement, and Atlanta president Taylor
Smith allowed that it was great to ``experience the rich culture of
Japan and its people.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure if he said that before or after the $165
room-service bill.
</P>
<P>
   My point is the American Bowl is an idea that has run its course
as an annual phenomenon. Especially when it co-stars the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance reflects a declining interest. The last time that
the Cowboys played in the Tokyo Dome, August of '92, they lost to
the then-Houston Oilers in front of 51,058. The crowd Saturday was
announced as 42,178, and the empty seats were conspicuous on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices for Cowboys-Falcons ranged from a $50 cheap seat
to $500 for so-called VIP seating. Let me suggest, therefore, that
the novelty has worn off.
</P>
<P>
   To us American ``gaijin'', the language barrier is daunting. But
the Japanese appear to have wisely figured it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Bowl'' translates to ``exhibition'' football, and
after years of watching teams of U.S. baseball players saunter
through on meaningless exhibition tours, the Japanese know all
about the e-word.
</P>
<P>
   NFL exhibition games are ripoffs in this country. Packaging them
for foreign lands probably violates the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL isn't going to expand into Tokyo or London, so what's
the point here?
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to disrupt training camp _ more on that later _ and
travel 15 hours each way, just for the sake of marketing exposure,
Owner Jones is doing his team a disservice.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Cowboys arrived home yesterday, for instance,
sporting a Mount Fuji-sized case of jet lag. Practices in Wichita
Falls will be predictably sluggish for the rest of the week. Add
the two days lost while in the air, plus the minimal
season-preparation work that was done in Tokyo, and coach Dave
Campo's team has lost a valuable stretch of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests that they can overcome it. The first Cowboys
team that played in Tokyo went on to win the Super Bowl. But in his
first camp as head coach, Campo needs some questions answered, and
this was a bad time to take a week off.
</P>
<P>
   The good people of Japan might be too polite to admit it, but
they're probably tired of the NFL sending them bad preseason fish
and charging Kobe steak prices. Baseball finally caught on, and
when they sent the Cubs and Mets to Tokyo in March to play real,
regular-season games, the Japanese people embraced the gesture.
Both games in the Tokyo Dome were 55,000-seat sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL really wants to spread its goodwill, it should
schedule one annual regular-season game across the seas. The people
of Japan would acknowledge the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The current format just doesn't translate anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Or is the league too busy selling American Bowl T-shirts to
notice? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000806.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-REGULATE-AZR &LR;      08-06 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGULATE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-REGULATE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MINE INSPECTIONS LAG(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CRAIG HARRIS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six months after the death of Jose Villanueva in a southern
Arizona underground copper mine, state Mine Inspector Doug Martin
is the first to admit he doesn't have enough inspectors to
thoroughly examine the 547 mining operations under his
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Asarco's mine in Sahaurita, where Villanueva was
killed in a rock fall Jan. 31, was thoroughly and properly
inspected the state-mandated four times last year, even though some
other mines weren't checked. And he said the Asarco underground
mine has been inspected this year.
</P>
<P>
   But since a shakeup in his office two years ago, Martin's staff
has conducted just roughly more than half of the required number of
inspections to surface and underground mines, and sand and gravel
pits, according to a report with the state Legislative Budget
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the reason just 56 percent of the required
inspections occurred in 1998 and only 61 percent happened last year
is because he has a small, inexperienced staff.
</P>
<P>
   He also said his office's recent battle with civil suits is
forcing inspectors out of the field and into courtrooms. This year,
he hopes to conduct 67 percent of the required inspections and have
100 percent by 2003, once his staff gains experience and the
Legislature gives him more personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was elected in 1988, blames part of his problems on
lawmakers for not giving him more than four full-time inspectors
and a chief deputy inspector who have to canvass the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Chairman Bob Burns, R-Glendale, said Martin
is to blame because he promoted three of his best field inspectors
to administrative jobs two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take your top performers off the line and put them
behind a desk, that's not the way the budget is supposed to work,''
Burns said. ``If he had positions in his office, he should have
sought those and not moved inspectors. He has a communications
problem when making his requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the three promoted inspectors - Operations Manager
Lawrence Nelson, Chief Deputy Inspector David Hamm and Assistant
State Mine Inspector Phil Howard - still conduct inspections on a
part-time basis in addition to their administrative jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Martin also said he has had to train three new inspectors in the
last year, after three experienced inspectors retired and another
one was fired. Before 1998, his office had conducted all of the
required inspections three of the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understaffing is the problem. Each year we request an increase
in personnel but it hasn't happened,'' Martin said. ``The
constitution only requires me. It doesn't say how many people I
have to have. So I try to convince the Legislature what I need to
do my job efficiently. I usually get a memo saying there are no new
funds available, therefore there's no increase in employment.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Mine Inspector's Office was created in 1912, when
Arizona became a state and mining was the major industry. The sole
purpose then was simple: Protect miners.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Martin said safety is his priority but his office has
limited regulatory powers.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows his office to issue citations, and it can shut
down an operation for safety hazards. Only once has Martin
temporarily shut down a mining operation, and his office cannot
assess financial penalties. But even if his office had that
authority, Martin said, he wouldn't use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with the policy of fines,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said fines create a negative relationship with the
companies, and he would rather have that money used to correct
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get those funds turned back into a safe practice, then
we have done a good job,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy clearly is not shared with the U.S. Mine Safety
and Health Administration, which assesses fines of $55 to $55,000,
depending on the severity of problems. MSHA can issue citations if
inspectors find loose rock, poor ventilation, noise problems or
vehicle defects.
</P>
<P>
   Although both the state and federal governments inspect mines in
Arizona, they are independent of each other and typically do not
share information. Federal inspections carry more weight because of
the power to assess fines, as well as the ability to shut down a
mine. MSHA can inspect any mine unannounced at any time if safety
complaints are made, but it typically inspects mines quarterly, as
it does with Asarco.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, MSHA is expected to announce the full
amount of fines it will assess on Asarco for the 26 violations it
found following the Jan. 31 accident that killed Villanueva and
severely injured Joe Olson and Javier Vargas. The state, however,
cited just minor violation during its two inspections following the
accident. The injured miners and Villanueva's family are seeking
multimillion-dollar settlements from the state. If they don't get
it, they say will sue Martin's office.
</P>
<P>
   Asarco, which was bought last year by mining giant Grupo Mexico,
was fined $40,000 by MSHA after a worker was electrocuted in 1997
at the Sahaurita mine south of Tucson. After appealing, the company
paid $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davitt McAteer, the top MSHA official and an assistant Labor
Department secretary, said the federal government assesses fines to
enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes certain the conditions for a violation do not
exist,'' said McAteer, noting the practice is like a police officer
writing a speeding ticket. ``They serve as a reminder and
encouragement to continue to have a mine violation-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, however, isn't alone when it comes to limited powers.
</P>
<P>
   Montana and Nevada also issue citations but can't fine mines. Of
the six Western mining states of similar size, only Wyoming
assesses fines, but the practice is rare. Colorado, New Mexico and
Utah have no regulatory authority over mines and leave that job to
MSHA. And only Nevada, with its 11 inspectors, has more inspectors
than Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona law requires an underground mine, such as Asarco's, to
be inspected each quarter, but Martin said his staff doesn't look
at the entire mine.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said just certain parts are inspected, and by the
end of the year an inspector may have looked at all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible with four people to look at all 547
operations,'' Martin said. ``The other thing is a mine is mining
all the time. Therefore, we might be there the first week of July,
and by the time we are there the next quarter, a whole area could
be mined out. {hellip} There is no way we could be there day by
day.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at craig.harris(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-8058.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND OF TWO PARTS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
