<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-06 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PRISONMOMS-AZR &LR;      08-06 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONMOMS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PRISONMOMS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    KIDS SUFFERING AS MORE MOMS GO TO PRISON(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has what many 10-year-old boys only dream of - a Sony
PlayStation, a snare drum set, his own VCR and enough Michael
Jordan paraphernalia to create a shrine to the retired Chicago
Bulls basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   But what this Phoenix fifth-grader lacks is what every boy wants
and needs: his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whose name is being withheld at his family's request,
is a victim of a growing problem in Arizona and the rest of the
country. He is among an estimated 200,000 children in the country
with mothers in prison. In Arizona, about 1,300, or 71 percent, of
the women in prison have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are children that are at risk for all kinds of
problems,'' said Cynthia Seymour, an attorney for the Child Welfare
League of America in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour was quick to add that not all children with prison moms
will wind up living in poverty, developing emotional problems,
falling behind in school, abusing drugs and alcohol or getting into
trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Although all are a possibility, assuming children will wind up
in trouble further stigmatizes them, Seymour said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt that the growing ranks of women in prison
means an increasing number of children on the outside who are
negatively affected, she said.
</P>
<P>
   No one has studied the effect in depth, but anecdotal evidence
indicates that most children whose moms are sent to prison are
being raised by their grandmothers, usually their mother's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if it weren't for his maternal grandmother, the Phoenix
boy would be without parents for the next 41/2 years until his
mother, Tracy James, is released from prison. James, who stabbed
her fianci to death during a domestic violence fight, has been in
jail since her only child began kindergarten. The boy's natural
father lives out of state and has never played a role in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been traumatized a lot in this situation,'' said James,
32, who is serving time at the Arizona State Prison Complex in
Perryville. She allowed a reporter to talk to her son and her
mother on the condition that neither would be identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard on children; they feel abandoned,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   When James first went to prison, her son became angry and
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The boy used to see a child psychologist. But today, he seems
well adjusted, spending time playing basketball, video games and
watching movies like (beginitalic)Billy Madison(enditalic) - a
reward recently for cleaning up his room, where a picture of him
and his mother hangs above his bunk bed.(beginitalic)
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)The boy used to call his grandmother ``momma'' until
James put a stop to it. He calls her ``Grammie'' now and isn't shy
about holding her hand as they shop Paradise Valley Mall or daring
her to go on the scariest rides at Water World.
</P>
<P>
   The two visit James every other Sunday, although occasionally,
the boy chooses not to make the hourlong trip.
</P>
<P>
   When the boy does visit, he and James usually play Yahtzee and
eat pizza and soda pop out of the prison's vending machines. The
boy also gets to sit on James' lap and hug her - something they
were prevented from doing for a year after James was first
incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   James tries to be a mother to her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've mothered my son from behind these walls,'' she said. ``I
tell him, `I'm your mother regardless of where I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's grandmother agrees: ``She has a lot of influence, even
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the mother-son relationship is never rocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes he's angry at her,'' the boy's grandmother
said. ``He hung up on her twice this week, once by accident and
once on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   James said she understands the anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't replace these years,'' she said. ``I can never get
these back.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son is looking forward to the day he can live with his
mother again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He counts my time by Halloween. He'll say, `In so many
Halloweens, my Mom will be out,''' James said.
</P>
<P>
   But the reunion could bring its own trouble. James wants to move
out of Arizona and make a fresh start, which means her son would
have to leave Grammie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets concerned about where they'll go,'' his grandmother
said. ``I tell him that I'll just get on a plane and come visit
him, or that he can come visit me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the time comes, it will be really rough.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at kerry.fehr-snyder(a)arizona republic.com
or (602) 444-8975.
</P>
