<HEADLINE>
OFF-THE-WALL LOSS FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ROYALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Lansing hit The Wall, one of the most unforgiving
edifices in America. And no sooner did the newest Red Sox second
baseman Sunday plunk his first ball off the storied structure than
he joined a long, inglorious list of its victims.
</P>
<P>
   Narrowly gunned down trying to turn a Wallball single into a
double, Lansing cost the Red Sox a crucial, leadoff runner in the
ninth, accidentally casting himself as a symbol of Boston's weekend
of missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the Kansas City Royals rolled out of the Hub
with a 3-1 victory, their second straight of the three-game series.
The Red Sox, still weary from a West Coast swing last week, headed
back across the continent for six games in Anaheim and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees, who also lost Sunday, still held a 3 1/2-game
lead over the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Red Sox stranded 20 runners in their back-to-back
losses to the Royals, including two in the ninth inning Sunday
after Lansing's rude introduction to the Green Monster.
</P>
<P>
   The lost chances helped to squander another strong outing by Tim
Wakefield (6-6), who allowed only two earned runs in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of been the story of the year,'' said catcher Scott
Hatteberg. ``There have been some great pitching performances and
we've been unable to score some runs. It's a trend we have to
change. Time is running out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, coming off an eight-inning effort in the 19-inning
``Sleepless in Seattle'' game last week, has pitched six or more
innings in his last eight starts, solidifying his spot as the
team's most dependable starter other than Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wakefield is winless in his last four outings, as the Sox
have failed to score more than five runs in any of the games,
including the 19-inning epic. This time, Wakefield concluded, ``I
just got outpitched.''
</P>
<P>
   By a guy named Dan Reichert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many people know about him,'' said right fielder
Trot Nixon, who managed one of Boston's seven hits off the rookie
righthander. ``But the guy's got outstanding stuff, a sinker that
just moves like I've never seen, and power. He has the ability to
dominate with those pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he did for eight innings, scattering those seven hits and
three walks. Only two Boston hitters reached third base, Nixon, who
was stranded there in the third inning, and Nomar Garciaparra, who
passed through on his home-run trot after launching a solo shot to
center in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra went 2 for 4, improving his average to .394. He tied
the score, 1-1, with the homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals scored an unearned run in the first when Johnny Damon
singled, moved to second on Rey Sanchez's ground out, and ambled
home when left fielder Troy O'Leary misplayed Jermaine Dye's
routine fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it got caught in the sun,'' manager Jimy Williams
said. For O'Leary, it was only his second error of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After Garciaparra's homer, his 17th, Kansas City countered in
the eighth. Carlos Febles led off by dinging a single off the
scoreboard and stealing second. Damon, who has torn apart the Sox
this year with a .542 average against them, followed by bunting
safely down the third-base line, advancing Febles to third.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it for Wakefield, who had thrown only 92 pitches
and felt strong enough to continue. But Williams turned to Hipolito
Pichardo, one of the bullpen's sinkerballer stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he can get a ground ball and get a double play,''
Williams said, explaining his move.
</P>
<P>
   Pichardo got the ground ball, from Sanchez. But it rolled too
slowly to third, allowing Manny Alexander to get only the force at
second, and Febles scored the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Sweeney singled, Dye knocked in Sanchez, making it
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox stranded two in the bottom of the inning and began the
ninth with Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   In the postgame autopsy of the inning, Williams considered what
might have been had Lansing, a career National Leaguer until the
Sox acquired him from Colorado 11 days ago, survived The Wall.
``Two runs down, leadoff hitter on first, three outs to go,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lansing charged around first without the green light from
coach Tommy Harper. ``I thought I could get there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he believes he did get there. He slid head-first into
the bag as Febles applied the tag. ``I know I did, and I don't need
to see a replay,'' he said. ``He tagged me on my ribs and my hand
was on the base.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansing protested briefly, without assistance from Williams or
Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he said he stood by his decision to take the risk.
``It's just the way I play,'' said Lansing, a hard-nosed throwback
sort of player. ``I understood the situation, but I also understood
that I thought I had a good chance to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The out was pivotal because the next batter, Rico Brogna,
singled to center, as did the next, pinch hitter Jason Varitek.
Lansing would have scored on the second hit, there would have been
no outs, and the Sox likely would have been able to send Carl
Everett to the plate, if not Garciaparra, before the inning ended.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon flied out for the second out and Brian Daubach
grounded out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some chances to score, we sure did,'' Williams said.
``We just couldn't get those hits with guys in scoring position.
Out of 162 games, it's bound to happen. But I guess it gets
magnified when the games are close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
