<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG SEASON WOULD BE REAL KICK FOR VINATIERI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Adam Vinatieri pointed to an ugly rug burn on
his left arm. Painful, yes, but a price well paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desmond,'' said Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't going to happen again,'' the Patriots kicker said.
``Desmond wasn't going to run back another one on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some memories never fade.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri had blasted the opening kickoff to the Detroit Lions
Friday night in the Pontiac Silverdome and there, waiting on the
goal line, was none other than Desmond Howard. And when the
returner eluded the first wave of Patriots, then the next, and
headed toward the left sideline, Vinatieri was New England's
tackler of last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desmond headed to the outside,'' said Vinatieri, ``and I saw
him coming. I said, `Uh-oh.' Then I said, `Not today.' I wanted to
make sure he didn't get me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Vinatieri, nor most Patriots fans, can forget what
Howard did in Super Bowl XXX. New England had just cut Green Bay's
lead to 27-21 in the third quarter, the momentum swinging to the
Patriots, when Vinatieri kicked off to Howard.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that Vinatieri was illegally blocked by a Packer on
Howard's return, but he then was the last hope for a tackle.
Howard, though, whizzed past him on a 99-yard return that
effectively ended the Super Bowl for New England. The Patriots
never could recover from Howard's TD return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to make sure it didn't happen again,'' said
Vinatieri, one of the better tacklers among kickers in the National
Football League. ``And this time I got him.''
</P>
<P>
   And the nasty rug burn in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But it was what Vinatieri did on the last play of the half
Friday night and the next-to-last play of the game that should
encourage Patriots fans more than Vinatieri's tackle of Howard. At
the end of the half, Vinatieri kicked a 50-yard field goal, and, at
game's end, he kicked the winning 28-yard field goal, giving New
England a 13-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if game-winning field goals are ever routine,''
said Vinatieri, ``but it was good to hit it. I know preseason games
don't mean anything in the standings, but it was good to hit the
field goal and win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   New England's dismal 8-8 season of 1999 might have been a more
healthy 10-6 if Vinatieri hadn't missed two makable late field
goals, against Kansas City and Buffalo. Indeed, the Patriots also
could have been 11-5 if tight end Ben Coates hadn't dropped a
third-down pass against the Dolphins at Foxboro Stadium just before
the two-minute mark of the fourth quarter. Coates, though, dropped
the ball, Miami gained possession, and soon came from behind and
won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget those (missed field goals vs. the Chiefs and
Bills),'' said Vinatieri. ``It keeps you honest and it keeps you
working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, aside from all the X's and O's of a new coaching staff,
the key question is how well two of the main point-makers for New
England _ Vinatieri and quarterback Drew Bledsoe _ have recovered
their confidence from the battering of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, it seems that Vinatieri may decide more than a few
games this season since it seems the New England defense is so
strong it won't allow opposing teams to get very far ahead and the
offense is so weak it won't be scoring enough points to give the
team a comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to put (the missed kicks) deep in the back of my
head and out of mind,'' said Vinatieri. ``Kickers have to have
short memories, good or bad. You just have to go out and kick the
next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri said 50 yards is more or less his limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit that (50-yarder) well,'' said Vinatieri. ``We had good
execution, the blocking was good, the snap was good, and the hold
was good. The ball just kind of went for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was kicked inside the domed home of the Lions
(interestingly, the wind inside the Silverdome was listed at 1 mile
per hour). Outside, and in normal conditions, Vinatieri said, his
range should be close to 50 yards, give or take a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on how well you're hitting the ball,'' he said,
``and how well you're hitting them that day. Obviously, there are
days when you feel there's no distance too far and then there are
other days. Friday was one of those days that, in my pregame kicks,
I was moving back to 53 and 54 yards and I felt pretty
comfortable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
