<SLUG> BC-FBC-CONNECTICUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN EXCITED BY SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ You can see the new stadium site _ 75 acres of
land that doesn't need to be cleared or bought or fought over _ as
you scoot down I-84 into East Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   You can feel the excitement if you listen to University of
Connecticut athletic director Lew Perkins talk about possible games
against Ohio State, North Carolina, Purdue, Miami, and perhaps even
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear it in the voice of UConn football coach Randy
Edsall as he talks about building a program from virtually ground
zero, with the selling point to new recruits a simple one: ``Help
create a tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   It still takes more imagination and vision than anything else to
focus on the complete picture simply because there is as yet no
tangible evidence of the Huskies' jump to Division 1-A in football.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly a decade of ``almosts,'' ``what ifs,'' and more
than a few ``if onlys,'' UConn will be off and running in a fast
new lane in September, when it makes its grand entrance into 1-A
football Sept. 2 at Eastern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I can't believe it,'' said Perkins, the
long-suffering AD who has seen false start after false start
regarding plans for a new stadium _ the key issue in the project.
``I felt like a bride who had been to the altar so many times and
never got married. This is obviously exciting. But to be honest
with you, there were more than a few times when I didn't think it
was ever going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next five seasons, the Huskies will be a 1-A
independent, playing teams in the Big East, Mid-American
Conference, and any other 1-A powers looking for a game against
what most people _ at first _ believe will be a vulnerable program.
</P>
<P>
   Official entrance into the Big East on a round-robin basis will
not be until 2005, although the Huskies will play Big East schools
beginning this season _ UConn will play at Boston College Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium, projected for 40,000 seats, will be ready for
the opener of the 2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Edsall two years ago was the first major step toward
establishing a tradition. He had Big East ties at Syracuse and BC,
as well as NFL experience _ he was an assistant on Tom Coughlin's
staff at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring Randy was important because of his background,'' said
Perkins, ``and because he had been in a transition program when
they were building the Jacksonville franchise. He knows what this
is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsall is not willing to take any shortcuts. ``The one thing I
learned under Tom was that no matter what people might say or what
happens at first, stick to your plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, UConn's plan has some logic. It will play eight games
against 1-A teams, then nine the next season, with the strength of
schedule peaking for the opening of the new stadium in 2003 when
Perkins wants at least one or two marquee teams to come to Hartford
to kick-start the enthusiasm for New England's second 1-A program.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins knows there is a delicate balance to scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be careful,'' he said, ``because now everybody
wants to play us. We want to be respectable.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn's track record suggests that will happen. The Huskies have
built solid programs in men's and women's sports, winning national
championships in men's and women's basketball the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment is there, so is the funding. With the stadium
issue settled, the Huskies believe they will have a showcase
facility to draw recruits to Storrs the same way basketball players
from all over the country have arrived the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   No one is expecting miracles any time soon. Unlike Marshall,
which went from being a dominant 1-AA team to a
much-better-than-average 1-A program overnight, the Huskies have
not dominated 1-AA _ they were 4-7 last season. In some preseason
rankings, the Huskies are ranked last out of 115 1-A teams for the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how you measure success,'' Perkins said. ``If we
can get to the point where we are competitive in the next five
years _ and by competitive I mean 4-7, 5-6, 6-5 _ we'll be all
right. Maybe we can catch a break and go 7-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins believes Hartford's failed flirtation with the New
England Patriots helped UConn.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perverted way, losing the Patriots was a blessing in
disguise,'' he said. ``Because after that fell through, there was
sort of a void and we came along and filled it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 42, Edsall is just hitting his stride in coaching. His
apprenticeship, culminating in a two-year stint as the defensive
coordinator at Georgia Tech before he came to UConn, was geared
toward one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because I wanted to be a 1-A coach,'' he said.
``And I wanted to coach in the Big East.''
</P>
<P>
   In the jumbled and confused days and weeks following the
resignation of BC coach Dan Henning four years ago, Edsall thought
he would be coming back to the Eagles, where he had been an
assistant on Coughlin's staff for two years.
</P>
<P>
   But miscommunication, which was the operative term around The
Heights in those days, prevailed, and Edsall wound up at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is at UConn and he already has raised the battle flag to
BC and every other school that wants New England high school
talent. He expects UConn to be a major player, sooner rather than
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to face some tough times, no question,'' said
Edsall, who will be doing that when he fields a team that will have
only 10 seniors and 59 players who are either freshmen, redshirt
freshmen, or sophomores. ``But we have a plan and we're going to
stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsall said he would prioritize. First, he wants to shut the
border for any talent in Connecticut. ``We're going to fight tooth
and nail to keep those players,'' he said. ``Then, we have to go
into areas such as Florida, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania and get
some players out of there. Having recruited in that area and
knowing the coaches in the Big East, I know the strengths and
weaknesses of those programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The selling point will be basic. ``We're going to sell players
on the idea they can play right away,'' said Edsall. ``We're going
to tell them they can be a big fish in a little pond, rather than a
little fish in a big pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsall also knows he will be the point man for the program. ``I
have to go above and beyond what other coaches do in selling myself
and the idea of this program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will do that by telling recruits in New England they have
another choice if they want to stay in the Northeast, not just
Syracuse, BC, and, to a lesser extent, Temple and Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal,'' he said with a laugh, ``is to go after recruits,
and when they take their five official visits, it's up to us to
make sure that UConn is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   And he makes it clear he wants to be on the fast track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell them that we can win the Big East
championship and get a BCS (Bowl Championship Series) slot,'' he
said. ``We're in this to win, and to get to the highest level we
can get. I don't see why there has to be a limit on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2355EDT &QL; 
