u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-06 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN WE CLOSE DOOR ON EVERETT INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The manager closing the door to his office is a
baseball tradition that can mean many things. Sometimes it's for a
happy occasion, other times it's an attempt to hide frustration.
Many times emotions come into play.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Jimy Williams's office was merely a holding tank for
media members curious about Saturday's shouting match between
Williams and outfielder Carl Everett, who was returning from a
10-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Before going out to face the Royals Saturday, Everett found
himself behind a closed door in Williams's office. Perhaps he
thought Williams was going to praise him for keeping himself in
shape during his time away. Everett then would promise to continue
to be the .300 hitter the Sox had acquired and paid good money to
in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams had something else on his mind. According to
several sources, Williams didn't appreciate the fact that on an
offday last Thursday, Everett flew home to Tampa rather than fly
from Seattle to Boston. Williams bit his tongue until the
closed-door meeting. Then he lit into his star center fielder like
a Little League father slams into his very talented son. Everett
responded with strong language, which easily could be heard
throughout the locker room. Neither side prevailed, and all the
ramifications of the incident have not been felt.
</P>
<P>
   Williams surely will fine Everett for leaving the team. Although
general manager Dan Duquette signs the players and thus greatly
determines the Red Sox style of play by his selections, Williams
runs the show on and off the field. He oversees the good times and
the bad, and when decisions have to be made, he usually can be
found with his staff behind the closed door of his office.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox gave Everett a three-year contract worth $21 million and
expected him to be a staple, like shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. But
Everett's place in the lineup is determined by Williams, which
gives the manager some power. Everett may not totally accept that,
but to survive in Boston he must.
</P>
<P>
   Everett must look in the mirror and realize he is not the same
guy who came to town several months ago and impressed fans and
media eager to create another baseball legend. His recent behavior
has upset some fans, and he recently termed the media, after its
coverage of his July 15 bumping incident with umpire Ronald Kulpa,
``wolverines.'' Surely, he knows the media has been called worse.
The media are just professionals doing a job, just like he is.
</P>
<P>
   Everett reminds one in some ways of the combustible Oil Can
Boyd, the Sox pitcher who had early success but then saw his career
begin to slide. On Aug. 22, 1985, Boyd suffered a 5-3 loss to Texas
at Fenway Park. Once in the locker room, he began to berate his
teammates for their lack of support in close games. His language
was offensive and Jim Rice, who was hitting .265 at the time, took
particular offense to the fact that Boyd was paying more attention
to himself than his team. They exchanged insults and twice had to
be separated. After a third attempt to get at each other, Boyd was
hauled off behind a closed door. He went on to finish 15-13 that
season, but his rage cost him $1,530 and had a lasting negative
effect.
</P>
<P>
   After a career-best record of 16-10 in 1986, Boyd won only 13
games in the next three seasons and had more trouble off the field
than Carter has you know what. After Boston, Boyd pitched for
Montreal and Texas before retiring with only a 78-77 record.
Currently, he is barnstorming in Mississippi, Arkansas, and Texas.
It seems a waste.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's fine will be more than $1,530. He could wind up in
some employee assistance program, as did Boyd or more recently Wil
Cordero, who was accused of assault and battery against his wife.
The incident could cost Everett millions over the long haul, too.
That is not to say that Everett will fall apart in the near future.
But these days a player of his stature must be careful about public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Boyd said after his experience:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being the center of controversy. As you all know,
I'm a very emotional player and sometimes my emotions are not fully
understood by others. My frustrations were not directed (at) anyone
in particular but rather the entire situation.''
</P>
<P>
   We're all tired of controversy, too. All you have to do is play
hard, Carl, try to catch the Yankees, and help bring an end to the
Curse of the Bambino. That's why you are here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-06-00 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
